Meaning: An adjective, commonly called the indefinite article, and signifying one or any, but less emphatically.

A, as a prefix to English words, is derived from various sources. (1) It frequently signifies on or in (from an, a forms of AS. on), denoting a state, as in afoot, on foot, abed, amiss, asleep, aground, aloft, away (AS. onweg), and analogically, ablaze, atremble, etc. (2) AS. of off, from, as in adown (AS. ofd/ne off the dun or hill). (3) AS. a- (Goth. us-, ur-, Ger. er-), usually giving an intensive force, and sometimes the sense of away, on, back, as in arise, abide, ago. (4) Old English y- or i- (corrupted from the AS. inseparable particle ge-, cognate with OHG. ga-, gi-, Goth. ga-), which, as a prefix, made no essential addition to the meaning, as in aware. (5) French a (L. ad to), as in abase, achieve. (6) L. a, ab, abs, from, as in avert. (7) Greek insep. prefix / without, or privative, not, as in abyss, atheist

As a prefix ad- assumes the forms ac-, af-, ag-, al-, an-, ap-, ar-, as-, at-, assimilating the d with the first letter of the word to which ad- is prefixed. It remains unchanged before vowels, and before d, h, j, m, v. Examples: adduce, adhere, adjacent, admit, advent, accord, affect, aggregate, allude, annex, appear, etc. It becomes ac- before qu, as in acquiesce.

A microscopic vegetable organism, belonging to the class Algae, usually in the form of a jointed rodlike filament, and found in putrefying organic infusions.  Bacteria are destitute of chlorophyll, and are the smallest of microscopic organisms. They are very widely diffused in nature, and multiply with marvelous rapidity, both by fission and by spores. Certain species are active agents in fermentation, while others appear to be the cause of certain infectious diseases. See Bacillus.

A California fish (Hemilepidotus spinosus), allied to the sculpin.
One whose occupation is to make cabinets or other choice articles of household furniture, as tables, bedsteads, bureaus, etc.
The art or occupation of making the finer articles of household furniture.
The art or occupation of working upon wooden furniture requiring nice workmanship
Certain deities originally worshiped with mystical rites by the Pelasgians in Lemnos and Samothrace and afterwards throughout Greece
Of or pertaining to the Cabiri, or to their mystical worship.
A large, strong rope or chain, of considerable length, used to retain a vessel at anchor, and for other purposes. It is made of hemp, of steel wire, or of iron links.
A message sent by a submarine telegraphic cable.
Composed of three three-stranded ropes, or hawsers, twisted together to form a cable.
A little cable less than ten inches in circumference.
A small piece of mutton or other meat roasted on a skewer
Showing the full face, but nothing of the neck
A house on deck, where the cooking is done
An apple-green mineral, a hydrous arseniate of nickel, cobalt, and magnesia

A name applied to various species of edible fishes of the genus Serranus, and related genera, inhabiting the Meditarranean, the coast of California, etc.  In California, some of them are also called rock bass and kelp salmon.
A one-horse carriage with two seats and a calash top.
A small line made of spun yarn, to bind or worm cables, seize tackles, etc.
A degenerated or poisoned condition of the blood.
A South American short-tailed monkey (Pithecia (/ Brachyurus) melanocephala).

A small evergreen tree (Theobroma Cacao) of South America and the West Indies. Its fruit contains an edible pulp, inclosing seeds about the size of an almond, from which cocoa, chocolate, and broma are prepared.

The sperm whale (Physeter macrocephalus).  It has in the top of its head a large cavity, containing an oily fluid, which, after death, concretes into a whitish crystalline substance called spermaceti. See Sperm whale.
A hole in the ground, or hiding place, for concealing and preserving provisions which it is inconvenient to carry.
An ornamental casing for a flowerpot, of porcelain, metal, paper, etc.
A seal, as of a letter.
A condition of ill health and impairment of nutrition due to impoverishment of the blood, esp. when caused by a specific morbid process (as cancer or tubercle).
Consisting of, or accompanied by, immoderate laughter.
A fermented liquor made in Cayenne from the grated root of the manioc, and resembling perry.
An opaque or milk-white chalcedony, a variety of quartz
A silvered aromatic pill, used to correct the odor of the breath.
An Andalusian dance in three-four time, resembling the bolero.
A pastil or troche, composed of various aromatic and other ingredients, highly celebrated in India as an antidote, and as a stomachic and antispasmodic.
To ease the body by stool
To make a sharp, broken noise or cry, as a hen or goose does.
A vitiated state of the humors, or fluids, of the body, especially of the blood.
Having the fluids of the body vitiated, especially the blood.
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, cacodyl.
Pertaining to, or characterized by, cacography
Incorrect or bad writing or spelling.
A chair, litter, or other contrivance fitted to the back or pack saddle of a mule for carrying travelers in mountainous districts, or for the transportation of the sick and wounded of an army.
A North American carnivore (Bassaris astuta), about the size of a cat, related to the raccoons. It inhabits Mexico, Texas, and California.
One of the seeds or large beans of a tropical vine (Entada scandens) used for making purses, scent bottles, etc.
An uncouth or disagreable sound of words, owing to the concurrence of harsh letters or syllables.
A corruption or corrupt state of art.
A hydrous phosphate of iron occurring in yellow radiated tufts. The phosphorus seriously injures it as an iron ore.
Belonging to, or like, the family of plants of which the prickly pear is a common example.

Any plant of the order Cactacae, as the prickly pear and the night-blooming cereus. See Cereus. They usually have leafless stems and branches, often beset with clustered thorns, and are mostly natives of the warmer parts of America.
Pertaining to the top of the palate
A person who stands at the door of an omnibus to open and shut it, and to receive fares
Of or pertaining to landed property.
An official statement of the quantity and value of real estate for the purpose of apportioning the taxes payable on such property.
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a corpse, or the changes produced by death
Having the appearance or color of a dead human body

The larva of a caddice fly. These larvae generally live in cylindrical cases, open at each end, and covered externally with pieces of broken shells, gravel, bits of wood, etc.  They are a favorite bait with anglers. Called also caddice worm, or caddis worm.
A small box, can, or chest to keep tea in.
The act or state of declining or sinking.
A species of inferior carpet imported from the Levant.
A parenthetic flourish or flight of ornament in the course of a piece, commonly just before the final cadence.
The position, rank, or commission of a cadet
Cheerful or mirthful, as after good eating or drinking
An inferior magistrate or judge among the Mohammedans, usually the judge of a town or village.
A Scotch errand boy, porter, or messenger.
A chief judge in the Turkish empire, so named originally because his jurisdiction extended to the cases of soldiers, who are now tried only by their own officers.
A large pear, shaped like a flattened top, used chiefly for cooking.

Of or pertaining to Cadmus, a fabulous prince of Thebes, who was said to have introduced into Greece the sixteen simple letters of the alphabet -- /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /, /. These are called Cadmean letters.
An oxide of zinc which collects on the sides of furnaces where zinc is sublimed. Formerly applied to the mineral calamine.
Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, cadmium

A comparatively rare element related to zinc, and occurring in some zinc ores. It is a white metal, both ductile and malleable. Symbol Cd. Atomic weight 111.8. It was discovered by Stromeyer in 1817, who named it from its association with zinc or zinc ore.
An instrument with a graduated disk by means of which the angles of gems are measured in the process of cutting and polishing.
The framework or skeleton upon which a regiment is to be formed
Relating to escheat, forfeiture, or confiscation.
Of or belonging to Mercury's caduceus, or wand.

The official staff or wand of Hermes or Mercury, the messenger of the gods. It was originally said to be a herald's staff of olive wood, but was afterwards fabled to have two serpents coiled about it, and two wings at the top.
With temporary gills: -- applied to those Amphibia in which the gills do not remain in adult life.
Dropping off or disappearing early, as the calyx of a poppy, or the gills of a tadpole.
Of or pertaining to the caecum, or blind gut.
A limbless amphibian belonging to the order Caeciliae or Ophimorpha. See Ophiomorpha.
A cavity open at one end, as the blind end of a canal or duct.
A cream-colored limestone for building, found near Caen, France.
A Roman emperor, as being the successor of Augustus Caesar. Hence, a kaiser, or emperor of Germany, or any emperor or powerful ruler. See Kaiser, Kesar.
Of or pertaining to Caesar or the Caesars
A system of government in which unrestricted power is exercised by a single person, to whom, as Caesar or emperor, it has been committed by the popular will
A rare alkaline metal found in mineral water
A metrical break in a verse, occurring in the middle of a foot and commonly near the middle of the verse
Of or pertaining to a caesura.
A humble inn or house of rest for travelers, where coffee is sold.
Pertaining to, or obtained from, coffee.
A white, bitter, crystallizable substance, obtained from coffee. It is identical with the alkaloid theine from tea leaves, and with guaranine from guarana.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the tannin of coffee.
A garment worn throughout the Levant, consisting of a long gown with sleeves reaching below the hands. It is generally fastened by a belt or sash.
A box or inclosure, wholly or partly of openwork, in wood or metal, used for confining birds or other animals.
A bird confined in a cage
A kind of parrot, of a beautiful green color, found in the Philippine Islands.
One of a race inhabiting the valleys of the Pyrenees, who until 1793 were political and social outcasts (Christian Pariahs). They are supposed to be a remnant of the Visigoths.
A number of sheets of paper put loosely together
Pertaining to, or derived from, cahinca, the native name of a species of Brazilian Chiococca, perhaps C. racemosa
The governor of a sanjak or district in Turkey.
A light skiff or rowboat used on the Bosporus
The refrain of a famous song of the French Revolution.
A rounded or conical heap of stones erected by early inhabitants of the British Isles, apparently as a sepulchral monument.
A yellow or smoky brown variety of rock crystal, or crystallized quartz, found esp, in the mountain of Cairngorm, in Scotland.
To deceive with flattery or fair words
A highly stimulating volatile inflammable oil, distilled from the leaves of an East Indian tree (Melaleuca cajuputi, etc.) It is greenish in color and has a camphoraceous odor and pungent taste.
A colorless or greenish oil extracted from cajuput.
A small mass of dough baked
A district on the west coast of Africa.
An alkaloid resembling physostigmine and occurring with it in the calabar bean.
A slope or declivity in a manege ground down which a horse is made to gallop, to give suppleness to his haunches.
A genus of aroideous plants, of which some species are cultivated for their immense leaves (which are often curiously blotched with white and red), and others (in Polynesia) for food.
A glossy woolen stuff, plain, striped, or checked.

A valuable furniture wood from India and Ceylon, of a hazel-brown color, with black stripes, very hard in texture. It is a species of ebony, and is obtained from the Diospyros quaesita. Called also Coromandel wood.

A cephalopod, belonging to the genus Loligo and related genera. There are many species. They have a sack of inklike fluid which they discharge from the siphon tube, when pursued or alarmed, in order to confuse their enemies. Their shell is a thin horny plate, within the flesh of the back, shaped very much like a quill pen. In America they are called squids. See Squid.
A species of agalloch, or aloes wood, of a dusky or mottled color, of a light, friable texture, and less fragrant than calambac
A mineral, the hydrous silicate of zinc.
A genus of perennial plants (Calamintha) of the Mint family, esp. the C. Nepeta and C. Acinos, which are called also basil thyme.
One who plays upon a reed or pipe.
To curl or friz, as the hair.
The act or process of curling the hair.
A comblike structure on the metatarsus of the hind legs of certain spiders (Ciniflonidae), used to curl certain fibers in the construction of their webs.

A fossil plant of the coal formation, having the general form of plants of the modern Equiseta (the Horsetail or Scouring Rush family) but sometimes attaining the height of trees, and having the stem more or less woody within. See Acrogen, and Asterophyllite.
Any great misfortune or cause of misery
The indian cane, a plant of the Palm family. It furnishes the common rattan. See Rattan, and Dragon's blood.
Gradually diminishing in rapidity and loudness.

A light carriage with low wheels, having a top or hood that can be raised or lowered, seats for inside, a separate seat for the driver, and often a movable front, so that it can be used as either an open or a close carriage.
A bronze-yellow massive mineral with metallic luster
One of the bones of the tarsus which in man, forms the great bone of the heel
A kind of oven, or reverberatory furnace, used for the calcination of sand and potash, and converting them into frit.
Having a spur, as the flower of the toadflax and larkspur
consisting of, or containing, calcareous and argillaceous earths.
Consisting of, or containing, lime and bitumen.
Consisting of, or containing calcareous and siliceous earths.
Partaking of the nature of calcite or calcium carbonate
Pertaining to, or situated near, the calcar of the brain.
A foul vein, like chalcedony, in some precious stones.
Shaped like a slipper, as one petal of the lady's-slipper
A genus of showy herbaceous or shrubby plants, brought from South America
Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, calcium or lime.
Bearing, producing, or containing calcite, or carbonate of lime.
Calciferous. Specifically: (Zool.) of or pertaining to the portion of the oviduct which forms the eggshell in birds and reptiles.
The process of change into a stony or calcareous substance by the deposition of lime salt
Consisting of, or containing, calcareous matter or lime salts
In the form of chalk or lime.
To make stony or calcareous by the deposit or secretion of salts of lime.
Tending to form, or to become, a calx or earthlike substance on being oxidized or burnt
Holding lime or other earthy salts
A white or colored wash for the ceiling or other plastering of a room, consisting of a mixture of clear glue, Paris white or zinc white, and water.

The act or process of disintegrating a substance, or rendering it friable by the action of heat, esp. by the expulsion of some volatile matter, as when carbonic and acid is expelled from carbonate of calcium in the burning of limestone in order to make lime.
To reduce to a powder, or to a friable state, by the action of heat
One who, or that which, calcines.
An order of marine sponges, containing calcareous spicules. See Porifera.

Calcium carbonate, or carbonate of lime. It is rhombohedral in its crystallization, and thus distinguished from aragonite.  It includes common limestone, chalk, and marble. Called also calc-spar and calcareous spar.
Relating to, or in the style of, calcography.
The art of drawing with chalk.
That may be calculated or ascertained by calculation.
To ascertain or determine by mathematical processes, usually by the ordinary rules of arithmetic
The act or process, or the result, of calculating
One who computes or reckons: one who estimates or considers the force and effect of causes, with a view to form a correct estimate of the effects.
Of the nature of a calculus
Any solid concretion, formed in any part of the body, but most frequent in the organs that act as reservoirs, and in the passages connected with them
A large kettle or boiler of copper, brass, or iron. [Written also cauldron.]
The ancient Latin name of Scotland
Of or pertaining to Caledonia or Scotland
A hydrous sulphate of copper and lead, found in some parts of Caledonia or Scotland.
The act of warming or heating
An orderly arrangement of the division of time, adapted to the purposes of civil life, as years, months, weeks, and days
Of or pertaining to the calendar or a calendar.

A machine, used for the purpose of giving cloth, paper, etc., a smooth, even, and glossy or glazed surface, by cold or hot pressure, or for watering them and giving them a wavy appearance. It consists of two or more cylinders revolving nearly in contact, with the necessary apparatus for moving and regulating.
Of or pertaining to a calendar.
The first day of each month in the ancient Roman calendar.
A genus of composite herbaceous plants. One species, Calendula officinalis, is the common marigold, and was supposed to blossom on the calends of every month, whence the name.
A gummy or mucilaginous tasteless substance obtained from the marigold or calendula, and analogous to bassorin.
A name formerly given to various fevers occuring in tropics
The young of the cow, or of the Bovine family of quadrupeds. Also, the young of some other mammals, as of the elephant, rhinoceros, hippopotamus, and whale.
The hide or skin of a calf
The tenth avatar or incarnation of the god Vishnu.
The diameter of the bore, as a cannon or other firearm, or of any tube
To ascertain the caliber of, as of a thermometer tube
The process of estimating the caliber a tube, as of a thermometer tube, in order to graduate it to a scale of degrees

One of the small cuplike cavities, often with elevated borders, covering the surface of most corals. Each is formed by a polyp. (b) One of the cuplike structures inclosing the zooids of certain hydroids. See Campanularian.
Plain white cloth made from cotton, but which receives distinctive names according to quality and use, as, super calicoes, shirting calicoes, unbleached calicoes, etc.
Relating to, or resembling, a cup
A pipe or duct used to convey hot air or steam.
Dimness or obscurity of sight, dependent upon a speck on the cornea
An alloy of lead and tin, of which the Chinese make tea canisters.
A part of a turtle which is next to the upper shell. It contains a fatty and gelatinous substance of a dull greenish tinge, much esteemed as a delicacy in preparations of turtle.
A part of a turtle which is attached to the lower shell. It contains a fatty and gelatinous substance of a light yellowish color, much esteemed as a delicacy.

An instrument, usually resembling a pair of dividers or compasses with curved legs, for measuring the diameter or thickness of bodies, as of work shaped in a lathe or planer, timber, masts, shot, etc.
The office, dignity, or government of a caliph or of the caliphs.
Of or pertaining to Calippus, an Athenian astronomer.
A valuable kind of Peruvian bark obtained from the Cinchona Calisaya, and other closely related species.
The science, art, or practice of healthful exercise of the body and limbs, to promote strength and gracefulness
An early form of hand gun, variety of the arquebus
To drive tarred oakum into the seams between the planks of (a ship, boat, etc.), to prevent leaking. The calking is completed by smearing the seams with melted pitch.
A calk on a shoe. See Calk, n., 1.
To command or request to come or be present
A genus of plants, of the order Araceae.
The Muse that presides over eloquence and heroic poetry
A popular name given to a few species of the genus Coreopsis, especially to C. tinctoria of Arkansas.
A somewhat riotous parade, accompanied with the blowing of tin horns, and other discordant noises
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a callithump.
Furnished with protuberant or hardened spots.
A hard or thickened spot or protuberance
The great band commissural fibers which unites the two cerebral hemispheres. See corpus callosum, under Carpus.
A plant coif or skullcap. Same as Calotte.
Freedom from motion, agitation, or disturbance
One who, or that which, makes calm.
The state of quality of being calm
A branch of the Mongolian race inhabiting parts of the Russian and Chinese empires
Mild chloride of mercury, Hg2Cl2, a heavy, white or yellowish white substance, insoluble and tasteless, much used in medicine as a mercurial and purgative
The conversion of obscure radiant heat into light
The fifth letter of the English alphabet.
A Latin prefix meaning out, out of, from
Every one of the two or more individuals composing a number of objects, considered separately from the rest. It is used either with or without a following noun
The state or quality of being eager

Any large, rapacious bird of the Falcon family, esp. of the genera Aquila and Haliaeetus. The eagle is remarkable for strength, size, graceful figure, keenness of vision, and extraordinary flight. The most noted species are the golden eagle (Aquila chrysaetus)

A concretionary nodule of clay ironstone, of the size of a walnut or larger, so called by the ancients, who believed that the eagle transported these stones to her nest to facilitate the laying of her eggs
A young eagle, or a diminutive eagle.
Having the wings of an eagle
A kind of fragrant wood. See Agallochum.
A wave, or two or three successive waves, of great height and violence, at flood tide moving up an estuary or river
Ache or pain in the ear.
A cap or cover to protect the ear from cold.
A disease in wheat, in which the blackened and contracted grain, or ear, is filled with minute worms.
The tympanum. See Illust. of Ear.
Fear or timidity, especially of something supernatural.

A nobleman of England ranking below a marquis, and above a viscount. The rank of an earl corresponds to that of a count (comte) in France, and graf in Germany. Hence the wife of an earl is still called countess. See Count.
Earnest money. Same as Arles penny.
The state of being early or forward

An officer of state in England who marshals and orders all great ceremonials, takes cognizance of matters relating to honor, arms, and pedigree, and directs the proclamation of peace and war. The court of chivalry was formerly under his jurisdiction, and he is still the head of the herald's office or college of arms.
A lock or curl of hair near the ear
A mark on the ear of sheep, oxen, dogs, etc., as by cropping or slitting.
The state or quality of being earnest
An instrument for removing wax from the ear.
An ornament consisting of a ring passed through the lobe of the ear, with or without a pendant.
A flattened marine univalve shell of the genus Haliotis
The globe or planet which we inhabit
A bag filled with earth, used commonly to raise or repair a parapet.
A bank or mound of earth.
The part of a plow, or other implement, that turns over the earth
A mythical monster of the early Anglo-Saxon literature
Vessels and other utensils, ornaments, or the like, made of baked clay. See Crockery, Pottery, Stoneware, and Porcelain.
A variety of asbestus. See Amianthus.
A pronged fork for turning up the earth.
The quality or state of being earthy, or of containing earth
The quality or state of being earthly
Having a mind devoted to earthly things
A name given to various roots, tubers, or pods grown under or on the ground
A species of pea (Amphicarpaea monoica). It is a climbing leguminous plant, with hairy underground pods.

A shaking, trembling, or concussion of the earth, due to subterranean causes, often accompanied by a rumbling noise. The wave of shock sometimes traverses half a hemisphere, destroying cities and many thousand lives
A curious fungus of the genus Geaster, in which the outer coating splits into the shape of a star, and the inner one forms a ball containing the dustlike spores.
A fungus of the genus Geoglossum.
Any construction, whether a temporary breastwork or permanent fortification, for attack or defense, the material of which is chiefly earth.
Any worm of the genus Lumbricus and allied genera, found in damp soil. One of the largest and most abundant species in Europe and America is L. terrestris
Any insect of the genus Forticula and related genera, belonging to the order Euplexoptera.
A witness by means of his ears
A frame (commonly) of wood serving to hold a canvas upright, or nearly upright, for the painter's convenience or for exhibition.
That which gives ease, relief, or assistance
The state or condition of being easy
The point in the heavens where the sun is seen to rise at the equinox, or the corresponding point on the earth

An annual church festival commemorating Christ's resurrection, and occurring on Sunday, the second day after Good Friday. It corresponds to the pasha or passover of the Jews, and most nations still give it this name under the various forms of pascha, pasque, paque, or pask.
A native of a country eastward of another
Situated or dwelling in the east
Belonging to, or relating to, the East Indies.
The distance measured toward the east between two meridians drawn through the extremities of a course
An armchair for ease or repose.
Eatable growth of grass for horses and cattle, esp. that of aftermath.
One who, or that which, eats.
French name for brandy.  Cf. Aqua vitae, under Aqua.
The edges or lower borders of the roof of a building, which overhang the walls, and cast off the water that falls on the roof.
To stand under the eaves, near a window or at the door, of a house, to listen and learn what is said within doors
One who stands under the eaves, or near the window or door of a house, to listen

The habit of lurking about dwelling houses, and other places where persons meet fro private intercourse, secretly listening to what is said, and then tattling it abroad. The offense is indictable at common law.

One of a sect of heretics, in the first centuries of the church, whose doctrine was a mixture of Judaism and Christianity. They denied the divinity of Christ, regarding him as an inspired messenger, and rejected much of the New Testament.
The system or doctrine of the Ebionites.
The prince of the evil spirits
A hard, black variety of vulcanite. It may be cut and polished, and is used for many small articles, as combs and buttons, and for insulating material in electric apparatus.
To make black, or stain black, in imitation of ebony
A hard, heavy, and durable wood, which admits of a fine polish or gloss. The usual color is black, but it also occurs red or green.
An instrument for observing the boiling point of liquids, especially for determining the alcoholic strength of a mixture by the temperature at which it boils.
A boiling or bubbling up of a liquid
A composition of dust of ivory or of bone with a cement
A condition of bone cartilage occurring in certain diseases of these tissues, in which they acquire an unnatural density, and come to resemble ivory.
Made of or relating to ivory.
The conversion of certain substances into others which have the appearance or characteristics of ivory.
A game at cards, played usually by two persons, in which the players may discard any or all of the cards dealt and receive others from the pack.

A genus of cucurbitaceous plants consisting of the single species Ecballium agreste (or Elaterium), the squirting cucumber. Its fruit, when ripe, bursts and violently ejects its seeds, together with a mucilaginous juice, from which elaterium, a powerful cathartic medicine, is prepared.
A figure in which the orator treats of things according to their events consequences.
Denoting a mere result or consequence, as distinguished from telic, which denotes intention or purpose
A digression in which a person is introduced speaking his own words.
A drug, as ergot, which by exciting uterine contractions promotes the expulsion of the contents of the uterus.
An alkaloid constituting the active principle of ergot
A contrivance for hatching eggs by artificial heat.
A picture which represents the Savior as given up to the people by Pilate, and wearing a crown of thorns.
Deviating or departing from the center, or from the line of a circle
To discolor by the production of an ecchymosis, or effusion of blood, beneath the skin
A livid or black and blue spot, produced by the extravasation or effusion of blood into the areolar tissue from a contusion.
The public legislative assembly of the Athenians.
An official of the Eastern Church, resembling a sacrist in the Western Church.
One of the canonical books of the Old Testament.
Of or pertaining to the church. See Ecclesiastical.
Of or pertaining to the church
Strong attachment to ecclesiastical usages, forms, etc.
The science or theory of church building and decoration.
A remedy which promotes discharges, as an emetic, or a cathartic.
The act of shedding, or casting off, an outer cuticular layer, as in the case of serpents, lobsters, etc.
A colorless, crystalline, nitrogenous base, obtained by the decomposition of cocaine.
A small chamber or place of protection for a sentinel, usually in the form of a projecting turret, or the like. See Castle.

An arrangement of a body of troops when its divisions are drawn up in parallel lines each to the right or the left of the one in advance of it, like the steps of a ladder in position for climbing. Also used adjectively
A monster, half maid and half serpent.
The clear, viscid fluid secreted by the poison glands of certain serpents

A parasite of man and of many domestic and wild animals, forming compound cysts or tumors (called hydatid cysts) in various organs, but especially in the liver and lungs, which often cause death. It is the larval stage of the Taenia echinococcus, a small tapeworm peculiar to the dog.
Relating or belonging to the echinoderms.
One of the grand divisions of the animal kingdom. By many writers it was formerly included in the Radiata.
Of or pertaining to the Echinoidea.

The class Echinodermata which includes the sea urchins. They have a calcareous, usually more or less spheroidal or disk-shaped, composed of many united plates, and covered with movable spines. See Spatangoid, Clypeastroid.
Set with small spines or prickles.
A division of Annelida which includes the genus Echiurus and allies. They are often classed among the Gephyrea, and called the armed Gephyreans.
A sound reflected from an opposing surface and repeated to the ear of a listener
One who, or that which, echoes.
A graduated scale for measuring the duration of sounds, and determining their different, and the relation of their intervals.
The art of measuring the duration of sounds or echoes.
An instrument for intensifying sounds produced by percussion of the thorax.
A kind of frosted cake, containing flavored cream.
The clearing up of anything which is obscure or not easily understood
A fancied perception of flashes of light, a symptom of epilepsy
Theory or practice of an eclectic.
A medicine made by mixing oils with sirups.

An interception or obscuration of the light of the sun, moon, or other luminous body, by the intervention of some other body, either between it and the eye, or between the luminous body and that illuminated by it. A lunar eclipse is caused by the moon passing through the earth's shadow

F is the sixth letter of the English alphabet, and a nonvocal consonant. Its form and sound are from the Latin. The Latin borrowed the form from the Greek digamma /, which probably had the value of English w consonant. The form and value of Greek letter came from the Phoenician, the ultimate source being probably Egyptian. Etymologically f is most closely related to p, k, v, and b
A syllable applied to the fourth tone of the diatonic scale in solmization.
Having the nature of a bean
One of the small sesamoid bones situated behind the condyles of the femur, in some mammals.
Of, pertaining to, or in the manner of, the Roman general, Quintus Fabius Maximus Verrucosus
A Feigned story or tale, intended to instruct or amuse
One of the metrical tales of the Trouveres, or early poets of the north of France.
To form into a whole by uniting its parts
The act of fabricating, framing, or constructing
Pertaining to a workman, or to work in stone, metal, wood etc.
One who invents or writes fables.
To invent, compose, or relate fables or fictions.
Feigned, as a story or fable
A species of counterpoint with a drone bass.
A large ornamental letter used, esp. by the early printers, at the commencement of the chapters and other divisions of a book.
The exterior form or appearance of anything
Witty or humorous writings or saying
Given to wit and good humor
The material of the outside or front side, as of a wall or building
Of or pertaining to the face
One who does anything, good or bad
The anterior part of the head
Easy to be done or performed: not difficult
To make easy or less difficult
The act of facilitating or making easy.
The quality of being easily performed
In a facing manner or position.
A copy of anything made, either so as to be deceptive or so as to give every part and detail of the original
One of the divisions or parties of charioteers (distinguished by their colors) in the games of the circus.
Made by art, in distinction from what is produced by nature
One who transacts business for another
The allowance given to a factor, as a compensation for his services
A factor who is a woman.
Of or pertaining to a factory.

Having the character of, or formed by, a filament.
A species of kangaroo (Macropus Brunii), inhabiting New Guinea.

Of or pertaining to a thread or line
A genus of slender, nematode worms of many species, parasitic in various animals. See Guinea worm.
The fruit of the Corylus Avellana or hazel. It is an oval nut, containing a kernel that has a mild, farinaceous, oily taste, agreeable to the palate.
To steal or take privily (commonly, that which is of little value)
Any plectognath fish of the genera Monacanthus, Alutera, balistes, and allied genera
One who works with a file.

To adopt as son or daughter

Pertaining to, or derived from, ferns

Shaped like a fern or like the parts of a fern leaf.
Fernlike, either in form or in the nature of the method of reproduction.
The relation of a son to a father
Having the shape of a thread or filament

Ornamental work, formerly with grains or breads, but now composed of fine wire and used chiefly in decorating gold and silver to which the wire is soldered, being arranged in designs frequently of a delicate and intricate arabesque pattern.
Suspended by, or strung upon, a thread
One of the thills or shafts of a carriage.
One who, or that which, fills
A little band, especially one intended to encircle the hair of the head.
To strike with the nail of the finger, first placed against the ball of the thumb, and forced from that position with a sudden spring
The rabbet on the outer edge of a sash bar to hold the glass and the putty.
Having the structure of a filoplume.
Any porous substance, as cloth, paper, sand, or charcoal, through which water or other liquid may passed to cleanse it from the solid or impure matter held in suspension
Defiled with filth, whether material or moral
The act or process of filtering
Light summer hemp, that bears no seed.
Having the edge or extremity bordered by filiform processes thicker than hairs
To carve or cut up, as a chub.
Liable or subject to a fine
Pertaining to the end or conclusion
The state of being final, finished, or complete
The income of a ruler or of a state
One charged with the administration of finance

Any whale of the genera Sibbaldius, Balaenoptera, and allied genera, of the family Balaenopteridae, characterized by a prominent fin on the back. The common finbacks of the New England coast are Sibbaldius tectirostris and S. tuberosus.
A small singing bird of many genera and species, belonging to the family Fringillidae.
Streaked or spotted on the back
To meet with, or light upon, accidentally

In a fine or finished manner.
The quality or condition of being fine.
Spun so as to be fine
Subtilty of contrivance to gain a point
To distill, as spirit from molasses or some saccharine preparation.
A South American bird (heliornis fulica) allied to the grebes. The name is also applied to several related species of the genus Podica.
One of the five terminating members of the hand
A prickly, climbing shrub of the genus Pisonia. The fruit is a kind of berry.
The knot or bunch of foliage, or foliated ornament, that forms the upper extremity of a pinnacle in Gothic architecture
To arrive at the end of
One who finishes, puts an end to, completes, or perfects
In a finite manner or degree.
A native or inhabitant of Finland.
Haddock cured in peat smoke, originally at Findon (pron. fin"an), Scotland. the name is also applied to other kinds of smoked haddock.
Of or pertaining to the Finns.
A variety of pigeon, with a crest somewhat resembling the mane of a horse.
Of or pertaining to Finland, to the Finns, or to their language.
Having, or abounding in, fins, as fishes
An umbelliferous plant (Foeniculum dulce) having a somewhat tuberous stem
Second best wool from Merino sheep.
3d pers. sing. pr. of Find, for findeth.
Having toes connected by a membrane
A narrow inlet of the sea, penetrating between high banks or rocks, as on the coasts of Norway and Alaska.
A species of creeping bent grass (Agrostis alba)
A variety of opal occuring in the cavities of volcanic tufa, in smooth and shining globular and botryoidal masses, having a pearly luster
Little flowers of ornament introduced into a melody by a singer or player.
The Spanish half real, or one sixteenth of a dollar, -- so called in Pennsylvania and the adjacent States.
A stopper, as in a wind instrument of music.

A genus (Abies) of coniferous trees, often of large size and elegant shape, some of them valued for their timber and others for their resin. The species are distinguished as the balsam fir, the silver fir, the red fir, etc.  The Scotch fir is a Pinus.
The evolution of light and heat in the combustion of bodies
A gun, pistol, or any weapon from a shot is discharged by the force of an explosive substance, as gunpowder.
One of several species of pheasants of the genus Euplocamus, having the lower back a bright, fiery red. They inhabit Southern Asia and the East Indies.
A ball filled with powder or other combustibles, intended to be thrown among enemies, and to injure by explosion
A very brilliantly luminous beetle (Pyrophorus noctilucus), one of the elaters, found in Central and South America
A chimney board or screen to close a fireplace when not in use.
An allowance of fuel. See Bote.
A small European kinglet (Regulus ignicapillus), having a bright red crest
A support for wood in a fireplace
A singular marine fish of the genus Pterois, family Scorpaenidae, of several species, inhabiting the Indo-Pacific region. They are usually red, and have very large spinose pectoral and dorsal fins.
A European sting ray of the genus Trygon (T. pastinaca)
Any luminous winged insect, esp. luminous beetles of the family Lampyridae.
An old form of gunlock, as the flintlock, which ignites the priming by a spark
A man whose business is to extinguish fires in towns
The part a chimney appropriated to the fire
The act or process of rendering anything incombustible
One who fires or sets fire to anything
A set of fire irons, including, commonly, tongs, shovel, and poker.
A place near the fire or hearth
Iron pyrites, formerly used for striking fire
An officer who has authority to direct in the extinguishing of fires, or to order what precautions shall be taken against fires
An American plant (Erechthites hiercifolia), very troublesome in spots where brushwood has been burned.

A device for producing a striking display of light, or a figure or figures in plain or colored fire, by the combustion of materials that burn in some peculiar manner, as gunpowder, sulphur, metallic filings, and various salts. The most common feature of fireworks is a paper or pasteboard tube filled with the combustible material. A number of these tubes or cases are often combined so as to make, when kindled, a great variety of figures in fire, often variously colored. The skyrocket is a common form of firework. The name is also given to various combustible preparations used in war.
The larva of a small tortricid moth which eats the leaves of the cranberry, so that the vines look as if burned
A varying measure of capacity, usually being the fourth part of a barrel
A dry measure formerly used in Scotland
In Turkey and some other Oriental countries, a decree or mandate issued by the sovereign
A chisel, thin in proportion to its width. It has a tang to enter the handle instead of a socket for receiving it.
The state or quality of being firm.
The principal rafters of a roof, especially a pair of rafters taken together.
Preceding all others of a series or kind
Obtained directly from the first or original source
Pertaining to the public treasury or revenue.
A yellow crystalline substance extracted from fustet, and regarded as its essential coloring principle
A counter, used in various games.
Bellying or swelling out on the under side
One whose occupation is to catch fish.
The business or practice of catching fish
A spear with barbed prongs used for harpooning fish.
The osprey (Pandion haliaetus), found both in Europe and America
The state or quality of being fishy or fishlike.
The skin of a fish (dog fish, shark, etc.)
A tackle or purchase used to raise the flukes of the anchor up to the gunwale. The block used is called the fish-block.
A process of reproduction intermediate between fission and gemmation.
Capable of being split, cleft, or divided in the direction of the grain, like wood, or along natural planes of cleavage, like crystals.
A group of Lacertilia having the tongue forked, including the common lizards.
A cleaving, splitting, or breaking up into parts.
Semipalmate and loboped, as a grebe's foot. See Illust. under Aves.
Reproducing by spontaneous fission. See Fission.
Having the toes separated to the base. [See Aves.]
A division of the Carnivora, including the dogs, cats, and bears, in which the feet are not webbed
Having the bill cleft beyond the horny part, as in the case of swallows and goatsuckers.
A group of birds having the bill deeply cleft.
Pertaining to a fissure or fissures
The act of dividing or opening
A narrow opening, made by the parting of any substance
A genus of marine gastropod mollusks, having a conical or limpetlike shell, with an opening at the apex
The hand with the fingers doubled into the palm
Pertaining to boxing, or to encounters with the fists
A cuff or blow with the fist or hand
An instrument used by the ancients in driving piles.
Hollow and cylindrical, like a pipe or reed.
A genus of fishes, having the head prolonged into a tube, with the mouth at the extremity.
Like or pertaining to the genus Fistularia.
To make hollow or become hollow like a fistula, or pipe.
Having the form or nature of a fistula
The European polecat (Putorius foetidus). See Polecat.
The state or quality of being fit
The state or quality of being fitted
One who fits or makes to fit
A plant (Eryngium foetidum) supposed to be a remedy for fits.
Having five leaflets, as the Virginia creeper.
A compound or twin crystal consisting of five individuals.
A kind of play with a ball against a wall, resembling tennis
Five-twenty bonds of the United States (bearing six per cent interest), issued in 1862, '64, and '65, redeemable after five and payable in twenty years.
The act of fixing, or the state of being fixed.
That which serves to set or fix colors or drawings, as a mordant.
In a fixed, stable, or constant manner.
The state or quality of being fixed
That which is fixed or attached to something as a permanent appendage
To make a hissing sound, as a burning fuse.
Quality or state of being flabby.
Yielding to the touch, and easily moved or shaken
The act of keeping fractured limbs cool by the use of a fan or some other contrivance.
Having the form of a fan
Having many nerves diverging radiately from the base
Yielding to pressure for want of firmness and stiffness
One of a fanatical sect which flourished in Europe in the 13th and 14th centuries, and maintained that flagellation was of equal virtue with baptism and the sacrament
An order of Infusoria, having one or two long, whiplike cilia, at the anterior end. It includes monads. See Infusoria, and Monad.
A young, flexible shoot of a plant
A small wooden pipe, having six or more holes, and a mouthpiece inserted at one end. It produces a shrill sound, softer than of the piccolo flute, and is said to have superseded the old recorder.
One who makes signals with a flag.
A vessel with a narrow mouth, used for holding and conveying liquors. It is generally larger than a bottle, and of leather or stoneware rather than of glass.
The vessel which carries the commanding officer of a fleet or squadron and flies his distinctive flag or pennant.
A staff on which a flag is hoisted.
A flat stone used in paving, or any rock which will split into such stones. See Flag, a stone.
A worm or grub found among flags and sedge.

An instrument for threshing or beating grain from the ear by hand, consisting of a wooden staff or handle, at the end of which a stouter and shorter pole or club, called a swipe, is so hung as to swing freely.
Consisting of flakes or of small, loose masses
A flaming torch, esp. one made by combining together a number of thick wicks invested with a quick-burning substance (anciently, perhaps, wax
Characterized by waving or flamelike curves, as in the tracery of windows, etc.
A name given in the East and West Indies to certain trees with brilliant blossoms, probably species of Caesalpinia.
A stream of burning vapor or gas, emitting light and heat

A priest devoted to the service of a particular god, from whom he received a distinguishing epithet. The most honored were those of Jupiter, Mars, and Quirinus, called respectively Flamen Dialis, Flamen Martialis, and Flamen Quirinalis.
Any bird of the genus Phoenicopterus. The flamingoes have webbed feet, very long legs, and a beak bent down as if broken. Their color is usually red or pink. The American flamingo is P. ruber
The act of setting in a flame or blaze.
Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, flame.
An external or internal rib, or rim, for strength, as the flange of an iron beam
The fleshy or muscular part of the side of an animal, between the ribs and the hip. See Illust. of Beef.
One who, or that which, flanks, as a skirmisher or a body of troops sent out upon the flanks of an army toguard a line of march, or a fort projecting so as to command the side of an assailing body.
A soft, nappy, woolen cloth, of loose texture.
Anything broad and limber that hangs loose, or that is attached by one side or end and is easily moved
A game in which the players catch raisins out burning brandy, and swallow them blazing.
A fklat cake turned on the griddle while cooking
One who, or that which, flaps.
To burn with an unsteady or waving flame
A sudden burst of anger or passion
To burst or break forth with a sudden and transient flood of flame and light
A board placed temporarily upon a milldam, to raise the water in the pond above its usual level
One who, or that which, flashes.
A small bottle-shaped vessel for holding fluids
A long, shallow basket, with two handles.
Having an even and horizontal surface, or nearly so, without prominences or depressions
Any bird of the genus Flatyrynchus. They belong to the family of flycatchers.
A boat with a flat bottom and square ends
Having an even lower surface or bottom
A kind of low-crowned cap formerly worn by all classes in England, and continued in London after disuse elsewhere
Any fish of the family Pleuronectidae
A foot in which the arch of the instep is flattened so that the entire sole of the foot rests upon the ground
Having a flat foot, with little or no arch of the instep.

Having a head with a flattened top
An iron with a flat, smooth surface for ironing clothes.
With the flat side, as of a sword
The quality or state of being flat.
To reduce to an even surface or one approaching evenness
One who, or that which, makes flat or flattens.
The act or practice of flattering
The state or quality of being flatulent.
Affected with flatus or gases generated in the alimentary canal

With the flat side downward, or next to another object
Any worm belonging to the Plathelminthes
A yellow, crystalline, organic dyestuff, C16H14N2, of artifical production. It is a strong base, and is a complex derivative of aniline and quinoline.
A yellow, vegetable dyestuff, resembling quercitron.

A yellow, crystalline substance, obtained from anthraquinone, and regarded as a hydroxyl derivative of it.
That quality of anything which affects the smell
A sort of flat custard or pie.
To scrape o/ pare, as a skin.

A plant of the genus Linum, esp. the L. usitatissimum, which has a single, slender stalk, about a foot and a half high, with blue flowers. The fiber of the bark is used for making thread and cloth, called linen, cambric, lawn, lace, etc. Linseed oil is expressed from the seed.

A plant in new Zealand (Phormium tenax), allied to the lilies and aloes. The leaves are two inches wide and several feet long, and furnish a fiber which is used for making ropes, mats, and coarse cloth.
One who strips off the skin.
One of various plants, supposed to have efficacy in driving away fleas. They belong, for the most part, to the genera Conyza, Erigeron, and Pulicaria.

A small beetle of the family Halticidae, of many species. They have strong posterior legs and leap like fleas. The turnip flea-beetle (Phyllotreta vittata) and that of the grapevine (Graptodera chalybea) are common injurious species.
The bite of a flea, or the red spot caused by the bite.
A light covering of reeds, over which the main covering is laid, in thatching houses.
A jumping plant louse of the family Psyllidae, of many species. That of the pear tree is Psylla pyri.
A sharp instrument used for opening veins, lancing gums, etc.
An herb used in medicine (Plantago Psyllium), named from the shape of its seeds.
A simple fieldwork, consisting of two faces forming a salient angle pointing outward and open at the gorge.
The act of bending, or state of being bent.
Capable of, or pertaining to, flection or inflection.
To run away, as from danger or evil
The entire coat of wood that covers a sheep or other similar animal
One who fleeces or strips unjustly, especially by trickery or fraund.
Covered with, made of, or resembling, a fleece.
A mixture of buttermilk and boiling whey
One who, or that which, banishes or expels.
A native or inhabitant of Flanders.
Pertaining to Flanders, or the Flemings.
To strip the blubber or skin from, as from a whale, seal, etc.
The aggregate of the muscles, fat, and other tissues which cover the framework of bones in man and other animals
The state or condition of having a form of flesh
Flesh-colored tights, worn by actors dancers.
Of or pertaining to the flesh
The act of fleshing, or the excitement attending a successful beginning.
A pot or vessel in which flesh is cooked
A quaking or trembling of the flesh
Full of, or composed of, flesh
One who fletches of feathers arrows
Finished at the ends with fleurs-de-lis
The pendulous or overhanging lateral parts of the upper lip of dogs, especially prominent in hounds
Having power to change the mind.
The state or quality of being flexible
Capable of being flexed or bent

A muscle which bends or flexes any part
Of, pertaining to, or resulting from, flexure
The act of flexing or bending
To whip lightly or with a quick jerk
A horizontal vane revolving over the surface of wort in a cooler, to produce a circular current in the liquor.
The state or quality of being flighty.
The distance to which an arrow or flight may be shot
The state or quality of being flimsy.
To withdraw from any suffering or undertaking, from pain or danger
To cast, send, to throw from the hand
One who kicks up the dust
A massive, somewhat impure variety of quartz, in color usually of a gray to brown or nearly black, breaking with a conchoidal fracture and sharp edge. It is very hard, and strikes fire with steel.

A soft, heavy, brilliant glass, consisting essentially of a silicate of lead and potassium. It is used for tableware, and for optical instruments, as prisms, its density giving a high degree of dispersive power
The state or quality of being flinty
A lock for a gun or pistol, having a flint fixed in the hammer, which on striking the steel ignites the priming.
A superior kind of earthenware into whose composition flint enters largely.
An Australian name for the very hard wood of the Eucalyptus piluralis.
Consisting of, composed of, abounding in, or resembling, flint
A mixture of beer, spirit, etc., stirred and heated by a hot iron.
To turn inside out, or with the leg part back over the foot, as a stocking in pulling off or for putting on.
The repeated stroke of something long and loose.
The state or quality of being flippant.
Of smooth, fluent, and rapid speech
State or quality of being flippant.
A broad flat limb used for swimming, as those of seals, sea turtles, whales, etc.
To throw with a jerk or quick effort
To move with celerity through the air
The side of a hog salted and cured
A term applied to the bark obtained from young oak trees.
Anything which floats or rests on the surface of a fluid, as to sustain weight, or to indicate the height of the surface, or mark the place of, something.
A small cartridge designed for target shooting
A delirious picking of bedclothes by a sick person, as if to pick off flocks of wool
Spotted with small tufts like wool.
Of or pertaining to the flocculus.
The process by which small particles of fine soils and sediments aggregate into larger lumps.
Clothed with small flocks or flakes
A small lobe in the under surface of the cerebellum, near the middle peduncle
The tuft of hair terminating the tail of mammals.
A company or collection of living creatures
A low, flat mass of floating ice.
To beat or strike with a rod or whip
The bottom or lower part of any room
Anything that floors or upsets a person, as a blow that knocks him down
The upper extermities of the floor of a vessel.
One who walks about in a large retail store as an overseer and director.
To clap or strike, as a bird its wings, a fish its tail, etc.
Having a tendency to flop or flap
The goddess of flowers and spring.
Pertaining to Flora, or to flowers
Tin ore scarcely perceptible in the stone
The eight month of the French republican calendar. It began April 20, and ended May 19. See Vendemiare.
An ancient gold coin of the time of Edward III., of six shillings sterling value.
Belonging or relating to Florence, in Italy.
Having the head adorned with flowers.
Pertaining to the cultivation of flowering plants.
One skilled in the cultivation of flowers
The large, roundish, flattened seed of Mucuna urens. See under Bean.
A subclass of algae including all the red or purplish seaweeds
The act, process, or time of flowering
Having the form of a flower
An Indian bustard (Otis aurita). The Bengal floriken is Sypheotides Bengalensis.

A silver coin of Florence, first struck in the twelfth century, and noted for its beauty. The name is given to different coins in different countries. The florin of England, first minted in 1849, is worth two shillings, or about 48 cents
A cultivator of, or dealer in, flowers.
One of a group of stalked rotifers, having ciliated tentacles around the lobed disk.
A variety of aragonite, occuring in delicate white coralloidal forms
A hopper-shaped box or /nortar in which ore is placed for the action of the stamps.
The slender styles of the pistillate flowers of maize
Pertaining to, made of, or resembling, floss
Represented as flying or streaming in the air
The act, process, or state of floating.
A little fleet, or a fleet of small vessels.
Goods lost by shipwreck, and floating on the sea
To throw the limbs and body one way and the other
A flatfish of the family Pleuronectidae, of many species.
The finely ground meal of wheat, or of any other grain
imp. sing. of Fly, v. i.
imp. pl. of Fly, v. i.
In the popular sense, the bloom or blossom of a plant
A genus of perennial herbs (Iris) with swordlike leaves and large three-petaled flowers often of very gay colors, but probably white in the plant first chosen for the royal French emblem.
A plant which flowers or blossoms.
A tropical leguminous bush (Poinciana, / Caesalpinia, pulcherrima) with prickly branches, and showy yellow or red flowers
A vessel, commonly or earthenware, for earth in which plants are grown.
A hydrocarbon extracted from gutta-percha, as a yellow, resinous substance
Soft clayey matter in the vein, or surrounding it.
The capacity or ability to fluctuate.
A motion like that of waves
An inclosed passage way for establishing and directing a current of air, gases, etc.
A general name for organ stops in which the sound is caused by wind passing through a flue or fissure and striking an edge above
Pertaining to, or resembling, fluff or nap
A grand piano or a harpsichord, both being wing-shaped.
Having particles which easily move and change their relative position without a separation of the mass, and which easily yield to pressure
Pertaining to a fluid, or to its flowing motion.
The quality of being fluid or capable of flowing
Formed like, or having, a fluke.
A light kind of food, formerly made of flour or meal
To fail, as on a lesson
A contemptuous name for a liveried servant or a footman.
The place or region of flunkies.
The quality or characteristics of a flunky
A combining form indicating fluorine as an ingredient
Pertaining to, derived from, or consisting of, fluorine and boron.
A fluoride of cerium, occuring near Fahlun in Sweden. Tynosite, from Colorado, is probably the same mineral.
A double salt of fluoric and phosphoric acids.
A white crystalline hydrocarbon C/H/, of a complex structure, found as one ingrdient of the higher boiling portion of coal tar.
A colorless, crystalline hydrocarbon, C13H10 having a beautiful violet fluorescence
A yellowish red, crystalline substance, C20H12O5, produced by heating together phthalic anhydride and resorcin

That property which some transparent bodies have of producing at their surface, or within their substance, light different in color from the mass of the material, as when green crystals of fluor spar afford blue reflections. It is due not to the difference in the color of a distinct surface layer, but to the power which the substance has of modifying the light incident upon it. The light emitted by fluorescent substances is in general of lower refrangibility than the incident light.
A colorless, amorphous substance which is produced by the reduction of fluorescein, and from which the latter may be formed by oxidation.
Pertaining to, obtained from, or containing, fluorine.
A binary compound of fluorine with another element or radical.

A non-metallic, gaseous element, strongly acid or negative, or associated with chlorine, bromine, and iodine, in the halogen group of which it is the first member. It always occurs combined, is very active chemically, and possesses such an avidity for most elements, and silicon especially, that it can neither be prepared nor kept in glass vessels. If set free it immediately attacks the containing material, so that it was not isolated until 1886. It is a pungent, corrosive, colorless gas. Symbol F. Atomic weight 19.
Calcium fluoride, a mineral of many different colors, white, yellow, purple, green, red, etc., often very beautiful, crystallizing commonly in cubes with perfect octahedral cleavage
An instrument for observing or exhibiting fluorescence.
A double fluoride of silicon and some other (usually basic) element or radical, regarded as a salt of fluosilicic acid
Composed of, or derived from, silicon and fluorine.
A sudden and brief blast or gust
A workman employed in cleaning sewers by flushing them with water.
To make hot and rosy, as with drinking
The act of flustering, or the state of being flustered

A musical wind instrument, consisting of a hollow cylinder or pipe, with holes along its length, stopped by the fingers or by keys which are opened by the fingers. The modern flute is closed at the upper end, and blown with the mouth at a lateral hole.
A beak flute, an older form of the flute, played with a mouthpiece resembling a beak, and held like a flageolet.
A fish of the genus Aulostoma, having a much elongated tubular snout.
One who plays on the flute
One who, or that which, flutters.
Soft and clear in tone, like a flute.
One who exlpains geological phenomena by the action of streams.
Formed by the joint action of a river and the sea, as deposits at the mouths of rivers.
Capable of being melted or fused, as a mineral.
Pertaining to, or having the nature of, fluxion or fluxions
To move in or pass thorugh the air with wings, as a bird.
A kind of catchfly of the genus Silene
Marked by, or as if by, the bite of flies.
To deposit eggs upon, as a flesh fly does on meat
The covering of an insect, esp. the elytra of beetles.
One of numerous species of birds that feed upon insects, which they take on the wing.
Having the habit of catching insects on the wing.
A California scorpaenoid fish (Sebastichthys rhodochloris), having brilliant colors.
To angle, using flies for bait.

A fish which is able to leap from the water, and fly a considerable distance by means of its large and long pectoral fins. These fishes belong to several species of the genus Exocoetus, and are found in the warmer parts of all the oceans.
One of a group of squirrels, of the genera Pteromus and Sciuropterus, having parachute-like folds of skin extending from the fore to the hind legs, which enable them to make very long leaps.
The driver of a fly, or light public carriage.
A name given to the series of sandstones and schists overlying the true nummulitic formation in the Alps, and included in the Eocene Tertiary.
A speck or stain made by the excrement of a fly
The young of any animal of the Horse family (Equidae)
The white substance, consisting of an aggregation of bubbles, which is formed on the surface of liquids, or in the mouth of an animal, by violent agitation or fermentation
A little pocket for a watch.
The act of focalizing or bringing to a focus, or the state of being focalized.
An assisting instrument for focusing an object in or before a camera.
A point in which the rays of light meet, after being reflected or refrcted, and at which the image is formed
A weight by which lead and some other metals were formerly sold, in England, varying from 19/ to 24 cwt.
Fitted for, or pertaining to, digging.
A group of African edentates including the aard-vark.
One who entertains personal enmity, hatred, grudge, or malice, against another
The Cornish name for a forge used for smelting tin.
Filled or abounding with fog, or watery exhalations
The principles and conduct of a fogy.

One who, or that which, folds
Belonging to, or having the texture or nature of, a leaf

Consisting of, or pertaining to, leaves

Originally, a vessel of the Mediterranean propelled by sails and by oars. The French, about 1650, transferred the name to larger vessels, and by 1750 it had been appropriated for a class of war vessels intermediate between corvettes and ships of the line. Frigates, from about 1750 to 1850, had one full battery deck and, often, a spar deck with a lighter battery. They carried sometimes as many as fifty guns. After the application of steam to navigation steam frigates of largely increased size and power were built, and formed the main part of the navies of the world till about 1870, when the introduction of ironclads superseded them.

An oily liquid, resembling, and possibly identical with, furfurol, and obtained from fucus, and other seaweeds.
The tail of a hare, coney, etc.
A tool for ornamenting the edge of a sole.
Of or pertaining to Terra del Fuego.
Any matter used to produce heat by burning
One who, or that which, supplies fuel.
in the gugue style, but not strictly like a fugue.
Fleeing from pursuit, danger, restraint, etc., escaping, from service, duty etc.
The quality or condition of being fugitive
A soldier especially expert and well drilled, who takes his place in front of a military company, as a guide for the others in their exercises

A polyphonic composition, developed from a given theme or themes, according to strict contrapuntal rules. The theme is first given out by one voice or part, and then, while that pursues its way, it is repeated by another at the interval of a fifth or fourth, and so on, until all the parts have answered one by one, continuing their several melodies and interweaving them in one complex progressive whole, in which the theme is often lost and reappears.
A musician who composes or performs fugues.
A suffix signifying full of, abounding with
A spectro-electric tube in which the decomposition of a liquid by the passage of an electric spark is observed.
A vitrified sand tube produced by the striking of lightning on sand
The condition or quality of being fuliginous
Filled up, having within its limits all that it can contain
The money or price paid for fulling or cleansing cloth.
Having a full supply of blood.
Full and large at the bottom, as wigs worn by certain civil officers in Great Britain.
One whose occupation is to full cloth.
The place or the works where the fulling of cloth is carried on.
Having reached the limits of growth
Completely furnished wiith men, as a ship.
The state of being full, or of abounding
Pertaining to a fuller of cloth.
Having the orb or disk complete or fully illuminated
Having large and strong or complete wings.
In a full manner or degree

One of several species of sea birds, of the family procellariidae, allied to the albatrosses and petrels. Among the well-known species are the arctic fulmar (Fulmarus glacialis) (called also fulmar petrel, malduck, and mollemock), and the giant fulmar (Ossifraga gigantea).
The act of fulminating or exploding
Pertaining to fulminic and cyanuric acids, and designating an acid so called.
A salted and smoked fish, as the pilchard.
Pertaining to, or derived from, fumitory (Fumaria officinalis).
An alkaloid extracted from fumitory, as a white crystalline substance.
A hole or spot in a volcanic or other region, from which fumes issue.
In the manner of one who fumbles.
The stench or high flavor of game or other meat when kept long.
One who, or that which, drives away smoke or fumes.
To subject to the action of smoke.
The act of fumigating, or applying smoke or vapor, as for disinfection.
One who, or that which, fumigates
Having the quality of purifying by smoke.

The common uame of several species of the genus Fumaria, annual herbs of the Old World, with finely dissected leaves and small flowers in dense racemes or spikes. F. officinalis is a common species, and was formerly used as an antiscorbutic.
To walk or to dance on a rope.
The act of executing or performing any duty, office, or calling
To execute or perform a function
Pertaining to, or connected with, a function or duty
To assign to some function or office.
One charged with the performance of a function or office

Of or pertaining to the Fungidae, a family of stony corals.
Things which may be furnished or restored in kind, as distinguished from specific things
Pertaining to, or obtained from, mushrooms
Shaped like a fungus or mushroom.
A name formerly given to cellulose found in certain fungi and mushrooms.
The quality of that which is fungous
Any one of the Fungi, a large and very complex group of thallophytes of low organization, -- the molds, mildews, rusts, smuts, mushrooms, toadstools, puff balls, and the allies of each.
A small cord, ligature, or fiber.
Consisting of a small cord or fiber.
A cord, baud, or bundle of fibers
Resembling a cord in toughness and flexibility, as the roots of some endogenous trees.
Pertaining to, or characterized by, great fear, or funking.
A vessel of the shape of an inverted hollow cone, terminating below in a pipe, and used for conveying liquids into a close vessel
Having the form of a funnel, or tunnel
The short, fine, soft hair of certain animals, growing thick on the skin, and distinguished from the hair, which is longer and coarser.
A plaited or gathered flounce on a woman's garment.
To rub or scour to brightness
The wishbone or merrythought of birds, formed by the united clavicles.
To draw up into a bundle
A colorless, oily substance, C4H4O, obtained by distilling certain organic substances, as pine wood, salts of pyromucic acid, etc.
Falling of scurf from the head
A white, crystalline base, obtained indirectly from furfurol.
A colorless oily liquid, C4H3O.CHO, of a pleasant odor, obtained by the distillation of bran, sugar, etc., and regarded as an aldehyde derivative of furfuran
A yellow, crystalline substance, (C4H3O)2.C2O2, obtained by the oxidation of furoin.
Pertaining to, or derived from, furile
To draw up or gather into close compass
An inclosed place in which heat is produced by the combustion of fuel, as for reducing ores or melting metals, for warming a house, for baking pottery, etc.
To supply with anything necessary, useful, or appropriate
One who supplies or fits out.
The act of furnishing, or of supplying furniture
That with which anything is furnished or supplied
A colorless, crystalline substance, C10H8O4, from furfurol.
A trench in the earth made by, or as by, a plow.
The act of furthering or helping forward
One who furthers. or helps to advance
Tending to further, advance, or promote
A superficial, inflammatory tumor, suppurating with a central core
Of or pertaining to a furuncle
A thorny evergreen shrub (Ulex Europaeus), with beautiful yellow flowers, very common upon the plains and hills of Great Britain
bounding in, or overgrown with, furze
Fine charcoal of willow wood, used as a drawing implement.
A molding generally placed under the echinus or quarter round of capitals in the Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian orders of architecture.
A brown, nitrogenous pigment contained in the retinal epithelium
A dark-colored substance obtained from empyreumatic animal oil.

A hot, acrid, oily liquid, accompanying many alcoholic liquors (as potato whisky, corn whisky, etc.), as an undesirable ingredient, and consisting of several of the higher alcohols and compound ethers, but particularly of amyl alcohol
CapabIe of being melted or liquefied.
Capable of being melted or rendered fluid by heat
Formerly, a soldier armed with a fusil. Hence, in the plural:
The act or operation of melting or rendering fluid by heat
The wood of the Rhus Cptinus or Venice sumach, a shrub of Southern Europe, which yields a fine orange color, which, however, is not durable without a mordant.
A kind of coarse twilled cotton or cotton and linen stuff, including corduroy, velveteen, etc.
The wood of the Maclura tinctoria, a tree growing in the West Indies, used in dyeing yellow
A punishment by beating with a stick or club
The jaws between which the hinder end of a carriage tongue is inserted.
One of the crooked timbers which are scarfed together to form the lower part of the compound rib of a vessel
That is to be or come hereafter
Without prospect of betterment in the future.

Relating to what is to come
State of being that is yet to come
A tube, filled with combustible matter, for exploding a shell, etc. See Fuse, n.
A suffix signifying to make, to form into, etc.
A word which expresses blame, dislike, disapprobation, abhorrence, or contempt. See Fie.
A long bag net distended by hoops, into which fish can pass easily, without being able to return
A rebated cross, formerly used as a secret emblem, and a common ornament. It is also called gammadion, and swastika.
The military force of the whole nation, consisting of all men able to bear arms.
G is the seventh letter of the English alphabet, and a vocal consonant. It has two sounds
The hook on the end of an eccentric rod opposite the strap. See. Illust. of Eccentric.
A kind of coarse cloth for packing goods.
A coarse frock or loose upper garment formerly worn by Jews
To talk fast, or to talk without meaning

A name originally given by the Italians to a kind of serpentine, later to the rock called euphotide, and now generally used for a coarsely crystalline, igneous rock consisting of lamellar pyroxene (diallage) and labradorite, with sometimes chrysolite (olivine gabbro).
A rent, service, tribute, custom, tax, impost, or duty
A collector of gabels or taxes.
A lighter, or vessel for inland navigation.
A hollow cylinder of wickerwork, like a basket without a bottom. Gabions are made of various sizes, and filled with earth in building fieldworks to shelter men from an enemy's fire.
A traverse made with gabions between guns or on their flanks, protecting them from enfilading fire.
The part of a fortification built of gabions.
A small gable, or gable-shaped canopy, formed over a tabernacle, niche, etc.
A false spur or gaff, fitted on the heel of a gamecock.
The point of a spear, or an arrowhead.
One who roves about idly, a rambling gossip.
A small British fish (Motella argenteola) of the Cod family.
Any dipterous insect of the genus Oestrus, and allied genera of botflies.
Of or pertaining to that division of the Celtic languages, which includes the Irish, Gaelic, and Manx.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the cod (Gadus)
Of or relating to Cadiz, in Spain.
Of or pertaining to the family of fishes (Gadidae) which includes the cod, haddock, and hake.
A rare earth, regarded by some as an oxide of the supposed element gadolinium, by others as only a mixture of the oxides of yttrium, erbium, ytterbium, etc.
A mineral of a nearly black color and vitreous luster, and consisting principally of the silicates of yttrium, cerium, and iron.
A supposed rare metallic element, with a characteristic spectrum, found associated with yttrium and other rare metals. Its individuality and properties have not yet been determined.
One who uses a gad or goad in driving.
A yellow or brown amorphous substance, of indifferent nature, found in cod-liver oil.
A large duck (Anas strepera), valued as a game bird, found in the northern parts of Europe and America
A Celt or the Celts of the Scotch Highlands or of Ireland
Of or pertaining to the Gael, esp. to the Celtic Highlanders of Scotland
A barbed spear or a hook with a handle, used by fishermen in securing heavy fish.
