A small triangular sail having its foot extended upon the gaff and its luff upon the topmast.
To stop the mouth of, by thrusting sometimes in, so as to hinder speaking
To make a noise like a goose
A lively French and Italian dance.
A square or beveled notch cut out of a girder, binding joist, or other timber which supports a floor beam, so as to receive the end of the floor beam.
Capable of being obtained or reached.
The horses, oxen, plows, wains or wagons and implements for carrying on tillage.
One who gainsays, contradicts, or denies.
A covering of cloth or leather for the ankle and instep, or for the whole leg from the knee to the instep, fitting down upon the shoe.
An agent exciting secretion of milk.
An amorphous, gelatinous substance containing nitrogen, found in milk and other animal fluids. It resembles peptone, and is variously regarded as a coagulating or emulsifying agent.
An instrument for ascertaining the quality of milk (i.e., its richness in cream) by determining its specific gravity
One who eats, or subsists on, milk.

A white, crystalline sugar, C6H12O6, isomeric with dextrose, obtained by the decomposition of milk sugar, and also from certain gums. When oxidized it forms mucic acid. Called also lactose (though it is not lactose proper).
A genus of African lemurs, including numerous species.
The pungent aromatic rhizome or tuber of certain East Indian or Chinese species of Alpinia (A. Galanga and A. officinarum) and of the Kaempferia Galanga), -- all of the Ginger family.
A dish of veal, chickens, or other white meat, freed from bones, tied up, boiled, and served cold.
The West Indian Sciadophyllum Brownei, a tree with very large digitate leaves.
Of or pertaining to Galatia or its inhabitants. -- A native or inhabitant of Galatia, in Asia Minor

A gum resin exuding from the stems of certain Asiatic umbelliferous plants, mostly species of Ferula. The Bubon Galbanum of South Africa furnishes an inferior kind of galbanum. It has an acrid, bitter taste, a strong, unpleasant smell, and is used for medical purposes, also in the arts, as in the manufacture of varnish.
The upper lip or helmet-shaped part of a labiate flower.
That division of elasmobranch fishes which includes the sharks.
A remedy or antidose for poison
A genus of flying Insectivora, formerly called flying lemurs. See Colugo.
Covered as with a hat or cap.
A cretaceous fossil sea urchin of the genus Galerites.
Of or pertaining to Galicia, in Spain, or to Galicia, the kingdom of Austrian Poland.

A porch or waiting room, usually at the west end of an abbey church, where the monks collected on returning from processions, where bodies were laid previous to interment, and where women were allowed to see the monks to whom they were related, or to hear divine service. Also, frequently applied to the porch of a church, as at Ely and Durham cathedrals.
A plant of the Sedge family (Cyperus longus) having aromatic roots
A small galley, formerly used in the Mediterranean, built mainly for speed. It was moved both by sails and oars, having one mast, and sixteen or twenty seats for rowers.
An impure resin of turpentine, hardened on the outside of pine trees by the spontaneous evaporation of its essential oil. When purified, it is called yellow pitch, white pitch, or Burgundy pitch.
The bitter, alkaline, viscid fluid found in the gall bladder, beneath the liver. It consists of the secretion of the liver, or bile, mixed with that of the mucous membrane of the gall bladder.
In a polite or courtly manner
The tread, treadle, or chalasa of an egg.
A large galley, having some features of the galleon, as broadside guns
A native or inhabitant of Galicia, in Spain
A red crystalline dyestuff, obtained by heating together pyrogallic and phthalic acids.
A sailing vessel of the 15th and following centuries, often having three or four decks, and used for war or commerce. The term is often rather indiscriminately applied to any large sailing vessel.
A long and narrow corridor, or place for walking
A little tile of glazed earthenware.
A vessel propelled by oars, whether having masts and sails or not
A chilognath myriapod of the genus Iulus, and allied genera, having numerous short legs along the sides
An insect that deposits its eggs in plants, and occasions galls, esp. any small hymenopteran of the genus Cynips and allied genera. See Illust. of Gall.
Consisting of two iambic dimeters catalectic, the last of which lacks the final syllable
Of or pertaining to Gaul or France

The principles, tendencies, or action of those, within the Roman Catholic Church in France, who (esp. in 1682) sought to restrict the papal authority in that country and increase the power of the national church.
A mode of speech peculiar to the French
To conform to the French mode or idiom.
Like the Gallinae (or Galliformes) in structure.
Senseless talk. [Obs. or R.] See Galimatias.
A hash of various kinds of meats, a ragout.
A substance obtained by the reduction of gallein.
One of the Gallinae or gallinaceous birds.
Resembling the domestic fowls and pheasants
An order of birds, including the common domestic fowls, pheasants, grouse, quails, and allied forms

One of several wading birds, having long, webless toes, and a frontal shield, belonging to the family Rallidae. They are remarkable for running rapidly over marshes and on floating plants. The purple gallinule of America is Ionornis Martinica, that of the Old World is Porphyrio porphyrio. The common European gallinule (Gallinula chloropus) is also called moor hen, water hen, water rail, moor coot, night bird, and erroneously dabchick. Closely related to it is the Florida gallinule (Gallinula galeata).
An inferior kind of olive oil, brought from Gallipoli, in Italy.
A glazed earthen pot or vessel, used by druggists and apothecaries for containing medicines, etc.
A rare metallic element, found in certain zinc ores. It is white, hard, and malleable, resembling aluminium, and remarcable for its low melting point (86/ F., 30/C). Symbol Ga. Atomic weight 69.9.
A small armed vessel, with sails and oars, -- used on the Malabar coast.
A West Indian lizard (Celestus occiduus), about a foot long, imagined by the natives to be venomous.
A round gall produced on the leaves and shoots of various species of the oak tree. See Gall, and Nutgall.
An excessive admiration of what is French.
A measure of capacity, containing four quarts
A narrow tapelike fabric used for binding hats, shoes, etc., -- sometimes made ornamental.
To move or run in the mode called a gallop
I horsemanship, a sidelong or curveting kind of gallop.
One who, or that which, gallops.
An under servant for the kitchen
Pertaining to the tannin or nutgalls.
To fright or terrify. See Gally, v. t.
A small horse of a breed raised at Galloway, Scotland
A heavy-armed foot soldier from Ireland and the Western Isles in the time of Edward /
A concretion, or calculus, formed in the gall bladder or biliary passages. See Calculus, n., 1.
A noisy, swaggering, or worthless fellow
A kind of lively dance, in 2-4 time

The act of process of galvanizing.
One who, or that which, galvanize.

Of, pertaining to, or measured by, a galvanometer.
The art or process of measuring the force of electric currents.

The art or process of electrotypy.
An instrument or apparatus for detecting the presence of electrical currents, especially such as are of feeble intensity.
Of or pertaining to a galvanoscope.
The use of galvanism in physiological experiments.
The tendency of a root to place its axis in the line of a galvanic current.
A species of grass (Tripsacum dactyloides) tall, stout, and exceedingly productive
Any bird of the genuis Totanus. See Tattler.

The inspissated juice of a plant (Uncaria Gambir) growing in Malacca. It is a powerful astringent, and, under the name of Terra Japonica, is used for chewing with the Areca nut, and is exported for tanning and dyeing.
A defensive garment formerly in use for the body, made of cloth stuffed and quilted.
A performer upon the viola di gamba. See under Viola.
A mode of opening the game, in which a pawn is sacrificed to gain an attacking position.
To play or game for money or other stake.

A concrete juice, or gum resin, produced by several species of trees in Siam, Ceylon, and Malabar. It is brought in masses, or cylindrical rolls, from Cambodia, or Cambogia, -- whence its name. The best kind is of a dense, compact texture, and of a beatiful reddish yellow. Taking internally, it is a strong and harsh cathartic and emetic.
Pertaining to, resembling, or containing, gamboge.
A skipping or leaping about in frolic
The hind leg of a horse.
A kind of twilled linen cloth for lining.
A handsome breed of the common fowl, remarkable for the great courage and pugnacity of the males.
One who has the care of game, especially in a park or preserve.
Pertaining to, or resulting from, sexual connection
A neglected and untrained city boy
The third letter (/, / = Eng. G) of the Greek alphabet.
A cross formed of four capital gammas, formerly used as a mysterious ornament on ecclesiastical vestments, etc. See Fylfot.
The buttock or thigh of a hog, salted and smoked or dried
The production of offspring by the union of parents of different sexes
That stage of growth or development in an organism, in which the reproductive elements are generated and matured in preparation for propagating the species.
Having the petals united or joined so as to form a tube or cup
Composed of leaves united by their edges (coalescent).
Having the flavor of game, esp. of game kept uncooked till near the condition of tainting
To drop from a high place upon sharp stakes or hooks, as the Turks dropped malefactors, by way of punishment.
The male of any species of goose.
The Hindoo god of wisdom or prudence.
One who oversees a gang of workmen.
Pertaining to, or inhabiting, the Ganges
The common English milkwort (Polygala vulgaris), so called from blossoming in gang week.
A short line attached to a trawl. See Trawl, n.
Having the form of a ganglion.

Pertaining to, containing, or consisting of, ganglia or ganglion cells

A kind of wild goose, by a flock of which a virtuoso was fabled to be carried to the lunar world.
A place of confinement, especially for minor offenses or provisional imprisonment
The keeper of a jail. See Jailer.
An opening in anything made by breaking or parting
The parasitic worm that causes the gapes in birds. See Illustration in Appendix.
One who is an object of open-mouthed wonder.
Any slender marine fish of the genera Belone and Tylosurus. See Garfish.
An extract of madder by sulphuric acid. It consists essentially of alizarin.
Offal, as the bowels of an animal or fish
To sift or bolt, to separate the fine or valuable parts of from the coarse and useless parts, or from dros or dirt
One of the planks next the keel on the outside, which form a garboard strake.
A genus of plants, including the mangosteen tree (Garcinia Mangostana), found in the islands of the Indian Archipelago

Coarse wool on the legs of sheep.
Characteristic of Gargantua, a gigantic, wonderful personage
A distemper in geese, affecting the head.
A water cooler or jug with a handle and spout
A spout projecting from the roof gutter of a building, often carved grotesquely.

A plant of the genus Allium (A. sativum is the cultivated variety), having a bulbous root, a very strong smell, and an acrid, pungent taste. Each root is composed of several lesser bulbs, called cloves of garlic, inclosed in a common membranous coat, and easily separable.
Any article of clothing, as a coat, a gown, etc.

A mineral having many varieties differing in color and in their constituents, but with the same crystallization (isometric), and conforming to the same general chemical formula. The commonest color is red, the luster is vitreous, and the hardness greater than that of quartz. The dodecahedron and trapezohedron are the common forms.
An amorphous mineral of apple-green color
One who, or that which, garnishes.
A small fishing vessel met with in the Persian Gulf.
One who lives in a garret
Small splinters of stone inserted into the joints of coarse masonry.
A body of troops stationed in a fort or fortified town.
A stick or small wooden cylinder used for tightening a bandage, in order to compress the arteries of a limb.

One who seizes a person by the throat from behind, with a view to strangle and rob him.
Talking much, especially about commonplace or trivial things
One of several species of California market fishes, of the genus Sebastichthys
A band used to prevent a stocking from slipping down on the leg.
A sauce made of small fish. It was prized by the ancients.
A chandelier arranged to burn gas.
The jet piece of a gas fixture where the gas is burned as it escapes from one or more minute orifices.
Of or pertaining to Gascony, in France, or to the Gascons
In the form, or of the nature, of gas, or of an aeriform fluid.
To make a gash, or long, deep incision in
The act or process of converting into gas.
To convert into gas, or an aeriform fluid, as by the application of heat, or by chemical processes.
A line or band used to lash a furled sail securely. Sea gaskets are common lines
The light yielded by the combustion of illuminating gas.
An apparatus for the generation of gases, or for impregnating a liquid with a gas, or a gas with a volatile liquid.

A highly volatile mixture of fluid hydrocarbons, obtained from petroleum, as also by the distillation of bituminous coal. It is used in making air gas, and in giving illuminating power to water gas. See Carburetor.
An apparatus for holding and measuring of gas
Of or pertaining to the measurement of gases
The art or practice of measuring gases
An apparatus for detecting the presence of any dangerous gas, from a gas leak in a coal mine or a dwelling house.
To open the mouth wide in catching the breath, or in laborious respiration
Relating to Casserio (L. Gasserius), the discover of the Gasserian ganglion.
The process of passing cotton goods between two rollers and exposing them to numerous minute jets of gas to burn off the small fibers
An order of fungi, in which the spores are borne inside a sac called the peridium, as in the puffballs.
So tightly fitted as to preclude the escape of gas
A genus of large eocene birds from the Paris basin.
Pain in the stomach or epigastrium, as in gastric disorders.
Of, pertaining to, or situated near, the stomach
One who appears to speak from his stomach
A voice or utterance which appears to proceed from the stomach
Inflammation of the stomach, esp. of its mucuos membrane.
A combining form from the Gr. /, /, the stomach, or belly
The muscle which makes the greater part of the calf of the leg.
Pertaining to both the stomach and the colon
That part of blastoderm where the hypoblast appears like a small disk on the inner face of the epibladst.
Pertaining to the stomach and duodenum
Inflammation of the stomach and duodenum. It is one of the most frequent causes of jaundice.

The operation of cutting into the upper part of the vagina, through the abdomen (without opening the peritoneum), for the purpose of removing a fetus. It is a substitute for the Caesarean operation, and less dangerous.
Inflammation of the lining membrane of the stomach and the intestines.
Of or pertaining to the stomach and omentum.
Pertaining to the stomach and liver
Of or pertaining to the stomach and intestines
The science which treats of the structure and functions of the stomach
A softening of the coats of the stomach
A kind of divination, by means of words seemingly uttered from the stomach.
The fungoid growths sometimes found in the stomach
One whose voice appears to proceed from the stomach
The art or science of good eating
Pertaining to the stomach and diaphragm
Pertaining to the alimentary canal and air passages, and to the cavities connected with them

One of the classes of Mollusca, of great extent. It includes most of the marine spiral shells, and the land and fresh-water snails. They generally creep by means of a flat, muscular disk, or foot, on the ventral side of the body. The head usually bears one or two pairs of tentacles. See Mollusca.
Of or pertaining to the Gastropoda.
The operation of sewing up wounds of the abdomen.
An instrument for viewing or examining the interior of the stomach.
Examination of the abdomen or stomach, as with the gastroscope.
Pertaining to the stomach and spleen
One of the large scales on the belly of a serpent.
The operation of making a permanent opening into the stomach, for the introduction of food.
A cutting into, or opening of, the abdomen or the stomach.
A group of small wormlike animals, having cilia on the ventral side. The group is regarded as an ancestral or synthetic one, related to rotifers and annelids.
A form of annelid larva having cilia on the ventral side.
Having the structure, or performing the functions, both of digestive and circulatory organs

An embryonic form having its origin in the invagination or pushing in of the wall of the planula or blastula (the blastosphere) on one side, thus giving rise to a double-walled sac, with one opening or mouth (the blastopore) which leads into the cavity (the archenteron) lined by the inner wall (the hypoblast). See Illust. under Invagination. In a more general sense, an ideal stage in embryonic development. See Gastraea.
The process of invagination, in embryonic development, by which a gastrula is formed.
A large door or passageway in the wall of a city, of an inclosed field or place, or of a grand edifice, etc.
A house connected or associated with a gate.
A post to which a gate is hung
A passage through a fence or wall
In the manner of a gate.
Capable of being gathered or collected
An American machine gun, consisting of a cluster of barrels which, being revolved by a crank, are automatically loaded and fired.
A name given to the small trees called guelder-rose (Viburnum Opulus), cornel (Cornus sanguinea), and spindle tree (Euonymus Europaeus).
One of the native inhabitants of the pampas, of Spanish-American descent. They live mostly by rearing cattle.
A mode of plaiting or fluting.
A gopher, esp. the pocket gopher.
To measure or determine with a gauge.
See Gauge rod, under Gauge, n.
The Anglicized form of Gallia, which in the time of the Romans included France and Upper Italy (Transalpine and Cisalpine Gaul).
Pertaining to ancient France, or Gaul
A series of beds of clay and marl in the South of England, between the upper and lower greensand of the Cretaceous period.

A genus of ericaceous shrubs with evergreen foliage, and, often, edible berries. It includes the American winter-green (Gaultheria procumbens), and the larger-fruited salal of Northwestern America (Gaultheria Shallon).
Attenuated, as with fasting or suffering
A frame for supporting barrels in a cellar or elsewhere.
An East Indian species of wild cattle (Bibos gauris), of large size and an untamable disposition.
A very thin, slight, transparent stuff, generally of silk
An ancient special kind of cessavit used in Kent and London for the recovery of rent.

A tenure by which land descended from the father to all his sons in equal portions, and the land of a brother, dying without issue, descended equally to his brothers. It still prevails in the county of Kent.
The division of birds which includes the gulls and terns.
A small tub or lading vessel.
A Southern Asiatic species of wild cattle (Bibos frontalis).
A vessel of Anam, with two or three masts, lofty triangular sails, and in construction somewhat resembling a Chinese junk.
A yellowish white, translucent mineral, consisting of the carbonates of lime and soda, with water.
Full of gayety. Mir. for Mag.
To fixx the eyes in a steady and earnest look
A summerhouse so situated as to command an extensive prospect.
A hound that pursues by the sight rather than by the scent.
One of several small, swift, elegantly formed species of antelope, of the genus Gazella, esp. G. dorcas
A Venetian coin, worth about three English farthings, or one and a half cents.
A writer of news, or an officer appointed to publish news by authority.
A person or thing gazed at with scorn or abhorrence
A portable apparatus for making soda water or aerated liquids on a small scale.
One of the pieces of sod used to line or cover parapets and the faces of earthworks.
A species of cherry tree common in Europe (Prunus avium)
An upward bend or flexure of a considerable portion of the earth's crust, resulting in the formation of a class of mountain elevations called anticlinoria
The channel or spout through which molten metal runs into a mold in casting.
A land crab of the genus Gecarcinus, or of allied genera.

Any lizard of the family Geckonidae. The geckoes are small, carnivorous, mostly nocturnal animals with large eyes and vertical, elliptical pupils. Their toes are generally expanded, and furnished with adhesive disks, by which they can run over walls and ceilings. They are numerous in warm countries, and a few species are found in Europe and the United States. See Wall gecko, Fanfoot.
Alluvial matter on the surface of land, not of recent origin.
The original native name for the ancient Ethiopic language or people. See Ethiopic.

The valley of Hinnom, near Jerusalem, where some of the Israelites sacrificed their children to Moloch, which, on this account, was afterward regarded as a place of abomination, and made a receptacle for all the refuse of the city, perpetual fires being kept up in order to prevent pestilential effluvia. In the New Testament the name is transferred, by an easy metaphor, to Hell.
Pertaining to, or derived from, earthy or vegetable mold.
A glass tube provided with platinum electrodes, and containing some gas under very low tension, which becomes luminous when an electrical discharge is passed through it
Fertilization of flowers by pollen from other flowers on the same plant.
A baboon (Gelada Ruppelli) of Abyssinia, remarkable for the length of the hair on the neck and shoulders of the adult male.
To convert into gelatin, or into a substance resembling jelly.
The act of process of converting into gelatin, or a substance like jelly.
Yielding gelatin on boiling with water
To convert into gelatin or jelly. Same as Gelatinate, v. t.
Of the nature and consistence of gelatin or the jelly
The process of becoming solid by cooling
An amorphous, gummy carbohydrate, found in Gelidium, agar-agar, and other seaweeds.
An alkaloid obtained from the yellow jasmine (Gelsemium sempervirens), as a bitter white semicrystalline substance
Pertaining to, or derived from, the yellow jasmine (Gelsemium sempervirens)
A genus of climbing plants. The yellow (false) jasmine (Gelsemium sempervirens) is a native of the Southern United States. It has showy and deliciously fragrant flowers.
The second part of the Talmud, or the commentary on the Mishna (which forms the first part or text).
One versed in the Gemara, or adhering to its teachings.
A constellation of the zodiac, containing the two bright stars Castor and Pollux
Having the flowers arranged in pairs.
A division of birds including the true pigeons.
A leaf bud, as distinguished from a flower bud.
Of or pertaining to gems or to gemmae
The formation of a new individual, either animal or vegetable, by a process of budding
The production of a bud or gem.
The state or quality of being gemmy
Animals which increase by budding, as hydroids.
The quality or characteristics of a gem or jewel.
A little leaf bud, as the plumule between the cotyledons.
Bearing or producing gemmules or buds.
A South African antelope (Oryx Capensis), having long, sharp, nearly straight horns.
An organ stop with conical tin pipes.
A small South American deer (Furcifer Chilensis), with simple forked horns.
A suffix used in scientific words in the sense of producing, generating: as, amphigen, amidogen, halogen.
A worsted yarn or cord of peculiar smoothness, used in the manufacture of braid, fringe, etc.
One of a body of heavy cavalry.
One who traces genealogies or the descent of persons or families.
To investigate, or relate the history of, descents.
An account or history of the descent of a person or family from an ancestor
The chief of a family or tribe.
Capable of being generated or produced.
Relating to a genus or kind
The chief commander of an army
Capable of being generalized, or reduced to a general form of statement, or brought under a general rule.
The act or process of generalizing
To bring under a genus or under genera
One who takes general or comprehensive views.
The condition or quality of being general
The act of generating or begetting
Having the power of generating, propagating, originating, or producing.
One who, or that which, generates, begets, causes, or produces.
Pertaining to a genus or kind
With regard to a genus, or an extensive class
The act or process of generalizing.
The closing subdivision of the Hamilton period in the American Devonian system
The doctrine or science of generation.
The act of producing, or giving birth or origin to anything
One of several species of small Carnivora of the genus Genetta, allied to the civets, but having the scent glands less developed, and without a pouch.
The science of calculating nativities, or predicting the future events of life from the stars which preside at birth.
Divination as to the destinies of one newly born
Pertaining to, concerned with, or determined by, the genesis of anything, or its natural mode of production or development.
Of or pertaining to Geneva, in Switzerland
Of or pertaining to Geneva, in Switzerland
Of or pertaining to the chin
Bent abruptly at an angle, like the knee when bent
A man of a particular turn of mind.
Of or pertaining to the chin and hyoid bone
The edible fruit of a West Indian tree (Genipa Americana) of the order Rubiaceae. It is oval in shape, as a large as a small orange, of a pale greenish color, and with dark purple juice.
A genus of plants including the common broom of Western Europe.
Pertaining to generation, or to the generative organs.
A species of apple that ripens very early.
Of or pertaining to that case (as the second case of Latin and Greek nouns) which expresses source or possession.  It corresponds to the possessive case in English.
Pertaining to the genital organs and the thigh
A good or evil spirit, or demon, supposed by the ancients to preside over a man's destiny in life
Of or pertaining to Genoa, a city of Italy.
A metal plate covering the knee.
A style of painting, sculpture, or other imitative art, which illustrates everyday life and manners.
A clan or family connection, embracing several families of the same stock, who had a common name and certain common religious rites
Possessing or exhibiting the qualities popularly regarded as belonging to high birth and breeding
Nobility of birth or of character
Any one of a genus (Gentiana) of herbaceous plants with opposite leaves and a tubular four- or five-lobed corolla, usually blue, but sometimes white, yellow, or red. See Illust. of Capsule.
Of or pertaining to a natural order of plants (Gentianaceae) of which the gentian is the type.
Pertaining to or derived from the gentian
A bitter, crystallizable substance obtained from gentian.
A crystallizable, sugarlike substance, with a slightly sweetish taste, obtained from the gentian.
To live like a gentile or heathen.
In a gentle or hoble manner
A bitter, yellow, crystalline substance, regarded as a glucoside, and obtained from the gentian.
A tasteless, yellow, crystalline substance, obtained from the gentian
Persons of gentle or good family and breeding.
Having a kind or gentle disposition.
The qualities or condition of a gentleman.
Of, pertaining to, resembling, or becoming, a gentleman
The carriage or quality of a gentleman.
The quality or state of being gentle, well-born, mild, benevolent, docile, etc.
The deportment or conduct of a gentleman.
A woman of good family or of good breeding
To bend the knee, as in worship.
The act of bending the knee, particularly in worship.
Belonging to, or proceeding from, the original stock
A class of objects divided into several subordinate species
Having reference to the earth as center
A lead-gray or grayish blue mineral with a metallic luster, consisting of sulphur, antimony, and lead, with a small proportion of arsenic.
Of, pertaining to, or illustrating, the revolutions of the earth
A nodule of stone, containing a cavity, lined with crystals or mineral matter.

That branch of applied mathematics which determines, by means of observations and measurements, the figures and areas of large portions of the earth's surface, or the general figure and dimenshions of the earth
A gigantic clam (Glycimeris generosa) of the Pacific coast of North America, highly valued as an article of food.
Of or pertaining to geognosy, or to a knowledge of the structure of the earth
That part of geology which treats of the materials of the earth's structure, and its general exterior and interior constitution.
Of or pertaining to geogony, or to the formation of the earth.
The branch of science which treats of the formation of the earth.
In a geographical manner or method
The science which treats of the world and its inhabitants
Of or pertaining to geology, or the science of the earth.
One versed in the science of geology.
To study geology or make geological investigations in the field
The science which treats: (a) Of the structure and mineral constitution of the globe
The tendency of an organism to respond, during its growth, to the force of gravitation.
One who practices, or is versed in, geomancy.
A kind of divination by means of figures or lines, formed by little dots or points, originally on the earth, and latterly on paper.
Pertaining to, or according to the rules or principles of, geometry
According to the rules or laws of geometry.
Pertaining or belonging to the Geometridae.
To investigate or apprehend geometrical quantities or laws
That branch of mathematics which investigates the relations, properties, and measurement of solids, surfaces, lines, and angles
The act or habit of eating earth. See Dirt eating, under Dirt.
One who eats earth, as dirt, clay, chalk, etc.
The division of Mollusca which includes the land snails and slugs.
Pertaining to tillage of the earth, or agriculture.
The art or science of cultivating the earth
A hollow globe on the inner surface of which a map of the world is depicted, to be examined by one standing inside.
A name given by miners to George Stephenson's safety lamp.
A figure of St. George (the patron saint of England) on horseback, appended to the collar of the Order of the Garter. See Garter.
A gold noble of the time of Henry VIII. See Noble, n.
Of or pertaining to Georgia, in Asia, or to Georgia, one of the United States.
Relating to agriculture and rural affairs.
The planet Uranus, so named by its discoverer, Sir W. Herschel.
Knowledge of the earth, ground, or soil, obtained by inspection.
Pertaining to the earth and moon
Relating to the pressure exerted by earth or similar substance.
the downward bend or subsidence of the earth's crust, which allows of the gradual accumulation of sediment, and hence forms the first step in the making of a mountain range
A thermometer specially constructed for measuring temperetures at a depth below the surface of the ground.
A disposition to turn or incline towards the earth
An order of marine Annelida, in which the body is imperfectly, or not at all, annulated externally, and is mostly without setae.
Belonging to the Gephyrea. -- n. One of the Gerphyrea.
Of or pertaining to a natural order of pants (Geraniaceae) which includes the genera Geranium, Pelargonium, and many others.
A valuable astringent obtained from the root of the Geranium maculatum or crane's-bill.

A genus of plants having a beaklike tours or receptacle, around which the seed capsules are arranged, and membranous projections, or stipules, at the joints. Most of the species have showy flowers and a pungent odor. Called sometimes crane's-bill.
The manager or acting partner of a company, joint-stock association, etc.
One of several species of small, jumping, murine rodents, of the genus Gerbillus. In their leaping powers they resemble the jerboa. They inhabit Africa, India, and Southern Europe.
A salmon returning from the sea the second time.
That which is to develop a new individual
A plant of the genus Teucrium (esp. Teucrium Chamaedrys or wall germander), mintlike herbs and low shrubs.
An idiom of the German language.

A rare element, recently discovered (1885), in a silver ore (argyrodite) at Freiberg. It is a brittle, silver-white metal, chemically intermediate between the metals and nonmetals, resembles tin, and is in general identical with the predicted ekasilicon. Symbol Ge. Atomic weight 72.3.
To make German, or like what is distinctively German
An organ in which the ova are developed in certain Turbellaria.
Pertaining or belonging to a germ
A polynuclear mass of protoplasm, not divided into separate cells, from which certain ova are developed.
That part of medicine which treats of regimen for old people.
Magistrates in Sparta, who with the ephori and kings, constituted the supreme civil authority.
A mixture composed of unfermented grape juice, brandy, sugar, etc., for adulteration of wines.
To divide (a State) into districts for the choice of representatives, in an unnatural and unfair way, with a view to give a political party an advantage over its opponent.
A kind of verbal noun, having only the four oblique cases of the singular number, and governing cases like a participle.
Pertaining to, or resembling, a gerund
Pertaining to, or partaking of, the nature of the gerund
In the manner of a gerund
The act of wearing (clothes or ornaments).
Pertaining to deeds or feats of arms
To make gestures or motions, as in speaking
The act of gesticulating, or making gestures to express passion or enforce sentiments.
Representing by, or belonging to, gestures.
A reciter of gests or legendary tales
the original third pers. sing. pres. of Go.
Something which gets or gains money
One who gets, gains, obtains, acquires, begets, or procreates.
One who contrives, makes, or arranges for, anything, as a book, a machine, etc.
A boiling spring which throws forth at frequent intervals jets of water, mud, etc., driven up by the expansive power of steam.
A loose hydrated form of silica, a variety of opal, deposited in concretionary cauliflowerlike masses, around some hot springs and geysers.
Egyptian dancing girls, of a lower sort than the almeh.
Butter clarified by boiling, and thus converted into a kind of oil.
A kind of small, prickly cucumber, much used for pickles.
The Jews'quarter in an Italian town or city.
One of a faction in Italy, in the 12th and 13th centuries, which favored the German emperors, and opposed the Guelfs, or adherents of the poses.
A pale unspotted variety of the wrymouth.
An imaginary evil being among Eastern nations, which was supposed to feed upon human bodies.
A ravine. See Gill a woody glen.
A term variously employed by early writers on art, though commonly designating the yellow oxide of lead, or massicot.
A man of extraordinari bulk and stature.
The state, personality, or character, of a giant
One of several finback whales of the North Atlantic

Any arboreal ape of the genus Hylobates, of which many species and varieties inhabit the East Indies and Southern Asia. They are tailless and without cheek pouches, and have very long arms, adapted for climbing.
The state of being gibbous or gibbose
Swelling by a regular curve or surface
A male cat, esp. an old one. See lst Gib. n.
To cast reproaches and sneering expressions
The inmeats, or edible viscera (heart, gizzard, liver, etc.), of poultry.
A staff to guage water, or to push a boat.
A disease of sheep, characterized by vertigo
The quality or state of being giddy.
Having in the head a sensation of whirling or reeling about
A person without thought fulness, prudence, or judgment.
A bird referred to in the Bible (Lev. xi. 18and Deut. xiv. 17) as unclean, probably the Egyptian vulture (Neophron percnopterus).
A mineral occurring in greenish gray six-sided prisms, having a greasy luster. It is probably a pseudomorph after elaeolite.
The act of killing, or one who kills, a giant.
An account or description of giants.
The leather strap by which the shield of a knight was slung across the shoulder, or across the neck and shoulder.
The muscular stomach, or gizzard, of birds.
To laugh with short catches of the breath or voice
The act of fastending the gige or leather strap to the shield.
A large tuberculated lizard (Heloderma suspectum) native of the dry plains of Arizona, New Mexico, etc. It is the only lizard known to have venomous teeth.
To overlay with a thin covering of gold
A drinking bout in which every one pays an equal share.
The art or practice of overlaying or covering with gold leaf
A shop where gill is sold.

A name given by old writers to the clove pink (Dianthus Caryophyllus) but now to the common stock (Matthiola incana), a cruciferous plant with showy and fragrant blossoms, usually purplish, but often pink or white.

A contrivance for permitting a body to incline freely in all directions, or for suspending anything, as a barometer, ship's compass, chronometer, etc., so that it will remain plumb, or level, when its support is tipped, as by the rolling of a ship. It consists of a ring in which the body can turn on an axis through a diameter of the ring, while the ring itself is so pivoted to its support that it can turn about a diameter at right angles to the first.
A small tool for boring holes. It has a leading screw, a grooved body, and a cross handle.
Joined work whose parts move within each other
Made or consisting of interlocked ring/ or links
A plant of the genus Zingiber, of the East and West Indies. The species most known is Z. officinale.
A kind of plain sweet cake seasoned with ginger, and sometimes made in fanciful shapes.
A kind of cotton or linen cloth, usually in stripes or checks, the yarn of which is dyed before it is woven
The lining of a mine shaft with stones or bricks to prevent caving.
Of or pertaining to the gums.

An order of ganoid fishes, including the modern gar pikes and many allied fossil forms. They have rhombic, ganoid scales, a heterocercal tail, paired fins without an axis, fulcra on the fins, and a bony skeleton, with the vertebrae convex in front and concave behind, forming a ball and socket joint. See Ganoidel.
Pertaining to, or resembling, a ginglymus, or hinge joint
A building where cotton is ginned.

A large ornamental tree (Ginkgo biloba) from China and Japan, belonging to the Yew suborder of Coniferae. Its leaves are so like those of some maidenhair ferns, that it is also called the maidenhair tree.
A small, strong carriage for conveying materials on a railroad.

A plant of the genus Aralia, the root of which is highly valued as a medicine among the Chinese. The Chinese plant (Aralia Schinseng) has become so rare that the American (A. quinquefolia) has largely taken its place, and its root is now an article of export from America to China. The root, when dry, is of a yellowish white color, with a sweetness in the taste somewhat resembling that of licorice, combined with a slight aromatic bitterness.
A shop or barroom where gin is sold as a beverage.
To take out the entrails of (herrings).
A kind of pouch formerly worn at the girdle.
An African ruminant (Camelopardalis giraffa) related to the deers and antelopes, but placed in a family by itself
A stroke with a rod or switch
That part of the body where the girdle is worn.
A young person of either sex
State or time of being a girl.
Like, or characteristic of, a girl
A member of the moderate republican party formed in the French legislative assembly in 1791. The Girondists were so called because their leaders were deputies from the department of La Gironde.
A band or strap which encircles the body
A weapon with a scythe-shaped blade, and a separate long sharp point, mounted on a long staff and carried by foot soldiers.
A native hydrated silicate of alumina, lime, and potash, first noticed near Rome.
A musical instrument, of unknown character, supposed by some to have been used by the people of Gath, and thence obtained by David. It is mentioned in the title of Psalms viii., lxxxi., and lxxxiv.
In just, correct, or suitable time.
To bestow without receiving a return
The second, or true, muscular stomach of birds, in which the food is crushed and ground, after being softened in the glandular stomach (crop), or lower part of the esophagus
The space between the eyebrows, also including the corresponding part of the frontal bone
The median, convex lobe of the head of a trilobite. See Trilobite.
Becoming smooth or glabrous from age.
To make smooth, plain, or bare.
Pertaining to ice or to its action
One who attributes the phenomena of the drift, in geology, to glaciers.
An immense field or stream of ice, formed in the region of perpetual snow, and moving slowly down a mountain slope or valley, as in the Alps, or over an extended area, as in Greenland.
Pertaining to, consisting of or resembling, ice
A gentle slope, or a smooth, gently sloping bank
An open passage through a wood
Of or pertaining to gladiators, or to contests or combatants in general.
The art or practice of a gladiator.
Conduct, state, or art, of a gladiator.
A lilylike plant, of the genus Gladiolus
A genus of plants having bulbous roots and gladiate leaves, and including many species, some of which are cultivated and valued for the beauty of their flowers
The internal shell, or pen, of cephalopods like the squids.
State or quality of being glad
A four-wheeled pleasure carriage with two inside seats, calash top, and seats for driver and footman.
The white of egg. It is used as a size or a glaze in bookbinding, for pastry, etc.
A glairy viscous substance, which forms on the surface of certain mineral waters, or covers the sides of their inclosures
Like glair, or partaking of its qualities
A weapon formerly used, consisting of a large blade fixed on the end of a pole, whose edge was on the outside curve
A copious gummy secretion of the humor of the eyelids, in consequence of some disorder
A charm affecting the eye, making objects appear different from what they really are.
A sudden flash of light or splendor.
An organ for secreting something to be used in, or eliminated from, the body
A feeding on nuts or mast.

A highly contagious and very destructive disease of horses, asses, mules, etc., characterized by a constant discharge of sticky matter from the nose, and an enlargement and induration of the glands beneath and within the lower jaw. It may transmitted to dogs, goats, sheep, and to human beings.
Having the form of a gland or nut
The situation and structure of the secretory vessels in plants.
A small gland or secreting vessel.
The vascular body which forms the apex of the penis, and the extremity of the clitoris.
To shine with a bright, dazzling light.

A hard, brittle, translucent, and commonly transparent substance, white or colored, having a conchoidal fracture, and made by fusing together sand or silica with lime, potash, soda, or lead oxide. It is used for window panes and mirrors, for articles of table and culinary use, for lenses, and various articles of ornament.
The larval state (Phyllosoma) of the genus Palinurus and allied genera. It is remarkable for its strange outlines, thinness, and transparency. See Phyllosoma.
A fish of the great lakes
Given to viewing one's self in a glass or mirror
A house where glass is made

A member of a Scottish sect, founded in the 18th century by John Glass, a minister of the Established Church of Scotland, who taught that justifying faith is "no more than a simple assent to the divine testimone passively recived by the understanding." The English and American adherents of this faith are called Sandemanians, after Robert Sandeman, the son-in-law and disciple of Glass.
One who makes, or manufactures, glass.
A remarkable vitreous sponge, of the genus Hyalonema, first brought from Japan. It has a long stem, consisting of a bundle of long and large, glassy, siliceous fibers, twisted together.
A small, transparent, land snail, of the genus Vitrina.
A long, footless lizard (Ophiosaurus ventralis), of the Southern United States
A siliceous sponge, of the genus Hyalonema, and allied genera
Ware, or articles collectively, made of glass.
A seashore plant of the Spinach family (Salicornia herbacea), with succulent jointed stems
A variety of the common hawthorn.
A mineral, consisting of the sulphates of soda and lime.
Sulphate of soda, a well-known cathartic. It is a white crystalline substance, with a cooling, slightly bitter taste, and is commonly called "salts."
Having a somewhat glaucous appearance or nature
Of or pertaining to the Glaucium or horned poppy
A metallic mineral having a grayish tin-white color, and containing cobalt and iron, with sulphur and arsenic.

Dimness or abolition of sight, with a diminution of transparency, a bluish or greenish tinge of the refracting media of the eye, and a hard inelastic condition of the eyeball, with marked increase of tension within the eyeball.
The green mineral characteristic of the greensand of the chalk and other formations. It is a hydrous silicate of iron and potash. See Greensand.
A mineral of a dark bluish color, related to amphibole. It is characteristic of certain crystalline rocks.
A genus of nudibranchiate mollusks, found in the warmer latitudes, swimming in the open sea. These mollusks are beautifully colored with blue and silvery white.
To grope with the hands, as in the dark.
To furnish (a window, a house, a sash, a ease, etc.) with glass.
One who applies glazing, as in pottery manufacture, etc.
One whose business is to set glass.
To disgorge filth, as a hawk.
The common European kite (Milvus ictinus). This name is also sometimes applied to the buzzard.
A name anciently given to an itinerant minstrel or musician.
A transparent mucous discharge from the membrane of the urethra, commonly an effect of gonorrhea.
A kind of Scotch whisky, named from the district in which it was first made.
Having the form of a smooth and shallow depression
An instrument for measuring the specific gravity and ascertaining the quantity of sugar contained in must.
One who, or that which, glides.
To give feeble or scattered rays of light
A tumor springing from the neuroglia or connective tissue of the brain, spinal cord, or other portions of the nervous system.
A sliding, as down a snow slope in the Alps.
The locus described by any point attached to a curve that slips continuously on another fixed curve, the movable curve having no rotation at any instant.
Having the form of a globe
A round or spherical body, solid or hollow

A plectognath fish of the genera Diodon, Tetrodon, and allied genera. The globefishes can suck in water or air and distend the body to a more or less globular form. Called also porcupine fish, and sea hedgehog. See Diodon.
A plant of the genus Trollius (T. Europaeus), found in the mountainous parts of Europe, and producing handsome globe-shaped flowers.
Having a round or globular tip.

A genus of small Foraminifera, which live abundantly at or near the surface of the sea. Their dead shells, falling to the bottom, make up a large part of the soft mud, generally found in depths below 3,000 feet, and called globigerina ooze. See Illust. of Foraminifera.
Having a rounded form resembling that of a globe
An instrument for measuring the number of red blood corpuscles in the blood.

An albuminous body, insoluble in water, but soluble in dilute solutions of salt. It is present in the red blood corpuscles united with haematin to form haemoglobin. It is also found in the crystalline lens of the eye, and in blood serum, and is sometimes called crystallin. In the plural the word is applied to a group of proteid substances such as vitellin, myosin, fibrinogen, etc., all insoluble in water, but soluble in dilute salt solutions.
A rudimentary form of crystallite, spherical in shape.
Resembling, or pertaining to, a globe
The larva or young of the mussel, formerly thought to be a parasite upon the parent's gills.
Gathered together in a roundish mass or dense cluster
The act of forming or gathering into a ball or round mass
Gathered or formed into a ball or round mass.
A head or dense cluster of flowers, formed by condensation of a cyme, as in the flowering dogwood.
The bunch of looped capillary blood vessels in a Malpighian capsule of the kidney.
Having small clusters of minutely branched coral-like excrescences.
A doxology (beginning Gloria Patri, Glory be to the Father), sung or said at the end of the Psalms in the service of the Roman Catholic and other churches.
The act of glorifyng or of giving glory to.
To make glorious by bestowing glory upon
A genus of climbing plants with very showy lilylike blossoms, natives of India.
Exhibiting attributes, qualities, or acts that are worthy of or receive glory
Praise, honor, admiration, or distinction, accorded by common consent to a person or thing
Brightness or luster of a body proceeding from a smooth surface
The tongue, or lingua, of an insect. See Hymenoptera.
Of or pertaining to the tongue
A disease of horses and cattle accompanied by carbuncles in the mouth and on the tongue.
Of or pertaining to glosses or to a glossary
In the manner of a glossary.
A writer of glosses or of a glossary
A collection of glosses or explanations of words and passages of a work or author
A writer of glosses or comments
A system of phonetic spelling based upon the present values of English letters, but invariably using one symbol to represent one sound only.
The condition or quality of being glossy
Pertaining to both tongue and epiglottis
The writing of glossaries, glosses, or comments for illustrating an author.
Pertaining to both the hyoidean arch and the tongue
One who defines and explains terms
The definition and explanation of terms
Pertaining to both the tongue and the pharynx
An oven in which glazed pottery is fired
Of or pertaining to, or produced by, the glottis
Of or pertaining to the glottis
The opening from the pharynx into the larynx or into the trachea. See Larynx.
The science of tongues or languages
A cover for the hand, or for the hand and wrist, with a separate sheath for each finger. The latter characteristic distinguishes the glove from the mitten.
One whose trade it is to make or sell gloves.
To shine with an intense or white heat
A coleopterous insect of the genus Lampyris
American genus of herbaceous plants with very handsome bell-shaped blossoms
Pertaining to, or obtained from, sugar
A white or gray tasteless powder, the oxide of the element glucinum
Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, glucinum

A rare metallic element, of a silver white color, and low specific gravity (2.1), resembling magnesium. It never occurs naturally in the free state, but is always combined, usually with silica or alumina, or both
Pertaining to, or derived from, glucose.

A variety of sugar occurring in nature very abundantly, as in ripe grapes, and in honey, and produced in great quantities from starch, etc., by the action of heat and acids. It is only about half as sweet as cane sugar. Called also dextrose, grape sugar, diabetic sugar, and starch sugar. See Dextrose.

One of a large series of amorphous or crystalline substances, occurring very widely distributed in plants, rarely in animals, and regarded as influental agents in the formation and disposition of the sugars. They are frequently of a bitter taste, but, by the action of ferments, or of dilute acids and alkalies, always break down into some characteristic substance (acid, aldehyde, alcohol, phenole, or alkaloid) and glucose (or some other sugar)
A condition in which glucose is discharged in the urine

A hard brittle brownish gelatin, obtained by boiling to a jelly the skins, hoofs, etc., of animals. When gently heated with water, it becomes viscid and tenaceous, and is used as a cement for uniting substances. The name is also given to other adhesive or viscous substances.
A utensil for melting glue, consisting of an inner pot holding the glue, immersed in an outer one containing water which is heated to soften the glue.
Characterized by a glume, or having the nature of a glume.
The bracteal covering of the flowers or seeds of grain and grasses
One of the pelets or inner chaffy scales of the flowers or spikelets of grasses.
To swallow, or to swallow greedlly
Pertaining to, or derived from, an acid intermediate between glutaric and aconitic acids.
The great muscle of the buttock in man and most mammals, and the corresponding muscle in many lower animals.
Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid so called
A nitrogenous substance, forming a heavy, sandy powder, white or nearly so. It is a derivative of pyridine.
Pertaining to, or in the region of, the glutaeus.
The viscid, tenacious substance which gives adhesiveness to dough.
The act of uniting with glue
One who eats voraciously, or to excess
Pertaining to, or derived from, glycerin.
A compound ether (formed from glycerin). Some glycerides exist ready formed as natural fats, others are produced artificially.

An oily, viscous liquid, C3H5(OH)3, colorless and odorless, and with a hot, sweetish taste, existing in the natural fats and oils as the base, combined with various acids, as oleic, margaric, stearic, and palmitic. It is a triatomic alcohol, and hence is also called glycerol. See Note under Gelatin.
A medicinal preparation made by mixing or dissolving a substance in glycerin.
A compound radical, C3H5, regarded as the essential radical of glycerin. It is metameric with allyl. Called also propenyl.
A colorless liquid, obtained from certain derivatives of glycerin, and regarded as a partially dehydrated glycerin
Pertaining to, or derived from, glycide
Pertaining to, or composed of, glycocoll and cholic acid.

A crystalline, nitrogenous substance, with a sweet taste, formed from hippuric acid by boiling with hydrochloric acid, and present in bile united with cholic acid. It is also formed from gelatin by decomposition with acids. Chemically, it is amido-acetic acid. Called also glycin, and glycocin.

A white, amorphous, tasteless substance resembling starch, soluble in water to an opalescent fluid. It is found abundantly in the liver of most animals, and in small quantity in other organs and tissues, particularly in the embryo. It is quickly changed into sugar when boiled with dilute sulphuric or hydrochloric acid, and also by the action of amylolytic ferments.
Pertaining to, or caused by, glycogen
The production or formation of sugar from gycogen, as in the liver.
A thick, colorless liquid, C2H4(OH)2, of a sweetish taste, produced artificially from certain ethylene compounds. It is a diacid alcohol, intermediate between ordinary ethyl alcohol and glycerin.
Pertaining to, or derived from, glycol
A white amorphous powder, C4H4O, obtained by heating and dehydrating glycolic acid.
Pertaining to, derived from, glycol and urea
A white, crystalline, nitrogenous substance, obtained by the reduction of allantoin.
A divalent, compound radical, CO.CH2, regarded as the essential radical of glycolic acid, and a large series of related compounds.
Consisting of a spondee, a choriamb, and a pyrrhic
An emulsion of glycerin and the yolk of eggs, used as an ointment, as a vehicle for medicines, etc.
An organic base, C6H6N4, produced artificially as a white, crystalline powder, by the action of ammonia on glyoxal.
A genus of papilionaceous herbaceous plants, one species of which (G. glabra), is the licorice plant, the roots of which have a bittersweet mucilaginous taste.
A glucoside found in licorice root (Glycyrrhiza), in monesia bark (Chrysophyllum), in the root of the walnut, etc., and extracted as a yellow, amorphous powder, of a bittersweet taste.
A glen. See Glen. [Obs. singly, but occurring often in locative names in Ireland, as Glen does in Scotland.]
A white, amorphous, deliquescent powder, (CO.H)2, obtained by the partial oxidation of glycol. It is a double aldehyde, between glycol and oxalic acid.
Pertaining to, or designating, an aldehyde acid, intermediate between glycol and oxalic acid.

A white, crystalline, organic base, C3H4N2, produced by the action of ammonia on glyoxal, and forming the origin of a large class of derivatives hence, any one of the series of which glyoxaline is a type
A white, crystalline, nitrogenous substance, produced by the action of hydroxylamine on glyoxal, and belonging to the class of oximes
A sunken channel or groove, usually vertical. See Triglyph.
Of or pertaining to sculpture or carving of any sort, esp. to glyphs.
A plate made by glyphography, or an impression taken from such a plate.
A process similar to etching, in which, by means of voltaic electricity, a raised copy of a drawing is made, so that it can be used to print from.
Of or pertaining to gem engraving.
The art of engraving on precious stones.
An extinct South American quaternary mammal, allied to the armadillos. It was as large as an ox, was covered with tessellated scales, and had fluted teeth.
One of a family (Glyptodontidae) of extinct South American edentates, of which Glyptodon is the type. About twenty species are known.
Relating to glyptography, or the art of engraving on precious stones.
The art or process of engraving on precious stones.
A building or room devoted to works of sculpture.
A rhombohedral zeolitic mineral, related in form and composition to chabazite.
A genus of composite plants with white or colored dry and persistent involucres
A knot or gnarl in wood
To strike together, as in anger or pain

A blood-sucking dipterous fly, of the genus Culex, undergoing a metamorphosis in water. The females have a proboscis armed with needlelike organs for penetrating the skin of animals. These are wanting in the males. In America they are generally called mosquitoes. See Mosquito.
Of or pertaining to the jaw.
The ramus of the lower jaw of a bird as far as it is naked
Any one of the mouth appendages of the Arthropoda. They are known as mandibles, maxillae, and maxillipeds.
A gnathopodite or maxilliped. See Maxilliped.
Any leglike appendage of a crustacean, when modified wholly, or in part, to serve as a jaw, esp. one of the maxillipeds.
One of a pair of broad plates, developed from the outer maxillipeds of crabs, and forming a cover for the other mouth organs.
A comprehensive division of vertebrates, including all that have distinct jaws, in contrast with the leptocardians and marsipobranchs (Cyclostoma), which lack them.
The horney covering of the lower mandible of a bird.
The aquatic larva of a gnat
To bite, as something hard or tough, which is not readily separated or crushed
One who, or that which, gnaws.

A crystalline rock, consisting, like granite, of quartz, feldspar, and mica, but having these materials, especially the mica, arranged in planes, so that it breaks rather easily into coarse slabs or flags. Hornblende sometimes takes the place of the mica, and it is then called hornblendic / syenitic gneiss. Similar varieties of related rocks are also called gneiss.
An imaginary being, supposed by the Rosicrucians to inhabit the inner parts of the earth, and to be the guardian of mines, quarries, etc.
In a gnomic, didactic, or sententious manner.
Pertaining to, of the nature of, or resembling, a gnomology.
A collection of, or a treatise on, maxims, grave sentences, or reflections.
The style or pin, which by its shadow, shows the hour of the day. It is usually set parallel to the earth's axis.
Of or pertaining to the gnomon, or the art of dialing.
According to the principles of the gnomonic projection.
The art or science of dialing, or of constructing dials to show the hour of the day by the shadow of a gnomon.
An alkaloid existing in small quantities in opium.
The system of philosophy taught by the Gnostics.
One of two species of large South African antelopes of the genus Catoblephas, having a mane and bushy tail, and curved horns in both sexes.
A species of antelope (Procapra picticauda), inhabiting Thibet.
A pointed instrument used to urge on a beast
That part of a mine from which the mineral has been partially or wholly removed
The mark set to bound a race, and to or around which the constestants run, or from which they start to return to it again
A bitter powder (also called araroba) found in the interspaces of the wood of a Brazilian tree (Andira araroba) and used as a medicine. It is the material from which chrysarobin is obtained.
A hollow-horned ruminant of the genus Capra, of several species and varieties, esp. the domestic goat (C. hircus), which is raised for its milk, flesh, and skin.
A part of a man's beard on the chin or lower lip which is allowed to grow, and trimmed so as to resemble the beard of a goat.
A fish of the genus Upeneus, inhabiting the Gulf of Mexico. It is allied to the surmullet.
The skin of a goat, or leather made from it.
One of several species of insectivorous birds, belonging to Caprimulgus and allied genera, esp. the European species (Caprimulgus Europaeus)
The refuse thrown back into the excavation after removing the coal. It is called also gob stuff.
To swallow or eat greedily or hastily
Pertaining to tapestry produced in the so-called Gobelin works, which have been maintained by the French Government since 1667.
Like, or pertaining to, the goby, or the genus Gobius.
A kind of cup or drinking vessel having a foot or standard, but without a handle.
One of the ropes or chains serving as stays for the dolphin striker or the bowsprit
One of several species of small marine fishes of the genus Gobius and allied genera.
A framework moving on casters, designed to support children while learning to walk.
One for whom a person becomes sponsor at baptism, and whom he promises to see educated as a Christian
A female for whom one becomes sponsor at baptism.
A man who becomes sponsor for a child at baptism, and makes himself a surety for its Christian training and instruction.
Having a reverential and loving feeling towards God
A corruption of God yield, i. e., God reward or bless.
Resembling or befitting a god or God
Careful observance of, or conformity to, the laws of God
A woman who becomes sponsor for a child in baptism. See Godfather
An ornament produced by notching or carving a rounded molding.
The rank or character of a god
A male for whom one has stood sponsor in baptism. See Godfather.

One of several species of long-billed, wading birds of the genus Limosa, and family Tringidae. The European black-tailed godwit (Limosa limosa), the American marbled godwit (L. fedoa), the Hudsonian godwit (L. haemastica), and others, are valued as game birds. Called also godwin.
A complex mixture of several substances extracted from Irish moss.
One who, or that which, goes
To plait, flute, or crimp. See Gauffer.

One of two or more species of American fresh-water fishes of the family Centrarchidae, esp. Chaenobryttus antistius, of Lake Michigan and adjacent waters, and Ambloplites rupestris, of the Great Lakes and Mississippi Valley
Having prominent and distorted or rolling eyes.
A carangoid oceanic fish (Trachurops crumenophthalmus), having very large and prominent eyes
An enlargement of the thyroid gland, on the anterior part of the neck
An old English name of some yellow flower, -- the marigold (Calendula), according to Dr. Prior, but in Chaucer perhaps the turnsole.
The art or process of reducing gold to extremely thin leaves, by beating with a hammer.
The European golden-crested kinglet (Regulus cristatus, or R. regulus)

A duck (Glaucionetta clangula), found in Northern Europe, Asia, and America. The American variety (var. Americana) is larger. Called whistler, garrot, gowdy, pied widgeon, whiteside, curre, and doucker. Barrow's golden-eye of America (G. Islandica) is less common.
In golden terms or a golden manner
A tall herb (Solidago Virga-aurea), bearing yellow flowers in a graceful elongated cluster. The name is common to all the species of the genus Solidago.
A beautiful bright-colored European finch (Carduelis elegans). The name refers to the large patch of yellow on the wings. The front of the head and throat are bright red
One of two or more species of European labroid fishes (Crenilabrus melops, and Ctenolabrus rupestris)
A small domesticated cyprinoid fish (Carassius auratus)
A conspicuous yellow flower, commonly the corn marigold (Chrysanthemum segetum).
An artisan who manufactures vessels and ornaments, etc., of gold.
A plant of several species of the genus Chrysocoma

A game played with a small ball and a bat or club crooked at the lower end. He who drives the ball into each of a series of small holes in the ground and brings it into the last hole with the fewest strokes is the winner.
Calvary. See the Note under Calvary.
A buffoon in the Middle Ages, who attended rich men's tables to make sport for the guests by ribald stories and songs.
The satirical or ribald poetry of the Goliards.
Any species of Goliathus, a genus of very large and handsome African beetles.
One of the followers of Francis Gomar or Gomarus, a Dutch disciple of Calvin in the 17th century, who strongly opposed the Arminians.
A disease of the teeth, which causes them to loosen and fall out of their sockets.
A form of union or immovable articulation where a hard part is received into the cavity of a bone, as the teeth into the jaws.

A black, fibrous substance resembling horsehair, obtained from the leafstalks of two kinds of palms, Metroxylon Sagu, and Arenga saccharifera, of the Indian islands. It is used for making cordage. Called also ejoo.
One of the masses of generative tissue primitively alike in both sexes, but giving rise to either an ovary or a testis

A long, narrow boat with a high prow and stern, used in the canals of Venice. A gondola is usually propelled by one or two oarsmen who stand facing the prow, or by poling. A gondola for passengers has a small open cabin amidships, for their protection against the sun or rain. A sumptuary law of Venice required that gondolas should be painted black, and they are customarily so painted now.
A man who rows a gondola.
The ensign or standard in use by certain princes or states, such as the mediaeval republics of Italy, and in more recent times by the pope.
One of an extinct genus of fossil cephalopods, allied to the Ammonites. The earliest forms are found in the Devonian formation, the latest, in the Triassic.
A special groove or furrow at one or both angles of the mouth of many Anthozoa.
Bluish green granules which occur in certain lichens, as Collema, Peltigera, etc., and which replace the more usual gonidia.
Pertaining to, or containing, gonidia or gonimia, as that part of a lichen which contains the green or chlorophyll-bearing cells.
An instrument for measuring angles, especially the angles of crystals, or the inclination of planes.
Pertaining to, or determined by means of, a goniometer
A reproductive bud of a hydroid
The bell of a sessile gonozooid.
Separation of the sexes in different individuals
A vegetable microorganism of the genus Micrococcus, occurring in the secretion in gonorrhea. It is believed by some to constitute the cause of this disease.
A sexual zooid produced as a medusoid bud upon a hydroid, sometimes becoming a free hydromedusa, sometimes remaining attached. See Hydroidea, and Illusts. of Athecata, Campanularian, and Gonosome.
A contagious inflammatory disease of the genitourinary tract, affecting especially the urethra and vagina, and characterized by a mucopurulent discharge, pain in urination, and chordee
The reproductive zooids of a hydroid colony, collectively.
A capsule developed on certain hydroids (Thecaphora), inclosing the blastostyle upon which the medusoid buds or gonophores are developed
A sexual zooid, or medusoid bud of a hydroid
Pertaining to the gonys of a bird's beak.
The keel or lower outline of a bird's bill, so far as the mandibular rami are united.
Having a cheerful spirit and demeanor
A familiar appellation of civility, equivalent to "My friend", "Good sir", "Mister
The quality of being good in any of its various senses
An exclamation of wonder, surprise, or entreaty.
A bonbon, cake, or the like
The state or quality of a goody or goodwife
A spiritual teacher, guide, or confessor amoung the Hindoos.
A species of merganser (M. merganser) of Northern Europe and America
Any large web-footen bird of the subfamily Anserinae, and belonging to Anser, Branta, Chen, and several allied genera. See Anseres.
Any thorny shrub of the genus Ribes
A genus of herbs (Chenopodium) mostly annual weeds
One of the clews or lower corners of a course or a topsail when the middle part or the rest of the sail is furled.
A sluice in embankments against the sea, for letting out the land waters, when the tide is out.
One of several North American burrowing rodents of the genera Geomys and Thomomys, of the family Geomyidae
A species of wood used in the construction of Noah's ark.
A paste prepared from tobacco, and smoked in hookahs in Western India.
An Indian goat antelope (Nemorhedus goral), resembling the chamois.
A pool of water to keep fish in
The moor cock, or red grouse. See Grouse.
A division of nematoid worms, including the hairworms or hair eels (Gordius and Mermis). See Gordius, and Illustration in Appendix.
Pertaining to Gordius, king of Phrygia, or to a knot tied by him
A genus of long, slender, nematoid worms, parasitic in insects until near maturity, when they leave the insect, and live in water, in which they deposit their eggs
A small gorget, as of a humming bird.
Imposing through splendid or various colors
In some columns, that part of the capital between the termination of the shaft and the annulet of the echinus, or the space between two neck moldings
A piece of armor, whether of chain mail or of plate, defending the throat and upper part of the breast, and forming a part of the double breastplate of the 14th century.
One of three fabled sisters, Stheno, Euryale, and Medusa, with snaky hair and of terrific aspect, the sight of whom turned the beholder to stone. The name is particularly given to Medusa.
A mask carved in imitation of a Gorgon's head.

A genus of Gorgoniacea, formerly very extensive, but now restricted to such species as the West Indian sea fan (Gorgonia flabellum), sea plume (G. setosa), and other allied species having a flexible, horny axis.
One of the principal divisions of Alcyonaria, including those forms which have a firm and usually branched axis, covered with a porous crust, or c/nenchyma, in which the polyp cells are situated.
Pertaining to, or resembling, a Gorgon
To have the effect of a Gorgon upon

A large, arboreal, anthropoid ape of West Africa. It is larger than a man, and is remarkable for its massive skeleton and powerful muscles, which give it enormous strength. In some respects its anatomy, more than that of any other ape, except the chimpanzee, resembles that of man.
A piece of canvas cut obliquely to widen a sail at the foot.
A large, handsome, marine, univalve shell (Triton femorale).
Covered with gore or clotted blood.

Any large hawk of the genus Astur, of which many species and varieties are known. The European (Astur palumbarius) and the American (A. atricapillus) are the best known species. They are noted for their powerful flight, activity, and courage. The Australian goshawk (A. Novae-Hollandiae) is pure white.
One who takes care of geese.
One of several species of pygmy geese, of the genus Nettepus. They are about the size of a teal, and inhabit Africa, India, and Australia.
To form according to the gospel
A fine, filmy substance, like cobwebs, floating in the air, in calm, clear weather, especially in autumn. It is seen in stubble fields and on furze or low bushes, and is formed by small spiders.
Decomposed rock, usually reddish or ferruginous (owing to oxidized pyrites), forming the upper part of a metallic vein.
A small British marine fish (Motella tricirrata)
The relationship between a person and his sponsors.
Full of, or given to, gossip.

A genus of plants which yield the cotton of the arts. The species are much confused. G. herbaceum is the name given to the common cotton plant, while the long-stapled sea-island cotton is produced by G. Barbadense, a shrubby variety. There are several other kinds besides these.
One of an ancient Teutonic race, who dwelt between the Elbe and the Vistula in the early part of the Christian era, and who overran and took an important part in subverting the Roman empire.
A hydrous oxide of iron, occurring in prismatic crystals, also massive, with a fibrous, reniform, or stalactitic structure. The color varies from yellowish to blackish brown.
A method of painting with opaque colors, which have been ground in water and mingled with a preparation of gum
a small fascine or fagot, steeped in wax, pitch, and glue, used in various ways, as for igniting buildings or works, or to light ditches and ramparts.
A chisel, with a hollow or semicylindrical blade, for scooping or cutting holes, channels, or grooves, in wood, stone, etc.
To scoop out with a gouge.
A sharp-edged, tubular, marine shell, of the genus Vermetus
An aqueous solution of the subacetate of lead, used as a lotion in cases of inflammation. Goulard's cerate is a cerate containing this extract.

One of several species of large, crested ground pigeons of the genus Goura, inhabiting New Guinea and adjacent islands. The Queen Victoria pigeon (Goura Victoria) and the crowned pigeon (G. coronata) are among the beat known species.

A very largo East Indian freshwater fish (Osphromenus gorami), extensively reared in artificial ponds in tropical countries, and highly valued as a food fish. Many unsuccessful efforts have been made to introduce it into Southern Europe.
A fleshy, three-celled, many-seeded fruit, as the melon, pumpkin, cucumber, etc., of the order Cucurbitaceae
A tree (the Crescentia Cujete, or calabash tree) of the West Indies and Central America.
The fluke of sheep. See Fluke.
A connoisseur in eating and drinking
A coarse umbelliferous plant of Europe (Aegopodium Podagraria)
Diseased with, or subject to, the gout
To direct and control, as the actions or conduct of men, either by established laws or by arbitrary will
Capable of being governed, or subjected to authority
A governor who has lieutenant or deputy governors under him
Having, abounding in, or decked with, daisies.
To make a, booby of one)
One whose professional habit is a gown, as a divine or lawyer, and particularly a member of an English university
Pertaining to, or discovered by, Regnier de Graaf, a Dutch physician.
A vessel used on the Malabar coast, having two or three masts.
The exercise of love, kindness, mercy, favor
Displaying grace or beauty in form or action
One of several American blackbirds, of the family Icteridae
To grade or arrange (parts in a whole, colors in painting, etc.), so that they shall harmonize.
The act of progressing by regular steps or orderly arrangement
Proceeding step by step, or by gradations
A step or degree in any series, rank, quality, order
One who grades, or that by means of which grading is done or facilitated.
Any member like a step, as the raised back of an altar or the like
A step or raised shelf, as above a sideboard or altar.  Cf. Superaltar, and Gradin.
The quality or state of being gradual
The act of graduating, or the state of being graduated
One who determines or indicates graduation
A dictionary of prosody, designed as an aid in writing Greek or Latin poetry.
A German title of nobility, equivalent to earl in English, or count in French. See Earl.
The scarp of a ditch or moat.
Inscriptions, figure drawings, etc., found on the walls of ancient sepulchers or ruins, as in the Catacombs, or at Pompeii.
A small shoot or scion of a tree inserted in another tree, the stock of which is to support and nourish it. The two unite and become one tree, but the graft determines the kind of fruit.
One who inserts scions on other stocks, or propagates fruit by ingrafting.
Bread made of unbolted wheat flour.
One who follows the dietetic system of Graham.
A book of offices in the Roman Catholic Church
A halfround single-cut file or fioat, having one curved face and one straight face, -- used by comb makers.
An infusion of pigeon's dung used by tanners to neutralize the effects of lime and give flexibility to skins
A field where grain is grown.
An order of birds which formerly included all the waders.  By later writers it is usually restricted to the sandpipers, plovers, and allied forms
Of or pertaining to the Grallatores, or waders.
Of or pertaining to the Grallae.
A suffix indicating something drawn or written, a drawing, writing

The unit of weight in the metric system. It was intended to be exactly, and is very nearly, equivalent to the weight in a vacuum of one cubic centimeter of pure water at its maximum density. It is equal to 15.432 grains. See Grain, n., 4.
The name of several kinds of pasture grasses found in the Western United States, esp. the Bouteloua oligostachya.
A word formerly used to express thankfulness, with surprise
Pertaining to, or resembling, the grasses
Like, Or pertaining to, grass. See Grass, n., 2.
Bearing leaves resembling those of grass.
Feeding or subsisting on grass, and the like food
The science which treats of the principles of language
One versed in grammar, or the construction of languages
The principles, practices, or peculiarities of grammarians.
A point or principle of grammar.
A toothed delphinoid cetacean, of the genus Grampus, esp. G. griseus of Europe and America, which is valued for its oil. It grows to be fifteen to twenty feet long

The fruit of certain species of passion flower (esp. Passiflora quadrangularis) found in Brazil and the West Indies. It is as large as a child's head, and is a good dessert fruit. The fruit of Passiflora edulis is used for flavoring ices.
A storehouse or repository for grain, esp. after it is thrashed or husked
The aunt of one's father or mother.
The daughter of one's son or daughter.
A man of elevated rank or station
The rank or estate of a grandee
The state or quality of being grand
Of or pertaining to a grand duke.
Like a grandfather in age or manner
The use of lofty words or phrases
The state or quality of being grandiose,
The mother of one's father or mother.
Like a grandmother in age or manner
The grandson of one's brother or sister.
The granddaughter of one's brother or sister.
The practice of illustrating a particular book by engravings collected from other books.
One who collects illustrations from various books for the decoration of one book.
To collect (illustrations from books) for decoration of other books.
Bearing grain, or seeds like grain.
Small grains or dust of cochineal or the coccus insect.

A crystalline, granular rock, consisting of quartz, feldspar, and mica, and usually of a whitish, grayish, or flesh-red color. It differs from gneiss in not having the mica in planes, and therefore in being destitute of a schistose structure.
Like granite in composition, color, etc.
The act or the process of forming into granite.
Resembling granite in structure or shape.
A kind of hard artificial stone, used for pavements.
The person to whom a grant or conveyance is made.
The person by whom a grant or conveyance is made.
To form into grains or small masses
The act or process of forming or crystallizing into grains
A little grain a small particle
A whitish, granular rock, consisting of feldspar and quartz intimately mixed

The main constituent of the starch grain or granule, in distinction from the framework of cellulose. Unlike cellulose, it is colored blue by iodine, and is converted into dextrin and sugar by boiling acids and amylolytic ferments.
