A well-known edible berry growing in pendent clusters or bunches on the grapevine. The berries are smooth-skinned, have a juicy pulp, and are cultivated in great quantities for table use and for making wine and raisins.
Wanting grapes or the flavor of grapes.
A building or inclosure used for the cultivation of grapes.

A cluster, usually nine in number, of small iron balls, put together by means of cast-iron circular plates at top and bottom, with two rings, and a central connecting rod, in order to be used as a charge for a cannon. Formerly grapeshot were inclosed in canvas bags.
A vine or climbing shrub, of the genus Vitis, having small green flowers and lobed leaves, and bearing the fruit called grapes.
Of or pertaining to the arts of painting and drawing.
The quality or state of being graphic.
The art or the science of drawing

Native carbon in hexagonal crystals, also foliated or granular massive, of black color and metallic luster, and so soft as to leave a trace on paper. It is used for pencils (improperly called lead pencils), for crucibles, and as a lubricator, etc. Often called plumbago or black lead.
Pertaining to, containing, derived from, or resembling, graphite.
Any species of slate suitable to be written on.
The art of judging of a person's character, disposition, and aptitude from his handwriting.
An optical instrument for magnifying engravings, photographs, etc., usually having one large lens and two smaller ones.

A process for producing a design upon a surface in relief so that it can be printed from. Prepared chalk or oxide of zinc is pressed upon a smooth plate by a hydraulic press, and the design is drawn upon this in a peculiar ink which hardens the surface wherever it is applied. The surface is then carefully rubbed or brushed, leaving the lines in relief.
A suffix denoting the art of writing or describing
A small anchor, with four or five flukes or claws, used to hold boats or small vessels
Pertaining to the genus Grapsus or the family Grapsidae.

One of numerous species of slender and delicate fossils, of the genus Graptolites and allied genera, found in the Silurian rocks. They belong to an extinct group (Graptolithina) supposed to be hydroids.
To seize and hold by clasping or embracing with the fingers or arms
A wandering about with evil intentions

Any jumping, orthopterous insect, of the families Acrididae and Locustidae. The species and genera are very numerous.  The former family includes the Western grasshopper or locust (Caloptenus spretus), noted for the great extent of its ravages in the region beyond the Mississippi. In the Eastern United States the red-legged (Caloptenus femurrubrum and C. atlanis) are closely related species, but their ravages are less important. They are closely related to the migratory locusts of the Old World. See Locust.
The state of abounding with grass
A plot or space covered with grass

An Australian plant of the genus Xanthorrhoea, having a thick trunk crowned with a dense tuft of pendulous, grasslike leaves, from the center of which arises a long stem, bearing at its summit a dense flower spike looking somewhat like a large cat-tail. These plants are often called "blackboys" from the large trunks denuded and blackened by fire. They yield two kinds of fragrant resin, called Botany-bay gum, and Gum Acaroides.
Having a due sense of benefits received
One who, or that which, grates
The division of a design or draught into squares, in order the more easily to reproduce it in larger or smaller dimensions.
A design or draught which has been divided into squares, in order to reproduce it in other dimensions.
The act of gratifying, or pleasing, either the mind, the taste, or the appetite
One of the essential principles of the hedge hyssop (Gratiola officinalis).
Given without an equivalent or recompense
Something given freely or without recompense
To salute with declaration of joy
The act of gratulating or felicitating
A final syllable signifying a ruler, as in landgrave, margrave. See Margrave.
To clean, as a vessel's bottom, of barnacles, grass, etc., and pay it over with pitch
The clothes or dress in which the dead are interred.
Small stones, or fragments of stone
A pebble, or small fragment of stone
A kind of fall apple, marked with streaks of deep red and orange, and of excellent flavor and quality.
The act, process, or art, of graving or carving
The sediment of melted tallow. Same as Greaves.
A stone laid over, or erected near, a grave, usually with an inscription, to preserve the memory of the dead
A yard or inclosure for the interment of the dead
An instrument for ascertaining the specific gravity of bodies.
Of or pertaining to measurement by weight
To obey the law of gravitation
Of or pertaining to the force of gravity
The juice or other liquid matter that drips from flesh in cooking, made into a dressing for the food when served up.
White mixed with black, as the color of pepper and salt, or of ashes, or of hair whitened by age
The common wild gray goose (Anser anser) of Europe, believed to be the wild form of the domestic goose. See Illust. of Goose.
A European fish (Thymallus vulgaris), allied to the trout, but having a very broad dorsal fin
A grayish or greenish compact rock, composed of feldspar and augite, and allied to basalt.
A conglomerate or grit rock, consisting of rounded pebbles sand firmly united together.
To feed or supply (cattle, sheep, etc.) with grass
One who pastures cattle, and rears them for market.
Animal fat, as tallow or lard, especially when in a soft state
One who, or that which, greases
The quality or state of being greasy, oiliness
Composed of, or characterized by, grease
The child of one's grandson or granddaughter.
A daughter of one's grandson or granddaughter.
The father of one's grandfather or grandmother.
The mother of one's grandfather or grandmother.
A son of one's grandson or granddaughter.
The state, condition, or quality of being great
The sediment of melted tallow. It is made into cakes for dogs' food. In Scotland it is called cracklings.

One of several swimming birds or divers, of the genus Colymbus (formerly Podiceps), and allied genera, found in the northern parts of America, Europe, and Asia. They have strong, sharp bills, and lobate toes.
An idiom of the Greek language
To conform to the Greek custom, especially in speech.
Having characteristics that are partly Greek and partly Roman
An ornament supposed to be of Greek origin, esp. a fret or meander.
Having a keen appetite for food or drink
An African talisman or Gri'gri' charm.
Of or pertaining to Greece or the Greeks
A little Greek, or one of small esteem or pretensions.
Having the color of grass when fresh and growing
One of the legal tender notes of the United States
One of those who supported greenback or paper money, and opposed the resumption of specie payments.
A plant of the genus Genista (G. tinctoria)

A board or court of justice formerly held in the counting house of the British sovereign's household, composed of the lord steward and his officers, and having cognizance of matters of justice in the household, with power to correct offenders and keep the peace within the verge of the palace, which extends two hundred yards beyond the gates.
A kind of plum of medium size, roundish shape, greenish flesh, and delicious flavor. It is called in France Reine Claude, after the queen of Francis I. See Gage.
An oyster which has the gills tinged with a green pigment, said to be due to an abnormal condition of the blood.
A retailer of vegetables or fruits in their fresh or green state.
A house in which tender plants are cultivated and sheltered from the weather.
l. (Zool.) One of numerous species of small American singing birds, of the genus Vireo, as the solitary, or blue-headed (Vireo solitarius)
Native cadmium sulphide, a mineral occurring in yellow hexagonal crystals, also as an earthy incrustation.
The retiring room of actors and actresses in a theater.
A variety of sandstone, usually imperfectly consolidated, consisting largely of glauconite, a silicate of iron and potash of a green color, mixed with sand and a trace of phosphate of lime.
A European sandpiper or snipe (Totanus canescens)
A stall at which greens and fresh vegetables are exposed for sale.
A name formerly applied rather loosely to certain dark-colored igneous rocks, including diorite, diabase, etc.
The state or quality of being green
A forest as it appears is spring and summer.
One who greets or salutes another.
A step. See Gree, a step.
Pertaining to, or like, a flock.

An order of Protozoa, allied to the Rhizopoda, and parasitic in other animals, as in the earthworm, lobster, etc.   When adult, they have a small, wormlike body inclosing a nucleus, but without external organs
Of or pertaining to the Gregarinae.
Habitually living or moving in flocks or herds
A short jacket or cloak, made of very thick, coarse cloth, with a hood attached, worn by the Greeks and others in the Levant.
Pertaining to, or originated by, some person named Gregory, especially one of the popes of that name.
Iron ore in coarse powder, prepared for reduction by the Catalan process.
A crystalline rock consisting of quarts and mica, common in the tin regions of Cornwall and Saxony.
Of or pertaining to the lap or bosom.
A hollow ball or shell of iron filled with powder of other explosive, ignited by means of a fuse, and thrown from the hand among enemies.
Originaly, a soldier who carried and threw grenades
A handsome tropical American wood, much used for making flutes and other wind instruments
A thin gauzelike fabric of silk or wool, for women's wear.
A slender, graceful breed of dogs, remarkable for keen sight and swiftness. It is one of the oldest varieties known, and is figured on the Egyptian monuments.
A small marine isopod crustacean (Limnoria lignorum or L. terebrans), which burrows into and rapidly destroys submerged timber, such as the piles of wharves, both in Europe and America.
A grating of thin parallel bars, similar to a gridiron.
An iron plate or pan used for cooking cakes.
A cake baked or fried on a griddle, esp. a thin batter cake, as of buckwheat or common flour.
To cut with a grating sound
A color mixed of white, and red, or a gray violet.
A grated iron utensil for broiling flesh and fish over coals.
Pain of mind on account of something in the past
A cause of uneasiness and complaint
One who, or that which, grieves.
The offspring of a mulatto woman and a negro
An Anglo-Indian name for a person just arrived from Europe.
A fabulous monster, half lion and half eagle. It is often represented in Grecian and Roman works of art.
A framework of sleepers and crossbeams forming a foundation in marshy or treacherous soil.
A young salmon after its first return from the sea.
A distortion of the countenance, whether habitual, from affectation, or momentary aad occasional, to express some feeling, as contempt, disapprobation, complacency, etc.
An old cat, esp. a she-cat.
A West African antelope (Cephalophus rufilotus) of a deep bay color, with a broad dorsal stripe of black
To reduce to powder by friction, as in a mill, or with the teeth
The dried stems and leaves of tarweed (Grindelia), used as a remedy in asthma and bronchitis.
One who, or that which, grinds.
A flat, circular stone, revolving on an axle, for grinding or sharpening tools, or shaping or smoothing objects.
3d pers. sing. pres. of Grind, contr. from grindeth.
In a griping or oppressive manner.
The man who manipulates a grip.
One who, or that which, grips or seizes.
Of a light color, or white, mottled with black or brown
A French girl or young married woman of the lower class
The quality or state of being grisly
A South American animal of the family Mustelidae (Galictis vittata). It is about two feet long, exclusive of the tail. Its under parts are black. Also called South American glutton.
Inhabitants of the eastern Swiss Alps.

A monkey of the upper Nile and Abyssinia (Cercopithecus griseo-viridis), having the upper parts dull green, the lower parts white, the hands, ears, and face black. It was known to the ancient Egyptians. Called also tota.
To give forth a low, moaning sound in breathing
An old English silver coin, equal to four pence.
Dried grain, as oats or wheat, hulled and broken or crushed
A trader who deals in tea, sugar, spices, coffee, fruits, and various other commodities.
The commodities sold by grocers, as tea, coffee, spices, etc.
A mixture of spirit and water not sweetened
A coarse stuff made of silk and mohair, or of coarse silk.
A shop or room where strong liquors are sold and drunk
A ring formed by twisting on itself a single strand of an unlaid rope
A plant of the genus Lithospermum (L. arvense), anciently used, because of its stony pericarp, in the cure of gravel. The German gromwell is the Stellera.
One who, or that which, grooms horses
A male attendant of a bridegroom at his wedding
A furrow, channel, or long hollow, such as may be formed by cutting, molding, grinding, the wearing force of flowing water, or constant travel
One who or that which grooves.
The act of forming a groove or grooves
To feel with or use the hands
A heavy silk with a dull finish
One of various species of finches having a large, stout beak. The common European grosbeak or hawfinch is Coccothraustes vulgaris.
A small silver coin and money of account of Germany, worth about two cents. It is not included in the new monetary system of the empire.
The act of making gross or thick, or the state of becoming so.
The state or quality of being gross
Pertaining too, or resembling, a gooseberry
A vegetable jelly, resembling pectin, found in gooseberries (Ribes Grossularia) and other fruits.
Like the figures found in ancient grottoes
A whimsical figure, or scene, such as is found in old crypts and grottoes.
A natural covered opening in the earth
Artificial and ornamental rockwork in imitation of a grotto.
A local tax paid by a ship for the ground or space it occupies while in port.
In a grounded or firmly established manner.
A fish that keeps at the bottom of the water, as the loach.
The fruit of the Arachis hypogaea (native country uncertain)
An annual composite plant (Senecio vulgaris), one of the most common and widely distributed weeds on the globe.
That which forms the foundation or support of anything

One of several species of valuable food fishes of the genus Epinephelus, of the family Serranidae, as the red grouper, or brown snapper  (E. morio), and the black grouper, or warsaw (E. nigritus), both from Florida and the Gulf of Mexico.

Any of the numerous species of gallinaceous birds of the family Tetraonidae, and subfamily Tetraoninae, inhabiting Europe, Asia, and North America. They have plump bodies, strong, well-feathered legs, and usually mottled plumage. The group includes the ptarmigans (Lagopus), having feathered feet.
A pointed timber attached to a boat and sliding vertically, to thrust into the ground as a means of anchorage.
A smaller group of trees than a forest, and without underwood, planted, or growing naturally as if arranged by art
To creep on the earth, or with the face to the ground
Pertaining to, or resembling, a grove
To increase in size by a natural and organic process
A decomposed granite, forming a mass of gravel, as in tin lodes in Cornwall.
To utter a deep guttural sound, sa an angry dog
A tool with a hardened steel point, formerly used instead of a diamond for cutting glass.
To dig in or under the ground, generally for an object that is difficult to reach or extricate
One who, or that which, grubs
To feel or grope in the dark.
To look upon with desire to possess or to appropriate
The state or quality of grudging, or of being full of grudge or unwillingness.
A light, liquid food, made by boiling meal of maize, oatmeal, or fiour in water or milk
Of a rough or stern manner, voice, or countenance
A West Indian name for several kinds of palm. See Macaw tree, under Macaw.
The larva or grub of a large South American beetle (Calandra palmarum), which lives in the pith of palm trees and sugar cane. It is eaten by the natives, and esteemed a delicacy.
To murmur or mutter with discontent
To make a deep, short noise, as a hog
One who, or that which, grunts
A kind of cheese made at Gruyere, Switzerland. It is a firm cheese containing numerous cells, and is known in the United States as Schweitzerkase.
A measure equal to one tenth of a line.
A genus of insects including the common crickets.
A genus of cretaceous fossil shells allied to the oyster.
A shell of the genus Gryphea.
A small South African antelope (Neotragus melanotis).  It is speckled with gray and chestnut, above
A nocturnal bird of South America and Trinidad (Steatornis Caripensis, or S. steatornis)
One of the mixed-blood (Spanish-Indian) inhabitants of the pampas of South America
A plant (Aristolochia anguicida) of Carthagena, used as an antidote to serpent bites.
A genus of small, crooked trees, growing in tropical America.
Any one of many species of large gallinaceous birds of Central and South America, belonging to Penelope, Pipile, Ortalis, and allied genera. Several of the species are often domesticated.

A South American mammal (Auchenia huanaco), allied to the llama, but of larger size and more graceful form, inhabiting the southern Andes and Patagonia. It is supposed by some to be the llama in a wild state.

A strongly alkaline base, CN3H5, formed by the oxidation of guanin, and also obtained combined with methyl in the decomposition of creatin. Boiled with dilute sulphuric acid, it yields urea and ammonia.
A crystalline substance (C5H5N5O) contained in guano. It is also a constituent of the liver, pancreas, and other glands in mammals.

A substance found in great abundance on some coasts or islands frequented by sea fowls, and composed chiefly of their excrement. It is rich in phosphates and ammonia, and is used as a powerful fertilizer.
A preparation from the seeds of Paullinia sorbilis, a woody climber of Brazil, used in making an astringent drink, and also in the cure of headache.
An alkaloid extracted from guarana. Same as Caffeine.

In law and common usage: A promise to answer for the payment of some debt, or the performance of some duty, in case of the failure of another person, who is, in the first instance, liable to such payment or performance
One who makes or gives a guaranty
In law and common usage: An undertaking to answer for the payment of some debt, or the performance of some contract or duty, of another, in case of the failure of such other to pay or perform
Capable of being guarded or protected.
A building which is occupied by the guard, and in which soldiers are confined for misconduct
One who guards, preserves, or secures
The office, duty, or care, of a guardian
The room occupied by the guard during its term of duty

A tropical tree, or its fruit, of the genus Psidium. Two varieties are well known, the P. pyriferum, or white guava, and P. pomiferum, or red guava.  The fruit or berry is shaped like a pomegranate, but is much smaller. It is somewhat astringent, but makes a delicious jelly.
Pertaining to a governor, or to government.
A small European freshwater fish (Gobio fluviatilis), allied to the carp. It is easily caught and often used for food and for bait. In America the killifishes or minnows are often called gudgeons.
A cultivated variety of a species of Viburnum (V. Opulus), bearing large bunches of white flowers
One of a faction in Germany and Italy, in the 12th and 13th centuries, which supported the House of Guelph and the pope, and opposed the Ghibellines, or faction of the German emperors.
Of or pertaining to the family or the faction of the Guelphs.
One of several long-tailed Oriental monkeys, of the genus Cercocebus, as the green monkey and grivet.

A beautiful Abyssinian monkey (Colobus guereza), having the body black, with a fringe of long, silky, white hair along the sides, and a tuft of the same at the end of the tail.  The frontal band, cheeks, and chin are white.
A projecting turret for a sentry, as at the salient angles of works, or the acute angles of bastions.
A South African plant (Nerine Sarniensis) with handsome lilylike flowers, naturalized on the island of Guernsey.
An irregular mode of carrying on war, by the constant attacks of independent bands, adopted in the north of Spain during the Peninsular war.
To form an opinion concerning, without knowledge or means of knowledge
A rope or hawser by which a vessel is towed or warped along
Work performed, or results obtained, by guess
The line by which a boat makes fast to the swinging boom.
In the manner of a guest.
One of several very small species and varieties of African antelopes, of the genus Cephalophus, as the Cape guevi or kleeneboc (Cephalophus pygmaea)
A loose, earthy deposit from water, found in the cavities or clefts of rocks, mostly white, but sometimes red or yellow, from a mixture of clay or ocher.
A colorless liquid, C6H4,OCH3.OH, resembling the phenols, found as a constituent of woodtar creosote, aud produced by the dry distillation of guaiac resin.
A West African antelope  (Tragelaphus scriptus), curiously marked with white stripes and spots on a reddish fawn ground, and hence called harnessed antelope
[Mahratta g/ekw/r, prop., a cowherd.]  The title of the sovereign of Guzerat, in Western India
The reward given to a guide for services.
The act or result of guiding
A board, as upon a guidepost having upon it directions or information as to the road.
A book of directions and information for travelers, tourists, etc.
A post at the fork of a road, with a guideboard on it, to direct travelers.
A South American ant bird of the genus Hylactes
A small flag or streamer, as that carried by cavalry, which is broad at one end and nearly pointed at the other, or that used to direct the movements of a body of infantry, or to make signals at sea
An association of men belonging to the same class, or engaged in kindred pursuits, formed for mutual aid and protection
A Dutch silver coin worth about forty cents
The hall where a guild or corporation usually assembles
One of several northern sea birds, allied to the auks. They have short legs, placed far back, and are expert divers and swimmers.
An ornament in the form of two or more bands or strings twisted over each other in a continued series, leaving circular openings which are filled with round ornaments.
A machine for beheading a person by one stroke of a heavy ax or blade, which slides in vertical guides, is raised by a cord, and let fall upon the neck of the victim.
The criminality and consequent exposure to punishment resulting from willful disobedience of law, or from morally wrong action
The quality or state of being guilty.
Made sick by consciousness of guilt.
A district on the west coast of Africa (formerly noted for its export of gold and slaves) after which the Guinea fowl, Guinea grass, Guinea peach, etc., are named.
A term used for lace of different kinds
Customary way of speaking or acting
A stringed instrument of music resembling the lute or the violin, but larger, and having six strings, three of silk covered with silver wire, and three of catgut, -- played upon with the fingers.
One of several species of small tropical American birds of the family Coerebidae, allied to the creepers
The upper front of the neck, next to the chin
Pertaining to the gula or throat
To give the color of gules to.
The tincture red, indicated in seals and engraved figures of escutcheons by parallel vertical lines. Hence, used poetically for a red color or that which is red.
A hollow place in the earth
A cement made in India from sea shells, pulverized and mixed with oil, and spread over a ship's bottom, to prevent the boring of worms.
An act, or the practice, of gulling
The tube by which food and drink are carried from the pharynx to the stomach
A system of excavating by means of gullets or channels.
To swallow eagerly, or in large draughts
The dense tissues which invest the teeth, and cover the adjacent parts of the jaws.
A soup thickened with the mucilaginous pods of the okra
A small suppurting inflamed spot on the gum.
A kind of soft tumor, usually of syphilitic origin.
A punch-cutting tool, or machine for deepening and enlarging the spaces between the teeth of a worn saw.
The state or quality of being gummy
A yellow amorphous mineral, essentially a hydrated oxide of uranium derived from the alteration of uraninite.
In Sanskrit grammar, a lengthening of the simple vowels a, i, e, by prefixing an a element. The term is sometimes used to denote the same vowel change in other languages.
A vessel of light draught, carrying one or more guns.
A sharpened flint for the lock of a gun, to ignite the charge. It was in common use before the introduction of percussion caps.
The lock of a gun, for producing the discharge. See Lock.
The number of guns carried by a ship of war.
One who works a gun, whether on land or sea
That branch of military science which comprehends the theory of projectiles, and the manner of constructing and using ordnance.
Space left by the removal of ore.
The act or practice of hunting or shooting game with a gun.

A strong, coarse kind of sacking, made from the fibers (called jute) of two plants of the genus Corchorus (C. olitorius and C. capsularis), of India. The fiber is also used in the manufacture of cordage.
A black, granular, explosive substance, consisting of an intimate mechanical mixture of niter, charcoal, and sulphur. It is used in gunnery and blasting.
The reach or distance to which a gun will shoot
An apartment on the after end of the lower gun deck of a ship of war, usually occupied as a messroom by the commissioned officers, except the captain
One whose occupation is to make or repair small firearms
The art or business of a gunsmith.
A stick to ram down the charge of a musket, etc.
The stock or wood to which the barrel of a hand gun is fastened.
A topmast arranged with metal bands so that it will readily slide up and down the lower mast.
The chain ordinarily used in measuring land. See Chain, n., 4, and Gunter's scale.
A logarithmic line on Gunter's scale, used for performing the multiplication and division of numbers mechanically by the dividers

A thin quadrant, made of brass, wood, etc., showing a stereographic projection on the plane of the equator. By it are found the hour of the day, the sun's azimuth, the altitude of objects in degrees, etc. See Gunter's scale.
A scale invented by the Rev. Edmund Gunter (1581-1626), a professor of astronomy at Gresham College, London, who invented also Gunter's chain, and Gunter's quadrant.
The upper edge of a vessel's or boat's side
To run or flow in a broken, irregular, noisy current, as water from a bottle, or a small stream among pebbles or stones.
A porous earthen jar for cooling water by evaporation.
A thin balsam or wood oil derived from the Diptcrocarpus laevis, an East Indian tree. It is used in medicine, and as a substitute for linseed oil in the coarser kinds of paint.
A young person of either sex. [Obs.] See Girl.
A pickax with one sharp point and one cutting edge.

One ofseveral European marine fishes, of the genus Trigla and allied genera, having a large and spiny head, with mailed cheeks. Some of the species are highly esteemed for food. The name is sometimes applied to the American sea robins.
A gutter or channel for water, hewn out of the bottom of a working drift.
To issue with violence and rapidity, as a fluid
A small piece of cloth inserted in a garment, for the purpose of strengthening some part or giving it a tapering enlargement.
Pertaining to, or subservient to, the sense of taste
Nice or keen appreciation or enjoyment
Subject to, or characterized by, gusts or squalls

A concrete juice produced by various trees found in the Malayan archipelago, especially by the Isonandra, /  Dichopsis, Gutta. It becomes soft, and unpressible at the tamperature of boiling water, and, on cooling, retains its new shape. It dissolves in oils and ethers, but not in water. In many of its properties it resembles caoutchouc, and it is extensively used for many economical purposes. The Mimusops globosa of Guiana also yields this material.
Spotted, as if discolored by drops.
Besprinkled with drops, or droplike spots.
The inspissated juice of a tree of the genus Artocarpus (A. incisa, or breadfruit tree), sometimes used in making birdlime, on account of its glutinous quality.
A channel at the eaves of a roof for conveying away the rain
A plant that exudes gum or resin.
Drop-shaped, as a spot of color.
Of or pertaining to the throat
A combining form denoting relation to the throat
A plant, Globularia Alypum, a violent purgative, found in Africa.
A rope, chain, or rod attached to anything to steady it
A roundlet of tincture sanguine, which is blazoned without mention of the tincture.
A fish (Coregonus ferus) of North Wales and Northern Europe, allied to the lake whitefish
Fermented wort used for making vinegar.
An Athenian officer who superintended the gymnasia, and provided the oil and other necessaries at his own expense.
A place or building where athletic exercises are performed
One who teaches or practices gymnastic exercises
Pertaining to athletic exercises intended for health, defense, or diversion
Of or pertaining to the Gymnoblastea.
Naked-fruited, the fruit either smooth or not adherent to the perianth.
A division of Hydroidea including the hydra. See Hydra.
A group of transparent, free-swimming Annelida, having setae only in the cephalic appendages.
A cytode without a proper cell wall, but with a nucleus.
A cytode without either a cell wall or a nucleus.
One of a group of plectognath fishes (Gymnodontes), having the teeth and jaws consolidated into one or two bony plates, on each jaw, as the diodonts and tetradonts. See Bur fish, Globefish, Diodon.
One of a class of plants, so called by Lindley, because the ovules are fertilized by direct contact of the pollen. Same as Gymnosperm.
A division of gastropods in which the odontophore is without teeth.
An order of Bryozoa, having no epistome.
The order of fishes which includes the Gymnotus or electrical eel. The dorsal fin is wanting.
Having young that are naked when hatched
An order of Amphibia, having a long, annulated, snakelike body. See Ophiomorpha.
A group of acalephs, including the naked-eyed medusae
A cell or mass of protoplasm devoid of an envelope, as a white blood corpuscle.
Having unfeathered nostrils, as certain birds.
One of the orders of Pteropoda.  They have no shell.

One of a sect of philosophers, said to have been found in India by Alexander the Great, who went almost naked, denied themselves the use of flesh, renounced bodily pleasures, and employed themselves in the contemplation of nature.
A plant that bears naked seeds (i. e., seeds not inclosed in an ovary), as the common pine and hemlock.  Cf. Angiosperm.
Having naked seeds, or seeds not inclosed in a capsule or other vessel.
A genus of South American fresh-water fishes, including the Gymnotus electricus, or electric eel. It has a greenish, eel-like body, and is possessed of electric power.
The part of a large house, among the ancients, exclusively appropriated to women.
A ventral canal or groove, in which the males of some di/cious trematodes carry the female. See Illust. of Haematozoa.
A plant having the stamens inserted in the pistil.
A class of plants in the Linnaean system, whose stamens grow out of, or are united with, the pistil.
Having stamens inserted in the pistil
An abnormal condition of certain animals, in which one side has the external characters of the male, and the other those of the female.
Pertaining to an abnormal condition of the flower, in which the stamens are converted into pistils.
Government by a woman, female power
The science which treats of the structure and diseases of women.
The adoration or worship of woman.
A dilated base or receptacle, supporting a multilocular ovary.
Pertaining to, or having, a gynobase.
Dioecious, but having some hermaphrodite or perfect flowers on an individual plant which bears mostly pistillate flowers.
The pistils of a flower, taken collectively. See Illust. of Carpophore.
The pedicel raising the pistil or ovary above the stamens, as in the passion flower.
The act or art of engraving on gypsum.
A cast taken in plaster of Paris, or in white lime.
A mineral consisting of the hydrous sulphate of lime (calcium). When calcined, it forms plaster of Paris. Selenite is a transparent, crystalline variety

One of a vagabond race, whose tribes, coming originally from India, entered Europe in 14th or 15th centry, and are now scattered over Turkey, Russia, Hungary, Spain, England, etc., living by theft, fortune telling, horsejockeying, tinkering, etc.  Cf. Bohemian, Romany.
The arts and practices or habits of gypsies
A labiate plant (the Lycopus Europaeus). Gypsies are said to stain their skin with its juice.
A genus of fossil fishes, found in Devonian and carboniferous strata
Moving in a circular path or way
The act of turning or whirling, as around a fixed center
Moving in a circle, or spirally
A circular motion, or a circle described by a moving body
The higher orders of Mammalia, in which the cerebrum is convoluted.

One of several species and varieties of large Arctic falcons, esp. Falco rusticolus and the white species F. Islandicus, both of which are circumpolar.  The black and the gray are varieties of the former. See Illust. of Accipiter.
A genus of extinct oolitic fishes, having rounded teeth in several rows adapted for crushing.
The petrified fruit of the Chara hispida, a species of stonewort. See Stonewort.
A genus of ganoid fishes, found in strata of the new red sandetone, and the lias bone beds.
A kind of divination performed by drawing a ring or circle, and walking in or around it.

A subordinary of triangular form having one of its angles at the fess point and the opposite aide at the edge of the escutcheon. When there is only one gyron on the shield it is bounded by two lines drawn from the fess point, one horizontally to the dexter side, and one to the dexter chief corner.
Covered with gyrons, or divided so as to form several gyrons
A flying object simulating a pigeon in flight, when projected from a spring trap. It is used as a flying target in shooting matches.

A rotating wheel, mounted in a ring or rings, for illustrating the dynamics of rotating bodies, the composition of rotations, etc. It was devised by Professor W. R. Johnson, in 1832, by whom it was called the rotascope.
Turned round like a crook, or bent to and fro.

A modification of the gyroscope, consisting essentially of a fly wheel fixed inside a rigid case to which is attached a thin flange of metal for supporting the instrument. It is used in studying the dynamics of rotating bodies.
Of or pertaining to the gyrostat or to gyrostatics.
The doctrine or theory of the gyrostat, or of the phenomena of rotating bodies.

the eighth letter of the English alphabet, is classed among the consonants, and is formed with the mouth organs in the same position as that of the succeeding vowel. It is used with certain consonants to form digraphs representing sounds which are not found in the alphabet, as sh, th, /, as in shall, thing, /ine (for zh see /274)

An exclamation denoting surprise, joy, or grief. Both as uttered and as written, it expresses a great variety of emotions, determined by the tone or the context. When repeated, ha, ha, it is an expression of laughter, satisfaction, or triumph, sometimes of derisive laughter
The deepsea fishing for cod, ling, and tusk, off the Shetland Isles.
A writ having for its object to bring a party before a court or judge
That part of a deed which follows the part called the premises, and determines the extent of the interest or estate granted
A dealer in small wares, as tapes, pins, needles, and thread
The goods and wares sold by a haberdasher
Properly, a short hauberk, but often used loosely for the hauberk.
The usual condition or state of a person or thing, either natural or acquired, regarded as something had, possessed, and firmly retained
The natural abode, locality or region of an animal or plant.
Formed or acquired by habit or use.
The act of habituating, or accustoming
One who habitually frequents a place
A short line used in drawing and engraving, especially in shading and denoting different surfaces, as in map drawing. See Hatching.
A large estate where work of any kind is done, as agriculture, manufacturing, mining, or raising of animals
A frame or grating of various kinds
A halter consisting of a long leather or rope strap and headstall, -- used for leading or tieing a pack animal.
A genus of trees (Celtis) related to the elm, but bearing drupes with scanty, but often edible, pulp. C. occidentalis is common in the Eastern United States.
The greater shearwater or hagdon. See Hagdon.
One who, or that which, hacks. Specifically: A cutting instrument for making notches
A cart with wooden wheels, drawn by bullocks.
A comb for dressing flax, raw silk, etc.
Rough or broken, as if hacked.
The driver of a hack or carriage for public hire.
The American larch (Larix Americana), a coniferous tree with slender deciduous leaves
A horse for riding or driving
A man who lets horses and carriages for hire.

A marine food fish (Melanogrammus aeglefinus), allied to the cod, inhabiting the northern coasts of Europe and America. It has a dark lateral line and a black spot on each side of the body, just back of the gills. Galled also haddie, and dickie.
The nether world (according to classical mythology, the abode of the shades, ruled over by Hades or Pluto)
The pilgrimage to Mecca, performed by Mohammedans.
An American herbivorous dinosaur of great size, allied to the iguanodon. It is found in the Cretaceous formation.
Literally, this-ness. A scholastic term to express individuality or singleness
Combining forms indicating relation or resemblance to blood, association with blood
A substance found in the blood of the octopus, which gives to it its blue color.
An apparatus for determining the number of corpuscles in a given quantity of blood.
An instrument for registering the velocity of the blood.
Pertaining to the blood or blood vessels
A brownish substance sometimes found in the blood, in cases of jaundice.
Having the limbs on, or directed toward, the ventral or hemal side, as in vertebrates
A form of apparatus (somewhat different from the hemadrometer) for measuring the velocity of the blood.
The measurement of the velocity of the blood.
Of or pertaining to the blood
One of the very minute, disk-shaped bodies found in blood with the ordinary red corpuscles and white corpuscles
The cold-blooded vertebrates. Same as Hematocrya.
The origin and development of blood.

A substance formed from the hematin of blood, by removal of the iron through the action of concentrated sulphuric acid. Two like bodies, called respectively haematoporphyrin and haematolin, are formed in a similar manner.
The science which treats of the blood. Same as Hematology.
A division of Cheiroptera, including the bloodsucking bats. See Vampire.
A vascular sac connected, beneath the brain, in many fishes, with the infundibulum.
The coloring principle of logwood. It is obtained as a yellow crystalline substance, C16H14O6, with a sweetish taste. Formerly called also hematin.
A genus of leguminous plants containing but a single species, the H. Campechianum or logwood tree, native in Yucatan.
A body obtained from hemoglobin, by the action of reducing agents in the absence of oxygen.
An apparatus for measuring the amount of hemoglobin in a fluid, by comparing it with a solution of known strength and of normal color.
A breaking up of the blood corpuscles, as by pressure, in distinction from solution of the corpuscles, or haemcytolysis.
A plant described by Milton as "of sovereign use against all enchantments."
An instrument devised by Hermann, for regulating and measuring the thickness of a layer of blood for spectroscopic examination.
A plant of the genus Prunus (P. Padus)
Born of a hag or witch.
A harquebus, of which the but was bent down or hooked for convenience in taking aim.
A soldier armed with a hagbut or arquebus.
One of several species of sea birds of the genus Puffinus
A story, anecdote, or legend in the Talmud, to explain or illustrate the text of the Old Testament.
A Scotch pudding made of the heart, liver, lights, etc., of a sheep or lamb, minced with suet, onions, oatmeal, etc., highly seasoned, and boiled in the stomach of the same animal
In the manner of a hag.
One who haggles or is difficult in bargaining.

The last of the three Jewish divisions of the Old Testament, or that portion not contained in the Law and the Prophets. It comprises Psalms, Proverbs, Job, Canticles, Ruth, Lamentations, Ecclesiastes, Esther, Daniel, Ezra, Nehemiah, and Chronicles.
Pertaining to the hagiographa, or to sacred writings.
One of the writers of the hagiographa
The invocation or worship of saints.
One who treats of the sacred writings
The history or description of the sacred writings or of sacred persons
An opening made in the interior walls of a cruciform church to afford a view of the altar to those in the transepts
Ridden by a hag or witch
The state or title of a hag.
A mineral consisting of the arseniate of lime
Formerly, a mercenary foot soldier in Hungary, now, a halberdier of a Hungarian noble, or an attendant in German or Hungarian courts.
A large piece of woolen or cotton cloth worn by Arabs as an outer garment.
The central chapel of the three forming the sanctuary of a Coptic church. It contains the high altar, and is usually closed by an embroidered curtain.
Small roundish masses of ice precipitated from the clouds, where they are formed by the congelation of vapor. The separate masses or grains are called hailstones.
Small shot which scatter like hailstones.
A single particle of ice falling from a cloud
A contraction of have not or has not
The collection or mass of filaments growing from the skin of an animal, and forming a covering for a part of the head or for any part or the whole of the body.
The diameter or breadth of a hair
Of a clear tint of brown, resembling brown human hair. It is composed of equal proportions of red and green.
A brush for cleansing and smoothing the hair.
Stuff or cloth made wholly or in part of hair.
One who dresses or cuts hair
A grass with very slender leaves or branches
The state of abounding, or being covered, with hair.
A pin, usually forked, or of bent wire, for fastening the hair in place, -- used by women.
A variety of native Epsom salt occurring in silky fibers.
One who makes excessively nice or needless distinctions in reasoning
Making excessively nice or trivial distinctions in reasoning
The slender recoil spring which regulates the motion of the balance in a timepiece.
A butterfly of the genus Thecla
Any species of marine fishes of the genus Trichiurus
A nematoid worm of the genus Gordius, resembling a hair. See Gordius.

The Egyptian asp or cobra (Naja haje.) It is related to the cobra of India, and like the latter has the power of inflating its neck into a hood. Its bite is very venomous. It is supposed to be the snake by means of whose bite Cleopatra committed suicide, and hence is sometimes called Cleopatra's snake or asp. See Asp.
A drying shed, as for unburned tile.
The general term for the Hebrew oral or traditional law
An appearance as of a halo of light, surrounding the edges of dark objects in a photographic picture.
An ancient long-handled weapon, of which the head had a point and several long, sharp edges, curved or straight, and sometimes additional points. The heads were sometimes of very elaborate form.
One who is armed with a halberd.
A kingfisher. By modern ornithologists restricted to a genus including a limited number of species having omnivorous habits, as the sacred kingfisher (Halcyon sancta) of Australia.
A genus of American shrubs containing several species, called snowdrop trees, or silver-bell trees. They have showy, white flowers, drooping on slender pedicels.
Consisting of a moiety, or half
A mixture of two malt liquors, esp. porter and ale, in about equal parts.
Any slender, marine fish of the genus Hemirhamphus, having the upper jaw much shorter than the lower
The relation between persons born of the same father or of the same mother, but not of both
Proceeding from a male and female of different breeds or races
A boot with a short top covering only the ankle. See Cocker, and Congress boot, under Congress.
Having only the back and corners in leather, as a book.
A brother by one parent, but not by both.
One born of a European parent on the one side, and of a Hindoo or Mohammedan on the other. Also adjective
To set the cock of (a firearm) at the first notch.
A shell of the genus Crepidula
One who possesses or gives half only
Showing only part of the face
A salmon in its fifth year of growth.
Imperfectly or partly heard to the end.
Done or happening at intervals of half an hour.
Of half the whole or ordinary length, as a picture.
A point some distance below the top of a mast or staff
The moon at the quarters, when half its disk appears illuminated.
A platform of a staircase where the stair turns back in exactly the reverse direction of the lower flight. See Quarterpace.
A short pike, sometimes carried by officers of infantry, sometimes used in boarding ships
One half of a shutter made in two parts for closing a porthole.
A straight line considered as drawn from a center to an indefinite distance in one direction, the complete ray being the whole line drawn to an indefinite distance in both directions.
A sister by one parent only.
Half the length of a sword
Constructed of a timber frame, having the spaces filled in with masonry
A jury, for the trial of a foreigner, composed equally of citizens and aliens.
A large, northern, marine flatfish (Hippoglossus vulgaris), of the family Pleuronectidae. It often grows very large, weighing more than three hundred pounds. It is an important food fish.
An order of sponges, having simple siliceous spicules and keratose fibers
A treatise upon fish or the art of fishing
One who writes about or describes the sea.
Like or pertaining to the genus Haliotis
A building or room of considerable size and stateliness, used for public purposes
A fee or toll paid for goods sold in a hall.
A kind of net for catching birds.
The official stamp of the Goldsmiths' Company and other assay offices, in the United Kingdom, on gold and silver articles, attesting their purity. Also used figuratively
The evening preceding Allhallows or All Saints' Day.
The feast of All Saints, or Allhallows.
A claylike mineral, occurring in soft, smooth, amorphous masses, of a whitish color.
Of or pertaining to the hallux.
One whose judgment and acts are affected by hallucinations
Partaking of, or tending to produce, hallucination.
The first, or preaxial, digit of the hind limb, corresponding to the pollux in the fore limb
The long jump, with weights in the hands, -- the most important of the exercises of the Pentathlon.

A luminous circle, usually prismatically colored, round the sun or moon, and supposed to be caused by the refraction of light through crystals of ice in the atmosphere. Connected with halos there are often white bands, crosses, or arches, resulting from the same atmospheric conditions.
An electro-negative element or radical, which, by combination with a metal, forms a haloid salt
Of the nature of a halogen.
An instrument for measuring the forms and angles of salts and crystals
Alternating transparent and opaque white rings which are seen outside the blastoderm, on the surface of the developing egg of the hen and other birds.
A plant found growing in salt marshes, or in the sea.
An instrument for exhibition or illustration of the phenomena of halos, parhelia, and the like.
An iron alum occurring in silky fibrous aggregates of a yellowish white color.
An explosive mixture, consisting of sawdust, charcoal, niter, and ferrocyanide of potassium, used as a substitute for gunpowder.
3d pers. sing. pres. of Hold, contraction for holdeth.
A term of reproach, implying that one is fit to be hanged.
In a halting or limping manner.
A rope or tackle for hoisting or lowering yards, sails, flags, etc.
A genus of Silurian fossil corals
A tree nymph whose life ended with that of the particular tree, usually an oak, which had been her abode.
The sacred baboon of Egypt (Cynocephalus Hamadryas).
A genus of plants which includes the witch-hazel (Hamamelis Virginica), a preparation of which is used medicinally.
A commercial city of Germany, near the mouth of the Elbe.
The felonious seeking and invasion of a person in his dwelling house.
A subdivision of the Devonian system of America
A large edible river fish (Erythrinus macrodon) of Guiana.
A fossil cephalopod of the genus Hamites, related to the ammonites, but having the last whorl bent into a hooklike form.
Pertaining to Ham or his descendants.
An instrument for driving nails, beating metals, and the like, consisting of a head, usually of steel or iron, fixed crosswise to a handle.
Capable of being formed or shaped by a hammer.

A member of one description of roof truss, called hammer-beam truss, which is so framed as not to have a tiebeam at the top of the wall. Each principal has two hammer-beams, which occupy the situation, and to some extent serve the purpose, of a tiebeam.
The cloth which covers a coach box.
Having the surface roughly shaped or faced with the stonecutter's hammer
One who works with a hammer.
To harden, as a metal, by hammering it in the cold state.

A shark of the genus Sphyrna or Zygaena, having the eyes set on projections from the sides of the head, which gives it a hammer shape. The Sphyrna zygaena is found in the North Atlantic. Called also hammer fish, and balance fish.
A bird of the Heron family
A stone with spangles of gold color in it.
A swinging couch or bed, usually made of netting or canvas about six feet wide, suspended by clews or cords at the ends.
Having the end hooked or curved.
A large basket, usually with a cover, used for the packing and carrying of articles
To fasten (an animal) by a rope binding the head to one of the fore legs
A small European rodent (Cricetus frumentarius). It is remarkable for having a pouch on each side of the jaw, under the skin, and for its migrations.
One of the great tendons situated in each side of the ham, or space back of the knee, and connected with the muscles of the back of the thigh.
Bearing a small hook at the end.
A rich goblet, esp. one used on state occasions.
A kind of basket, usually of wickerwork, and adapted for the packing and carrying of articles
That part of the fore limb below the forearm or wrist in man and monkeys, and the corresponding part in many other animals
A frame or barrow, without a wheel, carried by hand.
A loose, printed sheet, to be distributed by hand.
A book of reference, to be carried in the hand
A space equal to the breadth of the hand
A cart drawn or pushed by hand.
A fastening, consisting of an iron ring around the wrist, usually connected by a chain with one on the other wrist
One who hands over or transmits
In a handfast or publicly pledged manner.
As much as the hand will grasp or contain.
A small hole in a boiler for the insertion of the hand in cleaning, etc.
An allowance of a certain amount of time or distance in starting, granted in a race to the competitor possessing inferior advantages
One who determines the conditions of a handicap.
A trade requiring skill of hand
A man skilled or employed in handcraft.
The quality or state of being handy.
A piece of cloth, usually square and often fine and elegant, carried for wiping the face or hands.
A maid that waits at hand
A saw used with one hand.
A sale, gift, or delivery into the hand of another
A bar or lever, generally of wood, used in a windlass or capstan, for heaving anchor, and, in modified forms, for various purposes.
A somersault made with the assistance of the hands placed upon the ground.
As tight as can be made by the hand.
Having wings that are like hands in the structure and arrangement of their bones
The cast or form of writing peculiar to each hand or person
A child's play, one child guessing in which closed hand the other holds some small object, winning the object if right and forfeiting an equivalent if wrong
Seizure by, or grasp of, the hand
One who hangs, or causes to be hanged
One who hangs on, or sticks to, a person, place, or service
The office or character of a hangman.
A small piece or silver of skin which hangs loose, near the root of finger nail.
A nest that hangs like a bag or pocket.
A parcel consisting of two or more skeins of yarn or thread tied together.
To long (for) with a keen appetite and uneasiness
Of or pertaining to Hanover or its people, or to the House of Hanover in England.
An official report of proceedings in the British Parliament
That part of an elliptical or many-centered arch which has the shorter radius and immediately adjoins the impost.
Pertaining to the Hanse towns, or to their confederacy.
A light, low, two-wheeled covered carriage with the driver's seat elevated behind, the reins being passed over the top.
A contraction of have not, or has not, used in illiterate speech. In the United States the commoner spelling is hain't.
An order of freshwater fishes, including the true pikes, cyprinodonts, and blindfishes.
Having but one series of stamens, and that equal in number to the proper number of petals
By hap, chance, luck, or accident
Favored by hap, luck, or fortune
A large and valuable food fish (Polyprion prognathus) of New Zealand. It sometimes weighs one hundred pounds or more.
Suicide, by slashing the abdomen, formerly practiced in Japan, and commanded by the government in the cases of disgraced officials
A speech addressed to a large public assembly
One who harangues, or is fond of haranguing
The act of harassing, or state of being harassed
A station for rest and entertainment
One who, or that which, harbors.
An officer charged with the duty of executing the regulations respecting the use of a harbor.
Not easily penetrated, cut, or separated into parts
A sweetmeat of boiled brown sugar or molasses made with almonds, and flavored with orange or lemon juice, etc.
A tree of the genus Carpinus, of compact, horny texture
One who, or that which, hardens
A South African mullet, salted for food.
A term applied to a lachrymal gland on the inner side of the orbit of many animals which have a third eyelid, or nictitating membrane. See Nictitating membrane, under Nictitate.
Having coarse, unattractive or stern features.
A species of fern (Lomaria borealis), growing in Europe and Northwestern America.
A name given to several different grasses, especially to the Roltbollia incurvata, and to the species of Aegilops, from one of which it is contended that wheat has been derived.
A very astringent shrub (Spiraea tomentosa), common in pastures. The Potentilla fruticosa in also called by this name.
Having hard hands, as a manual laborer.
Clash or collision of heads in contest.
Boldness, united with firmness and constancy of mind
In a hard or difficult manner
The quality or state of being hard, literally or figuratively.
The hard substratum. Same as Hard pan, under Hard, a.
The refuse or coarse part of fiax
That which is hard to hear, as toil, privation, injury, injustice, etc.
A name given by soldiers and sailors to a kind of hard biscuit or sea bread.
Of a harsh or stern countenance
Ware made of metal, as cutlery, kitchen utensils, and the like
One who makes, or deals in, hardware.
A small, slender, branching plant (Campanula rotundifolia), having blue bell-shaped flowers
A long, narrow foot, carried (that is, produced or extending) forward
A lip, commonly the upper one, having a fissure of perpendicular division like that of a hare.
The apartments or portion of the house allotted to females in Mohammedan families.
A species of fern (Davallia Canariensis) with a soft, gray, hairy rootstock
A kind of grass (Eriophorum vaginatum). See Cotton grass, under Cotton.
The East Indian name of the Cynodon Dactylon
A ragout or stew of meat with beans and other vegetables.
A minor subdivision at the base of the Cambrian system in Wales.
A buffoon, dressed in party-colored clothes, who plays tricks, often without speaking, to divert the bystanders or an audience
A play or part of play in which the harlequin is conspicuous
Probably a corruption either of charlock or hardock.
An alkaloid found in the plant Peganum harmala. It forms bitter, yellow salts.
A dry, hot wind, prevailing on the Atlantic coast of Africa, in December, January, and February, blowing from the interior or Sahara. It is usually accompanied by a haze which obscures the sun.
A kind of rue (Ruta sylvestris) growing in India. At Lahore the seeds are used medicinally and for fumigation.
An alkaloid accompanying harmaline (in the Peganum harmala), and obtained from it by oxidation. It is a white crystalline substance.
A musical instrument, consisting of a series of hemispherical glasses which, by touching the edges with the dampened finger, give forth the tones.
A small, flat, wind instrument of music, in which the notes are produced by the vibration of free metallic reeds.
The doctrine or science of musical sounds.
An obsolete wind instrument with a keyboard, in which the sound, which resembled the oboe, was produced by the vibration of thin metallic plates, acted upon by blowing through a tube.
One who shows the agreement or harmony of corresponding passages of different authors, as of the four evangelists.

One of a religious sect, founded in Wurtemburg in the last century, composed of followers of George Rapp, a weaver. They had all their property in common. In 1803, a portion of this sect settled in Pennsylvania and called the village thus established, Harmony.

A musical instrument, resembling a small organ and especially designed for church music, in which the tones are produced by forcing air by means of a bellows so as to cause the vibration of free metallic reeds. It is now made with one or two keyboards, and has pedals and stops.
To agree in action, adaptation, or effect on the mind
An instrument for measuring the harmonic relations of sounds. It is often a monochord furnished with movable bridges.
The just adaptation of parts to each other, in any system or combination of things, or in things, or things intended to form a connected whole
A governor or prefect appointed by the Spartans in the cities subjugated by them.
A hydrous silicate of alumina and baryta, occurring usually in white cruciform crystals
Originally, the complete dress, especially in a military sense, of a man or a horse
A tub lashed to a vessel's deck and containing salted provisions for daily use
A musical instrument consisting of a triangular frame furnished with strings and sometimes with pedals, held upright, and played with the fingers.
A genus of marine univalve shells
The fore parts of the wales, which encompass the bow of a vessel, and are fastened to the stem.
A spear or javelin used to strike and kill large fish, as whales

A harp-shaped instrument of music set horizontally on legs, like the grand piano, with strings of wire, played by the fingers, by means of keys provided with quills, instead of hammers, for striking the strings. It is now superseded by the piano.
A fabulous winged monster, ravenous and filthy, having the face of a woman and the body of a vulture, with long claws, and the face pale with hunger. Some writers mention two, others three.

A firearm with match holder, trigger, and tumbler, made in the second half of the 15th century. the barrel was about forty inches long. A form of the harquebus was subsequently called arquebus with matchlock.
One of a small breed of hounds, used for hunting hares.

An implement of agriculture, usually formed of pieces of timber or metal crossing each other, and set with iron or wooden teeth. It is drawn over plowed land to level it and break the clods, to stir the soil and make it fine, or to cover seed when sown.
The quality or state of being harsh.
A large South African antelope (Alcelaphus caama), formerly much more abundant than it is now. The face and legs are marked with black, the rump with white.
The Hartford grape, a variety of grape first raised at Hartford, Connecticut, from the Northern fox grape. Its large dark-colored berries ripen earlier than those of most other kinds.
Melilot or sweet clover. See Melilot.
An Asiatic species of Cacalia (C. Kleinia), used medicinally in India.
The horn or antler of the hart, or male red deer.
A common British fern (Scolopendrium vulgare), rare in America.
A coarse umbelliferous plant of Europe (Tordylium maximum).
A diviner of ancient Rome. Same as Aruspice.
The art or practices of haruspices. See Aruspicy.
The gathering of a crop of any kind
The gathering and bringing home of the harvest
That which is hashed or chopped up
A slightly acrid gum resin produced by the common hemp (Cannabis saltiva), of the variety Indica, when cultivated in a warm climate
A basket made of rushes or flags, as for carrying fish.
The edible viscera, as the heart, liver, etc., of a beast, esp. of a hog.
A clasp, especially a metal strap permanently fast at one end to a staple or pin, while the other passes over a staple, and is fastened by a padlock or a pin
A rank tuft of bog grass
2d pers. sing. pres. of. Have, contr. of havest.
Shaped like the head of a halberd
The quality or state of being hasty
The lower group of the Wealden formation
A thick batter pudding made of Indian meal stirred into boiling water
Capable of being, or deserving to be, hated
A band round the crown of a hat
To cross with lines in a peculiar manner in drawing and engraving. See Hatching.
A vessel whose deck consists almost wholly of movable hatches
An instrument with long iron teeth set in a board, for cleansing flax or hemp from the tow, hards, or coarse part
One who hatches, or that which hatches
A house for hatching fish, etc.
A small ax with a short handle, to be used with one hand.

A sort of panel, upon which the arms of a deceased person are temporarily displayed, -- usually on the walls of his dwelling. It is lozenge-shaped or square, but is hung cornerwise. It is used in England as a means of giving public notification of the death of the deceased, his or her rank, whether married, widower, widow, etc. Called also achievement.
A square or oblong opening in a deck or floor, affording passage from one deck or story to another
To have a great aversion to, with a strong desire that evil should befall the person toward whom the feeling is directed
A stand of wood or iron, with hooks or pegs upon which to hang hats, etc.

A New Zealand lizard, which, in anatomical character, differs widely from all other existing lizards. It is the only living representative of the order Rhynchocephala, of which many Mesozoic fossil species are known
A irrevocable Turkish decree countersigned by the sultan.
Native sulphide of manganese a reddish brown or brownish black mineral.
A low-lying meadow by the side of a river.
To pull or draw with force
The denuded stems or stalks of such crops as buckwheat and the cereal grains, beans, etc.
One who, or that which, haunts.
In pale, with the head in chief
A large sturgeon (Acipenser huso) from the region of the Black Sea. It is sometimes twelve feet long.
A kind of graduated breech sight for a small arm, or a cannon.
An artificial division of insects, including all those with a sucking proboscis.
Provided with a haustellum, or sucking proboscis.
The sucking proboscis of various insects. See Lepidoptera, and Diptera.
One of the suckerlike rootlets of such plants as the dodder and ivy.
A wind instrument, sounded through a reed, and similar in shape to the clarinet, but with a thinner tone. Now more commonly called oboe. See Illust. of Oboe.
A raised part of the floor of a large room
A blue isometric mineral, characteristic of some volcani/ rocks. It is a silicate of alumina, lime, and soda, with sulphate of lime.
Of or pertaining to Havana, the capital of the island of Cuba
Of or pertaining to Havana, in Cuba.
A light cloth covering for the head and neck, used by soldiers as a protection from sunstroke.
A bay, recess, or inlet of the sea, or the mouth of a river, which affords anchorage and shelter for shipping
A bag for oats or oatmeal.
Pertaining to, or discovered by, Clopton Havers, an English physician of the seventeenth century.
In the British Indian armies, a noncommissioned officer of native soldiers, corresponding to a sergeant.
Belonging to Hawaii or the Sandwich Islands, or to the people of Hawaii.
Probably, the baked berry of the hawthorn tree, that is, coarse fare. See 1st Haw, 2.

One of numerous species and genera of rapacious birds of the family Falconidae. They differ from the true falcons in lacking the prominent tooth and notch of the bill, and in having shorter and less pointed wings. Many are of large size and grade into the eagles. Some, as the goshawk, were formerly trained like falcons. In a more general sense the word is not infrequently applied, also, to true falcons, as the sparrow hawk, pigeon hawk, duck hawk, and prairie hawk.
A sea turtle (Eretmochelys imbricata), which yields the best quality of tortoise shell
One who sells wares by crying them in the street

Any moth of the family Sphingidae, of which there are numerous genera and species. They are large, handsome moths, which fly mostly at twilight and hover about flowers like a humming bird, sucking the honey by means of a long, slender proboscis. The larvae are large, hairless caterpillars ornamented with green and other bright colors, and often with a caudal spine. See Sphinx, also Tobacco worm, and Tomato worm.
A plant of the genus Hieracium
A large rope made of three strands each containing many yarns.
Made in the manner of a hawser.  Cf. Cable-laid, and see Illust. of Cordage.

A thorny shrub or tree (the Crataegus oxyacantha), having deeply lobed, shining leaves, small, roselike, fragrant flowers, and a fruit called haw. It is much used in Europe for hedges, and for standards in gardens. The American hawthorn is Crataegus cordata, which has the leaves but little lobed.
An allowance of wood to a tenant for repairing his hedges or fences
A conical pile or hear of hay in the field.
A machine in which hay is chopped short, as fodder for cattle.
A field where grass for hay has been cut
A fork for pitching and tedding hay.
A loft or scaffold for hay.
One who cuts and cures hay.
The operation or work of cutting grass and curing it for hay.
A mow or mass of hay laid up in a barn for preservation.
A frame mounted on the running gear of a wagon, and used in hauling hay, straw, sheaves, etc.
A heap or pile of hay, usually covered with thatch for preservation in the open air.
A stack or conical pile of hay in the open air.
An officer who is appointed to guard hedges, and to keep cattle from breaking or cropping them, and whose further duty it is to impound animals found running at large.
A game of chance played with dice.
A player at the game of hazard
Light vapor or smoke in the air which more or less impedes vision, with little or no dampness
A shrub or small tree of the genus Corylus, as the C. avellana, bearing a nut containing a kernel of a mild, farinaceous taste
Of the color of the hazelnut
The quality or state of being hazy.
The man or male being (or object personified to which the masculine gender is assigned), previously designated
The anterior or superior part of an animal, containing the brain, or chief ganglia of the nervous system, the mouth, and in the higher animals, the chief sensory organs
A board or boarding which marks or forms the head of anything
The chief of a frankpledge, tithing, or decennary, consisting of ten families
A dish made of portions of the head, or head and feet, of swine, cut up fine, seasoned, and pressed into a cheeselike mass.
A covering or ornament for the head
One who, or that which, heads nails, rivets, etc., esp. a machine for heading.
A member of any tribe or race of savages who have the custom of decapitating human beings and preserving their heads as trophies. The Dyaks of Borneo are the most noted head-hunters.
In a heady or rash manner
A light, with a powerful reflector, placed at the head of a locomotive, or in front of it, to throw light on the track at night, or in going through a dark tunnel.
The line at the head or top of a page.
Lugged or dragged by the head.
A head or leading man, especially of a village community.
An old name for the condition of the skull, in which the bones ride, or are shot, over each other at the sutures.
A note at the head of a page or chapter
The quarters or place of residence of any chief officer, as the general in command of an army, or the head of a police force
That part of a boltrope which is sewed to the upper edge or head of a sail.
Any sail set forward of the foremast.
A significant shake of the head, commonly as a signal of denial.
An executioner who cuts off heads.
That part of a bridle or halter which encompasses the head.
A part (usually separate from the bed or frame) for supporting some of the principal working parts of a machine
The principal stone in a foundation
The progress made by a ship in motion
To cover, as a roof, with tiles, slate, lead, or the like.
A common herb of the Mint family (Brunela vulgaris), destitute of active properties, but anciently thought a panacea.
So as to heal or cure.
The state of being hale, sound, or whole, in body, mind, or soul
The state of being healthy or healthful
Without health, whether of body or mind
Being in a state of health
The afterbirth or secundines of a beast.
One who heaps, piles, or amasses.
A hind in the year of its age.
A cloth for covering a coffin when on a bier
A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood.
An uneasy, burning sensation in the stomach, often attended with an inclination to vomit. It is sometimes idiopathic, but is often a symptom of often complaints.
One who, or that which, heartens, animates, or stirs up.
The pavement or floor of brick, stone, or metal in a chimney, on which a fire is made
An exclamation used in addressing a familiar acquaintance.
A climbing plant of the genus Cardiospermum, having round seeds which are marked with a spot like a heart.
Having the shape of a heart
A nerve or tendon, supposed to brace and sustain the heart.
Rankling in, or swelling, the heart.
Having the heart or affections free

The hard, central part of the trunk of a tree, consisting of the old and matured wood, and usually differing in color from the outer layers. It is technically known as duramen, and distinguished from the softer sapwood or alburnum.
Wounded to the heart with love or grief.
Pertaining to, or proceeding from, the heart

A force in nature which is recognized in various effects, but especially in the phenomena of fusion and evaporation, and which, as manifested in fire, the sun's rays, mechanical action, chemical combination, etc., becomes directly known to us through the sense of feeling. In its nature heat is a mode if motion, being in general a form of molecular disturbance or vibration. It was formerly supposed to be a subtile, imponderable fluid, to which was given the name caloric.
One who, or that which, heats.

A low shrub (Erica, / Calluna, vulgaris), with minute evergreen leaves, and handsome clusters of pink flowers. It is used in Great Britain for brooms, thatch, beds for the poor, and for heating ovens. It is also called heather, and ling.
That part of the world where heathenism prevails
Of or pertaining to the heathen
The state or quality of being heathenish.
The religious system or rites of a heathen nation
State of being heathen or like the heathen.
The state, quality, or character of the heathen.
To cause to move upward or onward by a lifting effort
The expanse of space surrounding the earth
To render like heaven or fit for heaven.
The state or quality of being heavenly.
Pertaining to, resembling, or inhabiting heaven
Having the thoughts and affections placed on, or suitable for, heaven and heavenly objects
An offering or oblation heaved up or elevated before the altar, as the shoulder of the peace offering. See Wave offering.
One who, or that which, heaves or lifts
A disease of horses, characterized by difficult breathing, with heaving of the flank, wheezing, flatulency, and a peculiar cough
The state or quality of being heavy in its various senses
Native barium sulphate or barite, -- so called because of its high specific gravity as compared with other non-metallic minerals.
Consisting of seven days, or occurring at intervals of seven days
The goddess of youth, daughter of Jupiter and Juno. She was believed to have the power of restoring youth and beauty to those who had lost them.
The act of making blunt, dull, or stupid.
Of or pertaining to the Hebrews, or to the language of the Hebrews.
After the manner of the Hebrews or of the Hebrew language.
One versed in the Hebrew language and learning.
Pertaining to, or resembling, the Hebrew language or idiom.
In a Hebraistic sense or form.
To convert into the Hebrew idiom
An appellative of Abraham or of one of his descendants, esp. in the line of Jacob
Of or pertaining to the islands called Hebrides, west of Scotland.
A sacrifice of a hundred oxen or cattle at the same time
A name given to the old Parthenon at Athens, because measuring 100 Greek feet, probably in the width across the stylobate.

A white, semisolid, spermaceti-like hydrocarbon, C16H34, of the paraffin series, found dissolved as an important ingredient of kerosene, and so called because each molecule has sixteen atoms of carbon
The bolt or latch of a door.
A measure of area, or superficies, containing a hundred ares, or 10,000 square meters, and equivalent to 2.471 acres.

One of the arms of the male of most kinds of cephalopods, which is specially modified in various ways to effect the fertilization of the eggs. In a special sense, the greatly modified arm of Argonauta and allied genera, which, after receiving the spermatophores, becomes detached from the male, and attaches itself to the female for reproductive purposes.
A measure of weight, containing a hundred grams, or about 3.527 ounces avoirdupois.
A contrivance for multiple copying, by means of a surface of gelatin softened with glycerin.
A measure of liquids, containing a hundred liters
A measure of length, equal to a hundred meters. It is equivalent to 328.09 feet.
The disposition or the practice of a hector
A measure of solidity, containing one hundred cubic meters, and equivalent to 3531.66 English or 3531.05 United States cubic feet.
One of the sets of parallel doubled threads which, with mounting, compose the harness employed to guide the warp threads to the lathe or batten in a loom.
The eye or loop formed in each heddle to receive a warp thread.
The act of drawing the warp threads through the heddle-eyes of a weaver's harness
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, ivy.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the ivy (Hedera)
A thicket of bushes, usually thorn bushes

A small European insectivore (Erinaceus Europaeus), and other allied species of Asia and Africa, having the hair on the upper part of its body mixed with prickles or spines. It is able to roll itself into a ball so as to present the spines outwardly in every direction. It is nocturnal in its habits, feeding chiefly upon insects.
One who makes or mends hedges
A row of shrubs, or trees, planted for inclosure or separation of fields.
A hedge bill. See under Hedge.
To lean or tip to one side, as a ship
A composition of wax and lampblack, used by shoemakers for polishing, and by antiquaries in copying inscriptions.
A cock that strikes well with his heels or spurs.
A piece of armor to protect the heels.
The post supporting the outer end of a propeller shaft.
A slender bony or cartilaginous process developed from the heel bone of bats. It helps to support the wing membranes. See Illust. of Cheiropter.
One of the segments of leather in the heel of a shoe.
A tool used by turners in metal, having a bend forming a heel near the cutting end.
A yarn measure of six hundred yards or / of a spindle. See Spindle.
The system of logic and philosophy set forth by Hegel, a German writer (1770-1831).
The flight of Mohammed from Mecca, September 13, A. D. 622 (subsequently established as the first year of the Moslem era)
An exclamation of surprise, joy, dejection, uneasiness, weariness, etc.
One who, or that which, heightens.
One who inherits, or is entitled to succeed to the possession of, any property after the death of its owner
Any furniture, movable, or personal chattel, which by law or special custom descends to the heir along with the inheritance
The state, character, or privileges of an heir
Same as Hectare, Hectogram, Hectoliter, and Hectometer.
The act or process of repairing lesions made by ulcers, especially by a plastic operation.
See St. Elmo's fire, under Saint.
A neutral organic substance found in the root of the elecampane (Inula helenium), and extracted as a white crystalline or oily material, with a slightly bitter taste.
Emerging from the light of the sun, or passing into it
An artificial, orange dyestuff, analogous to tropaolin, and like it used as an indicator in alkalimetry
Of or pertaining to the Helianthoidea.
Of or pertaining to, or in the form of, a helix
A genus of composite plants, with shining, commonly white or yellow, or sometimes reddish, radiated involucres, which are often called "everlasting flowers."
Having the form of a helix
A glucoside obtained as a white crystalline substance by partial oxidation of salicin, from a willow (Salix Helix of Linnaeus.)
An instrument for drawing spiral lines on a plane.
A mountain in Boeotia, in Greece, supposed by the Greeks to be the residence of Apollo and the Muses.
One of numerous species of Heliconius, a genus of tropical American butterflies. The wings are usually black, marked with green, crimson, and white.
The opening by which the two scalae communicate at the top of the cochlea of the ear.
A combining form from Gr. "h`lios the sun.
pertaining to the sun's center, or appearing to be seen from it
Pertaining to, or produced by, heliochromy.
The art of producing photographs in color.
Of or pertaining to heliography or a heliograph
A fossil coral of the genus Heliolites, having twelve-rayed cells. It is found in the Silurian rocks.
An instrument devised originally for measuring the diameter of the sun
Of or pertaining to the heliometer, or to heliometry.
The apart or practice of measuring the diameters of heavenly bodies, their relative distances, etc. See Heliometer.
An East Indian stony coral now known to belong to the Alcyonaria
A telescope or instrument for viewing the sun without injury to the eyes, as through colored glasses, or with mirrors which reflect but a small portion of light.
An instrument consisting of a mirror moved by clockwork, by which a sunbeam is made apparently stationary, by being steadily directed to one spot during the whole of its diurnal period
An instrument or machine for showing when the sun arrived at the tropics and equinoctial line.
The person at a geodetic station who has charge of the heliotrope.
The phenomenon of turning toward the light, seen in many leaves and flowers.
A picture obtained by the process of heliotypy.
Relating to, or obtained by, heliotypy.
A method of transferring pictures from photographic negatives to hardened gelatin plates from which impressions are produced on paper as by lithography.
An order of fresh-water rhizopods having a more or less globular form, with slender radiating pseudopodia
