Chemistry applied to, or used in, medicine
Of or pertaining to iatromathematicians or their doctrine.
One of a school of physicians in Italy, about the middle of the 17th century, who tried to apply the laws of mechanics and mathematics to the human body, and hence were eager student of anatomy
One of several species of wild goats having very large, recurved horns, transversely ridged in front

Any bird of the genus Ibis and several allied genera, of the family Ibidae, inhabiting both the Old World and the New. Numerous species are known. They are large, wading birds, having a long, curved beak, and feed largely on reptiles.
A suffix signifying, in general, relating to, or characteristic of
Soaring too high for safety, like Icarus

J is the tenth letter of the English alphabet. It is a later variant form of the Roman letter I, used to express a consonantal sound, that is, originally, the sound of English y in yet. The forms J and I have, until a recent time, been classed together, and they have been used interchangeably.
A species of wild goat (Capra Nubiana) found in the mountains of Abyssinia, Upper Egypt, and Arabia
To talk rapidly, indistinctly, or unintelligibly
One of several large wading birds of the genera Mycteria and Xenorhynchus, allied to the storks in form and habits.
The native name of a South American rutaceous shrub (Pilocarpus pennatifolius). The leaves are used in medicine as an diaphoretic and sialogogue.
An alkaloid found in jaborandi leaves, from which it is extracted as a white amorphous substance. In its action it resembles atropine.
Originally, a kind of ruffle worn by men on the bosom of the shirt.

Any one of numerous species of tropical American birds of the genus Galbula and allied genera. They are allied to the kingfishers, but climb on tree trunks like nuthatches, and feed upon insects. Their colors are often brilliant.

Any of several wading birds belonging to the genus Jacana and several allied genera, all of which have spurs on the wings. They are able to run about over floating water weeds by means of their very long, spreading toes. Called also surgeon bird.
The native Brazilian name for certain leguminous trees, which produce the beautiful woods called king wood, tiger wood, and violet wood.
The common marmoset (Hapale vulgaris). Formerly, the name was also applied to other species of the same genus.

A large tree, the Artocarpus integrifolia, common in the East Indies, closely allied to the breadfruit, from which it differs in having its leaves entire. The fruit is of great size, weighing from thirty to forty pounds, and through its soft fibrous matter are scattered the seeds, which are roasted and eaten. The wood is of a yellow color, fine grain, and rather heavy, and is much used in cabinetwork. It is also used for dyeing a brilliant yellow.

Any one of several species of carnivorous animals inhabiting Africa and Asia, related to the dog and wolf. They are cowardly, nocturnal, and gregarious. They feed largely on carrion, and are noted for their piercing and dismal howling.
A small stuffed puppet to be pelted in Lent
A short upper garment, extending downward to the hips
Wearing, or furnished with, a jacket.
A large, strong clasp knife for the pocket
A jack in which a screw is used for lifting, or exerting pressure. See Illust. of 2d Jack, n., 5.
A smith who makes jacks. See 2d Jack, 4, c.
A rail of wood or iron stretching along a yard of a vessel, to which the sails are fastened.
One of the pebbles or pieces used in the game of jackstones.
Wood of the jack (Artocarpus integrifolia), used in cabinetwork.
A Hebrew patriarch (son of Isaac, and ancestor of the Jews), who in a vision saw a ladder reaching up to heaven (Gen. xxviii. 12)
A bulbous plant  (Amaryllis, / Sprekelia, formosissima) from Mexico. It bears a single, large, deep, red, lilylike flower.
Of or pertaining to a style of architecture and decoration in the time of James the First, of England.
Of or pertaining to the Jacobins of France
To taint with, or convert to, Jacobinism.
A partisan or adherent of James the Second, after his abdication, or of his descendants, an opposer of the revolution in 1688 in favor of William and Mary.
Of or pertaining to the Jacobites
An English gold coin, of the value of twenty-five shillings sterling, struck in the reign of James I.
A thin cotton fabric, between and muslin, used for dresses, neckcloths, etc.
Pertaining to, or invented by, Jacquard, a French mechanician, who died in 1834.
A half-hardy, deep crimson  rose of the remontant class

The name given to a revolt of French peasants against the nobles in 1358, the leader assuming the contemptuous title, Jacques Bonhomme, given by the nobles to the peasantry. Hence, any revolt of peasants.
A throwing or tossing of the body
Vain boasting or assertions repeated to the prejudice of another's right
To throw or cast, as a dart
The act of tossing, throwing, or hurling, as spears.

A stone, commonly of a pale to dark green color but sometimes whitish. It is very hard and compact, capable of fine polish, and is used for ornamental purposes and for implements, esp. in Eastern countries and among many early peoples.
One who carries about a small load
Raw palm sugar, made in the East Indies by evaporating the fresh juice of several kinds of palm trees, but specifically that of the palmyra (Borassus flabelliformis).
A village or district the government and revenues of which are assigned to some person, usually in consideration of some service to be rendered, esp. the maintenance of troops.
A great Brazilian palm (Maximiliana regia), having immense spathes which are used for baskets and tubs.

A large and powerful feline animal (Felis onca), ranging from Texas and Mexico to Patagonia. It is usually brownish yellow, with large, dark, somewhat angular rings, each generally inclosing one or two dark spots. It is chiefly arboreal in its habits. Called also the American tiger.

A South American wild cat (Felis jaguarondi), having a long, slim body and very short legs. Its color is grayish brown, varied with a blackish hue. It is arboreal in its habits and feeds mostly on birds.
The keeper of a jail or prison.
One of a numerous sect in British India, holding the tenets of Jainism.

The heterodox Hindoo religion, of which the most striking features are the exaltation of saints or holy mortals, called jins, above the ordinary Hindoo gods, and the denial of the divine origin and infallibility of the Vedas. It is intermediate between Brahmanism and Buddhism, having some things in common with each.
A South American striped frog (Pseudis paradoxa), remarkable for having a tadpole larger than the adult, and hence called also paradoxical frog.
An African parrot (Psittacus erithacus), very commonly kept as a cage bird

The tubers of the Mexican plant Ipomoea purga (or Exogonium purga), a climber much like the morning-glory. The abstract, extract, and powder, prepared from the tubers, are well known purgative medicines. Other species of Ipomoea yield several inferior kinds of jalap, as the I. Orizabensis, and I. tuberosa.
A glucoside found in the stems of the jalap plant and scammony. It is a strong purgative.
Long poles, topped with wisps of straw, used as landmarks and signals.
A Venetian or slatted inside window blind.
A kind of frock for children.
One of the West India is islands.
An alkaloid said to be contained in the bark of Geoffroya inermis, a leguminous tree growing in Jamaica and Surinam
The vertical side of any opening, as a door or fireplace
In the Middle Ages, armor for the legs below the knees.
A myrtaceous tree of the West Indies and tropical America (Calyptranthes Jambolana), with astringent bark, used for dyeing. It bears an edible fruit.
A silk fabric, with a woven pattern of sprigs of flowers.
A steel-gray mineral, of metallic luster, commonly fibrous massive. It is a sulphide of antimony and lead, with a little iron.
Antimonial powder, first prepared by Dr. James, ar English physician
The poisonous thorn apple or stramonium (Datura stramonium), a rank weed early noticed at Jamestown, Virginia. See Datura.
One of intermediate order between angels and men.
To sound harshly or discordantly, as bells out of tune.
Of or pertaining to the janizaries, or their government.
A soldier of a privileged military class, which formed the nucleus of the Turkish infantry, but was suppressed in 1826.
A long pole on two wheels, used in hauling logs.
The doctrine of Jansen regarding free will and divine grace.
A follower of Cornelius Jansen, a Roman Catholic bishop of Ypres, in Flanders, in the 17th century, who taught certain doctrines denying free will and the possibility of resisting divine grace.
A machine of great antiquity, used in Bengal for raising water to irrigate land.
The first month of the year, containing thirty-one days.

A Latin deity represented with two faces looking in opposite directions. Numa is said to have dedicated to Janus the covered passage at Rome, near the Forum, which is usually called the Temple of Janus. This passage was open in war and closed in peace.
Work varnished and figured in the Japanese manner
Of or pertaining to Japan, or its inhabitants.
One who varnishes in the manner of the Japanese, or one skilled in the art.
After the manner of the Japanese
Pertaining to, or derived from, Japheth, one of the sons of Noah
A species of Camellia (Camellia Japonica), a native of Japan, bearing beautiful red or white flowers. Many other genera have species of the same name.
A poisonous serpent of Brazil (Bothrops jararaca), about eighteen inches long, and of a dusky, brownish color, variegated with red and black spots.
An ornamental stand or receptacle for plants, flowers, etc., used as a piece of decorative furniture in room.
A callous tumor on the leg of a horse, below the hock.
To emit a harsh or discordant sound.
A variety of pear which ripens early.
Of or pertaining to the mineral jargon.
An ocher-yellow mineral occurring on minute rhombohedral crystals. It is a hydrous sulphate of iron and potash.
The mahoganylike wood of the Australian Eucalyptus marginata. See Eucalyptus.
In a jarring or discordant manner.
The driver of a hackney coach.

A shrubby plant of the genus Jasminum, bearing flowers of a peculiarly fragrant odor. The J. officinale, common in the south of Europe, bears white flowers. The Arabian jasmine is J. Sambac, and, with J. angustifolia, comes from the East Indies. The yellow false jasmine in the Gelseminum sempervirens (see Gelsemium). Several other plants are called jasmine in the West Indies, as species of Calotropis and Faramea.

An opaque, impure variety of quartz, of red, yellow, and other dull colors, breaking with a smooth surface. It admits of a high polish, and is used for vases, seals, snuff boxes, etc. When the colors are in stripes or bands, it is called striped /  banded jasper. The Egyptian pebble is a brownish yellow jasper.
To convert into, or make to resemble, jasper.
Consisting of jasper, or containing jasper
A compact siliceous rock resembling jasper.
An onyx, part or all of whose layers consist of jasper.
Of or pertaining to physic nuts, the seeds of plants of the genus Jatropha.

A morbid condition, characterized by yellowness of the eyes, skin, and urine, whiteness of the faeces, constipation, uneasiness in the region of the stomach, loss of appetite, and general languor and lassitude. It is caused usually by obstruction of the biliary passages and consequent damming up, in the liver, of the bile, which is then absorbed into the blood.
One of the islands of the Malay Archipelago belonging to the Netherlands.
Of or pertaining to Java, or to the people of Java.
A sort of light spear, to be thrown or cast by thew hand
A soldier armed with a javelin.
One of the bones, usually bearing teeth, which form the framework of the mouth.

Any one of the numerous species of birds belonging to Garrulus, Cyanocitta, and allied genera. They are allied to the crows, but are smaller, more graceful in form, often handsomely colored, and usually have a crest.
A name given to a free-booting, unenlisted, armed man or guerrilla.
A gem of an azure color.
A coat of defense made of small plates of metal sewed upon linen or the like
State or quality of being jealous.
A stone mason's tool, having a flat face and a pointed part.
An American herb with a pretty, white, solitary blossom, and deeply two-cleft leaves (Jeffersonia diphylla)
Pertaining to, or characteristic of, Thomas Jefferson or his policy or political doctrines.
A variety of pyroxene of olive-green color passing into brown. It contains zinc.
A Scripture name of the Supreme Being, by which he was revealed to the Jews as their covenant God or Sovereign of the theocracy
One who maintains that the vowel points of the word Jehovah, in Hebrew, are the proper vowels of that word
Relating to, or containing, Jehovah, as a name of God
The middle division of the small intestine, between the duodenum and ileum
A large, handsome squirrel (Sciurus Javensis), native of Java and Southern Asia
Brought to the state or consistence of jelly.
Anything brought to a gelatinous condition
Any one of the acalephs, esp. one of the larger species, having a jellylike appearance. See Medusa.
The chief or leader of a hand or body of persons
A Mexican name for the Sisal hemp (Agave rigida, var. Sisalana)
name of contempt for a flatterer of persons high in social or official life
A variety of early apple. See Juneating.
A familiar or pet form of the proper name Jane.
A fish of the genus Leuciscus
An oversight in pleading, or the acknowledgment of a mistake or oversight.
To expose to loss or injury
Exposure to death, loss, or injury
Any small jumping rodent of the genus Dipus, esp. D. Aegyptius, which is common in Egypt and the adjacent countries. The jerboas have very long hind legs and a long tail.
A blunt javelin used by the people of the Levant, especially in mock fights.
A tale of sorrow, disappointment, or complaint
To cut into long slices or strips and dry in the sun
The hipped part of a roof which is hipped only for a part of its height, leaving a truncated gable.
One belonging of the mediaeval religious orders called Hermits of St. Jerome.
A customhouse officer who searches ships for unentered goods.
The searching of a ship for unentered goods.
Built hastily and of bad materials
The finest of wool separated from the rest
The chief city of Palestine, intimately associated with the glory of the Jewish nation, and the life and death of Jesus Christ.
A poisonous alkaloid resembling veratrine, and found with it in white hellebore (Veratrum album)
A short strap of leather or silk secured round the leg of a hawk, to which the leash or line, wrapped round the falconer's hand, was attached when used. See Illust. of Falcon.
Any representation or suggestion of the genealogy of Christ, in decorative art
Having jesses on, as a hawk.
One of a religious order founded by Ignatius Loyola, and approved in 1540, under the title of The Society of Jesus.
Conforming to the principles of the Jesuits.
One of an order of nuns established on the principles of the Jesuits, but suppressed by Pope Urban in 1633.
Of or pertaining to the Jesuits, or to their principles and methods.
The principles and practices of the Jesuits.
A stream of water spouting from a fountain or pipe (especially from one arranged to throw water upward), in a public place or in a garden, for ornament.
A yellowness of the parts of plants which are normally green
Goods which sink when cast into the sea, and remain under water
The throwing overboard of goods from necessity, in order to lighten a vessel in danger of wreck.
A metal counter used in playing cards.
Made of jet, or like jet in color.
Originally, one belonging to the tribe or kingdom of Judah
A euphorbiaceous shrub of the genus Pedilanthus (P. tithymaloides), found in the West Indies, and possessing powerful emetic and drastic qualities.
An ornament of dress usually made of a precious metal, and having enamel or precious stones as a part of its design.
One who makes, or deals in, jewels, precious stones, and similar ornaments.
The art or trade of a jeweler.

A very large serranoid fish (Promicrops itaiara) of Florida and the Gulf of Mexico. It often reaches the weight of five hundred pounds. Its color is olivaceous or yellowish, with numerous brown spots. Called also guasa, and warsaw.
Of or pertaining to the Jews or Hebrews
A species of fungus (Hirneola Auricula-Judae, / Auricula), bearing some resemblance to the human ear.
An instrument of music, which, when placed between the teeth, gives, by means of a bent metal tongue struck by the finger, a sound which is modulated by the breath
A large clavate spine of a fossil sea urchin.
A wild goat (Capra Jemlaica) which inhabits the loftiest mountains of India. It has long, coarse hair, forming a thick mane on its head and neck.
A triangular sail set upon a stay or halyard extending from the foremast or fore-topmast to the bowsprit or the jib boom. Large vessels often carry several jibe
To shift, as the boom of a fore-and-aft sail, from one side of a vessel to the other when the wind is aft or on the quarter. See Gybe.
A species of flea (Sarcopsylla, / Pulex, penetrans), which burrows beneath the skin. See Chigoe.
Resembling, or suitable for, a jig, or lively movement.
A light, giddy, or wanton girl or woman. See Gill-flirt.
A woman who capriciously deceives her lover
A machine for bending or straightening rails.
A short crowbar used by burglars in breaking open doors.
A small portable piece of ordnance, mounted on a swivel.
To sound with a fine, sharp, rattling, clinking, or tinkling sound
One who, or that which, jingles.
A word used as a jocular oath.
The policy of the Jingoes, so called. See Jingo, 2.
An inclined road in a coal mine, on which loaded cars descend by gravity, drawing up empty ones.
A small, two-wheeled, hooded vehicle drawn by one more men.
A waistcoat or kind of stays for women.
One who works by the job.
The act or practice of jobbing.
The act or practice of jesting.
A professional rider of horses in races.
The art, character, or position, of a jockey
The state or quality of being jocund
A tall composite plant of the genus Eupatorium (E. purpureum), with purplish flowers, and whorled leaves.
To push or shake with the elbow or hand
Of or pertaining to John, esp. to the Apostle John or his writings.
A Portuguese gold coin of the value of eight dollars, named from the figure of King John which it bears
A fine white wine produced on the estate of Schloss (or Castle) Johannisberg, on the Rhine.
A proper name of a man.
A kind of bread made of the meal of maize (Indian corn), mixed with water or milk, etc., and baked.
The literary style of Dr. Samuel Johnson, or one formed in imitation of it

A tall perennial grass (Sorghum Halepense), valuable in the Southern and Western States for pasture and hay. The rootstocks are large and juicy and are eagerly sought by swine. Called also Cuba grass, Means grass, Evergreen millet, and Arabian millet.
Pertaining to or resembling Dr. Johnson or his style
A manner of acting or of writing peculiar to, or characteristic of, Dr. Johnson.
To bring together, literally or figuratively
One who, or that which, joins.
The art, or trade, of a joiner
Writing in which letters are joined in words
The place or part where two things or parts are joined or united
One who, or that which, joints.
A genus (Ephedra) of leafless shrubs, with the stems conspicuously jointed
A woman who has a jointure.
A slender, nearly leafless, American herb (Polygonum articulatum), with jointed spikes of small flowers.

The larva of a small, hymenopterous fly (Eurytoma hordei), which is found in gall-like swellings on the stalks of wheat, usually at or just above the first joint. In some parts of America it does great damage to the crop.
A piece of timber laid horizontally, or nearly so, to which the planks of the floor, or the laths or furring strips of a ceiling, are nailed
Something said for the sake of exciting a laugh
One who makes jokes or jests.
A boat of medium size belonging to a ship.
To shake with short, abrupt risings and fallings, as a carriage moving on rough ground
One who, or that which, jolts.
The Hebrew prophet, who was cast overboard as one who endangered the ship
In the Middle Ages, a court attendant or other person who, for hire, recited or sang verses, usually of his own composition. See Troubadour.

A bulbous plant of the genus Narcissus (N. Jonquilla), allied to the daffodil. It has long, rushlike leaves, and yellow or white fragrant flowers. The root has emetic properties. It is sometimes called the rush-leaved daffodil. See Illust. of Corona.
A pot or vessel with a large neck, formerly used by physicians and alchemists.
An outer garment worn in the 18th century
A composite herb (Tragopogon pratensis), of the same genus as the salsify.
A command to a horse, probably meaning "stand still."
An iron collar fastened to a wall or post, formerly used in Scotland as a kind of pillory. [Written also juggs.] See Juke.

A unit of work which is equal to 107 units of work in the C. G. S. system of units (ergs), and is practically equivalent to the energy expended in one second by an electric current of one ampere in a resistance of one ohm. One joule is approximately equal to 0.738 foot pounds.
The keeping of a journal or diary.
One who keeps a journal or diary.
Pertaining to journals or to journalists
To enter or record in a journal or diary.
The travel or work of a day.
Formerly, a man hired to work by the day
Originally, work done by the day
To engage in mock combat on horseback, as two knights in the lists
The chief divinity of the ancient Romans
Of or pertaining to the god, or the planet, Jupiter.
One who lives a jovial life.
The quality or state of being jovial.
Of or pertaining to Jove, or Jupiter (either the deity or the planet).
An adherent to the doctrines of Jovinian, a monk of the fourth century, who denied the virginity of Mary, and opposed the asceticism of his time.
A dog with large jowls, as the beagle.
The passion or emotion excited by the acquisition or expectation of good
A vessel for holding ale or wine
Pertaining to, or having the character of, a jubilee.

Every fiftieth year, being the year following the completion of each seventh sabbath of years, at which time all the slaves of Hebrew blood were liberated, and all lands which had been alienated during the whole period reverted to their former owners.
One of the tribe of Judah
Of or pertaining to the Jews.
The religious doctrines and rites of the Jews as enjoined in the laws of Moses.
One who believes and practices Judaism.
To conform to the doctrines, observances, or methods of the Jews
One who conforms to or inculcates Judaism
The disciple who betrayed Christ. Hence: A treacherous person
A public officer who is invested with authority to hear and determine litigated causes, and to administer justice between parties in courts held for that purpose.
Pertaining to the administration of justice
The state or profession of those employed in the administration of justice
Pertaining or appropriate to courts of justice, or to a judge
In a judicial capacity or judicial manner.
Of or pertaining to courts of judicature, or legal tribunals
Of or relating to a court
The quality or state of being judicious
A vessel, usually of coarse earthenware, with a swelling belly and narrow mouth, and having a handle on one side.
Relating to a yoke, or to marriage.
The figures of two heads on a medal or coin, either side by side or joined.
A Roman measure of land, measuring 28,800 square feet, or 240 feet in length by 120 in breadth.
An East Indian falcon. See Lugger.
One of the names under which Vishnu, in his incarnation as Krishna, is worshiped by the Hindoos.
To play tricks by sleight of hand
One who practices or exhibits tricks by sleight of hand
The art or act of a juggler
An extractive matter contained in the juice of the green shucks of the walnut (Juglans regia). It is used medicinally as an alterative, and also as a black hair dye.
An alkaloid found in the leaves of the walnut (Juglans regia).
A genus of valuable trees, including the true walnut of Europe, and the America black walnut, and butternut.
A yellow crystalline substance resembling quinone, extracted from green shucks of the walnut (Juglans regia)
Of or pertaining to the throat or neck
The lower throat, or that part of the neck just above the breast.
One of the ridges commonly found on the fruit of umbelliferous plants.
The characteristic fluid of any vegetable or animal substance
The state or quality of being juicy

The sweet and edible drupes (fruits) of several Mediterranean and African species of small trees, of the genus Zizyphus, especially the Z. jujuba, Z. vulgaris, Z. mucronata, and Z. Lotus. The last named is thought to have furnished the lotus of the ancient Libyan Lotophagi, or lotus eaters.
Like an ament, or bearing aments
A refreshing drink flavored with aromatic herbs
Relating to, or derived from, Julius Caesar.
A kind of soup containing thin slices or shreds of carrots, onions, etc.
Having the shape or appearance of a julus or catkin.
A catkin or ament. See Ament.
The seventh month of the year, containing thirty-one days.
The fabled offspring of a bull and a mare.
To mix in a confused mass
A kind of loose jacket for men.
One who, or that which, jumps.
Of. pertaining to, or resembling, a natural order of plants (Juncaceae), of which the common rush (Juncus) is the type.
Any bird of the genus Junco, which includes several species of North American finches
The act of joining, or the state of being joined
The sixth month of the year, containing thirty days.
The small applelike berry of American trees of genus Amelanchier
A genus of hepatic mosses, now much circumscribed, but formerly comprising most plants of the order, which is sometimes therefore called Jungermanniaceae.
A dense growth of brushwood, grasses, reeds, vines, etc.
Less advanced in age than another
The state or quality of being junior.
Any evergreen shrub or tree, of the genus Juniperus and order Coniferae.
A yellow amorphous substance extracted from juniper berries.
One of the fossil Coniferae, evidently allied to the juniper.
A fragment of any solid substance
A young German noble or squire
The principles of the aristocratic party in Prussia.
A secret council to deliberate on affairs of government or politics
A great Brazilian palm tree (Raphia taedigera), used by the natives for many purposes.
The supreme deity, king of gods and men, and reputed to be the son of Saturn and Rhea
A sleeveless jacket worn over the armor in the 14th century. It fitted closely, and descended below the hips.
1. A range of mountains between France and Switzerland.
Pertaining to natural or positive right.
Of the age of the middle Mesozoic, including, as divided in England and Europe, the Lias, Oolite, and Wealden
Relating to or comprising an oath
A term applied to many American Mesozoic strata, in which the characteristics of the Jurassic and Triassic periods appear to be blended.
A yellow carangoid fish of the Atlantic and Gulf coasts (Caranx chrysos), most abundant southward, where it is valued as a food fish
Pertaining to a judge or to jurisprudence
A man learned in the civil law
The legal power, right, or authority of a particular court to hear and determine causes, to try criminals, or to execute justice
One who professes the science of law
Of or pertaining to a jurist, to the legal profession, or to jurisprudence.
One who is impaneled on a jury, or who serves as a juror.
Rigged for temporary service. See Jury, a.
A delicate fiber, produced in the Philippine Islands from an unidentified plant, of which dresses, etc., are made.
Conforming or conformable to rectitude or justice
Liable to trial in a court of justice.
The office or dignity of a justice.
Proper to be examined in a court of justice.
An old name for the judges of the higher English courts.
Formerly, a close coat or waistcoat with sleeves.
Capable of being justified, or shown to be just.
The act of justifying or the state of being justified
To prove or show to be just
Of or pertaining to the Institutes or laws of the Roman Justinian.
To run or strike against each other
The coarse, strong fiber of the East Indian Corchorus olitorius, and C. capsularis
A native or inhabitant of Jutland in Denmark.
Of or pertaining to Jutland, or to the people of Jutland.
The state or quality of being juvenile
A Brazilian name for the lofty myrtaceous tree (Bertholetia excelsa) which produces the large seeds known as Brazil nuts.
The camel's thorn. See under Camel.
To place in close connection or contiguity
A placing or being placed in nearness or contiguity, or side by side

the eleventh letter of the English alphabet, is nonvocal consonant. The form and sound of the letter K are from the Latin, which used the letter but little except in the early period of the language. It came into the Latin from the Greek, which received it from a Phoenician source, the ultimate origin probably being Egyptian.  Etymologically K is most nearly related to c, g, h (which see).
A clay ironstone found in Ceylon.
A Berber, as in Algiers or Tunis. See Berber.
The Arabian name of two trees of the genus Balsamodendron, which yield a gum resin and a red aromatic wood.

One of a race which, with the Hottentots and Bushmen, inhabit South Africa. They inhabit the country north of Cape Colony, the name being now specifically applied to the tribes living between Cape Colony and Natal
A chantry chapel inclosed with lattice or screen work.

A singular, crested, grallatorial bird (Rhinochetos jubatus), native of New Caledonia. It is gray above, paler beneath, and the feathers of the wings and tail are handsomely barred with brown, black, and gray. It is allied to the sun bittern.
A kind of notary public, or attorney, in the Levant.

A long-nosed monkey (Semnopithecus nasalis), native of Borneo. The general color of the body is bright chestnut, with the under parts, shoulders, and sides of the head, golden yellow, and the top of the head and upper part of the back brown. Called also proboscis monkey.
A kind of headless cabbage. Same as Kale, 1.
Poultry, etc., required by the lease to be paid in kind by a tenant to his landlord.
Salts of potassium used in the manufacture of fertilizers.
A compound salt consisting chiefly of potassium chloride and magnesium sulphate, occurring at the Stassfurt salt mines in Prussian Saxony.
A pale buff or white crystalline alkaloid derived from quinoline, and used as an antipyretic in medicine.
An organic base obtained from quinoline. It is used as a febrifuge, and resembles kairine.
The ancient title of emperors of Germany assumed by King William of Prussia when crowned sovereign of the new German empire in 1871.
A New Zealand parrot of the genus Nestor, especially the brown parrot (Nestor meridionalis).

A singular nocturnal parrot (Strigops habroptilus), native of New Zealand. It lives in holes during the day, but is active at night. It resembles an owl in its colors and general appearance. It has large wings, but can fly only a short distance. Called also owl parrot, night parrot, and night kaka.
A kind of wood common in Demerara, durable in salt water, because not subject to the depredations of the sea worm and barnacle.
A long-tailed monkey of Borneo (Semnopithecus rubicundus). It has a tuft of long hair on the head.
A variety of cabbage in which the leaves do not form a head, being nearly the original or wild form of the species.
One of several species of large, crested, Asiatic pheasants, belonging to the genus Euplocamus, and allied to the firebacks.

An instrument invented by Professor Wheatstone, consisting of a reflecting knob at the end of a vibrating rod or thin plate, for making visible, in the motion of a point of light reflected from the knob, the paths or curves corresponding with the musical notes produced by the vibrations.

An instrument invented by Sir David Brewster, which contains loose fragments of colored glass, etc., and reflecting surfaces so arranged that changes of position exhibit its contents in an endless variety of beautiful colors and symmetrical forms. It has been much employed in arts of design.
Of, pertaining to, or formed by, a kaleidoscope
The last and worst of the four ages of the world
Forming alkalies with oxygen, as some metals.
The name of Vishnu in his tenth and last avatar.
A genus of North American shrubs with poisonous evergreen foliage and corymbs of showy flowers. Called also mountain laurel, ivy bush, lamb kill, calico bush, etc.
A fruit bat, esp. the Indian edible fruit bat (Pteropus edulis).
One of the Brahmanic eons, a period of 4,320,000,000 years. At the end of each Kalpa the world is annihilated.
The Hindoo Cupid. He is represented as a beautiful youth, with a bow of sugar cane or flowers.
The red dusty hairs of the capsules of an East Indian tree (Mallotus Philippinensis) used for dyeing silk. It is violently emetic, and is used in the treatment of tapeworm.

A title given to the celestial gods of the first mythical dynasty of Japan and extended to the demigods of the second dynasty, and then to the long line of spiritual princes still represented by the mikado.

A curious South American bird (Anhima, / Palamedea, cornuta), often domesticated by the natives and kept with poultry, which it defends against birds of prey. It has a long, slender, hornlike ornament on its head, and two sharp spurs on each wing. Although its beak, feet, and legs resemble those of gallinaceous birds, it is related in anatomical characters to the ducks and geese (Anseres). Called also horned screamer. The name is sometimes applied also to the chaja. See Chaja, and Screamer.
A kind of elastic floor cloth, made of India rubber, gutta-percha, linseed oil, and powdered cork.
A variety of mimetite or arseniate of lead in hexagonal prisms of a fine orange yellow.
A hot southwesterly wind in Egypt, coming from the Sahara.
An aboriginal tribe inhabiting the southern part of Kamtschatka.
A native of the Sandwich Islands.
A small chevrotain of the genus Tragulus, esp. T. pygmaeus, or T. kanchil, inhabiting Java, Sumatra, and adjacent islands

Any one of numerous species of jumping marsupials of the family Macropodidae. They inhabit Australia, New Guinea, and adjacent islands, They have long and strong hind legs and a large tail, while the fore legs are comparatively short and feeble. The giant kangaroo (Macropus major) is the largest species, sometimes becoming twelve or fourteen feet in total length. The tree kangaroos, belonging to the genus Dendrolagus, live in trees
A tribe of Indians allied to the Winnebagoes and Osages. They formerly inhabited the region which is now the State of Kansas, but were removed to the Indian Territory.
Of or pertaining to Immanuel Kant, the German philosopher
The doctrine or theory of Kant
A disciple or follower of Kant.
A very pure white clay, ordinarily in the form of an impalpable powder, and used to form the paste of porcelain
The process by which feldspar is changed into kaolin.
The fossil resin of the kauri tree of New Zealand.
A species of gray fox found in Russia.
A sect of Jews who adhere closely to the letter of the Scriptures, rejecting the oral law, and allowing the Talmud no binding authority
A West Indian plant of the Pineapple family (Nidularium Karatas).
One's acts considered as fixing one's lot in the future existence. (Theos.) The doctrine of fate as the inflexible result of cause and effect
One of a Mohammedan sect founded in the ninth century by Karmat.
The twenty-fourth part of a grain
A fibrous mineral occurring in tufts of a straw-yellow color. It is a hydrous silicate of alumina and manganese.
One of the dry table-lands of South Africa, which often rise terracelike to considerable elevations.
The indirect division of cells in which, prior to division of the cell protoplasm, complicated changes take place in the nucleus, attended with movement of the nuclear fibrils
The reticular network of fine fibers, of which the nucleus of a cell is in part composed
The protoplasmic substance of the nucleus of a cell: nucleoplasm

Direct cell division (in which there is first a simple division of the nucleus, without any changes in its structure, followed by division of the protoplasm of the karyostenotic mode of nuclear division.
An Arabian shrub Catha edulis) the leaves of which are used as tea by the Arabs.
(Physiol.) A substance formed by a katabolic process
A caoutchouc like substance obtained from the milky juice of the East Indian Euphorbia Kattimundoo. It is used as a cement.

A large, green, arboreal, orthopterous insect (Cyrtophyllus concavus) of the family Locustidae, common in the United States. The males have stridulating organs at the bases of the front wings. During the summer and autumn, in the evening, the males make a peculiar, loud, shrill sound, resembling the combination Katy-did, whence the name.
A lofty coniferous tree of New Zealand Agathis, / Dammara, australis), furnishing valuable timber and yielding one kind of dammar resin.
A species of Macropiper (M. methysticum), the long pepper, from the root of which an intoxicating beverage is made by the Polynesians, by a process of mastication
a New Zealand tree, the Cypress cedar (Libocedrus Doniana), having a valuable, fine-grained, reddish wood.

A light canoe, made of skins stretched over a frame, and usually capable of carrying but one person, who sits amidships and uses a double-bladed paddle. It is peculiar to the Eskimos and other Arctic tribes.
To heave or to retch, as in an effort to vomit.
The hollow stalk of an umbelliferous plant, such as the cow parsnip or the hemlock.
To move (a vessel) by carrying out a kedge in a boat, dropping it overboard, and hauling the vessel up to it.
A mass or lump of fat rolled up by the butcher.
The right of demanding a duty or toll for a ship entering a port
One employed in managing a Newcastle keel
To haul under the keel of a ship, by ropes attached to the yardarms on each side. It was formerly practiced as a punishment in the Dutch and English navies.
A pencil of black or red lead
A piece of timber in a ship laid on the middle of the floor timbers over the keel, and binding the floor timbers to the keel
A professional mourner who wails at a funeral.
The quality or state of being keen.
One who, or that which, keeps
The office or position of a keeper.
Anything kept, or given to be kept, for the sake of the giver
A vat or tub in which the mash is made
A mineral of a brownish black color, related to titanite in form. It consists chiefly of silica, titanium dioxide, lime, and yttria.
A black, two-horned, African rhinoceros (Atelodus keitloa). It has the posterior horn about as long as the anterior one, or even longer.
Applied to a variety of tumor forming hard, flat, irregular excrescences upon the skin.
The calcined ashes of seaweed, -- formerly much used in the manufacture of glass, now used in the manufacture of iodine.
A small California food fish (Heterostichus rostratus), living among kelp. The name is also applied to species of the genus Platyglossus.
An imaginary spirit of the waters, horselike in form, vulgarly believed to warn, by preternatural noises and lights, those who are to be drowned.
Coarse, rough hair wool or fur, injuring its quality.
The long flower stems of the ribwort plantain (Plantago Lanceolata).
A cloth colored green by dye obtained from the woad-waxen, formerly used by Flemish weavers at Kendal, in Westmoreland, England.
The water course of a street
A gambling game, a variety of the game of lotto, played with balls or knobs, numbered, and cards also numbered.
Modified evolution, in which nonprimitive characters make their appearance in consequence of a secondary adaptation of the embryo to the peculiar conditions of its environment
Having so marked an appearance as easily to be recognized.
A curved bugle, having six finger keys or stops, by means of which the performer can play upon every key in the musical scale
Pigs of iron used for ballast.
One of a group of nitrogenous phosphorized principles, supposed by Thudichum to exist in brain tissue.
A kind of long trumpet, used among the Persians.
A nitrogenous substance free from phosphorus, supposed to be present in the brain

A nitrogenous substance, or mixture of substances, containing sulphur in a loose state of combination, and forming the chemical basis of epidermal tissues, such as horn, hair, feathers, and the like. It is an insoluble substance, and, unlike elastin, is not dissolved even by gastric or pancreatic juice. By decomposition with sulphuric acid it yields leucin and tyrosin, as does albumin. Called also epidermose.
An instrument for dividing the cornea in operations for cataract.
The operation of removing a cataract by thrusting a needle through the cornea of the eye, and breaking up the opaque mass.
A gorgonian coral having a horny axis.
An order of sponges having a skeleton composed of hornlike fibers. It includes the commercial sponges.
A tough, horny animal substance entering into the composition of the skeleton of sponges, and other invertebrates
A figure or picture impressed by lightning upon the human body or elsewhere.
Covered, or bound round, with a kercher.
A square of fine linen worn by women as a covering for the head
A notch, channel, or slit made in any material by cutting or sawing.
A compound in which tar or asphaltum combined with animal or vegetable oils is vulcanized by sulphur, the product closely resembling rubber

The dried bodies of the females of a scale insect (Coccus ilicis), allied to the cochineal insect, and found on several species of oak near the Mediterranean. They are round, about the size of a pea, contain coloring matter analogous to carmine, and are used in dyeing. They were anciently thought to be of a vegetable nature, and were used in medicine.
A light-armed foot soldier of the ancient militia of Ireland and Scotland
The essential part of a seed

An oil used for illuminating purposes, formerly obtained from the distillation of mineral wax, bituminous shale, etc., and hence called also coal oil. It is now produced in immense quantities, chiefly by the distillation and purification of petroleum. It consists chiefly of several hydrocarbons of the methane series.
A kind of coarse, woolen cloth, usually ribbed, woven from wool of long staple.
The stomach of a calf, prepared for rennet.

A small, slender European hawk (Falco alaudarius), allied to the sparrow hawk. Its color is reddish fawn, streaked and spotted with white and black. Also called windhover and stannel. The name is also applied to other allied species.
An almost obsolete form of vessel, with a mainmast and a mizzenmast, -- usually from one hundred to two hundred and fifty tons burden.
One of a series of organic bases obtained by the reduction of certain isonitroso compounds of the ketones. In general they are unstable oily substances having a pungent aromatic odor.
The name of certain African species of Hibiscus, cultivated for the acid of their mucilage.
One of a series of series of complex nitrogenous substances, represented by methyl ketol and related to indol.

One of a large class of organic substances resembling the aldehydes, obtained by the distillation of certain salts of organic acids and consisting of carbonyl (CO) united with two hydrocarbon radicals. In general the ketones are colorless volatile liquids having a pungent ethereal odor.
Pertaining to, or derived from, a ketone
A metallic vessel, with a wide mouth, often without a cover, used for heating and boiling water or other liguids.
A drum made of thin copper in the form of a hemispherical kettle, with parchment stretched over the mouth of it.
One who plays on a kettledrum.
The upper division of the European Triassic. See Chart of Geology.
A strong cleat to which large ropes are belayed.
An instrument by means of which the bolt of a lock is shot or drawn
The whole arrangement, or one range, of the keys of an organ, typewriter, etc.
A hole or apertupe in a door or lock, for receiving a key.
The tonic or first tone of the scale in which a piece or passage is written
To form a key seat, as by cutting. See Key seat, under Key.
The central or topmost stone of an arch. This in some styles is made different in size from the other voussoirs, or projects, or is decorated with carving. See Illust. of Arch.
Dominion or jurisdiction of a khan.
A lofty West African tree (Khaya Senegalensis), related to the mahogany, which it resembles in the quality of the wood. The bark is used as a febrifuge.
An address or public prayer read from the steps of the pulpit in Mohammedan mosques, offering glory to God, praising Mohammed and his descendants, and the ruling princes.
Portions of small fish used for bait on the banks of Newfoundland.
A chap or crack in the flesh occasioned by cold
A tent used by the Kirghiz Tartars.
To strike, thrust, or hit violently with the foot
Capable or deserving of being kicked.
A tribe of Indians which formerly occupied the region of Northern Illinois, allied in language to the Sacs and Foxes.
One who, or that which, kicks.
That which is restless and uneasy.
A kind of ingrain carpeting, named from the English town where formerly most of it was manufactured.
A kind of basketwork wear in a river, for catching fish.
To take (any one) by force or fear, and against one's will, with intent to carry to another place.
One who steals or forcibly carries away a human being
A glandular organ which excretes urea and other waste products from the animal body
Having the form or shape of a kidney
A large tub or vat in which goods are subjected to the action of hot lye or bleaching liquor
Hydrous sulphate of magnesia found at the salt mines of Stassfurt, Prussian Saxony.

Any one of several small American cyprinodont fishes of the genus Fundulus and allied genera. They live equally well in fresh and brackish water, or even in the sea. They are usually striped or barred with black. Called also minnow, and brook fish. See Minnow.
The Cornish chough. See under Chough.
One who causes gloom or grief
An earth of a blackish or deep blue color.
The mouth or opening of an oven or kiln.

L is the twelfth letter of the English alphabet, and a vocal consonant. It is usually called a semivowel or liquid. Its form and value are from the Greek, through the Latin, the form of the Greek letter being from the Phoenician, and the ultimate origin prob. Egyptian. Etymologically, it is most closely related to r and u
A syllable applied to the sixth tone of the scale in music in solmization.

A follower of Jean de Labadie, a religious teacher of the 17th century, who left the Roman Catholic Church and taught a kind of mysticism, and the obligation of community of property among Christians.
An aqueous solution of hypochlorite of sodium, extensively used as a disinfectant.

The standard adopted by the Emperor Constantine after his conversion to Christianity. It is described as a pike bearing a silk banner hanging from a crosspiece, and surmounted by a golden crown. It bore a monogram of the first two letters (CHR) of the name of Christ in its Greek form. Later, the name was given to various modifications of this standard.
The act of labefying or making weak
The lower or apparently anterior petal of an orchidaceous flower, often of a very curious shape.
Of or pertaining to the lips or labia
The modification of an articulation by contraction of the lip opening.
To modify by contraction of the lip opening.
A forceps with a measuring attachment for ascertaining the size of the fetal head.
Liable to slip, err, fall, or apostatize.
Liability to lapse, err, or apostatize.
Formed or pronounced by the cooperation of the lips and teeth, as f and v.
Formed by the lips and the nose.
Having the appearance of being labiate
One of the labial palpi of an insect. See Illust. under Labium.
an East Indian name for several twining leguminous plants related to the bean, but commonly applied to the hyacinth bean (Dolichos Lablab).
Physical toil or bodily exertion, especially when fatiguing, irksome, or unavoidable, in distinction from sportive exercise
One who labors in a toilsome occupation
Made with, or requiring, great labor, pains, or diligence.
A region of British America on the Atlantic coast, north of Newfoundland.
A kind of feldspar commonly showing a beautiful play of colors, and hence much used for ornamental purposes. The finest specimens come from Labrador. See Feldspar.
A lip or edge, as of a basin.
A genus of marine fishes, including the wrasses of Europe. See Wrasse.
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the laburnum.
A poisonous alkaloid found in the unripe seeds of the laburnum.
A small leguminous tree (Cytisus Laburnum), native of the Alps. The plant is reputed to be poisonous, esp. the bark and seeds. It has handsome racemes of yellow blossoms.
An edifice or place full of intricate passageways which render it difficult to find the way from the interior to the entrance
Pertaining to, or resembling, a labyrinth
Of or pertaining to the Labyrinthici.
Like or pertaining to a labyrinth.
An order of teleostean fishes, including the Anabas, or climbing perch, and other allied fishes.
Having the form of a labyrinth
Pertaining to, or like, a labyrinth
A genus of very large fossil amphibians, of the Triassic period, having bony plates on the under side of the body. It is the type of the order Labyrinthodonta. Called also Mastodonsaurus.
Of or pertaining to the Labyrinthodonta.

An extinct order of Amphibia, including the typical genus Labyrinthodon, and many other allied forms, from the Carboniferous, Permian, and Triassic formations. By recent writers they are divided into two or more orders. See Stegocephala.
Pertaining to lac, or produced from it
A yellow amorphous substance obtained from lac.
A mass of igneous rock intruded between sedimentary beds and resulting in a mammiform bulging of the overlying strata.
That which binds or holds, especially by being interwoven
A shrub in the West Indies (Lagetta Iintearia)
Of or pertaining to Lacedaemon or Sparta, the chief city of Laconia in the Peloponnesus.
A man who deals in lace.
That can be lacerated or torn.
Lacerating, or having the power to lacerate
A muscle of the human body.
An order of Reptilia, which includes the lizards.
Like or belonging to the Lacertilia.
A bundle or fascicle of muscular fibers.

Any one of several species of neuropterous insects of the genus Chrysopa and allied genera. They have delicate, lacelike wings and brilliant eyes. Their larvae are useful in destroying aphids. Called also lace-winged fly, and goldeneyed fly.
A rich, sweet, red Neapolitan wine.
Containing, or intended to contain, tears
Having the form of a tear
One of the narrow, jagged, irregular pieces or divisions which form a sort of fringe on the borders of the petals of some flowers.
Consisting of, or abounding in, very minute laciniae.
One who is deficient in understanding
One who lacks or is in want.
Of or pertaining to Laconia, a division of ancient Greece
Expressing much in few words, after the manner of the Laconians or Spartans
A vigorous, brief manner of expression
To imitate the manner of the Laconians, especially in brief, pithy speech, or in frugality and austerity.
A varnish, consisting of a solution of shell-lac in alcohol, often colored with gamboge, saffron, or the like
One who lacquers, especially one who makes a business of lacquering.

A game of ball, originating among the North American Indians, now the popular field sport of Canada, and played also in England and the United States. Each player carries a long-handled racket, called a "crosse". The ball is not handled but caught with the crosse and carried on it, or tossed from it, the object being to carry it or throw it through one of the goals placed at opposite ends of the field.
The produce of animals yielding milk
One of a series of anhydrides of an amido type, analogous to the lactones, as oxindol.
Pertaining to, or designating, an amido acid related to lactic acid, and called also amido-propionic acid.
An acid amide derived from lactic acid, and obtained as a white crystalline substance having a neutral reaction. It is metameric with alanine.
A preparation of casein from milk, used in printing calico.
The state or quality of producing milk, or milklike juice
A white, crystalline substance, obtained from also, by extension, any similar substance.
Bearing or containing milk or a milky fluid
A medicine to check the secretion of milk, or to dispel a supposed accumulation of milk in any part of the body.
One of a series of anhydrides resembling the lactams, but of an imido type
A white, crystalline substance obtained as an anhydride of alanine, and regarded as an imido derivative of lactic acid.
The albumin present on milk, apparently identical with ordinary serum albumin. It is distinct from the casein of milk.
An instrument for determining the amount of butter fat contained in a given sample of milk.
A form of hydrometer, specially graduated, for finding the density of milk, and thus discovering whether it has been mixed with water or some of the cream has been removed.
An instrument for estimating the purity or richness of milk, as a measuring glass, a specific gravity bulb, or other apparatus.

One of a series of organic compounds, regarded as anhydrides of certain hydroxy acids. In general, they are colorless liquids, having a weak aromatic odor. They are so called because the typical lactone is derived from lactic acid.
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, lactone.
A peculiar albuminous body considered a normal constituent of milk.
An instrument for estimating the amount of cream contained in milk by ascertaining its relative opacity.
Sugar of milk or milk sugar
A genus of composite herbs, several of which are cultivated foe salad
The inspissated juice of the common lettuce, sometimes used as a substitute for opium.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the juice of the Lactuca virosa
A white, crystalline substance, having a bitter taste and a neutral reaction, and forming one of the essential ingredients of lactucarium.
A white, crystalline, tasteless substance, found in the milky sap of species of Lactuca, and constituting an essential ingredient of lactucarium.
Pertaining to, or designating, an organic amido acid, which is regarded as a derivative of lactic acid and urea.
An organic residue or radical derived from lactic acid.
Found in, or pertaining to, lakes or ponds, or growing in them
Ornamentation by means of lacquer painted or carved, or simply colored, sprinkled with gold or the like
p. p. of Lead, to guide.
A gum resin gathered from certain Oriental species of Cistus. It has a pungent odor and is chiefly used in making plasters, and for fumigation.
A frame usually portable, of wood, metal, or rope, for ascent and descent, consisting of two side pieces to which are fastened cross strips or rounds forming steps.
One who leads a pack horse
The small-flowered Fuchsia (F. coccinea), and other closely related species.
A Romansch dialect spoken in some parts of Switzerland and the Tyrol.
One of the half-breed descendants of whites and Indians
A cuplike spoon, often of large size, with a long handle, used in lading or dipping.
A quantity sufficient to fill a ladle.
A woman who looks after the domestic affairs of a family
Any one of numerous species of small beetles of the genus Coccinella and allied genera (family Coccinellidae)
A large, handsome oceanic fish (Albula vulpes), found both in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans
The state or quality of being a lady
A gallant who captivates the hearts of women.
The art or practice of captivating the hearts of women.
Like a lady in appearance or manners
The quality or state of being ladylike.
A climbing plant with fragrant blossoms (Clematis vitalba).
An umbelliferous plant (Scandix Pecten-Veneris), its clusters of long slender fruits remotely resembling a comb.
An herb growing in dense tufts
A plant of the genus Briza (B. media)
The rank or position of a lady
A genus of rosaceous herbs (Alchemilla), esp. the European A. vulgaris, which has leaves with rounded and finely serrated lobes.
Any orchidaceous plant of the genus Cypripedium, the labellum of which resembles a slipper. Less commonly, in the United States, the garden balsam (Impatiens Balsamina).
A plant of the genus Cardamine (C. pratensis)
An annual weed (Polygonum Persicaria), having a lanceolate leaf with a dark spot in the middle.
A name given to several species of the orchidaceous genus Spiranthes, in which the white flowers are set in spirals about a slender axis and remotely resemble braided hair.

A genus of huge, carnivorous, dinosaurian reptiles from the Cretaceous formation of the United States. They had very large hind legs and tail, and are supposed to have been bipedal. Some of the species were about eighteen feet high.
A division of amphipod Crustacea, in which the abdomen is small or rudimentary and the legs are often reduced to five pairs. The whale louse, or Cyamus, and Caprella are examples.
Of or pertaining to the Laemodipoda.
Having a smooth surface, as if polished.
The terminal part of the cochlea in birds and most reptiles
Like, or pertaining to, Lagena, a genus of Foraminifera having a straight, chambered shell.
Shaped like a bottle or flask
Originally a German beer, but now also made in immense quantities in the United States
Wine which has been kept for some time in the cellar.
A group of rodents, including the hares. They have four incisors in the upper jaw. Called also Duplicidentata.
A shallow sound, channel, pond, or lake, especially one into which the sea flows
A morbid condition in which the eye stands wide open, giving a peculiar staring appearance.
Having a dense covering of long hair, like the foot of a hare.
Of or pertaining to a layman or the laity.
The state or quality of being laic
A place in which to lie or rest
The state of being a laird
The people, as distinguished from the clergy
A pigment formed by combining some coloring matter, usually by precipitation, with a metallic oxide or earth, esp. with aluminium hydrate
The water pepper (Polygonum Hydropiper), an aquatic plant of Europe and North America.
An imperfect enunciation of the letter r, in which it sounds like l.
The powdered leaves of the baobab tree, used by the Africans to mix in their soup, as the southern negroes use powdered sassafras.  Cf. Couscous.
A modified form of Buddhism which prevails in Thibet, Mongolia, and some adjacent parts of Asia
Pertaining to, or involved in, the doctrines of Lamarckianism.

The theory that structural variations, characteristic of species and genera, are produced in animals and plants by the direct influence of physical environments, and esp., in the case of animals, by effort, or by use or disuse of certain organs.
A monastery or convent of lamas, in Thibet, Mongolia, etc.
A feast at the time of shearing lambs.
Taken by licking with the tongue.
The name of the Greek letter /, /, corresponding with the English letter L, l.
A fault in speaking or in composition, which consists in too frequent use of the letter l, or in doubling it erroneously.
Shaped like the Greek letter lambda (/)
The gigantic sugar pine of California and Oregon (Pinus Lambertiana). It has the leaves in fives, and cones a foot long. The timber is soft, and like that of the white pine of the Eastern States.
A kind of pendent scarf or covering attached to the helmet, to protect it from wet or heat.
A name given to several plants of the Goosefoot family, sometimes used as pot herbs, as Chenopodium album and Atriplex patulsa.
Moving with pain or difficulty on account of injury, defect, or temporary obstruction of a function
a thin plate or scale of anything, as a thin scale growing from the petals of certain flowers
Of or pertaining to lamella or to lamellae
Composed of, or furnished with, thin plates or scales. See Illust. of Antennae.
One of the Lamellibranchia. Also used adjectively.
A class of Mollusca including all those that have bivalve shells, as the clams, oysters, mussels, etc.
Having antennae terminating in a group of flat lamellae
A group of lamellicorn, plant-eating beetles
Bearing, or composed of, lamellae, or thin layers, plates, or scales
Having a lamellate bill, as ducks and geese.
A group of birds embracing the Anseres and flamingoes, in which the bill is lamellate.
An a lame, crippled, disabled, or imperfect manner
The condition or quality of being lame
Small steel plates combined together so as to slide one upon the other and form a piece of armor.
Foil or wire made of gold, silver, or brass.
A monster capable of assuming a woman's form, who was said to devour human beings or suck their blood
The quality or state of being laminable.
Capable of being split into laminae or thin plates, as mica
In, or consisting of, thin plates or layers
A genus of great seaweeds with long and broad fronds
Pertaining to seaweeds of the genus Laminaria, or to that zone of the sea (from two to ten fathoms in depth) where the seaweeds of this genus grow.
Consisting of, or covered with, laminae, or thin plates, scales, or layers, one over another
The process of laminating, or the state of being laminated.
Having a structure consisting of laminae, or thin layers.
Having the tarsus covered behind with a horny sheath continuous on both sides, as in most singing birds, except the larks.
Inflammation of the laminae or fleshy plates along the coffin bone of a horse

A very large vulture (Gypaetus barbatus), which inhabits the mountains of Southern Europe, Asia, and Northern Africa. When full-grown it is nine or ten feet in extent of wings. It is brownish black above, with the under parts and neck rusty yellow
One who gained the prize in the lampadrome.
A race run by young men with lighted torches in their hands. He who reached the goal first, with his torch unextinguished, gained the prize.
An inflammation and swelling of the soft parts of the roof of the mouth immediately behind the fore teeth in the horse
A supposed salt of lampic acid.

The fine impalpable soot obtained from the smoke of carbonaceous substances which have been only partly burnt, as in the flame of a smoking lamp. It consists of finely divided carbon, with sometimes a very small proportion of various impurities. It is used as an ingredient of printers' ink, and various black pigments and cements.
Pertaining to, or produced by, a lamp
Being without a lamp, or without light
One who, or that which, lights a lamp
A post (generally a pillar of iron) supporting a lamp or lantern for lighting a street, park, etc.

An eel-like marsipobranch of the genus Petromyzon, and allied genera. The lampreys have a round, sucking mouth, without jaws, but set with numerous minute teeth, and one to three larger teeth on the palate (see Illust. of Cyclostomi). There are seven small branchial openings on each side.
An insect of the genus Lampyris, or family Lampyridae. See Lampyris.
A genus of coleopterous insects, including the glowworms.
A mineral consisting of sulphate of lead, occurring either massive or in long slender prisms, of a greenish white or gray color.
A steam boiler having two flues which contain the furnaces and extend through the boiler from end to end.
Of or pertaining to the monitorial system of instruction followed by Joseph Lancaster, of England, in which advanced pupils in a school teach pupils below them.
A weapon of war, consisting of a long shaft or handle and a steel blade or head
A slender marine fish of the genus Ammodytes, especially Ammodytes tobianus of the English coast
A kind of spear anciently used. Its use was prohibited by a statute of Richard II.
A small fishlike animal (Amphioxus lanceolatus), remarkable for the rudimentary condition of its organs. It is the type of the class Leptocardia. See Amphioxus, Leptocardia.
Rather narrow, tapering to a point at the apex, and sometimes at the base also
A surgical instrument of various forms, commonly sharp-pointed and two-edged, used in venesection, and in opening abscesses, etc.

A tough, elastic wood, often used for the shafts of gigs, archery bows, fishing rods, and the like. Also, the tree which produces this wood, Duguetia Quitarensis (a native of Guiana and Cuba), and several other trees of the same family (Anonaseae).
Having the form of a lance.
A chief magistrate in some of the Swiss cantons.
A four-wheeled covered vehicle, the top of which is divided into two sections which can be let down, or thrown back, in such a manner as to make an open carriage.
One who lands, or makes a landing.
A sudden transference of property in land by the death of its owner.
An overflowing of land by river
A German nobleman of a rank corresponding to that of an earl in England and of a count in France.
The territory held by a landgrave.
A holder, owner, or proprietor of land.
A woman having real estate which she leases to a tenant or tenants.
To inclose, or nearly inclose, as a harbor or a vessel, with land.
Inclosed, or nearly inclosed, by land.
The lord of a manor, or of land
The state of being a landlord
One who passes his life on land
A man who lives or serves on land
A mark to designate the boundary of land
Pecuniarily embarrassed through owning much unprofitable land.
A subordinate officer on an extensive estate, who acts as an assistant to the steward.
A portion of land or territory which the eye can comprehend in a single view, including all the objects it contains.
The slipping down of a mass of land from a mountain, hill, etc.
One who lives on the land
That part of the reserve force in Germany which is called out last.
See Landing waiter, under Landing, a.
That part of the army, in Germany and Austria, which has completed the usual military service and is exempt from duty in time of peace, except that it is called out occasionally for drill.
A curious colubriform snake of the genus Xyphorhynchus, from Madagascar. It is brownish red, and its nose is prolonged in the form of a sharp blade.
One of numerous species of long-winged, shrikelike birds of Australia and the East Indies, of the genus Artamus, and allied genera
A linen roller used in dressing wounds.
A wolf (Canis pallipes), found in India, allied to the jackal.
A kind of shot formerly used at sea for tearing sails and rigging. It consisted of bolts, nails, and other pieces of iron fastened together or inclosed in a canister.
An old game at cards. See Loo (a).
Any means of conveying or communicating ideas
The dialect, closely akin to French, formerly spoken south of the Loire (in which the word for "yes" was oc)
The dialect formerly spoken north of the Loire (in which the word for "yes" was oil, F. oui).
Anything resembling the tongue in form or office
A state of the body or mind which is caused by exhaustion of strength and characterized by a languid feeling
Producing, or tending to produce, languor
One of several species of East Indian and Asiatic fresh-water fishes of the genus Ophiocephalus, remarkable for their power of living out of water, and for their tenacity of life
Shaped like a laniary, or canine, tooth.
Of or pertaining to the shrikes (family Laniidae).
The condition or quality or being lanky.
The state or quality of being lank.
A long-tailed falcon (Falco lanarius), of Southern Europe, Asia, and Northern Africa, resembling the American prairie falcon.
A peculiar fatlike body, made up of cholesterin and certain fatty acids, found in feathers, hair, wool, and keratin tissues generally.
The small, whitish brown fruit of an East Indian tree (Lansium domesticum). It has a fleshy pulp, with an agreeable subacid taste.
A German foot soldier in foreign service in the 15th and 16th centuries
Pertaining to, or designating, a nitrogenous organic acid of the uric acid group, obtained by the decomposition of allantoin, and usually called allanturic acid.
Something inclosing a light, and protecting it from wind, rain, etc.
Having lantern jaws or long, thin jaws
Hydrous carbonate of lanthanum, found in tabular while crystals.

A rare element of the group of the earth metals, allied to aluminium. It occurs in certain rare minerals, as cerite, gadolinite, orthite, etc., and was so named from the difficulty of separating it from cerium, didymium, and other rare elements with which it is usually associated. Atomic weight 138.5. Symbol La.
An alkaloid found in opium in small quantities, and extracted as a white crystalline substance.
Covered with down, or fine soft hair
The soft woolly hair which covers most parts of the mammal fetus, and in man is shed before or soon after birth.
A short piece of rope or line for fastening something in ships
A priest of Apollo, during the Trojan war. (See 2.)
Of or pertaining to Laodicea, a city in Phrygia Major
The loose part of a coat
A rupture or hernia in the lumbar regions.
A cutting through the walls of the abdomen, as in the Caesarean section.
A board used on the lap as a substitute for a table, as by tailors.
A small dog fondled in the lap.
That part of a garment which is turned back
As much as the lap can contain.
An artificer who cuts, polishes, and engraves precious stones
The state or quality of being lapidescent.
Undergoing the process of becoming stone
The act or process of lapidifying
To convert into stone or stony material
The state of being, or the act of making, stony.
Volcanic ashes, consisting of small, angular, stony fragments or particles.
An albuminous mineral of a rich blue color. Same as Lazuli, which see.
Having a lap joint, or lap joints, as many kinds of woodwork and metal work.
A native or inhabitant of Lapland
One who has been fondled to excess
One who takes up food or liquid with his tongue.
A small decorative fold or flap, esp, of lace or muslin, in a garment or headdress.
Of or pertaining to Lapland, or the Lapps.
Of or pertaining to the Lapps
A branch of the Mongolian race, now living in the northern parts of Norway, Sweden, and the adjacent parts of Russia.
A gliding, slipping, or gradual falling
A stone for the lap, on which shoemakers beat leather.
Made with boards whose edges lap one over another
Of or pertaining to Laputa, an imaginary flying island described in Gulliver's Travels as the home of chimerical philosophers. Hence, fanciful
Having edges or ends united by a lap weld

A small European bird of the Plover family (Vanellus cristatus, or V. vanellus). It has long and broad wings, and is noted for its rapid, irregular fight, upwards, downwards, and in circles. Its back is coppery or greenish bronze. Its eggs are the "plover's eggs" of the London market, esteemed a delicacy. It is called also peewit, dastard plover, and wype. The gray lapwing is the Squatarola cinerea.
Work in which one part laps over another.
Using a noose, as a gladiator.

An extensive series of strata, principally developed in the Rocky Mountain region, as in the Laramie Mountains, and formerly supposed to be of the Tertiary age, but now generally regarded as Cretaceous, or of intermediate and transitional character. It contains beds of lignite, often valuable for coal, and is hence also called the lignitic group. See Chart of Geology.
The left-hand side of a ship to one on board facing toward the bow
The unlawful taking and carrying away of things personal with intent to deprive the right owner of the same
A genus of coniferous trees, having deciduous leaves, in fascicles (see Illust. of Fascicle).
Of or pertaining to the larch.
A peculiar amyloid substance, colored blue by iodine and sulphuric acid, occurring mainly as an abnormal infiltration into the spleen, liver, etc.
A room or place where meat and other articles of food are kept before they are cooked.
One in charge of the larder.
A bit of fat pork or bacon used in larding.
Exceeding most other things of like kind in bulk, capacity, quantity, superficial dimensions, or number of constituent units
Having large hands, Fig.: Taking, or giving, in large quantities
Having a large or generous heart or disposition
The quality or state of being large.
A sport piece of bar iron for rolling into a sheet
Somewhat slow or slowly, but not so slowly as largo, and rather more so than andante.
The bestowment of a largess or gift.
A long, slender rope made of hemp or strips of hide, esp. one with a noose
Of or pertaining to the Gull family (Laridae).
Of, or derived from, the larch (Larix)
Having the sandy brown color of the European larks.

A genus of ranunculaceous plants (Delphinium), having showy flowers, and a spurred calyx. They are natives of the North Temperate zone. The commonest larkspur of the gardens is D. Consolida. The flower of the bee larkspur (D. elatum) has two petals bearded with yellow hairs, and looks not unlike a bee.
Like or belonging to the Gull family (Laridae).

Any young insect from the time that it hatches from the egg until it becomes a pupa, or chrysalis. During this time it usually molts several times, and may change its form or color each time. The larvae of many insects are much like the adults in form and habits, but have no trace of wings, the rudimentary wings appearing only in the pupa stage. In other groups of insects the larvae are totally unlike the parents in structure and habits, and are called caterpillars, grubs, maggots, etc.
Of or pertaining to a larva.
An order of Tunicata, including Appendicularia, and allied genera
Having the form or structure of a larva.
Depositing living larvae, instead of eggs
Of or pertaining to the larynx
A spasmodic state of the glottis, giving rise to contraction or closure of the opening.
One who applies himself to laryngology.
Systematized knowledge of the action and functions of the larynx
The sound of the voice as heard through a stethoscope when the latter is placed upon the larynx.
An instrument, consisting of an arrangement of two mirrors, for reflecting light upon the larynx, and for examining its image.
Of or pertaining to the inspection of the larynx.
The art of using the laryngoscope
The operation of cutting into the larynx, from the outside of the neck, for assisting respiration when obstructed, or for removing foreign bodies.
Pertaining to both larynx and trachea
The operation of cutting into the larynx and the upper part of the trachea, -- a frequent operation for obstruction to breathing.

The expanded upper end of the windpipe or trachea, connected with the hyoid bone or cartilage. It contains the vocal cords, which produce the voice by their vibrations, when they are stretched and a current of air passes between them. The larynx is connected with the pharynx by an opening, the glottis, which, in mammals, is protected by a lidlike epiglottis.
A native sailor, employed in European vessels
Any plant of the umbelliferous genus Laserpitium, of several species (as L. glabrum, and L. siler), the root of which yields a resinous substance of a bitter taste. The genus is mostly European.
The thong or braided cord of a whip, with which the blow is given.
The act of one who, or that which, lashes
A condition of the body, or mind, when its voluntary functions are performed with difficulty, and only by a strong exertion of the will
A rope or long thong of leather with, a running noose, used for catching horses, cattle, etc.
of Last, to endure, contracted from lasteth.
A duty exacted, in some fairs or markets, for the right to carry things where one will.
A workman whose business it is to shape boots or shoes, or place leather smoothly, on lasts
A superior quality of Turkish smoking tobacco, so called from the place where produced, the ancient Laodicea.
The string that fastens a shoe
A key used to raise, or throw back, the latch of a door, esp. a night latch.
A string for raising the latch of a door by a person outside. It is fastened to the latch and passed through a hole above it in the door.
Coming after the time when due, or after the usual or proper time
Of or pertaining to a peculiar rig used in the Mediterranean and adjacent waters, esp. on the northern coast of Africa. See below.
The state or quality of being latent.
The state, condition, or quality, of being late
In a secret or concealed manner
Of or pertaining to the sides
The state or condition of being lateral.
The church and palace of St. John Lateran, the church being the cathedral church of Rome, and the highest in rank of all churches in the Catholic world.
Growing from the stem by the side of a leaf
An argillaceous sandstone, of a red color, and much seamed
Consisting of, containing, or characterized by, laterite
A genus of large percoid fishes, of which one species (Lates Niloticus) inhabits the Nile, and another (L. calcarifer) is found in the Ganges and other Indian rivers. They are valued as food fishes.
A slight withdrawal from view or knowledge.
Slightly withdrawn from view or knowledge

A milky or colored juice in certain plants in cavities (called latex cells or latex tubes). It contains the peculiar principles of the plants, whether aromatic, bitter, or acid, and in many instances yields caoutchouc upon coagulation.

A thin, narrow strip of wood, nailed to the rafters, studs, or floor beams of a building, for the purpose of supporting the tiles, plastering, etc. A corrugated metallic strip or plate is sometimes used.
Formerly, a part or division of a county among the Anglo-Saxons. At present it consists of four or five hundreds, and is confined to the county of Kent.
Foam or froth made by soap moistened with water.
Formerly, the head officer of a lathe. See 1st Lathe.
Having a slender elongated form, like a lath
Belonging, or relating, to Latium, a country of ancient Italy. See Latin.
To retire into a den, or hole, and lie dormant in winter
A broad stripe of purple on the fore part of the tunic, worn by senators in ancient Rome as an emblem of office.
Of or pertaining to Latium, or to the Latins, a people of Latium
Of, pertaining to, or derived from, Latin
One who has but a smattering of Latin.
The Latin tongue, style, or idiom, or the use thereof
The act or process of Latinizing, as a word, language, or country.
To give Latin terminations or forms to, as to foreign words, in writing Latin.
In the manner of the Latin language
The broad-billed singing birds, such as the swallows, and their allies.
Having a broad breastbone, or sternum
Act or state of lying hid, or lurking.
A writ based upon the presumption that the person summoned was hiding.
Extent from side to side, or distance sidewise from a given point or line
The highest kind of worship, or that paid to God
A privy, or water-closet, esp. in a camp, hospital, etc.
A kind of brass hammered into thin sheets, formerly much used for making church utensils, as candlesticks, crosses, etc.
A pointed wooden tool used in glazing leaden lattice.
Any work of wood or metal, made by crossing laths, or thin strips, and forming a network
The line drawn through a focus of a conic section parallel to the directrix and terminated both ways by the curve. It is the parameter of the principal axis. See Focus, and Parameter.
A white organic base, resembling morphine, and obtained from certain varieties of opium.
Tincture of opium, used for various medical purposes.
Of or pertaining praise, or to the expression of praise

To show mirth, satisfaction, or derision, by peculiar movement of the muscles of the face, particularly of the mouth, causing a lighting up of the face and eyes, and usually accompanied by the emission of explosive or chuckling sounds from the chest and throat
