A movement (usually involuntary) of the muscles of the face, particularly of the lips, with a peculiar expression of the eyes, indicating merriment, satisfaction, or derision, and usually attended by a sonorous and interrupted expulsion of air from the lungs. See Laugh, v. i.
A mineral, of a white color and vitreous luster. It is a hydrous silicate of alumina and lime. Exposed to the air, it loses water, becomes opaque, and crumbles.
To throw, as a lance or dart
A plain sprinkled with trees or underbrush
One who follows the business of laundering.
A woman whose employment is laundering.
A man who follows the business of laundering.
A number of hermitages or cells in the same neighborhood occupied by anchorites who were under the same superior.
Belonging to, or resembling, a natural order (Lauraceae) of trees and shrubs having aromatic bark and foliage, and including the laurel, sassafras, cinnamon tree, true camphor tree, etc.
State, or office, of a laureate.
The act of crowning with laurel
An evergreen shrub, of the genus Laurus (L. nobilis), having aromatic leaves of a lanceolate shape, with clusters of small, yellowish white flowers in their axils
Crowned with laurel, or with a laurel wreath
Pertaining to, or near, the St. Lawrence River
The Viburnum Tinus, an evergreen shrub or tree of the south of Europe, which flowers during the winter mouths.
Pertaining to, or derived from, the European bay or laurel (Laurus nobilis).
A white crystalline substance extracted from the fruit of the bay (Laurus nobilis), and consisting of a complex mixture of glycerin ethers of several organic acids.
A rare sulphide of osmium and ruthenium found with platinum in Borneo and Oregon.

A genus of trees including, according to modern authors, only the true laurel (Laurus nobilis), and the larger L. Canariensis of Madeira and the Canary Islands. Formerly the sassafras, the camphor tree, the cinnamon tree, and several other aromatic trees and shrubs, were also referred to the genus Laurus.

The melted rock ejected by a volcano from its top or fissured sides. It flows out in streams sometimes miles in length. It also issues from fissures in the earth's surface, and forms beds covering many square miles, as in the Northwestern United States.
A European whitefish (Coregonus laveretus), found in the mountain lakes of Sweden, Germany, and Switzerland.
Like lava, or composed of lava

An aromatic plant of the genus Lavandula (L. vera), common in the south of Europe. It yields and oil used in medicine and perfumery. The Spike lavender (L. Spica) yields a coarser oil (oil of spike), used in the arts.
The quality or state of being lavish.
A supposed new metallic element. It is said to have been discovered in pyrites, and some other minerals, and to be of a silver-white color, and malleable.
An old dance, for two persons, being a kind of waltz, in which the woman made a high spring or bound.
In general, a rule of being or of conduct, established by an authority able to enforce its will
To cut off the claws and balls of, as of a dog's fore feet.
One who makes or enacts a law or system of laws
Contrary to, or unauthorized by, law

A very fine linen (or sometimes cotton) fabric with a rather open texture. Lawn is used for the sleeves of a bishop's official dress in the English Church, and, figuratively, stands for the office itself.

An Asiatic and North African shrub (Lawsonia inermis), with smooth oval leaves, and fragrant white flowers. Henna is prepared from the leaves and twigs. In England the shrub is called Egyptian privet, and in the West Indies, Jamaica mignonette.
One versed in the laws, or a practitioner of law
The act of loosening or slackening, or the state of being loosened or slackened.
Having a tendency to loosen or relax.
The state or quality of being lax
One who, or that which, lays.
One of the people, in distinction from the clergy
The condition of being a layman.
A place where rubbish, dung, etc., are laid or deposited.
A person infected with a filthy or pestilential disease
A public building, hospital, or pesthouse for the reception of diseased persons, particularly those affected with contagious diseases.

One of the Congregation of the Priests of the Mission, a religious institute founded by Vincent de Paul in 1624, and popularly called Lazarists or Lazarites from the College of St. Lazare in Paris, which was occupied by them until 1792.
The state or quality of being lazy.

A mineral of a fine azure-blue color, usually in small rounded masses. It is essentially a silicate of alumina, lime, and soda, with some sodium sulphide, is often marked by yellow spots or veins of sulphide of iron, and is much valued for ornamental work. Called also lapis lazuli, and Armenian stone.
A mineral of a light indigo-blue color, occurring in small masses, or in monoclinic crystals
A support for the back, attached to the seat of a carriage.
The homeless idlers of Naples who live by chance work or begging
Permitting liquids to pass by percolation

One of the elements, a heavy, pliable, inelastic metal, having a bright, bluish color, but easily tarnished. It is both malleable and ductile, though with little tenacity, and is used for tubes, sheets, bullets, etc. Its specific gravity is 11.37. It is easily fusible, forms alloys with other metals, and is an ingredient of solder and type metal. Atomic weight, 206.4. Symbol Pb (L. Plumbum). It is chiefly obtained from the mineral galena, lead sulphide.
One who, or that which, leads or conducts
A mineral of a yellowish or greenish white color, consisting of the sulphate and carbonate of lead
The man who heaves the lead.
A genus of maritime herbs (Plumbago). P. Europaea has lead-colored spots on the leaves, and nearly lead-colored flowers.
A colored, usually green, expansion growing from the side of a stem or rootstock, in which the sap for the use of the plant is elaborated under the influence of light
A coarse American composite weed (Polymnia Uvedalia).
Having leaflike expansions on the legs
Having a leaflike membrane on the nose
The stalk or petiole which supports a leaf.

A measure of length or distance, varying in different countries from about 2.4 to 4.6 English statute miles of 5.280 feet each, and used (as a land measure) chiefly on the continent of Europe, and in the Spanish parts of America. The marine league of England and the United States is equal to three marine, or geographical, miles of 6080 feet each.
The camp of a besieging army
A crack, crevice, fissure, or hole which admits water or other fluid, or lets it escape
Permitting water or other fluid to leak in or out
A dog held by a leam.
The condition or quality of being lean.
Having only one slope or pitch
Having but little sense or shrewdness.
One who, or that which, leaps.
A play among boys, in which one stoops down and another leaps over him by placing his hands on the shoulders of the former.
To learn. See Lere, to learn.
To gain knowledge or information of
To gather what harvesters have left behind
A thong of leather, or a long cord, by which a falconer holds his hawk, or a courser his dog.
Smallest, either in size or degree
An artificial water trench, esp. one to or from a mill.
The skin of an animal, or some part of such skin, tanned, tawed, or otherwise dressed for use
A large sea turtle (Sphargis coriacea), having no bony shell on its back. It is common in the warm and temperate parts of the Atlantic, and sometimes weighs over a thousand pounds
An imitation of leather, made of paper and cloth.
The sordid friar bird of Australia (Tropidorhynchus sordidus).
A small branching shrub (Dirca palustris), with a white, soft wood, and a tough, leathery bark, common in damp woods in the Northern United States
Resembling leather in appearance or consistence
Any substance that produces, or is designed to produce, fermentation, as in dough or liquids
Coagulated sour milk diluted with water
divination practiced with water in a basin, by throwing three stones into it, and invoking the demon whose aid was sought.

Pertaining to, or designating, an organic acid which is obtained from several varieties of lichen (Lecanora, Roccella, etc.), as a white, crystalline substance, and is called also orsellic, / diorsellinic acid, lecanorin, etc.
A complex, nitrogenous phosphorized substance widely distributed through the animal body, and especially conspicuous in the brain and nerve tissue, in yolk of eggs, and in the white blood corpuscles.
A kind of litter or portable couch.
A lesson or selection, esp. of Scripture, read in divine service.
A book, or a list, of lections, for reading in divine service.
A choir desk, or reading desk, in some churches, from which the lections, or Scripture lessons, are chanted or read

A genus of gigantic trees, chiefly Brazilian, of the order Myrtaceae, having woody capsules opening by an apical lid. Lecythis Zabucajo yields the delicious sapucaia nuts. L. Ollaria produces the monkey-pots, its capsules. Its bark separates into thin sheets, like paper, used by the natives for cigarette wrappers.
A shelf on which articles may be laid
A book in which a summary of accounts is laid up or preserved
A string-course or horizontal suit of moldings, such as the base moldings of a building.
A board, or frame of planks, lowered over the side of a vessel to lessen her leeway when closehauled, by giving her greater draught.
A plant of the genus Allium (A. Porrum), having broadly linear succulent leaves rising from a loose oblong cylindrical bulb. The flavor is stronger than that of the common onion.
One subject to the jurisdiction of a court-leet.
Pertaining to, or in the direction of, the part or side toward which the wind blows
The lateral movement of a ship to the leeward of her course
Having the left hand or arm stronger and more dexterous than the right
The state or quality of being left-handed
Toward or on the left side.
A limb or member of an animal used for supporting the body, and in running, climbing, and swimming
A gift of property by will, esp. of money or personal property
Created by, permitted by, in conformity with, or relating to, law
Strictness, or the doctrine of strictness, in conforming to law.
One who practices or advocates strict conformity to law
The state or quality of being legal
One to whom a legacy is bequeathed.
Of or pertaining to a legate
The sending forth or commissioning one person to act for another.
That which is appointed to be read
Of or pertaining to a legend or to legends
Anything that lies in a place
One who practices sleight of hand
A cover for the leg, like a long gaiter.
A straw plaiting used for bonnets and hats, made from the straw of a particular kind of wheat, grown for the purpose in Tuscany, Italy
Capable of being read or deciphered
The state or quality of being legible.
Of or pertaining to making laws.
A body of foot soldiers and cavalry consisting of different numbers at different periods, -- from about four thousand to about six thousand men, -- the cavalry being about one tenth.
Formed into a legion or legions
To make or enact a law or laws.
Making, or having the power to make, a law or laws
Of or pertaining to a legislator or legislature.
The body of persons in a state or kingdom invested with power to make and repeal laws
The portion of movable estate to which the children are entitled upon the death of the father.
The state, or quality, of being legitimate, or in conformity with law
Accordant with law or with established legal forms and requirements
The state or quality of being legitimate
The principles or plans of legitimists.
Pertaining to the literature of law.
A pod dehiscent into two pieces or valves, and having the seed attached at one suture, as that of the pea.
An albuminous substance resembling casein, found as a characteristic ingredient of the seeds of leguminous and grain-bearing plants.
Of or pertaining to the Leiotrichi.
The division of mankind which embraces the smooth-haired races.
Having smooth, or nearly smooth, hair.

A genus of Australian gallinaceous birds including but a single species (Leipoa ocellata), about the size of a turkey. Its color is variegated, brown, black, white, and gray. Called also native pheasant.
A spear armed with three or more prongs, for striking fish.
See Leading motive, under Leading, a.
A ray or glimmer of light
A preliminary or auxiliary proposition demonstrated or accepted for immediate use in the demonstration of some other proposition, as in mathematics or logic.
Any one of several species of small arctic rodents of the genera Myodes and Cuniculus, resembling the meadow mice in form. They are found in both hemispheres.
Of or pertaining to the isle of Lemnos.
A curve in the form of the figure 8, with both parts symmetrical, generated by the point in which a tangent to an equilateral hyperbola meets the perpendicular on it drawn from the center.
One of two oval bodies hanging from the interior walls of the body in the Acanthocephala.

An oval or roundish fruit resembling the orange, and containing a pulp usually intensely acid. It is produced by a tropical tree of the genus Citrus, the common fruit known in commerce being that of the species C. Limonum or C. Medica (var. Limonum). There are many varieties of the fruit, some of which are sweet.
A beverage consisting of lemon juice mixed with water and sweetened.

One of a family (Lemuridae) of nocturnal mammals allied to the monkeys, but of small size, and having a sharp and foxlike muzzle, and large eyes. They feed upon birds, insects, and fruit, and are mostly natives of Madagascar and the neighboring islands, one genus (Galago) occurring in Africa. The slow lemur or kukang of the East Indies is Nycticebus tardigradus. See Galago, Indris, and Colugo.
Spirits or ghosts of the departed
A hypothetical land, or continent, supposed by some to have existed formerly in the Indian Ocean, of which Madagascar is a remnant.
Like or pertaining to the lemurs or the Lemuroidea.
A suborder of primates, including the lemurs, the aye-aye, and allied species.
To allow the custody and use of, on condition of the return of the same
The longest, or longer, dimension of any object, in distinction from breadth or width
The state or quality of being lengthy
In the direction of the length
The quality or state of being lenient
Having the quality of softening or mitigating, as pain or acrimony
The quality or habit of being lenient
The state or quality of being lenient

A general name for a group of Algonquin tribes which formerly occupied the coast region of North America from Connecticut to Virginia. They included the Mohicans, Delawares, Shawnees, and several other tribes.
A light open cotton fabric used for window curtains.

A piece of glass, or other transparent substance, ground with two opposite regular surfaces, either both curved, or one curved and the other plane, and commonly used, either singly or combined, in optical instruments, for changing the direction of rays of light, and thus magnifying objects, or otherwise modifying vision. In practice, the curved surfaces are usually spherical, though rarely cylindrical, or of some other figure.
The season of Lenten or Lent.

One of the small, oval, rounded spots upon the stem or branch of a plant, from which the underlying tissues may protrude or roots may issue, either in the air, or more commonly when the stem or branch is covered with water or earth.
A kind of eruption upon the skin
Resembling a lentil in size or form
In the manner of a lens
A freckly eruption on the skin
A leguminous plant of the genus Ervum (Ervum Lens), of small size, common in the fields in Europe. Also, its seed, which is used for food on the continent.
Having the form of a lens
One or more detached verses at the end of a literary composition, serving to convey the moral, or to address the poem to a particular person
The Lion, the fifth sign of the zodiac, marked thus [/] in almanacs.
Of or pertaining to Leon, in Spain.
One of the shooting stars which constitute the star shower that recurs near the fourteenth of November at intervals of about thirty-three years
Pertaining to, or characteristic of, the lion
A genus of liguliflorous composite plants, including the fall dandelion (L. autumnale), and formerly the true dandelion

A large, savage, carnivorous mammal (Felis leopardus). It is of a yellow or fawn color, with rings or roselike clusters of black spots along the back and sides. It is found in Southern Asia and Africa. By some the panther (Felis pardus) is regarded as a variety of leopard.
A name of several harmless plants, as Arnica montana, Senecio Doronicum, and Paris quadrifolia.
A stalked barnacle of the genus Lepas, or family Lepadidae
Any one of various species of Lepas, a genus of pedunculated barnacles found attached to floating timber, bottoms of ships, Gulf weed, etc.
An organic base, C9H6.N.CH3, metameric with quinaldine, and obtained by the distillation of cinchonine.
One of an extinct family of trees allied to the modern club mosses, and including Lepidodendron and its allies.
A genus of fossil trees of the Devonian and Carboniferous ages, having the exterior marked with scars, mostly in quincunx order, produced by the separation of the leafstalks.
Any one of a division (Lepidoganoidei) of ganoid fishes, including those that have scales forming a coat of mail. Also used adjectively.
A species of mica, of a lilac or rose-violet color, containing lithia. It usually occurs in masses consisting of small scales. See Mica.
An iron-potash mica, of a raven-black color, usually found in granitic rocks in small six-sided tables, or as an aggregation of minute opaque scales. See Mica.
An order of insects, which includes the butterflies and moths. They have broad wings, covered with minute overlapping scales, usually brightly colored.
Of or pertaining to the Lepidoptera.
A division of reptiles, including the serpents and lizards

An eel-shaped ganoid fish of the order Dipnoi, having both gills and lungs. It inhabits the rivers of South America. The name is also applied to a related African species (Protopterus annectens). The lepidosirens grow to a length of from four to six feet. Called also doko.
Having a coat of scurfy scales, as the leaves of the oleaster.

A genus of wingless thysanurous insects having an elongated flattened body, covered with shining scales and terminated by seven unequal bristles. A common species (Lepisma saccharina) is found in houses, and often injures books and furniture. Called also shiner, silver witch, silver moth, and furniture bug.
Like or pertaining to the Lepisma.
Of or pertaining to a hare
The state or quality of being leprous or scaly

A cutaneous disease which first appears as blebs or as reddish, shining, slightly prominent spots, with spreading edges. These are often followed by an eruption of dark or yellowish prominent nodules, frequently producing great deformity. In one variety of the disease, anaesthesia of the skin is a prominent symptom. In addition there may be wasting of the muscles, falling out of the hair and nails, and distortion of the hands and feet with destruction of the bones and joints. It is incurable, and is probably contagious.
Having a form somewhat like leptus
The lowest class of Vertebrata, including only the Amphioxus. The heart is represented only by a simple pulsating vessel. The blood is colorless
Of or pertaining to the Leptocardia.
A bird or other animal having slender toes.
A minute and tedious discourse on trifling things.
Inflammation of the pia mater or of the arachnoid membrane.
An order of Crustacea, including Nebalia and allied forms.
A genus of bacteria, characterized by having their filaments very long, slender, and indistinctly articulated.
The six-legged young, or larva, of certain mites
A Linnaean genus of parasitic Entomostraca, -- the same as the family Lernaeidae.
A suborder of copepod Crustacea, including a large number of remarkable forms, mostly parasitic on fishes. The young, however, are active and swim freely. See Illustration in Appendix.

One of a family (Lernaeidae) of parasitic Crustacea found attached to fishes and other marine animals. Some species penetrate the skin and flesh with the elongated head, and feed on the viscera. See Illust. in Appendix.
A small European rodent (Eliomys nitela), allied to the dormouse.
Of or pertaining to the island anciently called Lesbos, now Mitylene, in the Grecian Archipelago.
A privative adjective suffix, denoting without, destitute of, not having
The person to whom a lease is given, or who takes an estate by lease.
One who, or that which, lessens.
The leavings or dung of beasts.
Anything read or recited to a teacher by a pupil or learner
A noun suffix having a diminutive force
One of the higher alcohols of the paraffine series obtained from spermaceti as a white crystalline solid. It is so called because it occurs in the ethereal salt of lauric acid.
Pertaining to, affected with, or resembling, lethargy
Sulphuric ether used as an anaesthetic agent.
To subject to the influence of letheon.
A device for letting off, releasing, or giving forth, as the warp from the cylinder of a loom.
One who makes, inscribes, or engraves, alphabetical letters.
The beautiful and highly elastic wood of a tree of the genus Brosimum (B. Aubletii), found in Guiana
Of or pertaining to the Letts
Of or pertaining to the Letts.
An Indo-European people, allied to the Lithuanians and Old Prussians, and inhabiting a part of the Baltic provinces of Russia.

A composite plant of the genus Lactuca (L. sativa), the leaves of which are used as salad. Plants of this genus yield a milky juice, from which lactucarium is obtained. The commonest wild lettuce of the United States is L. Canadensis.
A genus of evergreen shrubs from the Cape of Good Hope, having handsome foliage. Leucadendron argenteum is the silverboom of the colonists.
A colorless, crystalline, organic base, obtained from rosaniline by reduction, and also from other sources. It forms colorless salts.
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid obtained from leucin, and called also oxycaproic acid.

A white, crystalline, nitrogenous substance formed in the decomposition of albuminous matter by pancreatic digestion, by the action of boiling dilute sulphuric acid, and by putrefaction. It is also found as a constituent of various tissues and organs, as the spleen, pancreas, etc., and likewise in the vegetable kingdom. Chemically it is to be considered as amido-caproic acid.
A mineral having a glassy fracture, occurring in translucent trapezohedral crystals. It is a silicate of alumina and potash. It is found in the volcanic rocks of Italy, especially at Vesuvius.
A colorless corpuscle, as one of the white blood corpuscles, or those found in lymph, marrow of bone, connective tissue, etc.
A disease in which the white corpuscles of the blood are largely increased in number, and there is enlargement of the spleen, or the lymphatic glands
A nitrogenous organic base from coal tar, and identical with quinoline. Cf. Quinoline.
A white opacity in the cornea of the eye
An animal base or alkaloid, appearing in the tissue during life
Pertaining to, or designating, a complex organic acid, obtained as a yellowish white gum by the oxidation of croconic acid.
The state of an albino, or of a white child of black parents.
A mineral of a greenish yellow color
A dropsical habit of body, or the commencement of anasarca
Having a dropsical habit of body, with a white bloated skin.
A colorless substance isomeric with chlorophyll, contained in parts of plants capable of becoming green.
One of certain very minute whitish or colorless granules occurring in the protoplasm of plants and supposed to be the nuclei around which starch granules will form.
A mineral of a color between white and steel-gray, with a metallic luster, and consisting chiefly of arsenic and iron.
A discharge of a white, yellowish, or greenish, viscid mucus, resulting from inflammation or irritation of the membrane lining the genital organs of the female
A large antelope of North Africa (Oryx leucoryx), allied to the gemsbok.
An instrument, devised by Professor Helmholtz, for testing the color perception of the eye, or for comparing different lights, as to their constituent colors or their relative whiteness.
Like or pertaining to the Leucosoidea, a tribe of marine crabs including the box crab or Calappa.
Pertaining to, or designating, a nitrogenous organic substance of the uric acid group, called leucoturic acid or oxalantin. See Oxalantin.
A nearly opaque white mineral, in part identical with titanite, observed in some igneous rocks as the result of the alteration of titanic iron.
A goddess who protected newborn infants.
Rising or having risen from rest
Of or pertaining to the Levant.
A writ of execution at common law.
A muscle that serves to raise some part, as the lip or the eyelid.
See Levy in mass, under Levy, n.
A line or surface to which, at every point, a vertical or plumb line is perpendicular
One who, or that which, levels.
The disposition or endeavor to level all distinctions of rank in society.
In an even or level manner.
The state or quality of being level.
A hare in the first year of its age.
The American hop hornbeam (Ostrya Virginica), a small tree with very tough wood.
A trumpet call for rousing soldiers
An aquatic animal, described in the book of Job, ch. xli., and mentioned in other passages of Scripture.
The act or operation of levigating.

Of, pertaining to, or in accordance with, a law of the ancient Israelites and other tribes and races, according to which a woman, whose husband died without issue, was married to the husband's brother.
A group of birds, including the hornbills, kingfishers, and related forms.
To rise, or tend to rise, as if lighter than the surrounding medium
One of the tribe or family of Levi
Of or pertaining to a Levite or the Levites.
After the manner of the Levites
The third canonical book of the Old Testament, containing the laws and regulations relating to the priests and Levites among the Hebrews, or the body of the ceremonial law.
The quality of weighing less than something else of equal bulk
Turning or twisting the plane of polarization towards the left, as levulose, levotartaric acid, etc.
Turning or rotating the plane of polarization towards the left

A substance resembling dextrin, obtained from the bulbs of the dahlia, the artichoke, and other sources, as a colorless, spongy, amorphous material. It is so called because by decomposition it yields levulose.
Pertaining to, or denoting, an acid (called also acetyl-propionic acid), C5H8O3, obtained by the action of dilute acids on various sugars (as levulose).
An unfermentable carbohydrate obtained by gently heating levulose.

A sirupy variety of sugar, rarely obtained crystallized, occurring widely in honey, ripe fruits, etc., and hence called also fruit sugar. It is called levulose, because it rotates the plane of polarization to the left.
A name formerly given in Pennsylvania, Maryland, and Virginia to the Spanish real of one eighth of a dollar (or 12/ cents), valued at eleven pence when the dollar was rated at 7s. 6d.
A whitish, reddish, or yellowish, transparent or translucent mineral, allied to chabazite.
An iron dovetailed tenon, made in sections, which can be fitted into a dovetail mortise
Of or pertaining to a lexicon, to lexicography, or words
The author or compiler of a lexicon or dictionary.
Of or pertaining to, or according to, lexicography.
The art, process, or occupation of making a lexicon or dictionary
The science of the derivation and signification of words
A vocabulary, or book containing an alphabetical arrangement of the words in a language or of a considerable number of them, with the definition of each
The art or practice of defining words
Using, or interlarded with, pretentious words
The use of pretentious words, language, or style.

A glass jar or bottle used to accumulate electricity. It is coated with tin foil, within and without, nearly to its top, and is surmounted by a brass knob which communicates with the inner coating, for the purpose of charging it with electricity. It is so named from having been invented in Leyden, Holland.
Any crime committed against the sovereign power.
An igneous rock consisting largely of chrysolite, with pyroxene and picotite (a variety of spinel containing chromium).
A Chinese measure of distance, being a little more than one third of a mile.
Bound or obliged in law or equity
A union, or bond of union
A luxuriant woody plant, climbing high trees and having ropelike stems. The grapevine often has the habit of a liane. Lianes are abundant in the forests of the Amazon region.
A person who knowingly utters falsehood
The lowest of the three divisions of the Jurassic period
Of the age of the Lias
The act of pouring a liquid or liquor, usually wine, either on the ground or on a victim in sacrifice, in honor of some deity
A brief writing of any kind, esp. a declaration, bill, certificate, request, supplication, etc.
Like or pertaining to the dragon flies.

The inner bark of plants, lying next to the wood. It usually contains a large proportion of woody, fibrous cells, and is, therefore, the part from which the fiber of the plant is obtained, as that of hemp, etc.
Pertaining to, or characterized by, liberalism
The quality or state of being liberal
One who, or that which, liberalizes.
To release from restraint or bondage
The act of liberating or the state of being liberated.
One who, or that which, liberates
Pertaining to liberty, or to the doctrine of free will, as opposed to the doctrine of necessity.
The state of a libertine or freedman.
The state of a free person
A mineral of an olive-green color, commonly in orthorhombic crystals. It is a hydrous phosphate of copper.
The state or quality of being libidinous
One who has the care or charge of a library.
A considerable collection of books kept for use, and not as merchandise
To vibrate as a balance does before resting in equilibrium
The act or state of librating.

any one of five points in the plane of a system of two large astronomical bodies orbiting each other, as the Earth-moon system, where the gravitational pull of the two bodies on an object are approximately equal, and in opposite directions.  A solid object moving in the same velocity and direction as such a libration point will remain in gravitational equilibrium with the two bodies of the system and not fall toward either body.
A book containing the words of an opera or extended piece of music.
Having the form of liber, or resembling liber.
Of or pertaining to Libya, the ancient name of that part of Africa between Egypt and the Atlantic Ocean, or of Africa as a whole.
Authority or liberty given to do or forbear any act
The person to whom a license is given.
One who has a license to exercise a profession

One of a class of cellular, flowerless plants, (technically called Lichenes), having no distinction of leaf and stem, usually of scaly, expanded, frond-like forms, but sometimes erect or pendulous and variously branched. They derive their nourishment from the air, and generate by means of spores. The species are very widely distributed, and form irregular spots or patches, usually of a greenish or yellowish color, upon rocks, trees, and various bodies, to which they adhere with great tenacity. They are often improperly called rock moss or tree moss.
Belonging to, or covered with, lichens.
Of, pertaining to, or obtained from, lichens.
Having the form of a lichen.
A substance isomeric with starch, extracted from several species of moss and lichen, esp. from Iceland moss.
The science which treats of lichens.
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, lichens
An herb, the wall pellitory. See Pellitory.
The act of offering for sale to the highest bidder.
To draw or pass the tongue over
One who, or that which, licks.
A devourer or absorber of money.
A plant of the genus Glycyrrhiza (G. glabra), the root of which abounds with a sweet juice, and is much used in demulcent compositions.

An officer who bore an ax and fasces or rods, as ensigns of his office. His duty was to attend the chief magistrates when they appeared in public, to clear the way, and cause due respect to be paid to them, also to apprehend and punish criminals.
That which covers the opening of a vessel or box, etc.
Having no lid, or not covered with the lids, as the eyes
A concave metallic mirror attached to the object-glass end of a microscope, to throw down light on opaque objects
The simple tubular glands of the small intestines
A popular name for any society or club which meets for the practice of male part songs.
Of or pertaining to the spleen
One of the small nodules sometimes found in the neighborhood of the spleen
Of or pertaining to the spleen and intestine
Of or pertaining to, or of the nature of, a lientery.
A diarrhea, in which the food is discharged imperfectly digested, or with but little change.
In Gothic vaulting, any rib which does not spring from the impost and is not a ridge rib, but passes from one boss or intersection of the principal ribs to another.
The office, rank, or commission, of a lieutenant.
An officer who supplies the place of a superior in his absence
An army officer in rank next below a general and next above a major general.
The fiber by which the petioles of the date palm are bound together, from which various kinds of cordage are made.
The state of being which begins with generation, birth, or germination, and ends with death
A strong, buoyant boat especially designed for saving the lives of shipwrecked people.
Land held by a life estate.
Destitute of life, or deprived of life
An apparatus, made in very various forms, and of various materials, for saving one from drowning by buoying up the body while in the water.
That saves life, or is suited to save life, esp. from drowning
A nerve, or string, that is imagined to be essential to life.
One who, or that which, lifts.
Anything that ties or unites one thing or part to another
Goods sunk in the sea, with a buoy attached in order that they may be found again. See Jetsam and Flotsam.
The act of binding, or the state of being bound.
An instrument for ligating, or for placing and fastening a ligature.
The connection between sovereign and subject by which they were mutually bound, the former to protection and the securing of justice, the latter to faithful service
A baited line attached to a float, for night fishing. See Leger, a.
That agent, force, or action in nature by the operation of which upon the organs of sight, objects are rendered visible or luminous.
Armed with light weapons or accouterments.
One who, or that which, lights
The price paid for conveyance of goods on a lighter.
A person employed on, or who manages, a lighter.
Dexterous in taking and conveying away
Not having a full complement of men
A soldier who serves in the light horse. See under 5th Light.
A tower or other building with a powerful light at top, erected at the entrance of a port, or at some important point on a coast, to serve as a guide to mariners at night
A man who carries or takes care of a light.
The state, condition, or quality, of being light or not heavy

A discharge of atmospheric electricity, accompanied by a vivid flash of light, commonly from one cloud to another, sometimes from a cloud to the earth. The sound produced by the electricity in passing rapidly through the atmosphere constitutes thunder.
An old tune of a dance, the name of which made it a proverbial expression of levity, especially in love matters.
A small room from which the magazine of a naval vessel is lighted, being separated from the magazine by heavy glass windows.
The lungs of an animal or bird
A vessel carrying at the masthead a brilliant light, and moored off a shoal or place of dangerous navigation as a guide for mariners.
Pine wood abounding in pitch, used for torches in the Southern United States
Aloes wood, or agallochum. See  Agallochum.
A change in the character of a cell wall, by which it becomes harder. It is supposed to be due to an incrustation of lignin.
To convert into wood or into a ligneous substance.
A substance characterizing wood cells and differing from cellulose in its conduct with certain chemical reagents.

Mineral coal retaining the texture of the wood from which it was formed, and burning with an empyreumatic odor. It is of more recent origin than the anthracite and bituminous coal of the proper coal series. Called also brown coal, wood coal.
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid of the formic acid series, found in the tar, wax, or paraffine obtained by distilling certain kinds of wood, as the beech.
M, the thirteenth letter of the English alphabet, is a vocal consonant, and from the manner of its formation, is called the labio-nasal consonant. See Guide to Pronunciation, // 178-180, 242.
A large, pearly, spiral, marine shell (Turbo margaritaceus), from the Pacific Islands. It is used as an ornament.
An East Indian coin, of about one tenth of the weight of a rupee.
A spirituous liquor or drink distilled from potatoes
A kind of persimmon tree (Diospyros discolor) from the Philippine Islands, now introduced into the East and West Indies. It bears an edible fruit as large as a quince.
A prefix, in names of Scotch origin, signifying son.
Any one of several species of lemurs, as the ruffed lemur (Lemur macaco), and the ring-tailed lemur (L. catta).
A genus of monkeys, found in Asia and the East Indies. They have short tails and prominent eyebrows.
The process or act of macadamizing.
To cover, as a road, or street, with small, broken stones, so as to form a smooth, hard, convex surface.
Any one of several species of short-tailed monkeys of the genus Macacus
A gum of a crimson color, obtained from a tree (Macaranga Indica) that grows in the East Indies. It is used in taking impressions of coins, medallions, etc., and sometimes as a medicine.
Long slender tubes made of a paste chiefly of wheat flour, and used as an article of food
Pertaining to, or like, macaroni (originally a dish of mixed food)
A small cake, composed chiefly of the white of eggs, almonds, and sugar.
A kind of oil formerly used in dressing the hair
Any one of several species of small lemurs, as Lemur murinus, which resembles a rat in size.
A small Brazilian monkey (Callithrix torquatus), -- called also collared teetee.

Any parrot of the genus Sittace, or Macrocercus. About eighteen species are known, all of them American. They are large and have a very long tail, a strong hooked bill, and a naked space around the eyes. The voice is harsh, and the colors are brilliant and strongly contrasted.
Of or pertaining to Judas Maccabeus or to the Maccabees
The name given later times to the Asmonaeans, a family of Jewish patriots, who headed a religious revolt in the reign of Antiochus IV., 168-161 B. C., which led to a period of freedom for Israel.
A gambling game in vogue in the eighteenth century.
A money of account in China equal to one tenth of a tael
One who, or that which, macerates
The act or process of macerating.
A genus of extinct mammals allied to the cats, and having in the upper jaw canine teeth of remarkable size and strength

A large heavy knife resembling a broadsword, often two or three feet in length, -- used by the inhabitants of Spanish America as a hatchet to cut their way through thickets, and for various other purposes.
Of or pertaining to Machiavel, or to his supposed principles
The supposed principles of Machiavel, or practice in conformity to them

An opening between the corbels which support a projecting parapet, or in the floor of a gallery or the roof of a portal, shooting or dropping missiles upen assailants attacking the base of the walls. Also, the construction of such defenses, in general, when of this character. See Illusts. of Battlement and Castle.
One who machinates, or forms a scheme with evil designs

In general, any combination of bodies so connected that their relative motions are constrained, and by means of which force and motion may be transmitted and modified, as a screw and its nut, or a lever arranged to turn about a fulcrum or a pulley about its pivot, etc.
One who or operates a machine
A constrictor of machines and engines
The striped mullet of California (Mugil cephalus, / Mexicanus).
A thick blanket formerly in common use in the western part of the United States.
A genus of spiral gastropod shells, often of large size, characteristic of the lower Silurian rocks.
A coarse lace made of twine, used especially in decorating furniture.
A combining form signifying long, large, great
The science which treats of the chemical properties, actions or relations of substances in quantity
A division of birds including the swifts and humming birds. So called from the length of the distal part of the wing.
Of or pertaining to the macrocosm.
An immensely long blackish seaweed of the Pacific (Macrocystis pyrifera), having numerous almond-shaped air vessels.
One of a group of wading birds (Macrodactyli) having very long toes.
The longer of two diagonals, as of a rhombic prism. See Crystallization.
A dome parallel to the longer lateral axis of an orthorhombic crystal. See Dome, n., 4.
Enlargement or hypertrophy of the tongue.
Long and tedious talk without much substance
An instrument for determining the size or distance of inaccessible objects by means of two reflectors on a common sextant.
A short, straight, horizontal mark [-], placed over vowels to denote that they are to be pronounced with a long sound
One of the two planes of an orthorhombic crystal which are parallel to the vertical and longer lateral (macrodiagonal) axes.
Any one of a group of maioid crabs remarkable for the length of their legs
Having long or large feet, or a long stem.
A prism of an orthorhombic crystal between the macropinacoid and the unit prism
genus of marsupials including the common kangaroo.
A sporangium or conceptacle containing only large spores
One of the specially large spores of certain flowerless plants, as Selaginella, etc.
A large motile spore having four vibratile cilia
A subdivision of decapod Crustacea, having the abdomen largely developed. It includes the lobster, prawn, shrimp, and many similar forms.  Cf. Decapoda.
Like or pertaining to the Macrura.
Of or pertaining to the Macrura
The act of killing a victim for sacrifice.
Any marine bivalve shell of the genus Mactra, and allied genera. Many species are known. Some of them are used as food, as Mactra stultorum, of Europe. See Surf clam, under Surf.
A spot, as on the skin, or on the surface of the sun or of some other luminous orb.
Of or pertaining to spots upon a surface
A plant of the Rubia (R. tinctorum). The root is much used in dyeing red, and formerly was used in medicine. It is cultivated in France and Holland. See Rubiaceous.
A name proposed for any plant of the same natural order (Rubiaceae) as the madder.
A native or inhabitant of Madagascar, or Madecassee
The act of madefying, or making wet
A rich wine made on the Island of Madeira.
A French title of courtesy given to a girl or an unmarried lady, equivalent to the English Miss.
A house where insane persons are confined
A genus of composite plants, of which one species (Madia sativa) is cultivated for the oil yielded from its seeds by pressure. This oil is sometimes used instead of olive oil for the table.
An intoxicating confection from the hemp plant
A small Abyssinian antelope (Neotragus Saltiana), about the size of a hare.
A large fish pound used for the capture of the tunny in the Mediterranean
A genus of reef corals abundant in tropical seas. It includes than one hundred and fifty species, most of which are elegantly branched.
An extensive division of Anthozoa, including most of the species that produce stony corals. See Illust. of Anthozoa.
Any coral of the genus Madrepora
Resembling, or pertaining to, the genus Madrepora.
Resembling a madreporian coral in form or structure.
A thick plank, used for several mechanical purposes
A little amorous poem, sometimes called a pastoral poem, containing some tender and delicate, though simple, thought.
Of or pertaining to Madrid in Spain, or to its inhabitants.

the fourteenth letter of English alphabet, is a vocal consonent, and, in allusion to its mode of formation, is called the dentinasal or linguanasal consonent. Its commoner sound is that heard in ran, done
The edible berries of the Zizyphys Lotus, a tree of Northern Africa, and Southwestern Europe.
A deputy or viceroy in India
A pale red color, with a cast of orange.
A pearly substance which lines the interior of many shells, and is most perfect in the mother-of-pearl. [Written also nacker and naker.] See Pearl, and Mother-of-pearl.
That point of the heavens, or lower hemisphere, directly opposite the zenith
A spot or mark on the skin of children when born
A mineral of blackish lead-gray color and metallic luster, generally of a foliated massive structure
Any one of numerous species of small, fresh-water, chaetopod annelids of the tribe Naidina. They belong to the Oligochaeta.
Having a true natural luster without being cut
the horny scale of plate of epidermis at the end of the fingers and toes of man and many apes.
A brush for cleaning the nails.
One whose occupation is to make nails
A manufactory where nails are made.
Having a head like that of a nail
A thick sort of jaconet muslin, plain or striped, formerly made in India.
A distraining or levying of a distress

A large North American lake trout (Salvelinus namaycush). It is usually spotted with red, and sometimes weighs over forty pounds. Called also Mackinaw trout, lake trout, lake salmon, salmon trout, togue, and tuladi.
Talk or writing which is weakly sentimental or affectedly pretty.
The title by which any person or thing is known or designated
One who names, or calls by name.
One that has the same name as another
An African carnivore (Nandinia binotata), allied to the civets. It is spotted with black.
Any one of three species of South American ostriches of the genera Rhea and Pterocnemia. See Rhea.

A species of cloth, of a firm texture, originally brought from China, made of a species of cotton (Gossypium religiosum) that is naturally of a brownish yellow color quite indestructible and permanent.
A diminutive of Ann or Anne, the proper name.
A term used by modern archaeologists instead of cella. See Cella.
The back part of the neck.
An African bird of the genus Schizorhis, related to the plantain eaters.
A perfume distilled from orange flowers.

The complex mixture of volatile, liquid, inflammable hydrocarbons, occurring naturally, and usually called crude petroleum, mineral oil, or rock oil. Specifically: That portion of the distillate obtained in the refinement of petroleum which is intermediate between the lighter gasoline and the heavier benzine, and has a specific gravity of about 0.7, -- used as a solvent for varnishes, as a carburetant, illuminant, etc.

A white crystalline aromatic hydrocarbon, C10H8, analogous to benzene, and obtained by the distillation of certain bituminous materials, such as the heavy oil of coal tar. It is the type and basis of a large number of derivatives among organic compounds. Formerly called also naphthaline.
Pertaining to , or derived from, naphthalene
Pertaining to, derived from, or related to, naphthalene
To mingle, saturate, or impregnate, with naphtha.
A dyestuff, resembling alizarin, obtained from naphthoquinone as a red crystalline substance with a bright green, metallic luster
A peculiar hydrocarbon occuring as an ingredient of Caucasian petroleum.
A compound of naphthalene or its radical with a metallic element
Pertaining to, derived from, or related to, naphthalene
Any one of a series of hydroxyl derivatives of naphthalene, analogous to phenol. In general they are crystalline substances with a phenol (carbolic) odor.
A yellow crystalline substance, C10H6O2, analogous to quinone, obtained by oxidizing naphthalene with chromic acid.
A hydrocarbon radical regarded as the essential residue of naphthalene.
One of two basic amido derivatives of naphthalene, C10H7.NH2, forming crystalline solids.
Of, pertaining to, or discovered by, Napier, or Naper.
A set of rods, made of bone or other material, each divided into nine spaces, and containing the numbers of a column of the multiplication table
A little towel, or small cloth, esp. one for wiping the fingers and mouth at table.
A French gold coin of twenty francs, or about $3.86.
Of or pertaining to Napoleon I., or his family
A supporter of the dynasty of the Napoleons.
The quality of having a nap
A very small chevrotain (Tragulus Javanicus), native of Java. It is about the size of a hare, and is noted for its agility in leaping. Called also Java musk deer, pygmy musk deer, and deerlet.
A kind of turnip. See Navew.
An alkaloid found in small quantities in opium, and extracted as a white crystalline substance of a bitter astringent taste. It is a narcotic. Called also narceia.
A genus of endogenous bulbous plants with handsome flowers, having a cup-shaped crown within the six-lobed perianth, and comprising the daffodils and jonquils of several kinds.
Privation of sense or consciousness, due to a narcotic.
Having the properties of a narcotic
An alkaloid found in opium, and extracted as a white crystalline substance, tasteless and less poisonous than morphine
To imbue with, or subject to the influence of, a narcotic
An East Indian plant (Nardostachys Jatamansi) of the Valerian family, used from remote ages in Oriental perfumery.
An Australian name for Marsilea Drummondii, a four-leaved cryptogamous plant, sometimes used for food.
The nostrils or nasal openings, -- the anterior nares being the external or proper nostrils, and the posterior nares, the openings of the nasal cavities into the mouth or pharynx.
An apparatus for smoking tobacco. It has a long flexible tube, and the smoke is drawn through water.
Of or belonging to the nostrils.
Capable of being narrated or told.
A tribe of Indians who formerly inhabited the shores of Narragansett Bay.
To tell, rehearse, or recite, as a story
The act of telling or relating the particulars of an event
One who, or that which, narrows or contracts.
The condition or quality of being narrow.
A tall umbelliferous plant (Ferula communis). See Giant fennel, under Fennel.

An arctic cetacean (Monodon monocerous), about twenty feet long. The male usually has one long, twisted, pointed canine tooth, or tusk projecting forward from the upper jaw like a horn, whence it is called also sea unicorn, unicorn fish, and unicorn whale. Sometimes two horns are developed, side by side.
Of or pertaining to the nose.
The quality or state of being nasal.
The act of nasalizing, or the state of being nasalized.
A kind of pessary of medicated wool or cotton, formerly used.
Commencing, or in process of development
Bearing a horn, or horns, on the nose, as the rhinoceros.
Having the shape of a nose.
The middle point of the nasofrontal suture.
A combining form denoting pertaining to, or connected with, the nose
Connected with both the nose and the mouth
Of or pertaining to the nose and the front of the head
Connected with the lachrymal apparatus and the nose
Connected with both the nose and the palate
Of or pertaining to both throat and nose
Of or pertaining to the internasal septum.
Connected with, or near, both the turbinal and the nasal bones
Any species of marine gastropods, of the genera Nassa, Tritia, and other allied genera of the family Nassidae

Having a nice sense of smell.

The act of floating on the water
A tribe of Indians who formerly lived near the site of the city of Natchez, Mississippi. In 1729 they were subdued by the French
An annual grass (Eleusine coracona), cultivated in India as a food plant.
Any one of numerous species of marine gastropods belonging to Natica, Lunatia, Neverita, and other allied genera (family Naticidae.) They burrow beneath the sand, or mud, and drill other shells.
Like or belonging to Natica, or the family Naticidae.

The quality or state of being native.

The coming into life or into the world
A zeolite occuring in groups of glassy acicular crystals, and in masses which often have a radiated structure. It is a hydrous silicate of alumina and soda.
A European toad (Bufo calamita), having a yellow line along its back.
Belonging to the doctrines of naturalism.
The act or process of naturalizing, esp. of investing an alien with the rights and privileges of a native or citizen
In a natural manner or way

To endow with a nature or qualities

A crustacean larva having three pairs of locomotive organs (corresponding to the antennules, antennae, and mandibles), a median eye, and little or no segmentation of the body.

The power or act of discovering ships or land at considerable distances.
The act of nauseating, or the state of being nauseated.
Causing, or fitted to cause, nausea
An entertainment consisting chiefly of dancing by professional dancing (or Nautch) girls.

Shaped like the hull of a ship.
Like or pertaining to the nautilus

The only existing genus of tetrabranchiate cephalopods. About four species are found living in the tropical Pacific, but many other species are found fossil.  The shell is spiral, symmetrical, and chambered, or divided into several cavities by simple curved partitions, which are traversed and connected together by a continuous and nearly central tube or siphuncle. See Tetrabranchiata.
A tribe of Indians inhabiting New Mexico and Arizona, allied to the Apaches. They are now largely engaged in agriculture.
The block in the center of a wheel, from which the spokes radiate, and through which the axle passes
A mark or depression in the middle of the abdomen
A European perennial succulent herb (Cotyledon umbilicus), having round, peltate leaves with a central depression
A kind of small turnip, a variety of Brassica campestris. See Brassica.
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a boat or ship.
The quality or condition of being navigable
Originally, a laborer on canals for internal navigation
A deputy ruler or viceroy in India
A specied of wild sheep (Ovis Hodgsonii), native of Nepaul and Thibet. It has a dorsal mane and a white ruff beneath the neck.
A native or inhabitant of Nazareth

A Jew bound by a vow to lave the hair uncut, to abstain from wine and strong drink, and to practice extraordinary purity of life and devotion, the obligation being for life, or for a certain time. The word is also used adjectively.
Of or pertaining to a Nazarite, or to Nazarites.
The vow and practice of a Nazarite.
The tongue or pole of a cart or other vehicle drawn by two animals.
Left aground on the height of a spring tide, so that it will not float till the next spring tide
Of of pertaining to Naples in Italy.
At a little distance, in place, time, manner, or degree

Of or pertaining to a region of the earth's surface including all of temperate and arctic North America and Greenland. In the geographical distribution of animals, this region is marked off as the habitat certain species.
Having the feet so near together that they interfere in traveling.
The state or quality of being near
Seeing distinctly at short distances only
Cattle of the genus Bos, as distinguished from horses, sheep, and goats

A building for the shelter of neat cattle.
The state or quality of being neat.
A woman who takes care of cattle.
A genus of small marine Crustacea, considered the type of a distinct order (Nebaloidea, or Phyllocarida.)
A faint, cloudlike, self-luminous mass of matter situated beyond the solar system among the stars. True nebulae are gaseous
Clouded with indistinct color markings, as an animal.
Composed of successive short curves supposed to resemble a cloud
The act or process of nebulizing
To reduce (as a liquid) to a fine spray or vapor
The state or quality of being nebulous
An advocate of the doctrine of philosophical necessity
Of or pertaining to the doctrine of philosophical necessity in regard to the origin and existence of things, especially as applied to the actings or choices of the will
The act of making necessary, or the state of being made necessary
The quality or state of being necessary, unavoidable, or absolutely requisite
The part of an animal which connects the head and the trunk, and which, in man and many other animals, is more slender than the trunk.
A band which goes around the neck
A piece of any fabric worn around the neck.
A string of beads, etc., or any continuous band or chain, worn around the neck as an ornament.
A small convex molding surrounding a column at the jinction of the shaft and capital.
A scarf, band, or kerchief of silk, etc., passing around the neck or collar and tied in front
A collective term for cravats, collars, etc.
An American annual weed (veronica peregrina), with small white flowers and a roundish pod.
The death of a part by molecular disintegration and without loss of continuity, as in the processes of degeneration and atrophy.
One who gives an account of deaths.
An account of deaths, or of the dead
The art of revealing future events by means of a pretended communication with the dead
Fetid feldspar, a mineral which, when struck, exhales a fetid odor.
Of or pertaining to the Necrophaga
An exaggerated fear of death or horror of dead bodies.
Any one of numerous species of beetles of the genus Necrophorus and allied genera
Or or relating to post-mortem examinations.
Mortification or gangrene of bone, or the death of a bone or portion of a bone in mass, as opposed to its death by molecular disintegration. See Caries.
The drink of the gods (as ambrosia was their food)

A pet name for a donkey.

In a needy condition or manner
The state or quality of being needy
A small instrument of steel, sharply pointed at one end, with an eye to receive a thread, -- used in sewing.
A book-shaped needlecase, having leaves of cloth into which the needles are stuck.
The European great pipefich (Siphostoma, / Syngnathus, acus)
As much thread as is used in a needle at one time.
One who makes or uses needles
Distressed by want of the means of living
An Asiatic name for Melia Azadirachta, and M. Azedarach. See Margosa.

A writ to restrain a person from leaving the country, or the jurisdiction of the court. The writ was originally applicable to purposes of state, but is now an ordinary process of courts of equity, resorted to for the purpose of obtaining bail, or security to abide a decree.
Any fish of the genus Distichodus. Several large species inhabit the Nile.
The quality or state of being negative.
Not to attend to with due care or attention
The quality or state of being negligent
That may neglicted, disregarded, or left out of consideration.

The act or process of negotiating
The state of being busily occupied
A blackish fish (Hypoplectrus nigricans), of the Sea-bass family. It is a native of the West Indies and Florida.
A degraded Papuan race, inhabiting Luzon and some of the other east Indian Islands. They resemble negroes, but are smaller in size. They are mostly nomads.
A beverage made of wine, water, sugar, nutmeg, and lemon juice
A term supposed to mean, perforated wind instruments of music, as pipes or flutes.
A woman born in the state of villeinage
To utter the cry of the horse
A person who lives near another
The quality or condition of being a neighbor
The quality or state of being neighborly.
Apropriate to the relation of neighbors
The mahogany-like wood of the South African tree Pteroxylon utile, the sawdust of which causes violent sneezing (whence the name). Also called sneezewood.
A genus of great water lilies. The North American species is Nelumbo lutea, the Asiatic is the sacred lotus, N. speciosa.
A peculiar kind of fructification on certain red algae, consisting of an external mass of filaments at length separating into tetraspores.
An ordr of helminths, including the Nematoidea and Gordiacea
A combining form from Gr. nh^ma, nh`matos, a thread.
One of a peculiar kind of cups, or calicles, found upon hydroids of the family Plumularidae. They contain nematocysts. See Plumularia.

A lasso cell, or thread cell. See Lasso cell, under Lasso.

Of or pertaining to the Nematoidea.

Of or pertaining to Nemea, in Argolis, where the ancient Greeks celebrated games, and Hercules killed a lion.

The goddess of retribution or vengeance
One who is fond of forest or forest scenery
Of or pertaining to a wood or grove.

More recent than the Eocene, that is, including both the Miocene and Pliocene divisions of the Tertiary.
A term applied to the lowest deposits of the Cretaceous or chalk formation of Europe, being the lower greensand.
Of or pertaining to the universe in its present state
Government by new or inexperienced hands
In ancient Sparta, one of those Helots who were freed by the state in reward for military service.
An elementary substance which forms one of the constituents of didymium. Symbol Nd. Atomic weight 140.8.
Of or pertaining to the New World, or Western Hemisphere.
An alloy resembling silver, and consisting chiefly of copper, zinc, and nickel, with small proportions of tin, aluminium, and bismuth.
A new method or system of writing.
Applied to the Romance languages, as being mostly of Latin origin.
Of or pertaining to, or designating, an era characterized by late remains in stone.

A pantheistic eclectic school of philosophy, of which Plotinus was the chief (A. D. 205-270), and which sought to reconcile the Platonic and Aristotelian systems with Oriental theosophy. It tended to mysticism and theurgy, and was the last product of Greek philosophy.
A panorama of the interior of a building, seen from within.
The substance constituting the edible bird's nest.
One ho introduces new word/ or phrases.
Belonging to, or designating, a region of the earth's surface which comprises most of South America, the Antilles, and tropical North America.
More recent than the Paleozoic, -- that is, including the Mesozoic and Cenozoic.
A genus of aquatic hemipterus insects. The species feed upon other insects and are noted for their voracity
Of or pertaining to Nepaul, a kingdom in Northern Hindostan.
A drug used by the ancients to give relief from pain and sorrow
A genus of labiate plants, including the catnip and ground ivy.
One who advocates or practices nephalism.
A mineral occuring at Vesuvius, in glassy agonal crystals

A grandson or grandchild, or remoter lineal descendant.

Of or pertaining to a nephridium.

Of or pertaining to the kidneys or urinary organs

The son of Saturn and Ops, the god of the waters, especially of the sea.  He is represented as bearing a trident for a scepter.
Of or pertaining to the ocean or sea.
One who adopts the neptunian theory.
As seen from Neptune, or having Neptune as a center
A new metallic element, of doubtful genuineness and uncertain indentification, said to exist in certain minerals, as columbite.

A sea nymph, one of the daughters of Nereus, who were attendants upon Neptune, and were represented as riding on sea horses, sometimes with the human form entire, and sometimes with the tail of a fish.
Any annelid resembling Nereis, or of the family Lycoridae or allied families.
A genus of marine gastropods, mostly natives of warm climates.
Any mollusk of the genus Nerita.
A genus including numerous species of shells resembling Nerita in form. They mostly inhabit brackish water, and are often delicately tinted.
A Roman emperor notorius for debauchery and barbarous cruelty
An essential oil obtained by distillation from the flowers of the orange. It has a strong odor, and is used in perfumery, etc.

One of the whitish and elastic bundles of fibers, with the accompanying tissues, which transmit nervous impulses between nerve centers and various parts of the animal body.
Affected by a tremor, or by a nervous disease

To treat or test, as a liquid, with a solution of mercuric iodide in potassium iodide and potassium hydroxide, which is called Nessler's solution or Nessler's test, and is used to detect the presence of ammonia.
The bed or receptacle prepared by a fowl for holding her eggs and for hatching and rearing her young.
As much or many as will fill a nest.
To make and occupy a nest
A genus of parrots with gray heads. of New Zeland and papua, allied to the cockatoos. See Kaka.

An adherent of Nestorius, patriarch of Constantinople to the fifth century, who has condemned as a heretic for maintaining that the divine and the human natures were not merged into one nature in Christ (who was God in man), and, hence, that it was improper to call Mary the mother of Christ
The doctrines of the nestorian Christians, or of Nestorius.
A fabric of twine, thread, or the like, wrought or woven into meshes, and used for catching fish, birds, butterflies, etc.

A plant of the genus Urtica, covered with minute sharp hairs containing a poison that produces a stinging sensation. Urtica gracitis is common in the Northern, and U. chamaedryoides in the Southern, United States. the common European species, U. urens and U. dioica, are also found in the Eastern united States. U. pilulifera is the Roman nettle of England.
The halves of yarns in the unlaid end of a rope twisted for pointing or grafting.

relating to the nerves or nervous system

A disease, the chief symptom of which is a very acute pain, exacerbating or intermitting, which follows the course of a nervous branch, extends to its ramifications, and seems therefore to be seated in the nerve. It seems to be independent of any structural lesion.
Of or pertaining to, or having the character of, neuralgia
Of or pertaining to a neurapophysis.
One of the two lateral processes or elements which form the neural arch.

A poisonous organic base (a ptomaine) formed in the decomposition of protagon with boiling baryta water, and in the putrefraction of proteid matter. It was for a long time considered identical with choline, a crystalline body originally obtained from bile. Chemically, however, choline is oxyethyl-trimethyl-ammonium hydroxide, while neurine is vinyl-trimethyl-ammonium hydroxide.
Nerve force. See Vital force, under Vital.

A substance, resembling keratin, present in nerve tissue, as in the sheath of the axis cylinder of medullated nerve fibers. Like keratin it resists the action of most chemical agents, and by decomposition with sulphuric acid yields leucin and tyrosin.
One who is versed in neurology
The branch of science which treats of the nervous system.

An affection of the nervous system or of a nerve.
The ventral lobe or branch of a parapodium.

An opening at either end of the embryonic neural canal.

An order of hexapod insects having two pairs of large, membranous, net-veined wings. The mouth organs are adapted for chewing. They feed upon other insects, and undergo a complete metamorphosis. The ant-lion, hellgamite, and lacewing fly are examples. Formerly, the name was given to a much more extensive group, including the true Neuroptera and the Pseudoneuroptera.
Of or pertaining to the Neuroptera.
An extensive genus of fossil ferns, of which species have been found from the Devonian to the Triassic formation.
Pertaining to, or forming, both nerves and sense organs.

Of or pertaining to the neuroskeleton.
The deep-seated parts of the vertebrate skeleton which are relation with the nervous axis and locomation.
Of or pertaining to the nerves
An instrument for cutting or dissecting nerves.
One who skilled in or practices neurotomy.
The dissection, or anatomy, of the nervous system.

Neither the one thing nor the other
The state or quality of being neutral

A room where news is collected and disseminated, or periodicals sold
One who gathered news for, and wrote, news-letters.

Any one of several species of small aquatic salamanders. The common British species are the crested newt (Triton cristatus) and the smooth newt (Lophinus punctatus). In America, Diemictylus viridescens is one of the most abundant species.
Of or pertaining to Sir Isaac Newton, or his discoveries.
Of or pertaining to, or suitable for, the commencement of the year
the first day of a calendar year
A group of islands in the South Pacific Ocean.
A tribe of Indians, mostly inhabiting Idaho.

A subdivision or the American Upper Silurian system, embracing the Medina, Clinton, and Niagara epoch. The rocks of the Niagara epoch, mostly limestones, are extensively distributed, and at Niagara Falls consist of about eighty feet of shale supporting a greater thickness of limestone, which is gradually undermined by the removal of the shale. See Chart of Geology.
A small and pointed thing or part
To bite by little at a time
One who, or that which, nibbles.
A kind of golf stick used to lift the ball out of holes, ruts, etc.
The laughing falcon. See under laughing.
A mineral of a copper-red color and metallic luster
Of or pertaining to Nice, a town of Asia Minor, or to the ecumenial council held there A. D. 325.
Quality or state of being nice.
The quality or state of being nice (in any of the senses of that word.).
A cavity, hollow, or recess, generally within the thickness of a wall, for a statue, bust, or other erect ornament. hence, any similar position, literal or figurative.
An evil spirit of the waters.
Same as Nicker nut, Nicker tree.

A bright silver-white metallic element. It is of the iron group, and is hard, malleable, and ductile. It occurs combined with sulphur in millerite, with arsenic in the mineral niccolite, and with arsenic and sulphur in nickel glance. Symbol Ni. Atomic weight 58.6.
An alloy of nickel, a variety of German silver.
Of, pertaining to, or designating, those compounds of nickel in which, as contrasted with the nickelic compounds, the metal has a lower valence
One of the night brawlers of London formerly noted for breaking windows with half-pence.

A rounded seed, rather smaller than a nutmeg, having a hard smooth shell, and a yellowish or bluish color. The seeds grow in the prickly pods of tropical, woody climbers of the genus Caesalpinia. C. Bonduc has yellowish seeds
A name given in contempt, derision, or sportive familiarity
One of certain corrupt persons in the early church at Ephesus, who are censured in rev. ii. 6, 15.
A genus of American and Asiatic solanaceous herbs, with viscid foliage and funnel-shaped blossoms. Several species yield tobacco. See Tobacco.
A white waxy substance having a hot, bitter taste, extracted from tobacco leaves and called also tobacco camphor.
A complex, oily, nitrogenous base, isomeric with nicotine, and obtained by the reduction of certain derivatives of the pyridine group.
An alkaloid which is the active principle of tobacco. It is a colorless, transparent, oily liquid, having an acrid odor, and an acrid burning taste. It is intensely poisonous.
Pertaining to, or derived from, nicotine
Of, pertaining to, or baring, eggs or egg capsules
The act or process of building a nest.
Scent or savor of meat or food, cooked or cooking.
Resembling the smell or taste of roast meat, or of corrupt animal matter.
Nestling, as a bird in itss nest.
To make a nest, as a bird.
The time of remaining in the nest.
A Silurian fossil, formerly supposed to consist of eggs.
A nest: a repository for the eggs of birds, insects, etc.
One who practices the style of ornamentation called niello.
A metallic alloy of a deep black color.
A person meanly close and covetous

Meanly covetous or avarcious in dealing with others

In a near relation in place, time, degree, etc.
The quality or state of being nigh.

A cap worn in bed to protect the head, or in undress.
Going or traveling in the night.
A loose gown used for undress
A small, plain, brown and gray European song bird (Luscinia luscinia). It sings at night, and is celebrated for the sweetness of its song.
A goatsucker, esp. the European species. See Illust. of Goatsucker.
Of or pertaining to the night, or to every night
One whose business is emptying privies by night.
A fiend or incubus formerly supposed to cause trouble in sleep.
A common name of many species of the genus Solanum, given esp. to the Solanum nigrum, or black nightshade, a low, branching weed with small white flowers and black berries reputed to be poisonous.
A kind of nightgown for men.
The time from dusk to dawn
The complex, nitrogenous, organic base and dyestuff called also aniline black.
The act or process of making black.
A dark blue dyestuff, of the induline group
One who advocates the doctrine of nihilism
Of, pertaining to, or characterized by, nihilism.
An instrument for measuring the rise of water in the Nile during its periodical flood.
Of or pertaining to the river Nile
Serving to bring clouds or stormy weather.
A circle, or disk, or any indication of radiant light around the heads of divinities, saints, and sovereigns, upon medals, pictures, etc.
A white-flowered rosaceous shrub (Neillia, / Spiraea, opulifolia), common in the Northern United States.  The bark separates into many thin layers, whence the name.
A game in which nine holes are made in the ground, into which a ball is bowled.
An old English silver coin, worth nine pence.
A game played with nine pins, or pieces of wood, set on end, at which a wooden ball is bowled to knock them down
Nine times twenty, or one hundred and eighty.
Following the eighteenth and preceding the twentieth
Next in order after the eighty-ninth.
Following the eight and preceding the tenth
The daughter of Tantalus, and wife of Amphion, king of Thebes. Her pride in her children provoked Apollo and Diana, who slew them all. Niobe herself was changed by the gods into stone.
A later name of columbium. See Columbium.
A kind of snuff prepared by the natives of Venezuela from the roasted seeds of a leguminous tree (Piptadenia peregrina), thence called niopo tree.
One who, or that which, nips.

A yellow-flowered composite herb (Lampsana communis), formerly used as an external application to the nipples of women

In the Buddhist system of religion, the final emancipation of the soul from transmigration, and consequently a beatific enfrachisement from the evils of wordly existence, as by annihilation or absorption into the divine. See Buddhism.
The first month of the jewish ecclesiastical year, formerly answering nearly to the month of April, now to March, of the Christian calendar. See Abib.
The egg of a louse or other small insect.
Of, pertaining to, or designating, a complex organic acid produced as a white crystalline substance by the action of nitrous acid on hydroquinone.
Any one of a series of nitro derivatives of aniline. In general they are yellow crystalline substances.
Combined, or impregnated, with nitric acid, or some of its compounds.
A mineral occurring in transparent crystals, usually of a white, sometimes of a reddish gray, or lemon-yellow, color
An artificial bed of animal matter for the manufacture of niter by nitrification. See Nitrification, 2.
Of, pertaining to, or containing, nitrogen
A binary compound of nitrogen with a more metallic element or radical
The act, process, or result of combining with nitrogen or some of its compounds.
To combine or impregnate with nitrogen
Any one of a series of cyanogen compounds
A combining form or an adjective denoting the presence of niter.

A yellow aromatic liquid (C6H5.NO2), produced by the action of nitric acid on benzene, and called from its odor imitation oil of bitter almonds, or essence of mirbane. It is used in perfumery, and is manufactured in large quantities in the preparation of aniline. Fornerly called also nitrobenzol.
Nitrate of calcium, a substance having a grayish white color, occuring in efforescences on old walls, and in limestone caves, especially where there exists decaying animal matter.
A nitro derivative of methane, analogous to chloroform, obtained as a colorless oily or crystalline substance, CH.(NO2)3, quite explosive, and having well-defined acid properties.

Any tree or shrub of the genus Quercus. The oaks have alternate leaves, often variously lobed, and staminate flowers in catkins. The fruit is a smooth nut, called an acorn, which is more or less inclosed in a scaly involucre called the cup or cupule. There are now recognized about three hundred species, of which nearly fifty occur in the United States, the rest in Europe, Asia, and the other parts of North America, a very few barely reaching the northern parts of South America and Africa. Many of the oaks form forest trees of grand proportions and live many centuries. The wood is usually hard and tough, and provided with conspicuous medullary rays, forming the silver grain.
