One to whom anything is resigned, or in whose favor a resignation is made.
The act of resiling, springing back, or rebounding

Any one of a class of yellowish brown solid inflammable substances, of vegetable origin, which are nonconductors of electricity, have a vitreous fracture, and are soluble in ether, alcohol, and essential oils, but not in water
Any one of the salts the resinic acids.
Pertaining to, or obtained from, resin
By means, or in the manner, of resin.

The act, operation, or process of resolving. Specifically: (a) The act of separating a compound into its elements or component parts. (b) The act of analyzing a complex notion, or solving a vexed question or difficult problem.
The quality or condition of being resolvable
To separate the component parts of
So as to resolve or clear up difficulties
Returning, or capable of returning, sound

A colorless crystalline substance of the phenol series, obtained by melting certain resins, as galbanum, asafetida, etc., with caustic potash. It is also produced artificially and used in making certain dyestuffs, as phthalein, fluorescein, and eosin.
Of, or pertaining to, or producing, resorcin
That to which one resorts orr on which one depends for supply or support
The state or quality of being respectable
Placed so as to face one another
The act of sprinkling or scattering.
The quality or state of being respirable
The act of respiring or breathing again, or catching one's breath.

A divice of gauze or wire, covering the mouth or nose, to prevent the inhalation of noxious substances, as dust or smoke. Being warmed by the breath, it tempers cold air passing through it, and may also be used for the inhalation of medicated vapors.
A putting off of that which was appointed
The quality or state of being resplendent
A loan upon goods laden on board a ship. It differs from bottomry, which is a loan on the ship itself.
The state of being responsible, accountable, or answerable, as for a trust, debt, or obligation.
The keeper of an eathing house or a restaurant.
To force back against the current
A European leguminous plant (Ononis arvensis) with long, tough roots.
The quality or state of being resty
To restore to a former state.
The act of restoring anything to its rightful owner, or of making good, or of giving an equivalent for any loss, damage, or injury
The act of restoring or bringing back to a former place, station, or condition
The belief or doctrines of the Restorationists.
One who believes in a temporary future punishment and a final restoration of all to the favor and presence of God
To bring back to its former state
One who, or that which, restores.
One who, or that which, restrains.
The act or process of restraining, or of holding back or hindering from motion or action, in any manner
The act of restricting, or state of being restricted
Quality or state of being restringent
Resulting or issuing from a combination
Capable of, or admitting of, being resumed.
The state of luing on the back
Rising again, as from the dead.
One who steals bodies from the grave, as for dissection.
One who, or that which resuscitates. Also used adjectively.
The act of resuscitating, or state of being resuscitated.
One who, or that which, resuscitates.
A shelf behind the altar, for display of lights, vases of wlowers, etc.
The sale of commodities in small quantities or parcels
One who, or that which, retains.
One who takes again what has been taken
The act of retaliating, or of returning like for like
One who, or that which, retards.
To make an effort to vomit
Act of disclosing or uncovering something concealed.
A white crystalline hydrocarbon, polymeric with benzene. It is extracted from pine tar, and is also found in certain fossil resins.
The act of retaining, or the state of being ratined.
A muscle which serves to retain an organ or part in place, esp. when retracted. See Illust. of Phylactolemata.
Any one of several species of bryozoans of the genus Retepora. They form delicate calcareous corals, usually composed of thin fenestrated fronds.
The act of weaving or forming again.
A gladiator armed with a net for entangling his adversary and a trident for despatching him.
Any spider which spins webs to catch its prey.
The quality or state of being reticent, or keeping silence
Having the form of a net, or of network

An extensive division of rhizopods in which the pseudopodia are more or less slender and coalesce at certain points, forming irregular meshes. It includes the shelled Foraminifera, together with some groups which lack a true shell.
The quality or state of being reticulated, or netlike
A little bag, originally of network
The second stomach of ruminants, in which folds of the mucous membrane form hexagonal cells
Composed of crossing lines and interstices
The delicate membrane by which the back part of the globe of the eye is lined, and in which the fibers of the optic nerve terminate. See Eye.
Of or pertaining to the retina.
A translucent variety of serpentine, of a honey yellow or greenish yellow color, having a waxy resinlike luster.
That part of the eye of an invertebrate which corresponds in function with the retina of a vertebrate.
An inflammable mineral resin, usually of a yellowish brown color, found in roundish masses, sometimes with coal.
A hydrocarbon oil obtained by the distillation of resin, -- used in printer's ink.
One of group of two to four united cells which occupy the axial part of the ocelli, or ommatidia, of the eyes of invertebrates, and contain the terminal nerve fibrillae. See Illust. under Ommatidium.
The study of the retina of the eye by means of the ophthalmoscope.
The body of retainers who follow a prince or other distinguished person
One of the group of pigmented cells which surround the retinophorae of invertebrates. See Illust. under Ommatidium.
A bird having small polygonal scales covering the tarsi.
A kind of retrenchment, as in the body of a bastion, which may be disputed inch by inch after the defenses are dismantled. It usually consists of two faces which make a reentering angle.
The act of retiring, or the state of being retired
A white crystalline hydrocarbon produced indirectly from retene.
A group of spiders which spin irregular webs
Act of retorting or throwing back
To touch again, or rework, in order to improve
To trace back, as a line.
The act of retracting what has been said
The act of retracting, or drawing back
One who, or that which, retracts.
The withdrawing, or open renunciation, of a suit in court by the plaintiff, by which he forever lost his right of action.
The act of retiring or withdrawing one's self, especially from what is dangerous or disagreeable.
Furnishing or serving as a retreat.
The act or process of retrenching
A secdond trial, experiment, or test
That may be retrieved or recovered
A prefix or combining form signifying backward, back
To act backward, or in return
Any extension of a church behind the high altar, as a chapel
The act of retrograding, or moving backward.
Apparently moving backward, and contrary to the succession of the signs, that is, from east to west, as a planet.
The act of retrograding, or going backward
The quality or state of being retromingent.
Organized so as to discharge the urine backward.
The act, or the faculty, of looking back on things past.
The inoculation of a cow with human vaccine virus.
The act of retruding, or the state of being retruded.
To try (esp. judicially) a second time
A place or establishment where flax is retted. See Ret.
The act or process of preparing flax for use by soaking, maceration, and kindred processes
Capable of, or admitting of, being returned.
Having the end rounded and slightly indented
To vaccinate a second time or again.
To make known (that which has been concealed or kept secret)
The quality or state of being revealable
One who, or that which, reveals.
The beat of drum, or bugle blast, about break of day, to give notice that it is time for the soldiers to rise, and for the sentinels to forbear challenging.
The act of revealing, disclosing, or discovering to others what was before unknown to them.
The act of engaging in a revel
To inflict harm in return for, as an injury, insult, etc.
Full of, or prone to, revenge
That which returns, or comes back, from an investment
One who, or that which, produces reverberation.
To regard with reverence, or profound respect and affection, mingled with awe or fear
Profound respect and esteem mingled with fear and affection, as for a holy being or place
A loose or irregular train of thought occurring in musing or mediation
The act of returning, or coming back
Of or pertaining to a reversion
One who has a reversion, or who is entitled to lands or tenements, after a particular estate granted is terminated.
To turn back, or to the contrary
A remedy which restores the natural order of the inverted irritative motions in the animal system.
One who, or that which, reverts.
Capable of, or admitting of, reverting or being reverted
The apartment, in a church or temple, where the vestments, etc., are kept
To face, as an embankment, with masonry, wood, or other material.
A facing of wood, stone, or any other material, to sustain an embankment when it receives a slope steeper than the natural slope
To vibrate back or in return.
To vie with, or rival, in return.
To address or abuse with opprobrious and contemptuous language
A growing green or fresh again
The act of revising, or reviewing and reexamining for correction and improvement
To look at again for the detection of errors
Having the power or purpose to revise
The act of reviving, or the state of being revived.
A clergyman or layman who promotes revivals of religion
One who, or that which, revives.
The act of reviving, or the state of being revived
Revival of a suit which is abated by the death or marriage of any of the parties, -- done by a bill of revivor.
The act of calling back, or the state of being recalled
The act of revolving, or turning round on an axis or a center
Of or pertaining to a revolution in government
One who is engaged in effecting a revolution
The state of being in revolution
One engaged in effecting a change of government
To change completely, as by a revolution
Inclined to revolve things in the mind
To turn or roll round on, or as on, an axis, like a wheel
The act or state of revolving
One who, or that which, revolves
A strong pulling or drawing back
To give in return, whether good or evil
An obsolete phrase of disputed meaning, -- perhaps, smooth or polished bone.
To win again, or win back.
To repeat in the same words
An appelation applied after the manner of a proper name to the fox. Same as Renard.
A minute smooth rodlike or fusiform structure found in the tissues of many Turbellaria.
A suborder of Turbellaria including those that have a simple cylindrical, or saclike, stomach, without an intestine.
Of or pertaining to the Rhabdocoela.
A minute calcareous rodlike structure found both at the surface and the bottom of the ocean
One of numerous minute rodlike structures formed of two or more cells situated behind the retinulae in the compound eyes of insects, etc. See Illust. under Ommatidium.
One of the several parts composing a rhabdom.
An extinct division of Hydrozoa which includes the graptolities.
A genus of marine Bryozoa in which the tubular cells have a centralchitinous axis and the tentacles are borne on a bilobed lophophore. It is the type of the order Pterobranchia, or Podostomata
A minute sphere composed of rhabdoliths.
Of or pertaining to the rhachis

A division of marine gastropods having a retractile proboscis and three longitudinal rows of teeth on the radula. It includes many of the large ornamental shells, as the miters, murices, olives, purpuras, volutes, and whelks. See Illust. in Append.

Having gular teeth formed by a peculiar modification of the inferior spines of some of the vertebrae, as certain South African snakes (Dasypeltis) which swallow birds' eggs and use these gular teeth to crush them.
One of the three judges of the infernal regions
Pertaining to, or of the same horizon as, certain Mesozoic strata of the Rhetian Alps. These strata are regarded as closing the Triassic period. See the Chart of Geology.
A variety of the mineral cyanite.

Of or pertaining to a natural order of shrubs and trees (Rhamnaceae, or Rhamneae) of which the buckthorn (Rhamnus) is the type. It includes also the New Jersey tea, the supple-jack, and one of the plants called lotus (Zizyphus).
A genus of shrubs and small trees
A genus of pterodactyls in which the elongated tail supported a leathery expansion at the tip.
The horny covering of the bill of birds.
The continuation of the seed stalk along the side of an anatropous ovule or seed, forming a ridge or seam.
Minute transparent, often needle-shaped, crystals found in the tissues of plants.
Anciently, one who recited or composed a rhapsody
To utter as a rhapsody, or in the manner of a rhapsody
A recitation or song of a rhapsodist
The powerfully astringent root of a half-shrubby Peruvian plant (Krameria triandra). It is used in medicine and to color port wine.
The ramie or grass-cloth plant. See Grass-cloth plant, under Grass.
A suborder of struthious birds including the rheas.
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid (commonly called chrysophanic acid) found in rhubarb (Rheum).
One of the berries or drupes of the European buckthorn
Having a verb for its base
Of or pertaining to Rheimis, or Reima, in France.
Of or pertaining to the river Rhine
A metallic wire used for regulating the resistance of a circuit, or varying the strength of an electric current, by inserting a greater or less length of it in the circuit.
An instrument for measuring currents, especially the force or intensity of electrical currents
Of or pertaining to a rheometer or rheometry.
The measurement of the force or intensity of currents.
Any apparatus by which an electrical current is originated.
A connecting wire of an electric or voltaic apparatus, traversed by a current.
An instrument for detecting the presence or movement of currents, as of electricity.
A contrivance for adjusting or regulating the strength of electrical currents, operating usually by the intercalation of resistance which can be varied at will.
An instrument which periodically or otherwise interrupts an electric current.
An instrument for reversing the direction of an electric current.
Pertaining to the ancient Rhaeti, or Rhaetians, or to Rhaetia, their country
One well versed in the rules and principles of rhetoric.
A genus of plants. See Rhubarb.
Derived from, or having the character of, rheum
A general disease characterized by painful, often multiple, local inflammations, usually affecting the joints and muscles, but also extending sometimes to the deeper organs, as the heart.
Of or resembling rheum or rheumatism.
Pertaining to, or characterized by, rheum.
The class of skin disease developed by the dartrous diathesis. See under Dartrous.
A mixture of volatile hydrocarbons intermediate between gsolene and cymogene. It is obtained in the purification of crude petroleum, and is used as a refregerant.
Og or pertaining to the nose or olfactory organs.
Of or pertaining to the rhinencephalon.
The division of the brain in front of the prosencephalon, consisting of the two olfactory lobes from which the olfactory nerves arise.
A colorless stone of high luster, made of paste. It is much used as an inexpensive ornament.
A combining form from Greek //, ///, the nose, as in rhinolith, rhinology.
Of or pertaining to the rhinoceros

Any pachyderm belonging to the genera Rhinoceros, Atelodus, and several allied genera of the family Rhinocerotidae, of which several living, and many extinct, species are known. They are large and powerful, and usually have either one or two stout conical median horns on the snout.
Of or pertaining to the rhinoceros.
A concretion formed within the cavities of the nose.
The science which treats of the nose, and its diseases.
Any species of the genus Rhinilophus, or family Rhinolophidae, having a horseshoe-shaped nasal crest
Like or pertaining to the rhinolophids, or horseshoe bats.

One of the two tentacle-like organs on the back of the head or neck of a nudibranch or tectibranch mollusk. They are usually retractile, and often transversely furrowed or plicate, and are regarded as olfactory organs. Called also dorsal tentacles. See Illust.  under Pygobranchia, and Opisthobranchia.
Plastic surgery of the nose to correct deformity or to replace lost tissue. Tissue may be transplanted from the patient's cheek, forehead, arm, etc., or even from another person.
Any old-world bat of the genus Rhinopoma. The rhinopomes have a long tail extending beyond the web, and inhabit caves and tombs.

A rare disease of the skin, characterized by the development of very hard, more or less flattened, prominences, appearing first upon the nose and subsequently upon the neighboring parts, esp. the lips, palate, and throat.
A small mirror for use in rhinoscopy.
The examination or study of the soft palate, posterior nares, etc., by means of a laryngoscopic mirror introduced into the pharynx.
The sheath of the upper mandible of a bird.
A division of gastropod mollusks having a large number of long, divergent, hooklike, lingual teeth in each transverse row. It includes the scutibranchs. See Illustration in Appendix.
One of the Rhipiptera, a group of insects having wings which fold like a fan
Producing flowers from a rootstock, or apparently from a root.
A rootlike filament or hair growing from the stems of mosses or on lichens
Having perennial rootstocks or bulbs, but annual flowering stems
A division of Pectostraca including saclike parasites of Crustacea. They adhere by rootlike extensions of the head. See Illusration in Appendix.
A reptile whose teeth are rooted in sockets, as the crocodile.
One of a proposed class of flowering plants growning on the roots of other plants and destitute of green foliage.
Having the nature or habit of a rhizome or rootstock.
A division of marsupials. The wombat is the type.
A genus of trees including the mangrove. See Mangrove.

An extensive class of Protozoa, including those which have pseudopodia, by means of which they move about and take their food. The principal groups are Lobosa (or Am/bea), Helizoa, Radiolaria, and Foraminifera (or Reticularia). See Protozoa.
Of or pertaining to the rhizopods.
A suborder of Medusae which includes very large species without marginal tentacles, but having large mouth lobes closely united at the edges. See Illust. in Appendix.
The arrangement of the roots of plants.
Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, rhodium and ammonia
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid (commonly called sulphocyanic acid) which frms a red color with ferric salts.
Of or pertaining to Rhodes, an island of the Mediterranean.

A rare element of the light platinum group. It is found in platinum ores, and obtained free as a white inert metal which it is very difficult to fuse. Symbol Rh. Atomic weight 104.1.  Specific gravity 12.

Pertaining to, or designating, a colorless crystalline substance (called rhodizonic acid, and carboxylic acid) obtained from potassium carboxide and from certain quinones. It forms brilliant red, yellow, and purple salts.
Manganese carbonate, a rose-red mineral sometimes occuring crystallized, but generally massive with rhombohedral cleavage like calcite
A genus of shrubs or small trees, often having handsome evergreen leaves, and remarkable for the beauty of their flowers
Manganese spar, or silicate of manganese, a mineral occuring crystallised and in rose-red masses. It is often used as an ornamental stone.
The red pigment contained in the inner segments of the cones of the retina in animals. See Chromophane.
The visual purple. See under Visual.

An equilateral parallelogram, or quadrilateral figure whose sides are equal and the opposite sides parallel. The angles may be unequal, two being obtuse and two acute, as in the cut, or the angles may be equal, in which case it is usually called a square.
A ganoid fish having rhombic enameled scales
A dicyemid which produces infusorialike embryos
A solid contained by six rhomboids
An oblique-angled parallelogram like a rhomb, but having only the opposite sides equal, the length and with being different.
Having, or approaching, the shape of a rhomboid.
Between rhomboid and ovate, or oval, in shape.
Of or pertaining to a rhonchus

An adventitious whistling or snoring sound heard on auscultation of the chest when the air channels are partially obstructed. By some writers the term rhonchus is used as equivalent to rale in its widest sense. See Rale.
Applied to a line or verse in which each successive word has one more syllable than the preceding.
One of the marginal sensory bodies of medusae belonging to the Discophora.
A division of Lepidoptera including all the butterflies. They differ from other Lepidoptera in having club-shaped antennae.
An oversounding, or a misuse, of the letter r
The name of several large perennial herbs of the genus Rheum and order Polygonaceae.
A line which crosses successive meridians at a constant angle
A genus of shrubs and small treets. See Sumac.
A mixtire of caustic lime and orpiment, or tersulphide of arsenic, -- used in the depilation of hides.
An expression of thought in numbers, measure, or verse
The art or habit of making rhymes
A suborder of leeches including those that have a protractile proboscis, without jaws. Clepsine is the type.

An order of reptiles having biconcave vertebrae, immovable quadrate bones, and many other peculiar osteological characters. Hatteria is the only living genus, but numerous fossil genera are known, some of which are among the earliest of reptiles. See Hatteria. Called also Rhynchocephalia.
A genus of brachiopods of which some species are still living, while many are found fossil.
A group of Coleoptera having a snoutlike head
A quartzose trachyte, an igneous rock often showing a fluidal structure.
In ancient art, the painting of genre or still-life pictures.
An instrument, acting on the principle of Pitot's tube, for measuring the velocity of a fluid current, the speed of a ship, etc.
In the widest sense, a dividing into short portions by a regular succession of motions, impulses, sounds, accents, etc., producing an agreeable effect, as in music poetry, the dance, or the like.
One who writes in rhythm, esp. in poetic rhythm or meter.
Pertaining to, or of the nature of, rhythm
The department of musical science which treats of the length of sounds.
An instrument for marking time in musical movements. See Metronome.
One of the curved bones attached to the vertebral column and supporting the lateral walls of the thorax.
A low, vulgar, brutal, foul-mouthed wretch
An engine of war used in the Middle Ages, consisting of a protected elevated staging on wheels, and armed in front with pikes. It was (after the 14th century) furnished with small cannon.
A fillet or narrow woven fabric, commonly of silk, used for trimming some part of a woman's attire, for badges, and other decorative purposes.
The principles and practices of the Ribbonmen.  See Ribbon Society, under Ribbon.
A member of the Ribbon Society. See Ribbon Society, under Ribbon.
A malvaceous tree (Hoheria populnea) of New Zealand, the bark of which is used for cordage.
A genus of shrubs including gooseberries and currants of many kinds.
A species of plantain (Plantago lanceolata) with long, narrow, ribbed leaves

A well-known cereal grass (Oryza sativa) and its seed.  This plant is extensively cultivated in warm climates, and the grain forms a large portion of the food of the inhabitants. In America it grows chiefly on low, moist land, which can be overflowed.
Any one of numerous species of small white polished marine shells of the genus Olivella.
Having an abundance of material possessions
The quality or state of being rich (in any sense of the adjective).
An herb (Pilea pumila) of the Nettle family, having a smooth, juicy, pellucid stem
Pertaining to, or designating, an isomeric modification of ricinoleic acid obtained as a white crystalline solid.
The glycerin salt of ricinelaidic acid, obtained as a white crystalline waxy substance by treating castor oil with nitrous acid.
Pertaining to, or derived from, castor oil
A bitter white crystalline alkaloid extracted from the seeds of the castor-oil plant.
Pertaining to, or designating, a fatty acid analogous to oleic acid, obtained from castor oil as an oily substance, C/H/O/ with a harsh taste. Formerly written ricinolic.
The glycerin salt of ricinoleic acid, occuring as a characteristic constituent of castor oil

A genus of plants of the Spurge family, containing but one species (R. communis), the castor-oil plant. The fruit is three-celled, and contains three large seeds from which castor oil iss expressed. See Palma Christi.
A stack or pile, as of grain, straw, or hay, in the open air, usually protected from wet with thatching.
A stout pole for use in making a rick, or for a spar to a boat.

A disease which affects children, and which is characterized by a bulky head, crooked spine and limbs, depressed ribs, enlarged and spongy articular epiphyses, tumid abdomen, and short stature, together with clear and often premature mental faculties. The essential cause of the disease appears to be the nondeposition of earthy salts in the osteoid tissues. Children afflicted with this malady stand and walk unsteadily. Called also rachitis.
A kind of openwork edging made of serpentine braid.
A flooring or framework on which a rick is made.
A rebound or skipping, as of a ball along the ground when a gun is fired at a low angle of elevation, or of a fiat stone thrown along the surface of water.
Of or pertaining to the rictus
The gape of the mouth, as of birds
The act of ridding or freeing
One who, or that which, rids.
A sieve with coarse meshes, usually of wire, for separating coarser materials from finer, as chaff from grain, cinders from ashes, or gravel from sand.
To be carried on the back of an animal, as a horse.
One who, or that which, rides.
The back, or top of the back
The part of a harness which passes over the saddle, and supports the shafts of a cart
The timber forming the ridge of a roof, into which the rafters are secured.
An object of sport or laughter
The quality or state of being ridiculous
A favorite Italian public entertainment, consisting of music and dancing, -- held generally on fast eves.
The reedbuck, a South African antelope (Cervicapra arundinacea)
A trough or sluice having cleats, grooves, or steps across the bottom for holding quicksilver and catching particles of gold when auriferous earth is washed
A curved file used in carving wool and marble.
To seize and bear away by force
Any one of several species of beautiful birds of Australia and New Guinea, of the genera Ptiloris and Craspidophora, allied to the paradise birds.
A gay, lively dance for one couple, -- said to have been borrowed from Provence in France.
A species of pine (Pinus sylvestris), and its wood, which affords a valuable timber
A fixed star of the first magnitude in the left foot of the constellation Orion.
A turning directly about by the right, so as to face in the opposite direction
Containing a right angle or right angles
Doing, or according with, that which is right
The quality or state of being righteous
The quality or state of being rightful
Situated or being on the right
Using the right hand habitually, or more easily than the left.
The state or quality of being right-handed
Having a right heart or disposition.
Having a right or honest mind.
The bowhead, Arctic, or Greenland whale (Balaena mysticetus), from whose mouth the best whalebone is obtained.
The quality or state of being rigid
The quality or state of being rigid.
A succession of confused or nonsensical statements
A musical instrument formerly in use, consisting of several sticks bound together, but separated by beads, and played with a stick with a ball at its end.
A Danish coin worth about fifty-four cents. It was the former unit of value in Denmark.
A Swedish coin worth about twenty-seven cents. It was formerly the unit of value in Sweden.
One of certain narrow, crooked valleys seen, by aid of the telescope, on the surface of the moon.
The border, edge, or margin of a thing, usually of something circular or curving
The clouded tiger cat (Felis marmorata) of Southern Asia and the East Indies.
A short cylinder connecting a trunnion with the body of a cannon. See Illust. of Cannon.
An implement for cutting, trimming, or ornamenting the rim of anything, as the edges of pies, etc.
Full of rimes, fissures, or chinks.
A fold or wrinkle. See Rumple.
The external covering or coat, as of flesh, fruit, trees, etc.
A highly contagious distemper or murrain, affecting neat cattle, and less commonly sheep and goats
A small water course or gutter.
To cause to sound, especially by striking, as a metallic body
The reed bunting. It has a collar of white feathers. Called also ring bunting.
An eyebolt having a ring through the eye.
A morbid growth or deposit of bony matter between or on the small pastern and the great pastern bones.
A European wild pigeon (Columba palumbus) having a white crescent on each side of the neck, whence the name. Called also wood pigeon, and cushat.
Having the lips widely separated and gaping like an open mouth
One who, or that which, rings
An instrument used for stretching woolen cloth.
The leader of a circle of dancers
The ringed dotterel, or ring plover.
One in charge of the performances (as of horses) within the ring in a circus.

Any one of several species of small plovers of the genus Aegialitis, having a ring around the neck. The ring is black in summer, but becomes brown or gray in winter. The semipalmated plover (Ae. semipalmata) and the piping plover (Ae. meloda) are common North American species. Called also ring plover, and ring-necked plover.
Having a well defined ring of color around the neck.
Having circular streaks or lines on the body
A bird having a distinct band of color across the tail, as the hen harrier.
Having the tail crossed by conspicuous bands of color.
A game in which the object is to toss a ring so that it will catch upon an upright stick.

A contagious affection of the skin due to the presence of a vegetable parasite, and forming ring-shaped discolored patches covered with vesicles or powdery scales. It occurs either on the body, the face, or the scalp.  Different varieties are distinguished as Tinea circinata, Tinea tonsurans, etc., but all are caused by the same parasite (a species of Trichophyton).
The smooth and level extent of ice marked off for the game of curling.
One who skates at a rink.
One who, or that which, rinses.
The act or practice of rioting
Of or pertaining to the bank of a river
Growing along the banks of rivers
The state or quality of being ripe
A translucent mineral of a green color and micaceous structure, belonging to the chlorite group
A player in the ripieno portion of an orchestra. See Ripieno.
One who brings fish from the seacoast to markets in inland towns.
In fencing, a return thrust after a parry.
An implement, with teeth like those of a comb, for removing the seeds and seed vessels from flax, broom corn, etc.
A foundation or sustaining wall of stones thrown together without order, as in deep water or on a soft bottom.

Toward Rome, or toward the Roman Catholic Church.
A method of notation for all spoken sounds, proposed by Mr. Sweet
Belonging or relating to Rome, or to the Roman Catholic Church
Any one of several species of California sciaenoid food fishes, especially Roncador Stearnsi, which is an excellent market fish, and the red roncador (Corvina, / Johnius, saturna).

obs. p. p. of Renne, to run.

The cover of any building, including the roofing (see Roofing) and all the materials and construction necessary to carry and maintain the same upon the walls or other uprights. In the case of a building with vaulted ceilings protected by an outer roof, some writers call the vault the roof, and the outer protection the roof mask. It is better, however, to consider the vault as the ceiling only, in cases where it has farther covering.
A small roof, covering, or shelter.
The beam in the angle of a roof
The breeding place of a colony of rooks
The quality or state of being roomy
One of twe or more occupying the same room or rooms
A defamatory forgery or falsehood published for purposes of political intrigue.
The East Indian name for grass oil. See under Grass.
The male of the domestic fowl
The male of the domestic fowl
To turn up the earth with the snout, as swine.

A small piece of spun yarn or marline, used to fasten the head of the sail to the spar.
One who dances, walks, or performs acrobatic feats, on a rope extended through the air at some height.

To punish with a rope's end.

capable of being drawn into a thread, as a glutinous substance
A cloak reaching about to, or just below, the knees, worn in the 18th century.

Of or pertaining to a natural order of plants (Rosaceae) of which the rose is the type. It includes also the plums and cherries, meadowsweet, brambles, the strawberry, the hawthorn, applies, pears, service trees, and quinces.
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid (called also lithic acid) found in certain red precipitates of urine. See Uric.

These salts are essential components of many of the socalled aniline dyes, as fuchsine, aniline red, etc. By extension, any one of the series of substances derived from, or related to, rosaniline proper.

Called also methyl aurin, and, formerly, corallin.

An ecclesiastical court of Rome, called also Rota Romana, that takes cognizance of suits by appeal. It consists of twelve members.

in laundry work, to dry without smoothing or ironing.

That may be rowed, or rowed upon.

Called also roan tree, and mountain ash.  The name is also applied to two American trees of similar habit (Pyrus Americana, and P. sambucifolia).

It consists sometimes of a notch in the gunwale of a boat, sometimes of a pair of pins between which the oar rests on the edge of the gunwale, sometimes of a single pin passing through the oar, or of a metal fork or stirrup pivoted in the gunwale and suporting the oar.

the principles or conduct of royalists.

A rare metallic element. It occurs quite widely, but in small quantities, and always combined. It is isolated as a soft yellowish white metal, analogous to potassium in most of its properties.  Symbol Rb.  Atomic weight, 85.2.
Having the nature or quality of red
Having the appearance or color of iron rust

The unit of monetary value in Russia.  It is divided into 100 copecks, and in the gold coin of the realm (as in the five and ten ruble pieces) is worth about 77 cents. The silver ruble is a coin worth about 60 cents.
That part of any work in the early manuscripts and typography which was colored red, to distinguish it from other portions.

A genus of rosaceous plants, including the raspberry and blackberry.
A precious stone of a carmine red color, sometimes verging to violet, or intermediate between carmine and hyacinth red.  It is a red crystallized variety of corundum.

Any one of numerous species of humming birds belonging to Trochilus, Calypte, Stellula, and allies, in which the male has on the throat a brilliant patch of red feathers having metallic reflections

A plaited, quilled, or goffered strip of lace, net, ribbon, or other material, -- used in place of collars or cuffs, and as a trimming for women's dresses and bonnets.

Either of the feasts of the Holy Cross, occuring on May 3 and September 14, annually.

A perennial suffrutescent plant (Ruta graveolens), having a strong, heavy odor and a bitter taste
Causing one to rue or lament

A yellowish red crystalline substance related to anthracene, and obtained from opianic acid.
A phenol derivative of anthracene obtained as a white crystalline substance, which on oxidation produces a red dyestuff related to anthraquinone.

The quality or state of being rugose.
The act of falling or tumbling down
The act of ruining, or the state of being ruined.
One who, or that which, ruins.
Having the appearance of ruins, or of the ruins of houses
Causing, or tending to cause, ruin
That which is prescribed or laid down as a guide for conduct or action
Chopped meat stuffed into small bags of tripe. They are cut in slices and fried.

A kind of intoxicating liquor distilled from cane juice, or from the scummings of the boiled juice, or from treacle or molasses, or from the lees of former distillations. Also, sometimes used colloquially as a generic or a collective name for intoxicating liquor.

One who, or that which, rumbles.

Inclined to, or engaged in, rumination or meditation.

A large and tall glass, or drinking cup.

A Shakespearean word of uncertain meaning.  Perhaps "fattened in the rump, pampered."
One who, or that which, flees from danger, duty, restraint, etc.
Pinnately cut with the lobes pointing downwards, as the leaf of the dandelion.

A depilatory made of orpiment and quicklime, and used by the Turks. See Rhusma.
Of a reddish brown color, or (by some called) a red gray
A country of Europe and Asia.

Pertaining to, or obtained from, rue (Ruta)
A mineral usually of a reddish brown color, and brilliant metallic adamantine luster, occurring in tetragonal crystals. In composition it is titanium dioxide, like octahedrite and brookite.
Any species of lamellicorn beetles belonging to Rutila and allied genera, as the spotted grapevine beetle (Pelidnota punctata).

A glucoside resembling, but distinct from, quercitrin. Rutin is found in the leaves of the rue (Ruta graveolens) and other plants, and obtained as a bitter yellow crystalline substance which yields quercitin on decomposition.
An old crafty fox or beguiler -- a word of contempt.
A chart of a course, esp. at sea.
A rattling sound in the throat arising from difficulty of breathing
A liquid hydrocarbon, C10H18, of the acetylene series. It is produced artificially.
A clause added to a document

A piece of iron crossing the hole in the upper millstone by which the stone is supported on the spindle.

the nineteenth letter of the English alphabet, is a consonant, and is often called a sibilant, in allusion to its hissing sound. It has two principal sounds

Pertaining to the doctrines or tenets of Sabellius. See Sabellian, n.
The doctrines or tenets of Sabellius. See Sabellian, n.
Like, or related to, the genus Sabella.
A sword with a broad and heavy blade, thick at the back, and usually more or less curved like a scimiter
Of or pertaining to Saba in Arabia, celebrated for producing aromatic plants.
The very hard wood of a leguminous West Indian tree (Lysiloma Sabicu), valued for shipbuilding.
Of or pertaining to the ancient Sabines, a people of Italy.
A carnivorous animal of the Weasel family (Mustela zibellina) native of the northern latitudes of Europe, Asia, and America, -- noted for its fine, soft, and valuable fur.
A kind of wooden shoe worn by the peasantry in France, Belgium, Sweden, and some other European countries.
A kind of freezer for ices.
A leather case or pocket worn by cavalry at the left side, suspended from the sword belt.
A variety of applique work for quilts, table covers, etc.
A sudden, violent check of a horse by drawing or twitching the reins on a sudden and with one pull.
Having the form of a sack or pouch

The act, process or method of determining the amount and kind of sugar present in sirup, molasses, and the like, especially by the employment of polarizing apparatus.

Of, pertaining to, or derived from, saccharin
To convert into, or to impregnate with, sugar.

They are the active agents in producing fermentation of wine, beer, etc. Saccharomyces cerevisiae is the yeast of sedimentary beer. Also called Torula.
A family of fungi consisting of the one genus Saccharomyces.
A white crystalline substance, C6H8O6, obtained by the oxidation of saccharin, and regarded as the lactone of saccharonic acid.

A genus of tall tropical grasses including the sugar cane.

A chief of a tribe of the American Indians
The government or jurisdiction of a sachem.
Office or condition of a sachem.
A scent bag, or perfume cushion, to be laid among handkerchiefs, garments, etc., to perfume them.
A name formerly given to various dry Spanish wines.
The act of taking by storm and pillaging
A brass wind instrument, like a bass trumpet, so contrived that it can be lengthened or shortened according to the tone required

As much as a sack will hold.
Having a peculiar pouch developed near the front edge of the wing

The oath of allegiance taken by Roman soldiers

One who holds the doctrine of the real objective presence of Christ's body and blood in the holy eucharist.

Capable of being offered in sacrifice.

An officer of the church who has the care of the utensils or movables, and of the church in general
An apartment in a church where the sacred utensils, vestments, etc., are kept

Of or pertaining to both the sacrum and the hip

That part of the vertebral column which is directly connected with, or forms a part of, the pelvis.
A tribe of Indians, which, together with the Foxes, formerly occupied the region about Green Bay, Wisconsin.
A work in the Persian tongue, being a summary of the Zend-Avesta, or sacred books.

A fetid gum resin obtained from a species of Ferula. It has been used in hysteria, etc., but is now seldom met with.
A mixed woven fabric of silk and cotton, or silk and wool

A suffruticose labiate plant (Salvia officinalis) with grayish green foliage, much used in flavoring meats, etc. The name is often extended to the whole genus, of which many species are cultivated for ornament, as the scarlet sage, and Mexican red and blue sage.
A low irregular shrub (Artemisia tridentata), of the order Compositae, covering vast tracts of the dry alkaline regions of the American plains

A follower of the Count de St. Simon, who died in 1825, and who maintained that the principle of property held in common, and the just division of the fruits of common labor among the members of society, are the true remedy for the social evils which exist.
The principles, doctrines, or practice of the Saint-Simonians
One of an important religious sect in India which regards Siva with peculiar veneration.
A falcon (Falco sacer) native of Southern Europe and Asia, closely resembling the lanner.
Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Pithecia. They have large ears, and a long hairy tail which is not prehensile.
The divine energy, personified as the wife of a deity (Brahma, Vishnu, Siva, etc.)
An East Indian timber tree (Shorea robusta), much used for building purposes. It is of a light brown color, close-grained, heavy, and durable.
The quality or condition of being salable
A preparation of vegetables, as lettuce, celery, water cress, onions, etc., usually dressed with salt, vinegar, oil, and spice, and eaten for giving a relish to other food
The esculent swallow. See under Esculent.
The edible fruit of the Gaultheria Shallon, an ericaceous shrub found from California northwards. The berries are about the size of a common grape and of a dark purple color.
A salutation or compliment of ceremony in the east by word or act
Any one of numerous species of Urodela, belonging to Salamandra, Amblystoma, Plethodon, and various allied genera, especially those that are more or less terrestrial in their habits.
A suborder of Urodela, comprising salamanders.
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a salamander
Like or pertaining to the salamanders.

Denoting a tribe of Franks who established themselves early in the fourth century on the river Sala [now Yssel]

Belonging or relating to the willow.
A glucoside found in the bark and leaves of several species of willow (Salix) and poplar, and extracted as a bitter white crystalline substance.
The hypothetical radical of salicylic acid and of certain related compounds.

A thin, fragrant, colorless oil, HO.C6H4.CHO, found in the flowers of meadow sweet (Spiraea), and also obtained by oxidation of salicin, saligenin, etc. It reddens on exposure. Called also salicylol, salicylic aldehyde, and formerly salicylous, / spiroylous, acid.

Pertaining to, derived from, or designating, an acid formerly obtained by fusing salicin with potassium hydroxide, and now made in large quantities from phenol (carbolic acid) by the action of carbon dioxide on heated sodium phenolate. It is a white crystalline substance. It is used as an antiseptic, and in its salts in the treatment of rheumatism. Called also hydroxybenzoic acid.

The act of washing with salt water.
Consisting of salt, or containing salt
The quality or state of being salt
Having the form or the qualities of a salt, especially of common salt.

The ginkgo tree (Ginkgo biloba, or Salisburia adiantifolia).

To produce an abnormal flow of saliva in

A spacious and elegant apartment for the reception of company or for works of art
An aromatic drink prepared from sassafras bark and other ingredients, at one time much used in London.
Any species of Salpa, or of the family Salpidae.
A genus of transparent, tubular, free-swimming oceanic tunicates found abundantly in all the warmer latitudes. See Illustration in Appendix.
Chopped meat, bread, etc., used to stuff legs of veal or other joints
The Eustachian tube, or the Fallopian tube.
A mud volcano, the water of which is often impregnated with salts, whence the name.
Having a taste compounded of saltness and acidity
A genus of plants including the glasswort. See Glasswort.
Growing in brackish places or in salt marshes.

The chloride of sodium, a substance used for seasoning food, for the preservation of meat, etc. It is found native in the earth, and is also produced, by evaporation and crystallization, from sea water and other water impregnated with saline particles.
A popular Italian dance in quick 3-4 or 6-8 time, running mostly in triplets, but with a hop step at the beginning of each measure. See Tarantella.
A division of Orthoptera including grasshoppers, locusts, and crickets.
An Australian plant (Atriplex nummularia) of the Goosefoot family.
A mixture of salt, coarse meal, lime, etc., attractive to pigeons.
Formerly a large vessel, now a small vessel of glass or other material, used for holding salt on the table.
One who makes, sells, or applies salt
A building or place where salt is made by boiling or by evaporation
A large saltcellar formerly placed near the center of the table. The superior guests were seated above the saltfoot.

Pertaining to saltpeter, or partaking of its qualities
A popular name, esp. in the United States, for various cutaneous eruptions, particularly for those of eczema. See Eczema.
A name given to several plants which grow on the seashore, as the Batis maritima, and the glasswort. See Glasswort.
The act of saluting, or paying respect or reverence, by the customary words or actions

The student who pronounces the salutatory oration at the annual Commencement or like exercises of a college, -- an honor commonly assigned to that member of the graduating class who ranks second in scholarship.
To address, as with expressions of kind wishes and courtesy
The quality or condition of being salvable
The act of saving a vessel, goods, or life, from perils of the sea.
An evangelist, a member, or a recruit, of the Salvation Army.
A place where things are preserved
One who salves, or uses salve as a remedy
Tubular, with a spreading border. See Hypocraterimorphous.
A genus of plants including the sage. See Sage.
Tending to save or secure safety.
One who assists in saving a ship or goods at sea, without being under special obligation to do so.
A dry, indehiscent, usually one-seeded, winged fruit, as that of the ash, maple, and elm
Of or pertaining to Samaria, in Palestine.
A rare metallic element of doubtful identity.
Resembling a samara, or winged seed vessel.
A rare mineral having a velvet-black color and submetallic luster. It is a niobate of uranium, iron, and the yttrium and cerium metals.
A colloquial or humorous appellation for a negro
A genus of shrubs and trees
An ancient stringed instrument used by the Greeks, the particular construction of which is unknown.

An East Indian deer (Rusa Aristotelis) having a mane on its neck. Its antlers have but three prongs. Called also gerow. The name is applied to other species of the genus Rusa, as the Bornean sambur (R. equina).
The state of being the same
Of or pertaining to the island of Samos.
A hot and destructive wind that sometimes blows, in Turkey, from the desert. It is identical with the simoom of Arabia and the kamsin of Syria.
A species of silk stuff, or taffeta, generally interwoven with gold.
A machine for pressing the water from skins in tanning.
Of or pertaining to the Samoan Islands (formerly called Navigators' Islands) in the South Pacific Ocean, or their inhabitants.
A metal urn used in Russia for making tea. It is filled with water, which is heated by charcoal placed in a pipe, with chimney attached, which passes through the urn.
An ignorant and degraded Turanian tribe which occupies a portion of Northern Russia and a part of Siberia.
An article of food consisting of maize broken or bruised, which is cooked by boiling, and usually eaten with milk
A Chinese boat from twelve to fifteen feet long, covered with a house, and sometimes used as a permanent habitation on the inland waters.
A fleshy, suffrutescent, umbelliferous European plant (Crithmum maritimum). It grows among rocks and on cliffs along the seacoast, and is used for pickles.
One who makes up samples for inspection
A spirituous liquor distilled by the Chinese from the yeasty liquor in which boiled rice has fermented under pressure.
An Israelite of Bible record (see Judges xiii.), distinguished for his great strength
The quality or state of being sanable
Capable of being healed or cured
The act of healing or curing.
Having the power to cure or heal
An establishment for the treatment of the sick

To shelter by means of a sanctuary or sacred privileges.

Fine particles of stone, esp. of siliceous stone, but not reduced to dust
Shaped like a sandal or slipper.

The highly perfumed yellowish heartwood of an East Indian and Polynesian tree (Santalum album), and of several other trees of the same genus, as the Hawaiian Santalum Freycinetianum and S. pyrularium, the Australian S. latifolium, etc. The name is extended to several other kinds of fragrant wood.
An assaulter whose weapon is a sand bag. See Sand bag, under Sand.
A follower of Robert Sandeman, a Scotch sectary of the eighteenth century. See Glassite.

A small gray and brown sandpiper (Calidris arenaria) very common on sandy beaches in America, Europe, and Asia. Called also curwillet, sand lark, stint, and ruddy plover.

A nickname given to any "poor white" living in the pine woods which cover the sandy hills in Georgia and South Carolina.
The quality or state of being sandy, or of being of a sandy color.
A whitish substance which is cast up, as a scum, from the materials of glass in fusion, and, floating on the top, is skimmed off
A kind of minium, or red lead, made by calcining carbonate of lead, but inferior to true minium.
A mythical person who makes children sleepy, so that they rub their eyes as if there were sand in them.
Paper covered on one side with sand glued fast, -- used for smoothing and polishing.
Any one of numerous species of small limicoline game birds belonging to Tringa, Actodromas, Ereunetes, and various allied genera of the family Tringidae.

Wine and water sweetened and spiced, -- a favorite West Indian drink.
Freedom from agitation or excitement of mind
A genus of plants of the Poppy family.
The quality or state of being sanguinary.
