the great council of the Jews, which consisted of seventy members, to whom the high priest was added. It had jurisdiction of religious matters.
A collection of vedic hymns, songs, or verses, forming the first part of each Veda.
Any plant of the umbelliferous genus Sanicula, reputed to have healing powers.
A variety of orthoclase feldspar common in certain eruptive rocks, as trachyte
A thin, serous fluid commonly discharged from ulcers or foul wounds.
Pertaining to sanies, or partaking of its nature and appearance
Of or pertaining to health, or the laws of health
The condition or quality of being sane
A district or a subvision of a vilayet.
A Hindoo system of philosophy which refers all things to soul and a rootless germ called prakriti, consisting of three elements, goodness, passion, and darkness.

The ancient language of the Hindoos, long since obsolete in vernacular use, but preserved to the present day as the literary and sacred dialect of India. It is nearly allied to the Persian, and to the principal languages of Europe, classical and modern, and by its more perfect preservation of the roots and forms of the primitive language from which they are all descended, is a most important assistance in determining their history and relations. Cf. Prakrit, and Veda.
A colorless crystalline substance, isomeric with piperonal, but having weak acid properties. It is extracted from sandalwood.

Of or pertaining to a natural order of plants (Santalaceae), of which the genus Santalum is the type, and which includes the buffalo nut and a few other North American plants, and many peculiar plants of the southern hemisphere.
Of, pertaining to, or obtained from, sandalwood (Santalum)
A genus of trees with entire opposite leaves and small apetalous flowers. There are less than a dozen species, occurring from India to Australia and the Pacific Islands. See Sandalwood.
One of the seven confederated tribes of Indians belonging to the Sioux, or Dakotas.
Of, pertaining to, or designating, an acid (distinct from santoninic acid) obtained from santonin as a white crystalline substance.

A white crystalline substance having a bitter taste, extracted from the buds of levant wormseed and used as an anthelmintic. It occassions a peculiar temporary color blindness, causing objects to appear as if seen through a yellow glass.
Any marine annelid of the genus Hyalinaecia, especially H. tubicola of Europe, which inhabits a transparent movable tube resembling a quill in color and texture.
The juice of plants of any kind, especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating fluid essential to nutrition.

Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Cebus, having long and prehensile tails. Some of the species are called also capuchins. The bonnet sapajou (C. subcristatus), the golden-handed sapajou (C. chrysopus), and the white-throated sapajou (C. hypoleucus) are well known species. See Capuchin.
A dyewood yielded by Caesalpinia Sappan, a thorny leguminous tree of Southern Asia and the neighboring islands. It is the original Brazil wood.
Having the power of affecting the organs of taste
The quality or state of being sapid
Of or pertaining to an order of trees and shrubs (Sapindaceae), including the (typical) genus Sapindus, the maples, the margosa, and about seventy other genera.
A genus of tropical and subtropical trees with pinnate leaves and panicled flowers. The fruits of some species are used instead of soap, and their round black seeds are made into necklaces.
A tall, evergeen, tropical American tree (Achras Sapota)
A white crystalline substance obtained by the decomposition of saponin.
The quality or state of being saponaceous.
The act, process, or result, of soap making
To convert into soap, as tallow or any fat

A poisonous glucoside found in many plants, as in the root of soapwort (Saponaria), in the bark of soap bark (Quillaia), etc. It is extracted as a white amorphous powder, which occasions a soapy lather in solution, and produces a local anaesthesia. Formerly called also struthiin, quillaiin, senegin, polygalic acid, etc. By extension, any one of a group of related bodies of which saponin proper is the type.
A hydrous silicate of magnesia and alumina. It occurs in soft, soapy, amorphous masses, filling veins in serpentine and cavities in trap rock.
A soapy mixture obtained by treating an essential oil with an alkali
Power of affecting the organs of taste
Having the power to produce the sensation of taste
The quality of a body by which it excites the sensation of taste.

Of or pertaining to a natural order (Sapotaceae) of (mostly tropical) trees and shrubs, including the star apple, the Lucuma, or natural marmalade tree, the gutta-percha tree (Isonandra), and the India mahwa, as well as the sapodilla, or sapota, after which the order is named.
Of or pertaining to Sappho, the Grecian poetess
Native alumina or aluminium sesquioxide, Al2O3
Any one of several species of brilliant South American humming birds of the genus Sappho, having very bright-colored and deeply forked tails
One of a tribe of beetles which feed upon decaying animal and vegetable substances
Any plant growing on decayed animal or vegetable matter, as most fungi and some flowering plants with no green color, as the Indian pipe.
Feeding or growing upon decaying animal or vegetable matter
A kind of Swiss cheese, of a greenish color, flavored with melilot.
A Brazilian tree. See Lecythis, and Monkey-pot.
The alburnum, or part of the wood of any exogenous tree next to the bark, being that portion of the tree through which the sap flows most freely
One of certain vagrant or heretical Oriental monks in the early church.
A slow Spanish dance of Saracenic origin, to an air in triple time
Of or pertaining to the Saracens
The sakti or wife of Brahma
One of the outer pinions or feathers of the wing of a bird, esp. of a hawk.
The old squaw, or long-tailed duck.
A species of fine thin silk fabric, used for linings, etc.

A genus of bacteria found in various organic fluids, especially in those those of the stomach, associated with certain diseases. The individual organisms undergo division along two perpendicular partitions, so that multiplication takes place in two directions, giving groups of four cubical cells. Also used adjectively
To weed, or clear of weeds, with a hoe.
A combining form from Gr. sa`rx, sa`rkos, flesh
A fruit consisting of many dry indehiscent cells, which contain but few seeds and cohere about a common style, as in the mallows.
A minute yellowish body present in the interior of certain rhizopods.
The fleshy part of a stone fruit, situated between the skin, or epicarp, and the stone, or endocarp, as in a peach. See Illust. of Endocarp.
Any solid tumor of the testicle.
A gum resin obtained from certain shrubs of Africa (Penaea), -- formerly thought to cause healing of wounds and ulcers.
A name applied by Dujardin in 1835 to the gelatinous material forming the bodies of the lowest animals
A fleshy covering of a seed, lying between the external and internal integuments.
The very thin transparent and apparently homogeneous sheath which incloses a striated muscular fiber
That part of anatomy which treats of the soft parts. It includes myology, angiology, neurology, and splanchnology.
A suborder of carnivorous and insectivorous marsupials including the dasyures and the opossums.
Any animal which eats flesh, especially any carnivorous marsupial.

A species of limestone used among the Greeks for making coffins, which was so called because it consumed within a few weeks the flesh of bodies deposited in it. It is otherwise called lapis Assius, or Assian stone, and is said to have been found at Assos, a city of Lycia.
A flesh-eating animal, especially any one of the carnivorous marsupials.
A genus of parasitic mites including the itch mites.
Any species of the genus Sarcoptes and related genera of mites, comprising the itch mites and mange mites.
A division of raptorial birds comprising the vultures.
One of the mesenteries of an anthozoan.
A crystalline nitrogenous substance, formed in the decomposition of creatin (one of the constituents of muscle tissue). Chemically, it is methyl glycocoll.
Producing or promoting the growth of flesh.
A weeding, as with a hoe or a rake.
A variety of carnelian, of a rich reddish yellow or brownish red color. See the Note under Chalcedony.
A variety of agate containing sard.

Any one of several small species of herring which are commonly preserved in olive oil for food, especially the pilchard, or European sardine (Clupea pilchardus). The California sardine (Clupea sagax) is similar. The American sardines of the Atlantic coast are mostly the young of the common herring and of the menhaden.
Of or pertaining to the island, kingdom, or people of Sardinia.
A precious stone, probably a carnelian, one of which was set in Aaron's breastplate.
A variety of onyx consisting of sard and white chalcedony in alternate layers.

The principal garment of a Hindoo woman. It consists of a long piece of cloth, which is wrapped round the middle of the body, a portion being arranged to hang down in front, and the remainder passed across the bosom over the left shoulder.
The gulf weed. See under Gulf.
A genus of algae including the gulf weed.
Any one of several species of sparoid fishes belonging to Sargus, Pomadasys, and related genera
A small South American opossum (Didelphys opossum), having four white spots on the face.
Thin boards for sheathing, as above the rafters, and under the shingles or slates, and for similar purposes.
Of or pertaining to Sarmatia, or its inhabitants, the ancestors of the Russians and the Poles.
A prostrate filiform stem or runner, as of the strawberry. See Runner.
Bearing sarments, or runners, as the strawberry.
Long and filiform, and almost naked, or having only leaves at the joints where it strikes root
A sort of petticoat worn by both sexes in Java and the Malay Archipelago.
A Chaldean astronomical period or cycle, the length of which has been variously estimated from 3,600 years to 3,600 days, or a little short of 10 years.
A large bale or package of wool, containing eighty tods, or 2,240 pounds, in weight.
A coarse cloth made of hemp, and used for packing goods, etc.
A large toadfish of the Southern United States and the Gulf of Mexico (Batrachus tau, var. pardus).
A genus of American perennial herbs growing in bogs
Any plant of several tropical American species of Smilax.
One of the large sandstone blocks scattered over the English chalk downs
Of or pertaining to a tailor or his work.

A muscle of the thigh, called the tailor's muscle, which arises from the hip bone and is inserted just below the knee. So named because its contraction was supposed to produce the position of the legs assumed by the tailor in sitting.
A liturgy, or use, put forth about 1087 by St. Osmund, bishop of Sarum, based on Anglo-Saxon and Norman customs.
A scarf or band worn about the waist, over the shoulder, or otherwise
A kind of pad worn on the leg under the boot.
The Indian antelope (Antilope bezoartica, / cervicapra), noted for its beauty and swiftness. It has long, spiral, divergent horns.
A large African antelope (Alcelaphus lunata), similar to the hartbeest, but having its horns regularly curved.
An American tree of the Laurel family (Sassafras officinale)
A word used to emphasize a statement.
A sluice or lock, as in a river, to make it more navigable.
Native boric acid, found in saline incrustations on the borders of hot springs near Sasso, in the territory of Florence.
The rock pigeon. See under Pigeon.
The bark of a West African leguminous tree (Erythrophlaeum Guineense, used by the natives as an ordeal poison, and also medicinally
The evil and malicious disposition of Satan
A little sack or bag for carrying papers, books, or small articles of wearing apparel
To satisfy the desire or appetite of
A kind of dress goods made of cotton or woolen, with a glossy surface resembling satin.
An attendant attached to a prince or other powerful person
Pertaining to, or consisting of, satellites.
The state of being satiated or glutted
A silk cloth, of a thick, close texture, and overshot woof, which has a glossy surface.

The hard, lemon-colored, fragrant wood of an East Indian tree (Chloroxylon Swietenia). It takes a lustrous finish, and is used in cabinetwork. The name is also given to the wood of a species of prickly ash (Xanthoxylum Caribaeum) growing in Florida and the West Indies.
A composition, generally poetical, holding up vice or folly to reprobation
To make the object of satire
The act of satisfying, or the state of being satisfied
In general, to fill up the measure of a want of (a person or a thing)
The governor of a province in ancient Persia
Of or pertaining to a satrap, or a satrapy.
The government or jurisdiction of a satrap
A kind of ornamental hard-glazed pottery made at Satsuma in Kiushu, one of the Japanese islands.
To cause to become completely penetrated, impregnated, or soaked
The act of saturating, or the state of being saturating
One who, or that which, saturates.
The seventh or last day of the week
One of the elder and principal deities, the son of Coelus and Terra (Heaven and Earth), and the father of Jupiter. The corresponding Greek divinity was Kro`nos, later CHro`nos, Time.

The festival of Saturn, celebrated in December, originally during one day, but afterward during seven days, as a period of unrestrained license and merriment for all classes, extending even to the slaves.
Of or pertaining to the Saturnalia.
Of or pertaining to Saturn, whose age or reign, from the mildness and wisdom of his government, is called the golden age.
Appearing as if seen from the center of the planet Saturn
Born under, or influenced by, the planet Saturn.
A person of a dull, grave, gloomy temperament.
A sylvan deity or demigod, represented as part man and part goat, and characterized by riotous merriment and lasciviousness.
Immoderate venereal appetite in the male.
Any one of several kinds of orchids.

A South American ant (Oecodoma cephalotes) remarkable for having two large kinds of workers besides the ordinary ones, and for the immense size of its formicaries. The sauba ant cuts off leaves of plants and carries them into its subterranean nests, and thus often does great damage by defoliating trees and cultivated plants.
A composition of condiments and appetizing ingredients eaten with food as a relish
A small pan with a handle, in which sauce is prepared over a fire
A small pan or vessel in which sauce was set on a table.
The quality or state of being saucy
A long and slender pipe or bag, made of cloth well pitched, or of leather, filled with powder, and used to communicate fire to mines, caissons, bomb chests, etc.
Cabbage cut fine and allowed to ferment in a brine made of its own juice with salt, -- a German dish.
An American fresh-water food fish (Stizostedion Canadense)
A hired mourner at a funeral.
A kind of color prepared from calcined lapis lazuli
To wander or walk about idly and in a leisurely or lazy manner
Any carangoid fish of the genus Trachurus, especially T. trachurus, or T. saurus, of Europe and America, and T. picturatus of California. Called also skipjack, and horse mackerel.
A division of Reptilia formerly established to include the Lacertilia, Crocodilia, Dinosauria, and other groups. By some writers the name is restricted to the Lacertilia.
Of or pertaining to, or of the nature of, the Sauria.
Having the bones of the palate arranged as in saurians, the vomer consisting of two lateral halves, as in the woodpeckers (Pici).
Like or pertaining to the saurians.
The fossil track of a saurian.

An extinct order of herbivorous dinosaurs having the feet of a saurian type, instead of birdlike, as they are in many dinosaurs. It includes the largest known land animals, belonging to Brontosaurus, Camarasaurus, and allied genera. See Illustration in Appendix.
A comprehensive group of vertebrates, comprising the reptiles and birds.
An extinct order of birds having a long vertebrated tail with quills along each side of it. Archaeopteryx is the type. See Archaeopteryx, and Odontornithes.

A slender marine fish (Scomberesox saurus) of Europe and America. It has long, thin, beaklike jaws. Called also billfish, gowdnook, gawnook, skipper, skipjack, skopster, lizard fish, and Egypt herring.
An article of food consisting of meat (esp. pork) minced and highly seasoned, and inclosed in a cylindrical case or skin usually made of the prepared intestine of some animal.
A tough, compact mineral, of a white, greenish, or grayish color. It is near zoisite in composition, and in part, at least, has been produced by the alteration of feldspar.
To fry lightly and quickly, as meat, by turning or tossing it over frequently in a hot pan greased with a little fat.
An instrument used by masons and others to trace and form angles.
A white wine made in the district of Sauterne, France.
Capable of, or admitting of, being saved.
Of or pertaining to the forest
The state or quality of being savage.
A tract of level land covered with the vegetable growth usually found in a damp soil and warm climate, -- as grass or reeds, -- but destitute of trees.
Anything which saves fragments, or prevents waste or loss.

A coniferous shrub (Juniperus Sabina) of Western Asia, occasionally found also in the northern parts of the United States and in British America. It is a compact bush, with dark-colored foliage, and produces small berries having a glaucous bloom. Its bitter, acrid tops are sometimes used in medicine for gout, amenorrhoea, etc.
One who saves, preserves, or delivers from destruction or danger.
That property of a thing which affects the organs of taste or smell
Pleasing to the organs of taste or smell.
A variety of the common cabbage (Brassica oleracea major), having curled leaves, -- much cultivated for winter use.
A native or inhabitant of Savoy.
A corrupt spelling and pronunciation of solder.
Dust or small fragments of wood (or of stone, etc.) made by the cutting of a saw.

Any one of several species of elasmobranch fishes of the genus Pristis. They have a sharklike form, but are more nearly allied to the rays. The flattened and much elongated snout has a row of stout toothlike structures inserted along each edge, forming a sawlike organ with which it mutilates or kills its prey.

Any one of numerous species of hymenopterous insects belonging to the family Tenthredinidae. The female usually has an ovipositor containing a pair of sawlike organs with which she makes incisions in the leaves or stems of plants in which to lay the eggs. The larvae resemble those of Lepidoptera.
A kind of rack, shaped like a double St. Andrew's cross, on which sticks of wood are laid for sawing by hand
A mill for sawing, especially one for sawing timber or lumber.
An instrument used to set or turn the teeth of a saw a little sidewise, that they may make a kerf somewhat wider than the thickness of the blade, to prevent friction
An arctic seal (Lobodon carcinophaga), having the molars serrated
Having a tooth or teeth like those of a saw
A small North American owl (Nyctale Acadica), destitute of ear tufts and having feathered toes
Any plant of the composite genus Serratula
One whose occupation is to saw timber into planks or boards, or to saw wood for fuel
A kind of chopping instrument for trimming the edges of roofing slates.

A name given to a numerous family of brass wind instruments with valves, invented by Antoine Joseph Adolphe Sax (known as Adolphe Sax), of Belgium and Paris, and much used in military bands and in orchestras.
Any species of marine bivalve shells of the genus Saxicava. Some of the species are noted for their power of boring holes in limestone and similar rocks.
Of or pertaining to the saxicavas.
A genus of exogenous polypetalous plants, embracing about one hundred and eighty species. See Saxifrage.

Of or pertaining to a natural order of plants (Saxifragaceae) of which saxifrage is the type. The order includes also the alum root, the hydrangeas, the mock orange, currants and gooseberries, and many other plants.
Any plant of the genus Saxifraga, mostly perennial herbs growing in crevices of rocks in mountainous regions.
Dissolving stone, especially dissolving stone in the bladder.
One of a nation or people who formerly dwelt in the northern part of Germany, and who, with other Teutonic tribes, invaded and conquered England in the fifth and sixth centuries.
Relating to the Saxons or Anglo- Saxons.
An idiom of the Saxon or Anglo-Saxon language.
One versed in the Saxon language.
A wind instrument of brass, containing a reed, and partaking of the qualities both of a brass instrument and of a clarinet.
A powerful instrument of brass, curved somewhat like the Roman buccina, or tuba.
A mixed stuff, called also sagathy. See Sagathy.
p. p. of Senge, to singe.
An incrustation over a sore, wound, vesicle, or pustule, formed by the drying up of the discharge from the diseased part.
The case in which the blade of a sword, dagger, etc., is kept
The quality or state of being scabby.
A fragment or chip of stone.
Rough to the touch, like a file
A small carangoid fish (Trachurus saurus) abundant on the European coast, and less common on the American. The name is applied also to several allied species.
A temporary structure of timber, boards, etc., for various purposes, as for supporting workmen and materials in building, for exhibiting a spectacle upon, for holding the spectators at a show, etc.

An imitation of any veined and ornamental stone, as marble, formed by a substratum of finely ground gypsum mixed with glue, the surface of which, while soft, is variegated with splinters of marble, spar, granite, etc., and subsequently colored and polished.
A machine formerly employed for reducing dislocations of the humerus.
In the quaternion analysis, a quantity that has magnitude, but not direction

Any one of numerous species of marine gastropods of the genus Scalaria, or family Scalaridae, having elongated spiral turreted shells, with rounded whorls, usually crossed by ribs or varices. The color is generally white or pale. Called also ladder shell, and wentletrap. See Ptenoglossa, and Wentletrap.
Resembling a ladder in form or appearance
To burn with hot liquid or steam
A European flounder (Arnoglossus laterna, or Psetta arnoglossa)
Of or pertaining to the scalds of the Norsemen
Any one of numerous species of marine annelids of the family Polynoidae, and allies, which have two rows of scales, or elytra, along the back. See Illust. under Chaetopoda.
The lever or beam of a balance
A thin slip of wood used to justify a page.
Having the sides and angles unequal
Of or pertaining to a scalenohedron.
A pyramidal form under the rhombohedral system, inclosed by twelve faces, each a scalene triangle.
One who, or that which, scales
Having the wings covered with small scalelike structures, as the Lepidoptera
A scurf or scabby disease, especially of the scalp.
A kind of small onion (Allium Ascalonicum), native of Palestine

Any one of numerous species of marine bivalve mollusks of the genus Pecten and allied genera of the family Pectinidae. The shell is usually radially ribbed, and the edge is therefore often undulated in a characteristic manner. The large adductor muscle of some the species is much used as food. One species (Vola Jacobaeus) occurs on the coast of Palestine, and its shell was formerly worn by pilgrims as a mark that they had been to the Holy Land. Called also fan shell. See Pecten, 2.
A bed of oysters or mussels.
A small knife with a thin, keen blade, -- used by surgeons, and in dissecting.
One who, or that which, scalps.
A sort of second plinth or block, below the bases of Ionic and Corinthian columns, generally without moldings, and of smaller size horizontally than the pedestal.
A species of bindweed or Convolvulus (C. Scammonia).
A long, low war galley used by the Neapolitans and Sicilians in the early part of the nineteenth century.

Word: , a , or an . pcp.  it is presumably an older spelling of scanned. --2.
Meaning: Specifically (Pros.), to go through with, as a verse, marking and distinguishing the feet of which it is composed

Word: , a , or an . pcp.  it is presumably an older spelling of scanned. --2. specifically (pros.), to go through with, as a verse, marking and distinguishing the feet of which it is composed; to show, in reading, the metrical structure of; to recite metrically
Meaning: To go over and examine point by point
To offend the feelings or the conscience of (a person) by some action which is considered immoral or criminal
Giving offense to the conscience or moral feelings
In a manner to give offense
A defamatory speech or writing published to the injury of a person of dignity
A chemical earth, the oxide of scandium.
Of or pertaining to Scandinavia, that is, Sweden, Norway, and Denmark.

A rare metallic element of the boron group, whose existence was predicted under the provisional name ekaboron by means of the periodic law, and subsequently discovered by spectrum analysis in certain rare Scandinavian minerals (euxenite and gadolinite). It has not yet been isolated. Symbol Sc. Atomic weight 44.
An artifical group of birds formerly regarded as an order. They are distributed among several orders by modern ornithologists.
Quality or condition of being scanty.
The quality or condition of being scant
A peduncle rising from the ground or from a subterranean stem, as in the stemless violets, the bloodroot, and the like.
One who has narrowly escaped the gallows for his crimes.
A goat upon whose head were symbolically placed the sins of the people, after which he was suffered to escape into the wilderness.
The wheel in an escapement (as of a clock or a watch) into the teeth of which the pallets play.
The case, or impermeable apparel, in which a diver can work while under water.

An ancient mode of punishing criminals among the Persians, by confining the victim in a trough, with his head and limbs smeared with honey or the like, and exposed to the sun and to insects until he died.
Any fossil cephalopod shell of the genus Scaphites, belonging to the Ammonite family and having a chambered boat-shaped shell. Scaphites are found in the Cretaceous formation.
Of, pertaining to, or affected with, scaphocephaly.
A deformed condition of the skull, in which the vault is narrow, elongated, and more or less boat-shaped.
A flattened plate or scale attached to the second joint of the antennae of many Crustacea.
A thin leafike appendage (the exopodite) of the second maxilla of decapod crustaceans. It serves as a pumping organ to draw the water through the gill cavity.
Of or pertaining to the scaphoid and lunar bones of the carpus.

A class of marine cephalate Mollusca having a tubular shell open at both ends, a pointed or spadelike foot for burrowing, and many long, slender, prehensile oral tentacles. It includes Dentalium, or the tooth shells, and other similar shells. Called also Prosopocephala, and Solenoconcha.
Resembling a scape, or flower stem.
A grayish white mineral occuring in tetragonal crystals and in cleavable masses. It is essentially a silicate of alumina and soda.
To work roughly, or shape without finishing, as stone before leaving the quarry.
The principal bone of the shoulder girdle in mammals
Of or pertaining to the scapula or the shoulder.
A loose sleeveless vestment falling in front and behind, worn by certain religious orders and devout persons.
A secondary mouth fold developed at the base of each of the armlike lobes of the manubrium of many rhizostome medusae. See Illustration in Appendix.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the scapula or the shoulder
A mark in the skin or flesh of an animal, made by a wound or ulcer, and remaining after the wound or ulcer is healed
Any one of numerous species of lamellicorn beetles of the genus Scarabaeus, or family Scarabaeidae, especially the sacred, or Egyptian, species (Scarabaeus sacer, and S. Egyptiorum).
Of or pertaining to the family Scarabaeidae, an extensive group which includes the Egyptian scarab, the tumbledung, and many similar lamellicorn beetles.
A personage in the old Italian comedy (derived from Spain) characterized by great boastfulness and poltroonery
An offset where a wall or bank of earth, etc., retreats, leaving a shelf or footing.
The quality or condition of being scarce
Anything set up to frighten crows or other birds from cornfields
An instrument, principally used in cupping, containing several lancets moved simultaneously by a spring, for making slight incisions.
To scratch or cut the skin of
Thin, dry, membranous, and not green.
A deep bright red tinged with orange or yellow, -- of many tints and shades
Of or pertaining to the Scaridae, a family of marine fishes including the parrot fishes.
A band in the same position as the bend sinister, but only half as broad as the latter.
Bearing scars or marks of wounds.
A Mediterranean food fish (Sparisoma scarus) of excellent quality and highly valued by the Romans
Barren land having only a thin coat of grass.
A kind of bit for the bridle of a horse
One who has no fixed habitation or residence
A bed or stratum of shellfish
A tool with a semicircular edge, -- used by engravers to clear away the spaces between the lines of an engraving.
A toll or duty formerly exacted of merchant strangers by mayors, sheriffs, etc., for goods shown or offered for sale within their precincts.
To cleanse, as streets, from filth.

A person whose employment is to clean the streets of a city, by scraping or sweeping, and carrying off the filth. The name is also applied to any animal which devours refuse, carrion, or anything injurious to health.
A preliminary sketch of the plot, or main incidents, of an opera.
The structure on which a spectacle or play is exhibited
The man who manages the movable scenes in a theater.
One who moves the scenes in a theater
A perspective representation or general view of an object.
The art or act of representing a body on a perspective plane
To perceive by the olfactory organs
A staff or baton borne by a sovereign, as a ceremonial badge or emblem of authority
Having a straight shaft with whorls of spines
etc. See Skeptic, Skeptical, Skepticism, etc.
Of or pertaining to a scepter
Cursory writing on a loose sheet.
A written or printed scroll or sheet of paper
Calcium tungstate, a mineral of a white or pale yellowish color and of the tetragonal system of crystallization.
An outline or image universally applicable to a general conception, under which it is likely to be presented to the mind
Of or pertaining to a scheme or a schema.
Combination of the aspects of heavenly bodies.
To form a scheme or schemes.
A combination of things connected and adjusted by design
An Egyptian or Persian measure of length, varying from thirty-two to sixty stadia.
In a playful or sportive manner.
A playful, humorous movement, commonly in 3-4 measure, which often takes the place of the old minuet and trio in a sonata or a symphony.
General state or disposition of the body or mind, or of one thing with regard to other things
Of or pertaining to the habit of the body
Holland gin made at Schiedam in the Netherlands.

The peculiar bronzelike luster observed in certain minerals, as hypersthene, schiller spar, etc. It is due to the presence of minute inclusions in parallel position, and is sometimes of secondary origin.
The act or process of producing schiller in a mineral mass.
Any one of several small German and Dutch coins, worth from about one and a half cents to about five cents.
A form of articulation in which one bone is received into a groove or slit in another.
An interval equal to half a comma.

Any crystalline rock having a foliated structure (see Foliation) and hence admitting of ready division into slabs or slates. The common kinds are mica schist, and hornblendic schist, consisting chiefly of quartz with mica or hornblende and often feldspar.
The quality or state of being schistose.
A combining form denoting division or cleavage
A dry fruit which splits at maturity into several closed one-seeded portions.
Pertaining to, or of the nature of, a schizocoele.
Any bird with a schizognathous palate.
The condition of having a schizognathous palate.
Having the maxillo-palatine bones separate from each other and from the vomer, which is pointed in front, as in the gulls, snipes, grouse, and many other birds.
An order of Schizophyta, including the so-called fission fungi, or bacteria. See Schizophyta, in the Supplement.
A group of nemerteans comprising those having a deep slit along each side of the head. See Illust. in Appendix.
Having the two flexor tendons of the toes entirely separate, and the flexor hallucis going to the first toe only.
One of a class of vegetable organisms, in the classification of Cohn, which includes all of the inferior forms that multiply by fission, whether they contain chlorophyll or not.
one of the Schizopoda. Also used adjectively.
Of or pertaining to a schizopod, or the Schizopoda.
A division of shrimplike Thoracostraca in which each of the thoracic legs has a long fringed upper branch (exopodite) for swimming.
The finer portion of a crushed ore, as of gold, lead, or tin, separated by the water in certain wet processes.
A kind of glass of a red or ruby color, made in Bohemia.
Discovered or described by C. V. Schneider, a German anatomist of the seventeenth century.
The formation belonging to the middle of the three subdivisions of the Corniferous period in the American Devonian system
Like a scholar, or learned person
The character and qualities of a scholar
Pertaining to, or suiting, a scholar, a school, or schools
The method or subtilties of the schools of philosophy
Of or pertaining to a scholiast, or his pursuits.
A book used in schools for learning lessons.
A boy belonging to, or attending, a school.
One bred at the same school
A girl belonging to, or attending, a school.
A house appropriated for the use of a school or schools, or for instruction.
One versed in the niceties of academical disputation or of school divinity.
The man who presides over and teaches a school
A pupil who attends the same school as another.
A woman who governs and teaches a school
A room in which pupils are taught.

A vessel employed as a nautical training school, in which naval apprentices receive their education at the expense of the state, and are trained for service as sailors. Also, a vessel used as a reform school to which boys are committed by the courts to be disciplined, and instructed as mariners.
One who teaches or instructs a school.

Originally, a small, sharp-built vessel, with two masts and fore-and-aft rig. Sometimes it carried square topsails on one or both masts and was called a topsail schooner. About 1840, longer vessels with three masts, fore-and-aft rigged, came into use, and since that time vessels with four masts and even with six masts, so rigged, are built. Schooners with more than two masts are designated three-masted schooners, four-masted schooners, etc. See Illustration in Appendix.
Partaking of the nature and character of schorl
A Scotch round dance in 2-4 time, similar to the polka, only slower
A mineral occurring in steel-gray flexible folia. It contains iron, nickel, and phosphorus, and is found only in meteoric iron.
The substance of the medullary sheath.
A member of a religious sect founded by Kaspar von Schwenkfeld, a Silesian reformer who disagreed with Luther, especially on the deification of the body of Christ.
Of or pertaining to the Sciaenidae, a family of marine fishes which includes the meagre, the squeteague, and the kingfish.
An old term for a vertical section of a building
The art or science of projecting or delineating shadows as they fall in nature.
Of or pertaining to the hip

Neuralgia of the sciatic nerve, an affection characterized by paroxysmal attacks of pain in the buttock, back of the thigh, or in the leg or foot, following the course of the branches of the sciatic nerve. The name is also popularly applied to various painful affections of the hip and the parts adjoining it. See Ischiadic passion, under Ischiadic.
With, or by means of, sciatica.
A glucoside extracted from squill (Scilla) as a light porous substance.
A bitter principle extracted from the bulbs of the squill (Scilla), and probably consisting of a complex mixture of several substances.
A saber with a much curved blade having the edge on the convex side, -- in use among Mohammedans, esp., the Arabs and persians.
Of or pertaining to the family Scincidae, or skinks.
A tribe of lizards including the skinks. See Skink.

Any one of numerous species of lizards of the family Scincidae or tribe Scincoidea. The tongue is not extensile. The body and tail are covered with overlapping scales, and the toes are margined. See Illust. under Skink.
Some kind of stinging or biting insect, as a flea, a gnat, a sandfly, or the like.
Emitting sparks, or fine igneous particles
To emit sparks, or fine igneous particles.
One who knows many things superficially
Of or pertaining to sciolism, or a sciolist
A shoot or sprout of a plant
Of or pertaining to an optical arrangement for forming images in a darkened room, usually called scioptic ball.
The art or process of exhibiting luminous images, especially those of external objects, in a darkened room, by arrangements of lenses or mirrors.
Of or pertaining to the island Scio (Chio or Chios).
Of or pertaining to a sundial.

A judicial writ, founded upon some record, and requiring the party proceeded against to show cause why the party bringing it should not have advantage of such record, or (as in the case of scire facias to repeal letters patent) why the record should not be annulled or vacated.
A morbid induration, as of a gland
The clippings of metals made in various mechanical operations.
Capable of being cut or divided by a sharp instrument.
The act of dividing with an instrument having a sharp edge.
To cut with scissors or shears
A cutting instrument resembling shears, but smaller, consisting of two cutting blades with handles, movable on a pin in the center, by which they are held together. Often called a pair of scissors.

A tyrant flycatcher (Milvulus forficatus) of the Southern United States and Mexico, which has a deeply forked tail. It is light gray above, white beneath, salmon on the flanks, and fiery red at the base of the crown feathers.
Having the outer feathers much the longest, the others decreasing regularly to the median ones.
A longitudinal opening in a body, made by cutting
Of or pertaining to a natural order of plants (Scitamineae), mostly tropical herbs, including the ginger, Indian shot, banana, and the plants producing turmeric and arrowroot.
Of or pertaining to the Squirrel family.
Resembling the tail of a squirrel
A tribe of rodents containing the squirrels and allied animals, such as the gophers, woodchucks, beavers, and others.
A genus of rodents comprising the common squirrels.
Vegetable tissue composed of short cells with thickened or hardened walls, as in nutshells and the gritty parts of a pear. See Sclerotic.
Pertaining to, or composed of, sclerenchyma.
A morbid induration of the edge of the eyelid.
A hard chitinous or calcareous process or corpuscle, especially a spicule of the Alcyonaria.
The calcareous or hornlike coral forming the central stem or axis of most compound alcyonarians
One of a tribe of plectognath fishes (Sclerodermi) having the skin covered with hard scales, or plates, as the cowfish and the trunkfish.
A disease of adults, characterized by a diffuse rigidity and hardness of the skin.
Having the integument, or skin, hard, or covered with hard plates.
The thickening matter of woody cells
Making or secreting a hard substance
Having a hard texture, as nutshells.
Induration of the tissues. See Sclerema, Scleroderma, and Sclerosis.
An instrument for determining with accuracy the degree of hardness of a mineral.
That part of the skeleton which is developed in tendons, ligaments, and aponeuroses.
A hardened body formed by certain fungi, as by the Claviceps purpurea, which produces ergot.
One of the bony, cartilaginous, or membranous partitions which separate the myotomes.
Having the form of, or resembling, sawdust or raspings.
Raspings of ivory, hartshorn, metals, or other hard substance.
To find fault or rail with rude clamor
A zeolitic mineral occuring in delicate radiating groups of white crystals. It is a hydrous silicate of alumina and lime. Called also lime mesotype.
The embryo produced directly from the egg in a metagenetic series, especially the larva of a tapeworm or other parasitic worm. See Illust. of Echinococcus.
A lateral curvature of the spine.
A tubular structure found in Potsdam sandstone, and believed to be the fossil burrow of a marine worm.
Of or pertaining to the Scolopacidae, or Snipe family.
A genus of venomous myriapods including the centipeds. See Centiped.
Like or pertaining to the Scolopendra.
Any one of numerous species of small bark-boring beetles of the genus Scolytus and allied genera. Also used adjectively.
A genus of acanthopterygious fishes which includes the common mackerel.
A division of fishes including the mackerels, tunnies, and allied fishes.
Like or pertaining to the Mackerel family.
A fortification, or work for defense
A cake, thinner than a bannock, made of wheat or barley or oat meal.
One who, or that which, scoops.
A yellow gelatinous or crystalline substance found in broom (Cytisus scoparius) accompanying sparteine.
Having the surface closely covered with hairs, like a brush.
A combining form usually signifying an instrument for viewing (with the eye) or observing (in any way)
Like or pertaining to fishes of the genus Scopelus, or family Scopelodae, which includes many small oceanic fishes, most of which are phosphorescent.
Bearing a tuft of brushlike hairs.
Having the form of a broom or besom.
Any one of numerous species of small owls of the genus Scops having ear tufts like those of the horned owls, especially the European scops owl (Scops giu), and the American screech owl (S. asio).
A peculiar brushlike organ found on the foot of spiders and used in the construction of the web.
Any species of bee which has on the hind legs a brush of hairs used for collecting pollen, as the hive bees and bumblebees.
One who, or that which, scores.
The recrement of metals in fusion, or the slag rejected after the reduction of metallic ores
The act, process, or result of scorifying, or reducing to a slag
One who, or that which, scorifies
To reduce to scoria or slag
A leek-green or brownish mineral occurring in orthorhombic crystals. It is a hydrous arseniate of iron.
Of or pertaining to the family Scorpaenidae, which includes the scorpene, the rosefish, the California rockfishes, and many other food fishes. [Written also scorpaenid.] See Illust. under Rockfish.
A marine food fish of the genus Scorpaena, as the European hogfish (S. scrofa), and the California species (S. guttata).
Having the inflorescence curved or circinate at the end, like a scorpion's tail.
Any one of numerous species of pulmonate arachnids of the order Scorpiones, having a suctorial mouth, large claw-bearing palpi, and a caudal sting.
A leguminous plant (Ornithopus scorpioides) of Southern Europe, having slender curved pods.
The keeping of an alehouse by an officer of a forest, and drawing people to spend their money for liquor, for fear of his displeasure.
Of or pertaining to Scotland, its language, or its inhabitants
A native or inhabitant of Scotland
Any one of several species of northern sea ducks of the genus Oidemia.
A concave molding used especially in classical architecture.

A follower of (Joannes) Duns Scotus, the Franciscan scholastic (d. 1308), who maintained certain doctrines in philosophy and theology, in opposition to the Thomists, or followers of Thomas Aquinas, the Dominican scholastic.
An instrument for writing in the dark, or without seeing.
An instrument that discloses objects in the dark or in a faint light.
Of or pertaining to the Scotch
The burning of a wad of pease straw at the end of harvest.
An idiom, or mode of expression, peculiar to Scotland or Scotchmen.
To cause to become like the Scotch
Of or pertaining to the inhabitants of Scotland, their country, or their language
The domain or sphere of scoundrels
The practices or conduct of a scoundrel
To rub hard with something rough, as sand or Bristol brick, especially for the purpose of cleaning
One who, or that which, scours.
A sailor's dish. Bread scouse contains no meat
A large flat-bottomed boat, having broad, square ends.
To wrinkle the brows, as in frowning or displeasure
A Lenten dish, composed of eggs boiled hard, chopped, and seasoned with butter, salt, and pepper.
To scrape, paw, or scratch with the hands
Rough with irregular points, or a broken surface
Quality or state of being scragged.
The quality or state of being scraggy
To clamber with hands and knees
To grind with the teeth, and with a crackling sound
A blank book in which extracts cut from books and papers may be pasted and kept.
To rub over the surface of (something) with a sharp or rough instrument
One who gathers and hoards money in trifling sums
An instrument with which anything is scraped.
To rub and tear or mark the surface of with something sharp or ragged
A toy which imitates the sound of tearing cloth, -- used by drawing it across the back of unsuspecting persons.
A stiff wire brush for cleaning iron castings and other metal.
One who, or that which, scratches
To utter suddenly a sharp, shrill sound
To cry out with a shrill voice

Any one of three species of South American birds constituting the family Anhimidae, and the suborder Palamedeae. They have two spines on each wing, and the head is either crested or horned. They are easily tamed, and then serve as guardians for other poultry. The crested screamers, or chajas, belong to the genus Chauna. The horned screamer, or kamichi, is Palamedea cornuta.
To utter a harsh, shrill cry
The picarian birds, as distinguished from the singing birds.
A strip of plaster of the thickness proposed for the coat, applied to the wall at intervals of four or five feet, as a guide.
Anything that separates or cuts off inconvenience, injury, or danger
The refuse left after screening sand, coal, ashes, etc.

A cylinder, or a cylindrical perforation, having a continuous rib, called the thread, winding round it spirally at a constant inclination, so as to leave a continuous spiral groove between one turn and the next, -- used chiefly for producing, when revolved, motion or pressure in the direction of its axis, by the sliding of the threads of the cylinder in the grooves between the threads of the perforation adapted to it, the former being distinguished as the external, or male screw, or, more usually the screw
Adapted for forming a screw by cutting
A tool for turning screws so as to drive them into their place. It has a thin end which enters the nick in the head of the screw.
One who, or that which, screws.
Capable of being written, or of being written upon.
Skillful in, or fond of, writing.
A sharp-pointed tool, used by joiners for drawing lines on stuff
The character and opinions of a Jewish scribe in the time of Christ.
A kind of light cotton or linen fabric, often woven in openwork patterns, -- used for curtains, etc,
To make too small or short
To ornament, as shells, ivory, etc., by engraving, and (usually) rubbing pigments into the incised lines.
A chest, bookcase, or other place, where writings or curiosities are deposited
The contents of a scrip, or wallet.
In an abbey or monastery, the room set apart for writing or copying manuscripts
The quality or state of being scriptural
One who adheres literally to the Scriptures.
One who is strongly attached to, or versed in, the Scriptures, or who endeavors to regulate his life by them.
One of the smooth areas surrounding the tubercles of a sea urchin.
Having numerous small, shallow depressions or hollows
A young codfish, especially when cut open on the back and dressed.
Mottled pottery made from scraps of differently colored clays.

A constitutional disease, generally hereditary, especially manifested by chronic enlargement and cheesy degeneration of the lymphatic glands, particularly those of the neck, and marked by a tendency to the development of chronic intractable inflammations of the skin, mucous membrane, bones, joints, and other parts, and by a diminution in the power of resistance to disease or injury and the capacity for recovery. Scrofula is now generally held to be tuberculous in character, and may develop into general or local tuberculosis (consumption).
Any affection of the skin dependent on scrofula.
Pertaining to scrofula, or partaking of its nature
A stunted shrub, bush, or branch.
A roll of paper or parchment
A genus of coarse herbs having small flowers in panicled cymes

Of or pertaining to a very large natural order of gamopetalous plants (Scrophulariaceae, or Scrophularineae), usually having irregular didynamous flowers and a two-celled pod. The order includes the mullein, foxglove, snapdragon, figwort, painted cup, yellow rattle, and some exotic trees, as the Paulownia.
Of or pertaining to the scrotum
A rupture or hernia in the scrotum
The bag or pouch which contains the testicles
One who, or that which, scrubs
The quality or state of being scruppulous
Discoverable by scrutiny, inquiry, or critical examination.
To squeeze, compress, crush, or bruise.
A silver coin, and money of account, used in Italy and Sicily, varying in value, in different parts, but worth about 4 shillings sterling, or about 96 cents
The back part of the neck
To strive or struggle with a close grapple
A boat rowed by one man with two sculls, or short oars.
A place where dishes, kettles, and culinary utensils, are cleaned and kept

Any one of numerous species of marine cottoid fishes of the genus Cottus, or Acanthocottus, having a large head armed with sharp spines, and a broad mouth. They are generally mottled with yellow, brown, and black. Several species are found on the Atlantic coasts of Europe and America.
The art of carving, cutting, or hewing wood, stone, metal, etc., into statues, ornaments, etc., or into figures, as of men, or other things
The extraneous matter or impurities which rise to the surface of liquids in boiling or fermentation, or which form on the surface by other means

To cover lighty, as a painting, or a drawing, with a thin wash of opaque color, or with color-crayon dust rubbed on with the stump, or to make any similar additions to the work, so as to produce a softened effect.
To cause to loathe, or feel disgust at.
An opening cut through the waterway and bulwarks of a ship, so that water falling on deck may flow overboard
An American grape, a form of Vitis vulpina, found in the Southern Atlantic States, and often cultivated.
Thin dry scales or scabs upon the body
Quality or state of being scurfy.
Such as befits a buffoon or vulgar jester
The quality or state of being scurrile or scurrilous
Using the low and indecent language of the meaner sort of people, or such as only the license of buffoons can warrant
The quality or state of being scurvy
Covered or affected with scurf or scabs
The tail of a hare, or of a deer, or other animal whose tail is short, sp. when carried erect
Of or pertaining to a shield.
Emblazoned on or as a shield.
A kind of pasture grass (Cynodon Dactylon). See Bermuda grass: also Illustration in Appendix.
Formed like a plate or salver
the entire covering, or mode of arrangement, of scales, as on the legs and feet of a bird.
Having broad scutella on the front, and small scales on the posterior side, of the tarsus
A rounded apothecium having an elevated rim formed of the proper thallus, the fructification of certain lichens.
An order of gastropod Mollusca having a heart with two auricles and one ventricle. The shell may be either spiral or shieldlike.
Having the gills protected by a shieldlike shell
Any species of chilopod myriapods of the genus Scutigera. They sometimes enter buildings and prey upon insects.
Having the anterior surface of the tarsus covered with scutella, or transverse scales, in the form of incomplete bands terminating at a groove on each side
An oblong shield made of boards or wickerwork covered with leather, with sometimes an iron rim
Arm scye, a cutter's term for the armhole or part of the armhole of the waist of a garnment.

A dangerous rock on the Italian coast opposite the whirpool Charybdis on the coast of Sicily, -- both personified in classical literature as ravenous monsters. The passage between them was formerly considered perilous
A genus of oceanic nudibranchiate mollusks having the small branched gills situated on the upper side of four fleshy lateral lobes, and on the median caudal crest.
One of a family (Scyllaridae) of macruran Crustacea, remarkable for the depressed form of the body, and the broad, flat antennae. Also used adjectively.
A white crystalline substance of a sweetish taste, resembling inosite and metameric with dextrose. It is extracted from the kidney of the dogfish (of the genus Scylium), the shark, and the skate.
The young attached larva of Discophora in the stage when it resembles a hydroid, or actinian.
An order of fishes including the blennioid and gobioid fishes, and other related families.
An order of fresh-water fishes inhabiting tropical Africa. They have rudimentary electrical organs on each side of the tail.
A kind of large drinking cup, -- used by Greeks and Romans, esp. by poor folk.

An instrument for mowing grass, grain, or the like, by hand, composed of a long, curving blade, with a sharp edge, made fast to a long handle, called a snath, which is bent into a form convenient for use.
Of or pertaining to Scythia (a name given to the northern part of Asia, and Europe adjoining to Asia), or its language or inhabitants.
An exclamation expressive of impatience or anger.
One of the larger bodies of salt water, less than an ocean, found on the earth's surface
Any one of numerous species of soft-bodied Anthozoa, belonging to the order Actrinaria
The fruit of a West Indian palm (Manicaria Plukenetii), often found floating in the sea.
A squid of the genus Ommastrephes. See Squid.

A large marine food fish (Serranus, / Centropristis, atrarius) which abounds on the Atlantic coast of the United States. It is dark bluish, with black bands, and more or less varied with small white spots and blotches. Called also, locally, blue bass, black sea bass, blackfish, bluefish, and black perch.
A beach lying along the sea.
Any fur seal. See under Fur.
A green seaweed (Cladophora rupestris) growing in dense tufts.
Any large marine mammal, as a seal, walrus, or cetacean.
Any swimming bird frequenting the sea
A plant (Suaeda maritima) of the Goosefoot family, growing in salt marches.
A boat or vessel adapted to the open sea
A breaking or overflow of a bank or a dike by the sea.
Any one of several species of sparoid fishes, especially the common European species (Pagellus centrodontus), the Spanish (P. Oweni), and the black sea bream (Cantharus lineatus)
Built at, in, or by the sea.
The captain of a vessel that sails upon the sea.
A chart or map on which the lines of the shore, islands, shoals, harbors, etc., are delineated.
A fleshy plant (Arenaria peploides) growing in large tufts in the sands of the northern Atlantic seacoast
Any one of the large bivalve mollusks found on the open seacoast, especially those of the family Mactridae, as the common American species. (Mactra, / Spisula, solidissima)
The shore or border of the land adjacent to the sea or ocean. Also used adjectively.
In a steamship, a cock or valve close to the vessel's side, for closing a pipe which communicates with the sea.

A magnificent palm (Lodoicea Sechellarum) found only in the Seychelles Islands. The fruit is an immense two-lobed nut. It was found floating in the Indian Ocean before the tree was known, and called sea cocoanut, and double cocoanut.
A large blackfish seaweed (Agarum Turneri), the frond of which is punctured with many little holes.
The mariner's compass. See under Compass.
A yellow cylindrical mass of egg capsule of certain species of whelks (Buccinum), which resembles an ear of maize.
Any crustacean of the genus Palinurus and allied genera, as the European spiny lobster (P. vulgaris), which is much used as an article of food. See Lobster.
Any large holothurian, especially one of those belonging to the genus Pentacta, or Cucumaria, as the common American and European species. (P. frondosa).
Any very large ray, especially any species of the genus Manta or Cepholoptera, some of which become more than twenty feet across and weigh several tons. See also Ox ray, under Ox.
The little auk, or rotche. See Illust. of Rotche.

Any one of numerous species of ducks which frequent the seacoasts and feed mainly on fishes and mollusks. The scoters, eiders, old squaw, and ruddy duck are examples. They may be distinguished by the lobate hind toe.
Any one of several species of fish-eating eagles of the genus Haliaeetus and allied genera, as the North Pacific sea eagle. (H. pelagicus), which has white shoulders, head, rump, and tail
Any species of ear-shaped shells of the genus Haliotis. See Abalone.

A very large seal (Macrorhinus proboscideus) of the Antarctic seas, much hunted for its oil. It sometimes attains a length of thirty feet, and is remarkable for the prolongation of the nose of the adult male into an erectile elastic proboscis, about a foot in length. Another species of smaller size (M. angustirostris) occurs on the coast of Lower California, but is now nearly extinct.
Any gorgonian which branches in a fanlike form, especially Gorgonia flabellum of Florida and the West Indies.
One who follows the sea as a business
Following the business of a mariner
Any gorgonian which branches in a plumelike form.
Any gorgonian which branches like a fern.
An engagement between ships at sea
A sertularian hydroid, especially Sertularia abietina, which branches like a miniature fir tree.
A sea anemone, or any related anthozoan.
Any bird which habitually frequents the sea, as an auk, gannet, gull, tern, or petrel
A long, rolling swell of the sea.
Any small holothurian resembling in form a gherkin.
A hydroid coral of the genus Millepora, especially M. alcicornis, of the West Indies and Florida. So called because it stings the tongue like ginger. See Illust. under Millepore.
A kind of kelp (Laminaria digitata) with palmately cleft fronds
Surrounded by the water of the sea or ocean
A goddess supposed to live in or reign over the sea, or some part of the sea.
A gown or frock with short sleeves, formerly worn by mariners.
The gulf weed. See under Gulf.
The green color of sea water.
Of a beautiful bluish green color, like sea water on soundings.
Any gull living on the seacoast.
A Jewish dry measure containing one third of an an ephah.
Any tectibranchiate mollusk of the genus Aplysia. See Aplysia.
A low perennial plant (Frankenia laevis) resembling heath, growing along the seashore in Europe.
An evergeen seashore plant (Eryngium maritimum). See Eryngium.
A fabulous creature, half horse and half fish, represented in classic mythology as driven by sea dogs or ridden by the Nereids. It is also depicted in heraldry. See Hippocampus.
Of or pertaining to certain islands along the coast of South Carolina and Georgia
Soap prepared for use in milling cloth.
One of the leaders among the Norsemen who passed their lives in roving the seas in search of plunder and adventures
Any aquatic carnivorous mammal of the families Phocidae and Otariidae.
A kind of seaweed (Chorda Filum) having blackish cordlike fronds, often many feet long.
The peculiar language or phraseology of seamen
The gray snapper. See under Snapper.
Of a rich dark brown color, like the fur of the fur seal after it is dyed.
Legs able to maintain their possessor upright in stormy weather at sea, that is, ability stand or walk steadily on deck when a vessel is rolling or pitching in a rough sea.
Any one of several species of nudibranchiate mollusks of the genus Doris and allied genera, having a smooth, thick, convex yellow body.
Any one of several species of spotted seals, especially Ogmorhinus leptonyx, and Leptonychotes Weddelli, of the Antarctic Ocean. The North Pacific sea leopard is the harbor seal.
The customary certificate of national character which neutral merchant vessels are bound to carry in time of war
The green papery fronds of several seaweeds of the genus Ulva, sometimes used as food.
The level of the surface of the sea
A compound of the resinous materials, pigments, etc., used as a material for seals, as for letters, documents, etc.
Any one of several large species of seals of the family Otariidae native of the Pacific Ocean, especially the southern sea lion (Otaria jubata) of the South American coast
Any one of numerous species of isopod crustaceans of Cymothoa, Livoneca, and allied genera, mostly parasites on fishes.
Having or showing the skill of a practical seaman.
The skill of a good seaman
Land which borders on the sea
Any elevated object on land which serves as a guide to mariners
Any bryozoan of the genus Flustra or allied genera which form frondlike corals.
A low, fleshy perennial herb (Glaux maritima) found along northern seashores.
Any branched marine bryozoan resembling moss.
A dorsibranchiate annelid, belonging to Aphrodite and allied genera, having long, slender, hairlike setae on the sides.
One who sews well, or whose occupation is to sew.
A woman whose occupation is sewing
A rich slimy deposit in salt marshes and along the seashore, sometimes used as a manure
A session, as of some public body
A bard among the Highlanders of Scotland, who preserved and repeated the traditions of the tribes
A large American holothurian (Lophothuria Fabricii) having a bright orange convex body covered with finely granulated scales. Its expanded tentacles are bright red.

An aquatic carnivore (Enhydris lutris, / marina) found in the North Pacific Ocean.  Its fur is highly valued, especially by the Chinese. It is allied to the common otter, but is larger, with feet more decidedly webbed.
The gilthead (Crenilabrus melops), a fish of the British coasts.
A document carried by neutral merchant vessels in time of war, to show their nationality
A beautiful American ascidian (Cynthia, / Halocynthia, pyriformis) having the size, form, velvety surface, and color of a ripe peach.
A pedunculated ascidian of the genus Boltonia.
The oyster catcher, a limicoline bird of the genus Haematopus.
A picture representing a scene at sea
The horn poppy. See under Horn.
Any fish of the genus Diodon, and allied genera, whose body is covered with spines. See Illust. under Diodon.
An American compound ascidian (Amoraecium stellatum) which forms large whitish masses resembling salt pork.
A port on the seashore, or one accessible for seagoing vessels. Also used adjectively
The horny egg case of a skate, and of certain sharks.

the twentieth letter of the English alphabet, is a nonvocal consonant. With the letter h it forms the digraph th, which has two distinct sounds, as in thin, then. See Guide to Pronunciation, //262-264, and also //153, 156, 169, 172, 176, 178-180.
The flap or latchet of a shoe fastened with a string or a buckle.
A genus of blood sucking flies, including the horseflies.

A sort of tunic or mantle formerly worn for protection from the weather. When worn over the armor it was commonly emblazoned with the arms of the wearer, and from this the name was given to the garment adopted for heralds.
A stout silk having satin stripes, -- used for furniture.

A concretion in the joints of the bamboo, which consists largely or chiefly of pure silica. It is highly valued in the East Indies as a medicine for the cure of bilious vomitings, bloody flux, piles, and various other diseases.
A fabric like poplin, with a watered surface.
A kind of waved silk, usually called watered silk, manufactured like taffeta, but thicker and stronger. The watering is given to it by calendering.
To cause to waste gradually, to emaciate.
A secretary or notary under the Roman empire
A slightly built or temporary habitation
Of or pertaining to a tabernacle, especially the Jewish tabernacle.
Progressive emaciation of the body, accompained with hectic fever, with no well-marked logical symptoms.
A painting on a wall or ceiling
A smooth, flat surface, like the side of a board
A cloth for covering a table, especially one with which a table is covered before the dishes, etc., are set on for meals.
A common table for guests at a hotel
A broad, level, elevated area of land
A spoon of the largest size commonly used at the table
As much as a tablespoon will hold
A small table or flat surface.
Ware, or articles collectively, for table use.

A total prohibition of intercourse with, use of, or approach to, a given person or thing under pain of death, -- an interdict of religious origin and authority, formerly common in the islands of Polynesia
A small drum used as an accompaniment to a pipe or fife, both being played by the same person.
One who plays on the tabor.
One of certain Bohemian reformers who suffered persecution in the fifteenth century
Having the form of, or pertaining to, a table (in any of the uses of the word).
The act of tabularizing, or the state of being tabularized
An artificial group of stony corals including those which have transverse septa in the calicles. The genera Pocillopora and Favosites are examples.
To form into a table or tables
The act of forming into a table or tables
A kind of customary payment by a tenant
A bitter balsamic resin obtained from tropical American trees of the genus Elaphrium (E. tomentosum and E. Tacamahaca), and also from East Indian trees of the genus Calophyllum
The cross, or church, of St. Antony. See Illust. (6), under Cross, n.
Something used for taking hold or holding
A hydrous chloride of calcium and magnesium occurring in yellowish masses which rapidly deliquesce upon exposure. It is found in the salt mines at Stassfurt.
Any one of numerous species of Diptera belonging to Tachina and allied genera. Their larvae are external parasites of other insects.

the twenty-first letter of the English alphabet, is a cursive form of the letter V, with which it was formerly used interchangeably, both letters being then used both as vowels and consonants. U and V are now, however, differentiated, U being used only as a vowel or semivowel, and V only as a consonant. The true primary vowel sound of U, in Anglo-Saxon, was the sound which it still retains in most of the languages of Europe, that of long oo, as in tool, and short oo, as in wood, answering to the French ou in tour. Etymologically U is most closely related to o, y (vowel), w, and v

V, the twenty-second letter of the English alphabet, is a vocal consonant. V and U are only varieties of the same character, U being the cursive form, while V is better adapted for engraving, as in stone. The two letters were formerly used indiscriminately, and till a comparatively recent date words containing them were often classed together in dictionaries and other books of reference (see U). The letter V is from the Latin alphabet, where it was used both as a consonant (about like English w) and as a vowel. The Latin derives it from it from a form (V) of the Greek vowel / (see Y), this Greek letter being either from the same Semitic letter as the digamma F (see F), or else added by the Greeks to the alphabet which they took from the Semitic. Etymologically v is most nearly related to u, w, f, b, p

The acorn cup of two kinds of oak (Quercus macrolepis, and Q. vallonea) found in Eastern Europe. It contains abundance of tannin, and is much used by tanners and dyers.
Of or pertaining to Valsalva, an Italian anatomist of the 17th century.
So as to be of value.

One who assesses, or sets a value on, anything

A genus of small spiral fresh-water gastropods having an operculum.

Any fresh-water gastropod of the genus Valvata.
Of or pertaining to a valve or valves

A volatile liquid hydrocarbon, C5H6, related to ethylene and acetylene, but possessing the property of unsaturation in the third degree. It is the only known member of a distinct series of compounds. It has a garlic odor.
The piece designed to protect the arm from the elbow to the wrist.
Belief in the existence of vampires.
A round of iron on the shaft of a tilting spear, to protect the hand.
Pertaining to, or obtained from, vanadium
A mineral occurring in yellowish, and ruby-red hexagonal crystals. It consist of lead vanadate with a small proportion of lead chloride.
A salt of vanadious acid, analogous to a nitrite or a phosphite.

A rare element of the nitrogen-phosphorus group, found combined, in vanadates, in certain minerals, and reduced as an infusible, grayish-white metallic powder. It is intermediate between the metals and the non-metals, having both basic and acid properties. Symbol V (or Vd, rarely). Atomic weight 51.2.
The hypothetical radical VO, regarded as a characterized residue of certain vanadium compounds.

One of a Teutonic race, formerly dwelling on the south shore of the Baltic, the most barbarous and fierce of the northern nations that plundered Rome in the 5th century, notorious for destroying the monuments of art and literature.
Of or pertaining to the Vandals
The spirit or conduct of the Vandals
Of or pertaining to the style of Vandyke the painter
A contrivance attached to some elevated object for the purpose of showing which way the wind blows
Any one of numerous species of handsomely colored butterflies belonging to Vanessa and allied genera. Many of these species have the edges of the wings irregularly scalloped.
A ditch on the outside of the counterscarp, usually full of water.
A rope to steady the peak of a gaff.
The troops who march in front of an army
A genus of climbing orchidaceous plants, natives of tropical America.
Pertaining to, or derived from, vanilla or vanillin

A white crystalline aldehyde having a burning taste and characteristic odor of vanilla. It is extracted from vanilla pods, and is also obtained by the decomposition of coniferin, and by the oxidation of eugenol.
An inferior kind of vanilla, the pods of Vanilla Pompona.
The hypothetical radical characteristic of vanillic alcohol.
To pass from a visible to an invisible state
The quality or state of being vain
The Australian pied crow shrike (Strepera graculina). It is glossy bluish black, with the under tail coverts and the tips and bases of the tail feathers white.
A machine for concentrating ore. See Frue vanner.
A process by which ores are washed on a shovel, or in a vanner.
To conquer, overcome, or subdue in battle, as an enemy.
One who, or that which, vanquishes.
The act of vanquishing, or the state of being vanquished.
An ichneumon (Herpestes galera) native of Southern Africa and Madagascar. It is reddish brown or dark brown, grizzled with white. Called also vondsira, and marsh ichneumon.
superior or more favorable situation or opportunity
Being on, or towards, the van, or front.
That which is vapid, insipid, or lifeless
Having lost its life and spirit
The quality or state of being vapid
Any substance in the gaseous, or aeriform, state, the condition of which is ordinarily that of a liquid or solid.
The quality or state of being vaporable.
Capable of being converted into vapor by the agency of heat
The act or process of converting into vapor, or of passing off in vapor
Existing in a vaporous form or state
An instrument for measuring the volume or the tension of any vapor
Capable of being vaporized into vapor.
The act or process of vaporizing, or the state of being converted into vapor
To convert into vapor, as by the application of heat, whether naturally or artificially.
One who, or that which, vaporizes, or converts into vapor.
Having the form or nature of vapor.
The act of beating or whipping.
One who has charge of cattle, horses, etc.
A Spanish measure of length equal to about one yard. The vara now in use equals 33.385 inches.
One of the Northmen who founded a dynasty in Russia in the 9th century
A genus of very large lizards native of Asia and Africa. It includes the monitors. See Monitor, 3.
A wand or staff of authority or justice.
The calcined ashes of any coarse seaweed used for the manufacture of soda and iodine
The ringtailed lemur (Lemur catta) of Madagascar. Its long tail is annulated with black and white.
The quality or state of being variable
Having the capacity of varying or changing
The quality or state of being variable
The quality or state of being variant
Varying in from, character, or the like
A varicose enlargement of the veins of the spermatic cord
The quality or state of being varicose.
The act of variegating or diversifying, or the state of being diversified, by different colors
Of or pertaining to a variety
The quality or state of being various
A kind of diorite or diabase containing imbedded whitish spherules, which give the rock a spotted appearance.
Thickly marked with small, round specks
Of or pertaining to the smallpox
An apple-green mineral occurring in reniform masses. It is a hydrous phosphate of alumina.
An imperfection on the inside of the hind leg in horses, different from a curb, but at the same height, and frequently injuring the sale of the animal by growing to an unsightly size.
A uneven, permanent dilatation of a vein.
A servant, especially to a knight

A viscid liquid, consisting of a solution of resinous matter in an oil or a volatile liquid, laid on work with a brush, or otherwise. When applied the varnish soon dries, either by evaporation or chemical action, and the resinous part forms thus a smooth, hard surface, with a beautiful gloss, capable of resisting, to a greater or less degree, the influences of air and moisture.
A doctor or teacher in the Armenian church. Members of this order of ecclesiastics frequently have charge of dioceses, with episcopal functions.
In falconry, one of the rings secured to the ends of the jesses.
Consisting of, or containing, vessels as an essential part of a structure
The quality or state of being vascular.
One of the substances of which vegetable tissue is composed, differing from cellulose in its solubility in certain media.
A vessel adapted for various domestic purposes, and anciently for sacrificial uses

A yellowish translucent substance, almost odorless and tasteless, obtained as a residue in the purification of crude petroleum, and consisting essentially of a mixture of several of the higher members of the paraffin series. It is used as an unguent, and for various purposes in the arts. See the Note under Petrolatum.
Formed like a vase, or like a common flowerpot.
Having the form of a vessel, or duct.
Causing constriction of the blood vessels

Concerned in the development and formation of blood vessels and blood corpuscles
Causing movement in the walls of vessels
The grantee of a fief, feud, or fee

A magnificent assemblage of buildings at Rome, near the church of St. Peter, including the pope's palace, a museum, a library, a famous chapel, etc.
One who strongly adheres to the papal authority
The murder, or the murderer, of a prophet.
A kind of song of a lively character, frequently embodying a satire on some person or event, sung to a familiar air in couplets with a refrain
An inhabitant, or the inhabitants, of the Swiss canton of Vaud.
An arched structure of masonry, forming a ceiling or canopy.
Chromate of copper and lead, of various shades of green.
The vassal or tenant of a baron
The quality or tenure of the fee held by a vavasor
Any one of several species of parrots of the genus Coracopsis, native of Madagascar
The thirteenth, or intercalary, month of the Jewish ecclesiastical calendar, which is added about every third year.
The flesh of a calf when killed and used for food.
The act of carrying, or state of being carried.
The ancient sacred literature of the Hindus
A system of philosophy among the Hindus, founded on scattered texts of the Vedas, and thence termed the "Anta," or end or substance.
Of or pertaining to the Vedas.
One versed in the doctrines of the Vedantas.
A sentinel, usually on horseback, stationed on the outpost of an army, to watch an enemy and give notice of danger
A Russian liquid measure, equal to 3.249 gallons of U. S. standard measure, or 2.706 imperial gallons.

An American thrush (Turdus fuscescens) common in the Northern United States and Canada. It is light tawny brown above. The breast is pale buff, thickly spotted with brown. Called also Wilson's thrush.
A brilliant star of the first magnitude, the brightest of those constituting the constellation Lyra.
The quality or state of being vegetable.
Of or pertaining to vegetables, or the vegetable kingdom
The quality or state of being vegetal, or vegetable.

To convey by means of a vehicle

Of, pertaining to, or designating, certain secret tribunals which flourished in Germany from the end of the 12th century to the middle of the 16th, usurping many of the functions of the government which were too weak to maintain law and order, and inspiring dread in all who came within their jurisdiction.
Something hung up, or spread out, to intercept the view, and hide an object
One of the vessels which carry blood, either venous or arterial, to the heart. See Artery, 2.

Having the power of vellicating, plucking, or twitching

A fine kind of parchment, usually made from calfskin, and rendered clear and white, -- used as for writing upon, and for binding books.
An apparatus for measuring speed, as of machinery or vessels, but especially of projectiles.

A light road carriage propelled by the feet of the rider. Originally it was propelled by striking the tips of the toes on the roadway, but commonly now by the action of the feet on a pedal or pedals connected with the axle of one or more of the wheels, and causing their revolution. They are made in many forms, with two, three, or four wheels. See Bicycle, and Tricycle.
One who rides on a velocipede.
One of many textile fabrics having a pile like that of velvet.
Any one of several species of marine gastropods belonging to Velutina and allied genera.
Having the surface covered with a fine and dense silky pubescence
A kind of velvet having cotton back.
A silk fabric, having a short, close nap of erect threads. Inferior qualities are made with a silk pile on a cotton or linen back.
A kind of cloth, usually cotton, made in imitation of velvet
The fine shag or nap of velvet
A name given to several plants which have soft, velvety leaves, as the Abutilon Avicennae, the Cissampelos Pareira, and the Lavatera arborea, and even the common mullein.
Made of velvet, or like velvet
The quality or state of being venal, or purchasable
The hunting spiders, which run after, or leap upon, their prey.
The arrangement or system of veins, as in the wing of an insect, or in the leaves of a plant. See Illust. in Appendix.
To transfer to another person for a pecuniary equivalent
A European lake whitefish (Coregonus Willughbii, or C. Vandesius) native of certain lakes in Scotland and England. It is regarded as a delicate food fish. Called also vendis.
The person to whom a thing is vended, or sold
The first month of the French republican calendar, dating from September 22, 1792.
The quality or state of being vendible, or salable.
Capable of being vended, or sold
To cry up. as if for sale
