To overlay or plate with a thin layer of wood or other material for outer finish or decoration
The act or practice of poisoning.
The quality or state of being venerable
An extensive tribe of bivalve mollusks of which the genus Venus is the type. The shells are usually oval, or somewhat heartshaped, with a conspicuous lunule.  See Venus.
The act of venerating, or the state of being venerated
Of or pertaining to venery, or sexual love
Devoted to the offices of Venus, or love
The act or operation of opening a vein for letting blood
Of or pertaining to Venice in Italy.
A bout, or turn, as at fencing
Punishment inflicted in return for an injury or an offense
The quality or state of being venial
A judicial writ or precept directed to the sheriff, requiring him to cause a certain number of qualified persons to appear in court at a specified time, to serve as jurors in said court.
The 95th Psalm, which is said or sung regularly in the public worship of many churches. Also, a musical composition adapted to this Psalm.
Matter fatal or injurious to life
The quality or state of being venous.
Of or pertaining to a vein or veins
A small hole, as the stop in a flute
That part of a helmet which is intended for the admission of air, -- sometimes in the visor.

To open and expose to the free passage of air
The act of ventilating, or the state of being ventilated

Swelling out on one side or unequally
Of or pertaining to a ventricle
Any one of numerous species of siliceous fossil sponges belonging to Ventriculites and allied genera, characteristic of the Cretaceous period.

The act, art, or practice of speaking in such a manner that the voice appears to come, not from the person speaking, but from some other source, as from the opposite side of the room, from the cellar, etc.
One who practices, or is skilled in, ventriloquism.

Gold powder for covering varnished surfaces.

The goddess of beauty and love, that is, beauty or love deified.

An open, roofed gallery or portico, adjoining a dwelling house, forming an out-of-door sitting room.  See Loggia.
A yellowish amorphous alkaloid extracted from the rootstock of Veratrum album.

A poisonous alkaloid obtained from the root hellebore (Veratrum) and from sabadilla seeds as a white crystalline powder, having an acrid, burning taste. It is sometimes used externally, as in ointments, in the local treatment of neuralgia and rheumatism. Called also veratria, and veratrina.
A liquid hydrocarbon obtained by the decomposition of veratric acid, and constituting the dimethyl ether of pyrocatechin.
A genus of coarse liliaceous herbs having very poisonous qualities.
Expressed in words, whether spoken or written, but commonly in spoken words
A literal adherent to, or a minute critic of, words
The quality or state of being verbal
The act of verbalizing, or the state of being verbalized.
A game in word making.  See Logomachy, 2.
A genus of herbaceous plants of which several species are extensively cultivated for the great beauty of their flowers

Of or pertaining to a natural order (Verbenaceae) of gamopetalous plants of which Verbena is the type. The order includes also the black and white mangroves, and many plants noted for medicinal use or for beauty of bloom.
To strew with verbena, or vervain, as in ancient sacrifices and rites.
The use of many words without necessity, or with little sense
The quality or state of being verbose
The privilege of cutting green wood within a forest for fuel.
The quality or state of being verdant.
Covered with growing plants or grass
An officer who has the charge of the king's forest, to preserve the vert and venison, keep the assizes, view, receive, and enroll attachments and presentments of all manner of trespasses.

A green poisonous substance used as a pigment and drug, obtained by the action of acetic acid on copper, and consisting essentially of a complex mixture of several basic copper acetates.
A small yellow-headed bird (Auriparus flaviceps) of Lower California, allied to the titmice
A commercial name for green aniline dye.
Charged with leaves, fruits, flowers, etc.

Any one of numerous species of club-shaped, compound Alcyonaria belonging to Veretillum and allied genera, of the tribe Pennatulacea. The whole colony can move about as if it were a simple animal.

The ornament of woodwork upon the gable of a house, used extensively in the 15th century. It was generally suspended from the edge of the projecting roof (see Verge, n., 4), and in position parallel to the gable wall. Called also bargeboard.

One who carries a verge, or emblem of office.

One who, or that which, verifies.

Agreeable to truth or to fact

An extensive artificial division of the animal kingdom, including the parasitic worms, or helminths, together with the nemerteans, annelids, and allied groups. By some writers the branchiopods, the bryzoans, and the tunicates are also included. The name was used in a still wider sense by Linnaeus and his followers.

Any one of many species of marine gastropods belonging to Vermetus and allied genera, of the family Vermetidae. Their shells are regularly spiral when young, but later in life the whorls become separate, and the shell is often irregularly bent and contorted like a worm tube.

The flour of a hard and small-grained wheat made into dough, and forced through small cylinders or pipes till it takes a slender, wormlike form, whence the Italian name. When the paste is made in larger tubes, it is called macaroni.

A tribe of edentates comprising the South American ant-eaters. The tongue is long, slender, exsertile, and very flexible, whence the name.
A bright red pigment consisting of mercuric sulphide, obtained either from the mineral cinnabar or artificially. It has a fine red color, and is much used in coloring sealing wax, in printing, etc.
The generation or breeding of vermin.
A liqueur made of white wine, absinthe, and various aromatic drugs, used to excite the appetite.
Belonging to the country of one's birth
The act or process of making vernacular, or the state of being made vernacular.
A kind of sweet wine from Italy.
Of or pertaining to the spring
The arrangement of the leaves within the leaf bud, as regards their folding, coiling, rolling, etc.

A short scale made to slide along the divisions of a graduated instrument, as the limb of a sextant, or the scale of a barometer, for indicating parts of divisions. It is so graduated that a certain convenient number of its divisions are just equal to a certain number, either one less or one more, of the divisions of the instrument, so that parts of a division are determined by observing what line on the vernier coincides with a line on the instrument.
An alkaloid extracted from the shoots of the vetch, red clover, etc., as a white crystalline substance.
A glucoside extracted from the root of a South African plant of the genus Vernonia, as a deliquescent powder, and used as a mild heart tonic.
Of or pertaining to Verona, in Italy.
A portrait or representation of the face of our Savior on the alleged handkerchief of Saint Veronica, preserved at Rome
Having thickset tufts of parallel hairs, bristles, or branches.
Shaped like a wart or warts.
A verse or verses.  See Verse.
The quality or state of being versable.
The quality or state of being versatile
A line consisting of a certain number of metrical feet (see Foot, n., 9) disposed according to metrical rules.
The act, art, or practice, of versifying, or making verses
One who versifies, or makes verses
A change of form, direction, or the like
One who makes or favors a version
The reverse, or left-hand, page of a book or a folded sheet of paper
The turning factor of a quaternion.
A Russian measure of length containing 3,500 English feet.
Of or pertaining to a verse.
Everything that grows, and bears a green leaf, within the forest
One of the serial segments of the spinal column.
Of or pertaining to a vertebrae, or the vertebral column
At or within a vertebra or vertebrae
Of or pertaining to a vertebrae and an artery

One of the grand divisions of the animal kingdom, comprising all animals that have a backbone composed of bony or cartilaginous vertebrae, together with Amphioxus in which the backbone is represented by a simple undivided notochord. The Vertebrata always have a dorsal, or neural, cavity above the notochord or backbone, and a ventral, or visceral, cavity below it. The subdivisions or classes of Vertebrata are Mammalia, Aves, Reptilia, Amphibia, Pisces, Marsipobranchia, and Leptocardia.
Having a backbone, or vertebral column, containing the spinal marrow, as man, quadrupeds, birds, amphibia, and fishes.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, a vertebra, vertebrae, or vertebral column
Of or pertaining to the vertex
The quality or state of being vertical

A whorl of flowers apparently of one cluster, but composed of two opposite axillary cymes, as in mint.  See Illust. of Whorl.

An elevation, or crest, in the wall of the urethra where the seminal ducts enter it.
Any plant of the genus Verbena.
Excitement of imagination such as animates a poet, artist, or musician, in composing or performing
A South African monkey (Cercopithecus pygerythrus, / Lelandii). The upper parts are grayish green, finely specked with black. The cheeks and belly are reddish white.
A rare metallic element of which little is known. It is said by Scacchi to have been extracted from a yellowish incrustation from the cracks of a Vesuvian lava erupted in 1631.
Of or pertaining to the bladder.
To raise little bladders or blisters upon
The process of vesicating, or of raising blisters.
Tending, or having power, to raise a blister.
A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with, or relation to, the bladder
Of a pertaining to the bladder and the prostrate gland.
Of or pertaining to the bladder and the uterus.
Of or pertaining to the bladder and the vagina.
Any one of numerous species of marine Bryozoa belonging to Vesicularia and allied genera. They have delicate tubular cells attached in clusters to slender flexible stems.
The state of containing vesicles, or the process by which vesicles are formed.
A genus of Hymenoptera including the common wasps and hornets.
One of the little hours of the Breviary.
A genus of bats including some of the common small insectivorous species of North America and Europe.
A tribe of bats including the common insectivorous bats of America and Europe, belonging to Vespertilio and allied genera. They lack a nose membrane.
Of or pertaining to the Vespertiliones.
Of or pertaining to the evening
A nest, or habitation, of insects of the wasp kind.
One who carried out the dead bodies of the poor at night for burial.

Of or pertaining to a vestige or remnant

Any one of several species of actinians belonging to the genus Cerianthus. These animals have a long, smooth body tapering to the base, and two separate circles of tentacles around the mouth. They form a tough, flexible, feltlike tube with a smooth internal lining, in which they dwell, whence the name.
A room appendant to a church, in which sacerdotal vestments and sacred utensils are sometimes kept, and where meetings for worship or parish business are held
Of or pertaining to Vesuvius, a volcano near Naples.

A mineral occurring in tetragonal crystals, and also massive, of a brown to green color, rarely sulphur yellow and blue. It is a silicate of alumina and lime with some iron magnesia, and is common at Vesuvius. Also called idocrase.
A trade name for a brown dyestuff obtained from certain basic azo compounds of benzene
Any leguminous plant of the genus Vicia, some species of which are valuable for fodder. The common species is V. sativa.
Any small leguminous plant of the genus Lathyrus, especially L. Nissolia.
Consisting of vetches or of pea straw.
Long exercised in anything, especially in military life and the duties of a soldier
To reenlist for service as a soldier.
One skilled in the diseases of cattle or domestic animals
Of or pertaining to the art of healing or treating the diseases of domestic animals, as oxen, horses, sheep, etc.
One who uses, or sustains the use of, the veto.

A small bottle, usually of glass

Of or pertaining to a journey or traveling.

One of the movable, slender, spinelike organs or parts with which certain bryozoans are furnished. They are regarded as specially modified zooids, of nearly the same nature as Avicularia.

Of or pertaining to a vicar
Having delegated power, as a vicar

A smith who works at the vice instead of at the anvil.

Full of, or subject to, changes.
A West Indian duck, sometimes domesticated.
Of or pertaining to the viscount or sheriff of a country.
A living being sacrificed to some deity, or in the performance of a religious rite
To make a victim of, esp. by deception

A genus of aquatic plants named in honor of Queen Victoria.  The Victoria regia is a native of Guiana and Brazil. Its large, spreading leaves are often over five feet in diameter, and have a rim from three to five inches high
Of or pertaining to the reign of Queen Victoria of England
Of or pertaining to victory, or a victor' being a victor
The defeat of an enemy in battle, or of an antagonist in any contest
A woman who wins a victory

the twenty-third letter of the English alphabet, is usually a consonant, but sometimes it is a vowel, forming the second element of certain diphthongs, as in few, how. It takes its written form and its name from the repetition of a V, this being the original form of the Roman capital letter which we call U. Etymologically it is most related to v and u.  See V, and U. Some of the uneducated classes in England, especially in London, confuse w and v, substituting the one for the other, as weal for veal, and veal for weal
To move staggeringly or unsteadily from one side to the other
A soft, earthy, dark-colored rock or clay derived from the alteration of basalt.
An earthy oxide of manganese, or mixture of different oxides and water, with some oxide of iron, and often silica, alumina, lime, or baryta
To walk with short steps, swaying the body from one side to the other, like a duck or very fat person
One who, or that which, waddles.
One who, or that which, wades.
A coarse, hairy, woolen cloth, formerly used for garments by the poor, and for various other purposes.
A kind of pledge or mortgage.
One who holds by a wadset.
A ravine through which a brook flows
A thin cake made of flour and other ingredients.
A dealer in the cakes called wafers
A thin cake baked and then rolled
To give notice to by waving something
Conveyance on a buoyant medium, as air or water.
One who, or that which, wafts.
To move one way and the other with quick turns
A small East Indian wild cat (Felis wagati), regarded by some as a variety of the leopard cat.
A south African proteaceous tree (Protea grandiflora)
Something deposited, laid, or hazarded on the event of a contest or an unsettled question
One who wagers, or lays a bet.
A compensation given to a hired person for services
The young of the great black-backed gull (Larus marinus), formerly considered a distinct species.
The manner or action of a wag
To reel, sway, or move from side to side
One who moves or wears a halter
A fluophosphate of magnesia, occurring in yellowish crystals, and also in massive forms.
Money paid for carriage or conveyance in wagon.
A kind of pleasure wagon, uncovered and with seats extended along the sides, designed to carry six or eight persons besides the driver.
As much as a wagon will hold
Having a top, or head, shaped like the top of a covered wagon, or resembling in section or outline an inverted U, thus /
Having a roof, or top, shaped like an inverted U
Conveyance by means of a wagon or wagons.

Any one of many species of Old World singing birds belonging to Motacilla and several allied genera of the family Motacillidae. They have the habit of constantly jerking their long tails up and down, whence the name.
Goods found of which the owner is not known
A four-wheeled vehicle for the transportation of goods, produce, etc.
Capable of being plowed or cultivated
A finding of carriages, carts, etc., for the transportation of goods, produce, etc.
See Cartbote.  See also the Note under Bote.
A piece of plank two yard/ long and a foot broad.
That part of the human body which is immediately below the ribs or thorax
The band which encompasses the waist
A cloth or wrapper worn about the waist
A short, sleeveless coat or garment for men, worn under the coat, extending no lower than the hips, and covering the waist
A seaman, usually a green hand or a broken-down man, stationed in the waist of a vessel of war.
One who, or that which, waits
The act of waiving, or not insisting on, some right, claim, or privilege.
The track left by a vessel in the water
Any plant of the genus Arum, especially, in England, the cuckoopint (Arum maculatum).
Time during which one is awake.

A sect of dissenters from the ecclesiastical system of the Roman Catholic Church, who in the 13th century were driven by persecution to the valleys of Piedmont, where the sect survives. They profess substantially Protestant principles.
Of or pertaining to the Waldenses.
In the old German empire, the head forest keeper.
A genus of brachiopods of which many species are found in the fossil state. A few still exist in the deep sea.
A streak or mark made on the skin by a rod or whip
In racing, the going over a course by a horse which has no competitor for the prize
A kind of knot often used at the end of a rope
A leguminous tree (Eperua falcata) of Demerara, with pinnate leaves and clusters of red flowers. The reddish brown wood is used for palings and shingles.

Any one of numerous species of kangaroos belonging to the genus Halmaturus, native of Australia and Tasmania, especially the smaller species, as the brush kangaroo (H. Bennettii) and the pademelon (H. thetidis). The wallabies chiefly inhabit the wooded district and bushy plains.
A black variety of the jaguar
Any one of several species of kangaroos of the genus Macropus, especially M. robustus, sometimes called the great wallaroo.
A form of degeneration occurring in nerve fibers as a result of their division
A bag or sack for carrying about the person, as a bag for carrying the necessaries for a journey
An eye in which the iris is of a very light gray or whitish color
Having an eye of a very light gray or whitish color.
A perennial, cruciferous plant (Cheiranthus Cheiri), with sweet-scented flowers varying in color from yellow to orange and deep red. In Europe it very common on old walls.
A Romanic people inhabiting that part of Belgium which comprises the provinces of Hainaut, Namur, Liege, and Luxembourg, and about one third of Brabant
To move quickly, but with great effort
To roll one's self about, as in mire
One who, or that which, wallows.
The spotted flycatcher. It builds its nest on walls.
The dwarf elder, or danewort (Sambucus Ebulus).
The fruit or nut of any tree of the genus Juglans

A very large marine mammal (Trichecus rosmarus) of the Seal family, native of the Arctic Ocean. The male has long and powerful tusks descending from the upper jaw. It uses these in procuring food and in fighting.  It is hunted for its oil, ivory, and skin. It feeds largely on mollusks. Called also morse.
A dance performed by two persons in circular figures with a whirling motion
A tree (Cookia punctata) of the Orange family, growing in China and the East Indies
Beads made of shells, used by the North American Indians as money, and also wrought into belts, etc., as an ornament.
To ramble here and there without any certain course or with no definite object in view
The act of wandering, or roaming.

A large monkey (Macacus silenus) native of Malabar. It is black, or nearly so, but has a long white or gray beard encircling the face. Called also maha, silenus, neelbhunder, lion-tailed baboon, and great wanderoo.
Long and flexible, like a wand.
A sharp or uneven edge on a board that is cut from a log not perfectly squared, or that is made in the process of squaring.  See Wany, a.
The jaw, jawbone, or cheek bone.
A boat for conveying provisions, tools, etc.
The Chinese name of one or two species of bamboo, or jointed cane, of the genus Phyllostachys. The slender stems are much used for walking sticks.
An East Indian plant (Kaempferia Galanga) of the Ginger family.  See Galanga.
A word of uncertain signification, used only in the phrase with a wanion, apparently equivalent to with a vengeance, with a plague, or with misfortune.
In a wan, or pale, manner.
The quality or state of being wan
A colloquial contraction of was not.
The quality or state of being wanton
One destitute of wit or sense
A surcingle, or strap of leather, used for binding a load upon the back of a beast
The American hawk owl.  See under Hawk.
The edible tuber of a species of arrowhead (Sagittaria variabilis)

In some northern counties of England, a division, or district, answering to the hundred in other counties. Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and Nottinghamshire are divided into wapentakes, instead of hundreds.
An exhibition of arms. according to the rank of the individual, by all persons bearing arms
The American elk (Cervus Canadensis). It is closely related to the European red deer, which it somewhat exceeds in size.
A word of doubtful meaning used once by Shakespeare.
A small, hard tumor which is produced on the back of a horse by the heat or pressure of the saddle in traveling.
One who, or that which, warbles
A preparation containing quinine and many other ingredients, often used in the treatment of malarial affections. It was invented by Dr. Warburg of London.
Suffixes denoting course or direction to
The duty of keeping watch and ward (see the Note under Watch, n., 1) with a horn to be blown upon any occasion of surprise.
The office or jurisdiction of a warden.
Designating, or pertaining to, a kind of glass inclosure for keeping ferns, mosses, etc., or for transporting growing plants from a distance
Anciently, a meeting of the inhabitants of a ward
A room or apartment where clothes are kept, or wearing apparel is stored
A room occupied as a messroom by the commissioned officers of a war vessel.  See Gunroom.
The office of a ward or keeper
A Brazilian fly whose larvae live in the skin of man and animals, producing painful sores.
A storehouse for wares, or goods.
A room in which goods are stored or exhibited for sale.
A South American monkey, one of the sapajous.
The quality or state of being wary
To protect from the effects of
Having heat in a moderate degree
One who, or that which, warms.
One who makes ar a trade or business
An American freshwater bream, or sunfish (Chaenobryttus gulosus)
The quality or state of being warm
The route taken by a party of Indians going on a warlike expedition.
One who, or that which, warps or twists out of shape.
The obligation by which a person, conveying a subject or a right, is bound to uphold that subject or right against every claim, challenge, or burden arising from circumstances prior to the conveyance
Authorized by commission, precept, or right
The person to whom a warrant or warranty is made.
One who warrants, gives authority, or legally empowers.

A covenant real, whereby the grantor of an estate of freehold and his heirs were bound to warrant and defend the title, and, in case of eviction by title paramount, to yield other lands of equal value in recompense. This warranty has long singe become obsolete, and its place supplied by personal covenants for title. Among these is the covenant of warranty, which runs with the land, and is in the nature of a real covenant.
A place privileged, by prescription or grant the king, for keeping certain animals (as hares, conies, partridges, pheasants, etc.) called beasts and fowls of warren.
An Australian lorikeet (Trichoglossus multicolor) remarkable for the variety and brilliancy of its colors
A man engaged or experienced in war, or in the military life
The black grouper (Epinephelus nigritus) of the southern coasts of the United States.
A small, usually hard, tumor on the skin formed by enlargement of its vascular papillae, and thickening of the epidermis which covers them.
Having little knobs on the surface

Either one of two species of large, savage African wild hogs of the genus Phacoch/rus.  These animals have a pair of large, rough, fleshy tubercles behind the tusks and second pair behind the eyes. The tusks are large and strong, and both pairs curve upward. The body is scantily covered with bristles, but there is long dorsal mane. The South African species (Phacoch/rus Aethiopicus) is the best known. Called also vlacke vark. The second species (P. Aeliani) is native of the coasts of the Red Sea.
A name given to several plants because they were thought to be a cure for warts, as a kind of spurge (Euphorbia Helioscopia), and the nipplewort (Lampsana communis).
A dark brown or black mineral, occurring in prismatic crystals imbedded in limestone near Warwick, New York. It consists of the borate and titanate of magnesia and iron.
The first and third persons singular of the verb be, in the indicative mood, preterit (imperfect) tense
A bundle of straw, or other material, to relieve the pressure of burdens carried upon the head.
To cleanse by ablution, or dipping or rubbing in water
Capable of being washed without damage to fabric or color.
A fluted, or ribbed, board on which clothes are rubbed in washing them.
A basin, or bowl, to hold water for washing one's hands, face, etc.
One who, or that which, washes.
A man who washes clothes, esp. for hire, or for others.
A woman who washes clothes, especially for hire, or for others.
An outbuilding for washing, esp. one for washing clothes
The quality or state of being washy, watery, or weak.
Pertaining to, or characteristic of, George Washington
The washing out or away of earth, etc., especially of a portion of the bed of a road or railroad by a fall of rain or a freshet
A pot or vessel in which anything is washed.
A piece of furniture holding the ewer or pitcher, basin, and other requisites for washing the person.
A tub in which clothes are washed.
A variety of allanite from Sweden supposed to contain wasium.
A rare element supposed by Bahr to have been extracted from wasite, but now identified with thorium.
Any one of numerous species of stinging hymenopterous insects, esp. any of the numerous species of the genus Vespa, which includes the true, or social, wasps, some of which are called yellow jackets.
An ancient expression of good wishes on a festive occasion, especially in drinking to some one.
The second person singular of the verb be, in the indicative mood, imperfect tense
Loss by use, decay, evaporation, leakage, or the like
A basket used in offices, libraries, etc., as a receptacle for waste paper.
A book in which rough entries of transactions are made, previous to their being carried into the journal.
A kind of white and fine bread or cake
The quality or state of being waste
One who, or that which, wastes
An overfall, or weir, for the escape, or overflow, of superfluous water from a canal, reservoir, pond, or the like.
A dog kept to watch and guard premises or property, and to give notice of the approach of intruders.
The leaves of Saracenia flava.  See Trumpets.
A house in which a watch or guard is placed.
One whose occupation is to make and repair watches.
A tower in which a sentinel is placed to watch for enemies, the approach of danger, or the like.

A word given to sentinels, and to such as have occasion to visit the guards, used as a signal by which a friend is known from an enemy, or a person who has a right to pass the watch from one who has not
The fluid which descends from the clouds in rain, and which forms rivers, lakes, seas, etc.
Money paid for transportation of goods, etc., by water.
A kind of bur marigold (Bidens tripartita) found in wet places in Europe.
An aroid herb (Calla palustris) having a white spathe. It is an inhabitant of the north temperate zone.
An officer of the customs, whose duty it is to search vessels.
Water confined in specially constructed compartments in a vessel's hold, to serve as ballast.
A barometer in which the changes of atmospheric pressure are indicated by the motion of a column of water instead of mercury. It requires a column of water about thirty-three feet in height.
A device for regulating the temperature of anything subjected to heat, by surrounding the vessel containing it with another vessel containing water which can be kept at a desired temperature
A voltaic battery in which the exciting fluid is water.
Any species of Tardigrada, 2.  See Illust. of Tardigrada.
A kind of mattress made of, or covered with, waterproof fabric and filled with water. It is used in hospitals for bedridden patients.

Any one of numerous species of aquatic beetles belonging to Dytiscus and allied genera of the family Dytiscidae, and to various genera of the family Hydrophilidae.  These beetles swim with great agility, the fringed hind legs acting together like oars.
The European water ousel, or dipper.
A board set up to windward in a boat, to keep out water.
Prevented by a flood from proceeding.
Any arthropod that breathes by means of gills.

A large, heavy antelope (Kobus ellipsiprymnus) native of Central Africa. It frequents the banks of rivers and is a good swimmer. It has a white ring around the rump. Called also photomok, water antelope, and waterbok.
A large, open-headed cask, set up on end, to contain water.
Any one of several species of Nuphar
A very acrid herb (Ranunculus sceleratus) growing in ditches and wet places
The fruit of Trapa natans and Trapa bicornis, Old World water plants bearing edible nutlike fruits armed with several hard and sharp points
A large West African chevrotain (Hyaemoschus aquaticus). It has a larger body and shorter legs than the other allied species. Called also water deerlet.
A small annual plant (Montia fontana) growing in wet places in southern regions.
The American lotus, and its edible seeds, which somewhat resemble chinquapins.   Cf. Yoncopin.
An instrument or machine serving to measure time by the fall, or flow, of a certain quantity of water

A large gallinule (Gallicrex cristatus) native of Australia, India, and the East Indies. In the breeding season the male is black and has a fleshy red caruncle, or horn, on the top of its head. Called also kora.
A color ground with water and gum or other glutinous medium
One who paints in water colors.
Any vessel or boat plying on water
A goose-neck apparatus for supplying water from an elevated tank, as to the tender of a locomotive.
A perennial cruciferous herb (Nasturtium officinale) growing usually in clear running or spring water. The leaves are pungent, and used for salad and as an antiscorbutic.
An aquatic kind of buttercup (Ranunculus aquatilis), used as food for cattle in parts of England.
A covering of painting canvas for the equipments of a dragoon's horse.
A small Chinese deer (Hydropotes inermis). Both sexes are destitute of antlers, but the male has large, descending canine tusks.
The rapacious larva of a large water beetle (Hydrophilus piceus), and of other similar species.  See Illust. of Water beetle.
A tall, coarse dock growing in wet places. The American water dock is Rumex orbiculatus, the European is R. Hydrolapathum.
One who professes to be able to divine diseases by inspection of the urine.
A dog accustomed to the water, or trained to retrieve waterfowl. Retrievers, waters spaniels, and Newfoundland dogs are so trained.
A drain or channel for draining off water.
The treatment of wounds or ulcers by the application of water
A European poisonous umbelliferous plant (Enanthe fistulosa) with large hollow stems and finely divided leaves.
One who, or that which, waters.
A fall, or perpendicular descent, of the water of a river or stream, or a descent nearly perpendicular
A European species of Iris (Iris Pseudacorus) having bright yellow flowers.
A floating mass formed in pools by the entangled filaments of a European fresh-water alga (Cladophora crispata).
Any one of numerous species of small aquatic Entomostraca belonging to the genera Cyclops, Daphnia, etc
Any bird that frequents the water, or lives about rivers, lakes, etc., or on or near the sea
A name given to the first power spinning machine, because driven by water power.
A deep furrow for conducting water from the ground, and keeping the surface soil dry.
A cavity made in the earth by a torrent of water
A passage for water, such as was usually made in a sea wall, to drain water out of marshes.
A gate, or valve, by which a flow of water is permitted, prevented, or regulated.
A wall or bank to hold water back.
A gavel or rent paid for a privilege, as of fishing, in some river or water.
A labiate plant (Teucrium Scordium) found in marshy places in Europe.
The act, or the process, of gilding metallic surfaces by covering them with a thin coating of amalgam of gold, and then volatilizing the mercury by heat
A fabulous deity supposed to dwell in, and preside over, some body of water.
A liquid food composed of water and a small portion of meal, or other farinaceous substance, boiled and seasoned.

A vessel partly filled with water, exhausted of air, and hermetically sealed. When reversed or shaken, the water being unimpeded by air, strikes the sides in solid mass with a sound like that of a hammer.
A small American hare or rabbit (Lepus aquaticus) found on or near the southern coasts of the United States
A poisonous umbelliferous plant (Cicuta virosa) of Europe
A pile of salted fish heaped up to drain.
Either of several tropical aquatic plants of the genus Eichhornia, related to the pickerel weed.
Water flavored, sweetened, and frozen, to be eaten as a confection.
Same as Inch of water, under Water.
The quality or state of being watery

A joint in a stone pavement where the stones are left slightly higher than elsewhere, the rest of the surface being sunken or dished. The raised surface is intended to prevent the settling of water in the joints.
One of a body of Dutch Anabaptists who separated from the Mennonites in the sixteenth century
Any plant of the American genus Hydrophyllum, herbs having white or pale blue bell-shaped flowers.
The edible fruit of two species of passion flower (Passiflora laurifolia, and P. maliformis)
A plant (Pistia stratiotes) which floats on tropical waters, and forms a rosette of spongy, wedge-shaped leaves.
The level formed by the surface of still water.
A blossom or plant of any species of the genus Nymphaea, distinguished for its large floating leaves and beautiful flowers.  See Nymphaea.
Any one of certain lines of a vessel, model, or plan, parallel with the surface of the water at various heights from the keel.
Any aquatic lizard of the genus Varanus, as the monitor of the Nile.  See Monitor, n., 3.
A thorny leguminous tree (Gleditschia monosperma) which grows in the swamps of the Mississippi valley.
Filled or saturated with water so as to be heavy, unmanageable, or loglike
A man who plies for hire on rivers, lakes, or canals, or in harbors, in distinction from a seaman who is engaged on the high seas
A mark indicating the height to which water has risen, or at which it has stood
A meadow, or piece of low, flat land, capable of being kept in a state of fertility by being overflowed with water from some adjoining river or stream.
A measure formerly used for articles brought by water, as coals, oysters, etc. The water-measure bushel was three gallons larger than the Winchester bushel.
Any one of numerous species of water
The very large ovoid or roundish fruit of a cucurbitaceous plant (Citrullus vulgaris) of many varieties
A contrivance for measuring a supply of water delivered or received for any purpose, as from a street main.
Any plant of the genus Myriophyllum, aquatic herbs with whorled leaves, the submersed ones pinnately parted into capillary divisions.
A mill whose machinery is moved by water
A kind of mint (Mentha aquatica) growing in wet places, and sometimes having a perfume resembling bergamot.

Any of numerous species of aquatic mites belonging to Hydrachna and allied genera of the family Hydrachnidae, usually having the legs fringed and adapted for swimming. They are often red or red and black in color, and while young are parasites of fresh-water insects and mussels.  Called also water tick, and water spider.

A venomous North American snake (Ancistrodon piscivorus) allied to the rattlesnake but destitute of a rattle. It lives in or about pools and ponds, and feeds largely of fishes. Called also water snake, water adder, water viper.
The shrew mole.  See under Shrew.

A very large lizard (Varanaus salvator) native of India. It frequents the borders of streams and swims actively. It becomes five or six feet long. Called also two-banded monitor, and kabaragoya. The name is also applied to other aquatic monitors.

Any one of several species of mice belonging to the genus Hydromys, native of Australia and Tasmania. Their hind legs are strong and their toes partially webbed. They live on the borders of streams, and swim well. They are remarkable as being the only rodents found in Australia.
A kind of murrain affecting cattle.
Any one of numerous species of aquatic salamanders
A goddess of any stream or other body of water, whether one of the Naiads, Nereids, or Oceanides.
See Yapock, and the Note under Opossum.
Same as Ordeal by water.  See the Note under Ordeal, n., 1.

Any one of several species of small insessorial birds of the genus Cinclus (or Hydrobates), especially the European water ousel (C. aquaticus), and the American water ousel (C. Mexicanus). These birds live about the water, and are in the habit of walking on the bottom of streams beneath the water in search of food.
Any plant of the aquatic umbelliferous genus Sium, poisonous herbs with pinnate or dissected leaves and small white flowers.
A plant that grows in water
A kind of plant with acrid leaves.  See under 2d Plantain.
A plate heated by hot water contained in a double bottom or jacket.
Meadow reed grass.  See under Reed.
A pore by which the water tubes of various invertebrates open externally.
A vessel for holding or conveying water, or for sprinkling water on cloth, plants, etc.
The power of water employed to move machinery, etc.
A variety of chicken pox, or varicella.
The advantage of using water as a mechanical power
Proof against penetration or permeation by water
The act or process of making waterproof.
A coarse yellow-flowered plant (Nasturtium amphibium) related to the water cress and to the horse-radish.
Any one of numerous species of rails of the genus Rallus, as the common European species (Rallus aquaticus).  See Illust. of Rail.
The water vole.  See under Vole.
A rate or tax for a supply of water.
To ret, or rot, in water, as flax
A cruciferous plant (Nasturtium sylvestre) with small yellow flowers.
To rot by steeping in water
A small sail sometimes set under a studding sail or under a driver boom, and reaching nearly to the water.
A deep blue variety of iolite, sometimes used as a gem
The whole region or extent of country which contributes to the supply of a river or lake.
An aquatic American plant (Brasenia peltata) having floating oval leaves, and the covered with a clear jelly.
A sprig or shoot from the root or stock of a tree.

Any one of several species of shrews having fringed feet and capable of swimming actively. The two common European species (Crossopus fodiens, and C. ciliatus) are the best known. The most common American water shrew, or marsh shrew (Neosorex palustris), is rarely seen, owing to its nocturnal habits.
Any aquatic pulmonate gastropod belonging to Planorbis, Limnaea, and allied genera
A common North American colubrine snake (Tropidonotus sipedon) which lives chiefly in the water.
An aquatic European plant (Stratiotes aloides) with bayonet-shaped leaves.
A dish consisting of small fish stewed and served in a little water.
A curly-haired breed of spaniels, naturally very fond of the water.
A kind of speedwell (Veronica Anagallis) found in wet places in Europe and America.

An aquatic European spider (Argyoneta aquatica) which constructs its web beneath the surface of the water on water plants. It lives in a bell-shaped structure of silk, open beneath like a diving bell, and filled with air which the spider carries down in the form of small bubbles attached one at a time to the spinnerets and hind feet. Called also diving spider.
A remarkable meteorological phenomenon, of the nature of a tornado or whirlwind, usually observed over the sea, but sometimes over the land.
A sprite, or spirit, imagined as inhabiting the water.
An aquatic plant (Schollera graminea) with grassy leaves, and yellow star-shaped blossoms.
X, the twenty-fourth letter of the English alphabet, has three sounds
An amido derivative of xanthic acid obtained as a white crystalline substance, C2H5O.CS.NH2
Of or pertaining to Xanthus, an ancient town on Asia Minor
Tending toward a yellow color, or to one of those colors, green being excepted, in which yellow is a constituent, as scarlet, orange, etc.
A compound or derivative of xanthogen.

A genus of minute unicellular algae of the desmids. These algae have a rounded shape and are armed with glochidiate or branched aculei. Several species occur in ditches, and others are found fossil in flint or hornstone.

A crystalline nitrogenous body closely related to both uric acid and hypoxanthin, present in muscle tissue, and occasionally found in the urine and in some urinary calculi. It is also present in guano. So called from the yellow color of certain of its salts (nitrates).
A complex nitrogenous substance related to urea and uric acid, produced as a white powder
A genus of composite plants in which the scales of the involucre are united so as to form a kind of bur
A combining form from Gr. xanqo`s yellow
A division of the Caucasian races, comprising the lighter-colored members.
Having a yellowish or fair complexion
The hypothetical radical supposed to be characteristic of xanthic acid.
Producing a yellow color or compound
A skin disease marked by the development or irregular yellowish patches upon the skin, especially upon the eyelids
The yellow pigment present in the inner segments of the retina in animals.  See Chromophane.
A yellow coloring matter found in yellow autumn leaves, and also produced artificially from chlorophyll
Having a yellow stipe, or stem.
Pertaining to, or derived from, xanthoprotein
A yellow acid substance formed by the action of hot nitric acid on albuminous or proteid matter. It is changed to a deep orange-yellow color by the addition of ammonia.
One of three alkaloids found in the root of the yellow puccoon (Hydrastis Canadensis). It is a yellow crystalline substance, and resembles berberine.
A glucoside extracted from Persian berries as a yellow crystalline powder, used as a dyestuff.
A genus of shrubby ranunculaceous plants of North America, including only the species Xanthorhiza apiifolia, which has roots of a deep yellow color
A genus of endogenous plants, native to Australia, having a thick, sometimes arborescent, stem, and long grasslike leaves.  See Grass tree.
An orange-yellow substance found in pigment spots of certain crabs.
The yellow discoloration often observed in cancerous tumors.
A liquid hydrocarbon of the terpene series extracted from the seeds of a Japanese prickly ash (Xanthoxylum pipertium) as an aromatic oil.
A genus of prickly shrubs or small trees, the bark and rots of which are of a deep yellow color

A small three-masted vessel, with projecting bow stern and convex decks, used in the Mediterranean for transporting merchandise, etc. It carries large square sails, or both. Xebecs were formerly armed and used by corsairs.
A Spartan institution which prohibited strangers from residing in Sparta without permission, its object probably being to preserve the national simplicity of manners.
A present given to a guest or stranger, or to a foreign ambassador.
A house for the reception of strangers.
A mania for, or an inordinate attachment to, foreign customs, institutions, manners, fashions, etc.
A suborder of soft-rayed fresh-water fishes of which the blackfish of Alaska (Dallia pectoralis) is the type.
A suborder of fishes including Gobiesox and allied genera. These fishes have soft-rayed fins, and a ventral sucker supported in front by the pectoral fins. They are destitute of scales.
A native phosphate of yttrium occurring in yellowish-brown tetragonal crystals.
The radical characteristic of xenylic compounds.
Pertaining to, derived from, designating, certain amido compounds obtained by reducing certain nitro derivatives of diphenyl.
An old money of account in Bombay, equal to three fifths of a rupee.
A gold coin formerly current in Egypt and Turkey, of the value of about  9s. 6d., or about $2.30
Pertaining to, or designating, an acid, C8H12O4, related to fumaric acid, and obtained from citraconic acid as an oily substance having a bittersweet taste
Among the primitive Christians, the living on a diet of dry food in Lent and on other fasts.
An abnormal dryness of the eyeball produced usually by long-continued inflammation and subsequent atrophy of the conjunctiva.
A genus of fishes comprising the common swordfish.
A genus of plants of the order Haemodraceae, having two-ranked, sword-shaped leaves.
Of, pertaining to, or resembling, a cetacean of the genus Xiphius or family Xiphiidae.
The posterior, or fourth, lateral plate in the plastron of turtles
The posterior segment, or extremity, of the sternum
A genus of cetaceans having a long, pointed, bony beak, usually two tusklike teeth in the lower jaw, but no teeth in the upper jaw.
An extinct genus of artiodactylous mammals found in the European Tertiary formations. It had slender legs, didactylous feet, and small canine teeth.
Same as Limuloidea. Called also Xiphosura.
An acid amide derivative of xylic acid, obtained as a white crystalline substance.
That portion of a fibrovascular bundle which has developed, or will develop, into wood cells

Any of a group of three metameric hydrocarbons of the aromatic series, found in coal and wood tar, and so named because found in crude wood spirit. They are colorless, oily, inflammable liquids, C6H4.(CH3)2, being dimethyl benzenes, and are called respectively orthoxylene, metaxylene, and paraxylene. Called also xylol.
Any one of six metameric phenol derivatives of xylene, obtained as crystalline substances, (CH3)2.C6H3.OH.
Pertaining to, or designating, a complex acid related to mesitylenic acid, obtained as a white crystalline substance by the action of sodium and carbon dioxide on crude xylenol.
Pertaining to, derived from, or related to, xylene
Pertaining to, or designating, either one of two distinct acids which are derived from xylic acid and related compounds, and are metameric with uvitic acid.

Any one of six metameric hydrocarbons, (CH3)2.C6H3.NH2, resembling aniline, and related to xylene. They are liquids, or easily fusible crystalline substances, of which three are derived from metaxylene, two from orthoxylene, and one from paraxylene. They are called the amido xylenes.
A green or blue pigment produced by Peziza in certain kinds of decayed wood, as the beech, oak, birch, etc., and extracted as an amorphous powder resembling indigo.
A liquid hydrocarbon found in crude wood spirits.
A yellow oil having a geraniumlike odor, produced as a side product in making phorone
A combining form from Gr. xy`lon wood
The dried twigs of a Syrian tree (Balsamodendron Gileadense).
Bearing fruit which becomes hard or woody.
A genus of hymenopterous insects including the carpenter.  See Carpenter bee, under Carpenter.
An engraving on wood, or the impression from such an engraving
Of or pertaining to xylography, or wood engraving.
The art of engraving on wood.
A substance resembling pyroxylin, obtained by the action of nitric acid on starch
A genus of marine bivalves which bore holes in wood. They are allied to Pholas.
One of a tribe of beetles whose larvae bore or live in wood.
A tribe or family of dipterous flies whose larvae live in decayed wood. Some of the tropical species are very large.
Eating, boring in, or destroying, wood
One of a tribe of beetles (Xylophili) whose larvae live on decayed wood.
Of or pertaining to the xylophilans.

An instrument common among the Russians, Poles, and Tartars, consisting of a series of strips of wood or glass graduated in length to the musical scale, resting on belts of straw, and struck with two small hammers. Called in Germany strohfiedel, or straw fiddle.
Formed of wood pulp by molds
The art or practice of burning pictures on wood with a hot iron
Any one of a group of quinone compounds obtained respectively by the oxidation of certain xylidine compounds. In general they are yellow crystalline substances.
A derivative of xylene obtained as a white crystalline substance which on exposure in the air becomes red
A glucoside found in the poisonous berries of a species of honeysuckle (Lonicera xylosteum), and extracted as a bitter, white, crystalline substance.
A genus of marine bivalves closely allied to Teredo, and equally destructive to timber. One species (Xylotrya fimbriata) is very common on the Atlantic coast of the United States.
Any one of three metameric radicals which are characteristic respectively of the three xylenes.
Any one of three metameric radicals, CH2.C6H4.CH2, derived respectively from the three xylenes. Often used adjectively
Of or pertaining to a natural order (Xyrideae) of endogenous plants, of which Xyris is the type.
A genus of endogenous herbs with grassy leaves and small yellow flowers in short, scaly-bracted spikes
A long and open portico, for athletic exercises, as wrestling, running, etc., for use in winter or in stormy weather.
An office/ having the superintendence of the xyst.
Y, the twenty-fifth letter of the English alphabet, at the beginning of a word or syllable, except when a prefix (see Y-), is usually a fricative vocal consonant

A South American crocodilian (Jacare sclerops) resembling the alligator in size and habits. The eye orbits are connected together, and surrounded by prominent bony ridges. Called also spectacled alligator, and spectacled cayman.
A West Indian name for two large timber trees (Podocarpus coriaceus, and P. Purdicanus) of the Yew family. The wood, which is much used, is pale brownish with darker streaks.
A light and elegantly furnished vessel, used either for private parties of pleasure, or as a vessel of state to convey distinguished persons from one place to another
One engaged in sailing a jacht.
Sailing for pleasure in a yacht.
One who owns or sails a yacht

The European green woodpecker (Picus, / Genius, viridis). It is noted for its loud laughlike note. Called also eccle, hewhole, highhoe, laughing bird, popinjay, rain bird, yaffil, yaffler, yaffingale, yappingale, yackel, and woodhack.
In the German army, one belonging to a body of light infantry armed with rifles, resembling the chasseur of the French army.

A bovine mammal (Poephagus grunnies) native of the high plains of Central Asia. Its neck, the outer side of its legs, and its flanks, are covered with long, flowing, fine hair. Its tail is long and bushy, often white, and is valued as an ornament and for other purposes in India and China. There are several domesticated varieties, some of which lack the mane and the long hair on the flanks. Called also chauri gua, grunting cow, grunting ox, sarlac, sarlik, and sarluc.

A large Asiatic antelope (Budorcas taxicolor) native of the higher parts of the Himalayas and other lofty mountains. Its head and neck resemble those of the ox, and its tail is like that of the goat. Called also budorcas.
(Ethnol.) A nomadic Mongolian tribe native of Northern Siberia, and supposed to be of Turkish stock. They are mainly pastoral in their habits.
A kind of demigod attendant on Kuvera, the god of wealth.
The oil of the mahwa tree.
A large, esculent, farinaceous tuber of various climbing plants of the genus Dioscorea

The king of the infernal regions, corresponding to the Greek Pluto, and also the judge of departed souls. In later times he is more exclusively considered the dire judge of all, and the tormentor of the wicked. He is represented as of a green color, with red garments, having a crown on his head, his eyes inflamed, and sitting on a buffalo, with a club and noose in his hands.
The cry of the wild goose
A nickname for a native or citizen of New England, especially one descended from old New England stock
The name of a tune adopted popularly as one of the national airs of the United States.
A Yankee idiom, word, custom, or the like.
A fermented drink, or milk beer, made by the Turks.

A South American aquatic opossum (Chironectes variegatus) found in Guiana and Brazil. Its hind feet are webbed, and its fore feet do not have an opposable thumb for climbing. Called also water opossum.
The power of moving, or being managed, at sea
Either half of a square-rigged vessel's yard, from the center or mast to the end.
As much as a yard will contain
A measure of land of uncertain quantity, varying from fifteen to forty acres
A stick three feet, or a yard, in length, used as a measure of cloth, etc.
To growl or snarl as a dog.

An American and European composite plant (Achillea Millefolium) with very finely dissected leaves and small white corymbed flowers. It has a strong, and somewhat aromatic, odor and taste, and is sometimes used in making beer, or is dried for smoking. Called also milfoil, and nosebleed.
A long knife, or short saber, common among Mohammedan nations, usually having a double curve, sometimes nearly straight.
To cry out like a child
One who, or that which, yaups.

A shrub (Ilex Cassine) of the Holly family, native from Virginia to Florida. The smooth elliptical leaves are used as a substitute for tea, and were formerly used in preparing the black drink of the Indians of North Carolina. Called also South-Sea tea.
To rise in blisters, breaking in white froth, as cane juice in the clarifiers in sugar works.
A small ship's boat, usually rowed by four or six oars.
Having two masts with fore-and-aft sails, but differing from a schooner in that the after mast is very small, and stepped as far aft as possible.  See Illustration in Appendix.
To open the mouth involuntarily through drowsiness, dullness, or fatigue

A disease, occurring in the Antilles and in Africa, characterized by yellowish or reddish tumors, of a contagious character, which, in shape and appearance, often resemble currants, strawberries, or raspberries. There are several varieties of this disease, variously known as framboesia, pian, verrugas, and crab-yaws.
A low, shrubby, rubiaceous plant (Morinda Royoc) growing along the seacoast of the West Indies. It has small, white, odorous flowers.
Properly, a variant of the defective imperfect yode, but sometimes mistaken for a present.  See the Note under Yede.
To bring forth young, as a goat or a sheep
The time of the apparent revolution of the sun trough the ecliptic
The California poison oak (Rhus diversiloba).  See under Poison, a.
An animal one year old, or in the second year of its age
Happening, accruing, or coming every year
The maws, or stomachs, of young calves, used as a rennet for curdling milk.

The foam, or troth (top yeast), or the sediment (bottom yeast), of beer or other in fermentation, which contains the yeast plant or its spores, and under certain conditions produces fermentation in saccharine or farinaceous substances
A term used of beer when the froth of the yeast has reentered the body of the beer.
The quality or state of being yeasty, or frothy.
To cry out, or shriek, with a hideous noise
Being of a bright saffronlike color
The American goldfinch, or thistle bird.  See Goldfinch.
Covered or bound in yellow paper.
A rock trout (Pleurogrammus monopterygius) found on the coast of Alaska
A certain plant, probably the yellow oxeye.

A common European finch (Emberiza citrinella). The color of the male is bright yellow on the breast, neck, and sides of the head, with the back yellow and brown, and the top of the head and the tail quills blackish. Called also yellow bunting, scribbling lark, and writing lark.
Any one of several species of long-legged sandpipers of the genus Totanus, in which the legs are bright yellow
The quality or state of being yellow
Any one of several plants with yellow roots.
A disease of the bile in horses, cattle, and sheep, causing yellowness of the eyes
A kind of pepper grass (Lepidium campestre).
Any one of several species of marine carangoid fishes of the genus Seriola
Any one of several species of American ground warblers of the genus Geothlypis, esp. the Maryland yellowthroat (G. trichas), which is a very common species.
A kind of grass, perhaps a species of Agrostis.
The wood of any one of several different kinds of trees
A European yellow-flowered, gentianaceous (Chlora perfoliata). The whole plant is intensely bitter, and is sometimes used as a tonic, and also in dyeing yellow.
An animal that yelps, or makes a yelping noise.
A silicate of iron and lime occurring in black prismatic crystals
A common man, or one of the commonly of the first or most respectable class
Resembling, or suitable to, a yeoman
The position or rank of a yeoman.
To throw or thrust with a sudden, smart movement
An earthnut, or groundnut.  See Groundnut (d).
Any one of several species of large marine gastropods belonging to the genus Yetus, or Cymba
Of or pertaining to Yezdegerd, the last Sassanian monarch of Persia, who was overthrown by the Mohammedans
See in the Dictionary of Noted Names in Fiction.
To give in return for labor expended
A suffix used as a characteristic termination of chemical radicals
To sing in a manner common among the Swiss and Tyrolese mountaineers, by suddenly changing from the head voice, or falsetto, to the chest voice, and the contrary

A species of asceticism among the Hindoos, which consists in a complete abstraction from all worldly objects, by which the votary expects to obtain union with the universal spirit, and to acquire superhuman faculties.
A follower of the yoga philosophy
A cry of encouragement to foxhounds.
A measure of distance, varying from four to ten miles, but usually about five.
A bar or frame of wood by which two oxen are joined at the heads or necks for working together.
An associate or companion in, or as in
Having two toes in front and two behind, as the trogons and woodpeckers.
The yellow part of an egg
At a distance, but within view
A local name in parts of the Mississippi Valley for the American lotus (Nelumbo lutea).
At a distance, but within view.
The symbol under which Sakti, or the personification of the female power in nature, is worshiped.  Cf. Lingam.
A county in the north of England.
The one of the three printed uses of England which was followed in the north. It was based on the Sarum use.  See Use, n., 6.
The pronoun of the second person, in the nominative, dative, and objective case, indicating the person or persons addressed.  See the Note under Ye.
Like a young person or thing
The quality or state of being young.
The form of the possessive case of the personal pronoun you.
An emphasized or reflexive form of the pronoun of the second person
The quality or state of being a youth
To utter a loud, long, and mournful cry, as a dog
Fine bobbin lace made at Ypres in Belgium, usually exactly like Valenciennes lace.
In the form of the letter Y
Pertaining to, or derived from, ytterbium
A rare element of the boron group, sometimes associated with yttrium or other related elements, as in euxenite and gadolinite. Symbol Yb
The oxide, Y2O3, or earth, of yttrium.
Pertaining to, derived from, or containing, yttrium.
Bearing or containing yttrium or the allied elements
A rare metallic element of the boron-aluminium group, found in gadolinite and other rare minerals, and extracted as a dark gray powder.  Symbol Y.  Atomic weight, 89.
A mineral of a violet-blue color, inclining to gray and white. It is a hydrous fluoride of cerium, yttrium, and calcium.
A tantalate of uranium, yttrium, and calcium, of a brown or black color.

The crowned gibbon (Hylobates pileatus), native of Siam, Southern China, and the Island of Hainan. It is entirely arboreal in its habits, and has very long arms. the males are dark brown or blackish, with a caplike mass of long dark hair, and usually with a white band around the face. The females are yellowish white, with a dark spot on the breast and another on the crown. Called also wooyen, and wooyen ape.
Any one of the four ages, Krita, or Satya, Treta, Dwapara, and Kali, into which the Hindoos divide the duration or existence of the world.
A species of Magnolia (M. conspicua) with large white blossoms that open before the leaves.  See the Note under Magnolia.
A tribe of Indians native of Arizona and the adjacent parts of Mexico and California. They are agricultural, and cultivate corn, wheat, barley, melons, etc.
A genus of birds comprising the wrynecks.

Z, the twenty-sixth and last letter of the English alphabet, is a vocal consonant. It is taken from the Latin letter Z, which came from the Greek alphabet, this having it from a Semitic source. The ultimate origin is probably Egyptian. Etymologically, it is most closely related to s, y, and j
An old solfeggio name for B flat
An oil pressed by the Arabs from the fruit of a small thorny tree (Balanites Aegyptiaca), and sold to piligrims for a healing ointment.

A pigment obtained, usually by roasting cobalt glance with sand or quartz, as a dark earthy powder. It consists of crude cobalt oxide, or of an impure cobalt arseniate. It is used in porcelain painting, and in enameling pottery, to produce a blue color, and is often confounded with smalt, from which, however, it is distinct, as it contains no potash. The name is often loosely applied to mixtures of zaffer proper with silica, or oxides of iron, manganese, etc.
A Turkish chief who supports a mounted militia bearing the same name.
A district from which a Zaim draws his revenue.
A horse of a dark color, neither gray nor white, and having no spots.
Of or pertaining to a tribe (Zalambdodonta) of Insectivora in which the molar teeth have but one V-shaped ridge.

An immense leguminous tree (Pithecolobium Saman) of Venezuela. Its branches form a hemispherical mass, often one hundred and eighty feet across. The sweet pulpy pods are used commonly for feeding cattle. Also called rain tree.
The child of a mulatto and a negro
A genus of cycadaceous plants, having the appearance of low palms, but with exogenous wood.  See Coontie, and Illust. of Strobile.
A fossil cycad of the genus Zamia.

A West African buffalo (Bubalus brachyceros) having short horns depressed at the base, and large ears fringed internally with three rows of long hairs. It is destitute of a dewlap. Called also short-horned buffalo, and bush cow.
A sort of bagpipe formerly in use among Italian peasants. It is now almost obsolete.
A European pike perch (Stizostedion lucioperca) allied to the wall-eye
A kind of seedless grape or raisin
A native or inhabitant of Zante, one of the Ionian Islands.
State or character of a zany
An extinct genus of cyathophylloid corals common in the Paleozoic formations. It is cup-shaped with numerous septa, and with a deep pit in one side of the cup.
Of or pertaining to Zarathustra, or Zoroaster
A hydrous carbonate of nickel occurring as an emerald-green incrustation on chromite
Native sulphide of arsenic, including sandarach, or realgar, and orpiment.
A species of macaque (Macacus pileatus) native of India and Ceylon. It has a crown of long erect hair, and tuft of radiating hairs on the back of the head. Called also capped macaque.
A genus of flowering plants.  Zauschneria Californica is a suffrutescent perennial, with showy red flowers much resembling those of the garden fuchsia.
A tool for trimming and puncturing roofing slates.
A public shed, or portico, for travelers, worshipers, etc.
A genus of large grasses of which the Indian corn (Zea Mays) is the only species known. Its origin is not yet ascertained.  See Maize.
Passionate ardor in the pursuit of anything
Like, or suitable to, a zealot
The character or conduct of a zealot
The character and behavior of a zealot
Filled with, or characterized by, zeal
Either one of two species of South African wild horses remarkable for having the body white or yellowish white, and conspicuously marked with dark brown or brackish bands.
A kind of cabinet wood having beautiful black, brown, and whitish stripes, the timber of a tropical American tree (Connarus Guianensis).
Pertaining to, or resembling, the zebra.

A bovine mammal (Ros Indicus) extensively domesticated in India, China, the East Indies, and East Africa. It usually has short horns, large pendulous ears, slender legs, a large dewlap, and a large, prominent hump over the shoulders
A large noxious fly of Abyssinia, which like the tsetse fly, is destructive to cattle.
The upper division of the Permian (Dyas) of Europe. The prevailing rock is a magnesian limestone.
A medicinal substance obtained in the East Indies, having a fragrant smell, and a warm, bitter, aromatic taste. It is used in medicine as a stimulant.
An Austrian silver coin equal to ten kreutzers, or about five cents.
A nitrogenous substance of the nature of gluten, obtained from the seeds of Indian corn (Zea) as a soft, yellowish, amorphous substance.

The blind mole rat (Spalax typhlus), native of Eastern Europe and Asia. Its eyes and ears are rudimentary, and its fur is soft and brownish, more or less tinged with gray. It constructs extensive burrows.
The part of a dwelling appropriated to women.
Properly, the translation and exposition in the Huzv/resh, or literary Pehlevi, language, of the Avesta, the Zoroastrian sacred writings
The sacred writings of the ancient Persian religion, attributed to Zoroaster, but chiefly of a later date.
A South African burrowing mammal (Suricata tetradactyla), allied to the civets. It is grayish brown, with yellowish transverse stripes on the back. Called also suricat.
That point in the visible celestial hemisphere which is vertical to the spectator
Of or pertaining to the zenith.

A term now used to designate any one of a family of minerals, hydrous silicates of alumina, with lime, soda, potash, or rarely baryta. Here are included natrolite, stilbite, analcime, chabazite, thomsonite, heulandite, and others. These species occur of secondary origin in the cavities of amygdaloid, basalt, and lava, also, less frequently, in granite and gneiss. So called because many of these species intumesce before the blowpipe.
Of or pertaining to a zeolite
Having the form of a zeolite.
A piece of orange or lemon peel, or the aromatic oil which may be squeezed from such peel, used to give flavor to liquor, etc.
A Greek letter  corresponding to our z.
A branch of algebra which relates to the direct search for unknown quantities.
A genus of extinct Eocene whales, remains of which have been found in the Gulf States. The species had very long and slender bodies and broad serrated teeth.  See Phocodontia.
A figure by which an adjective or verb, which agrees with a nearer word, is, by way of supplement, referred also to another more remote
The chief deity of the Greeks, and ruler of the upper world (cf. Hades). He was identified with Jupiter.
Any one of a group of bombycid moths of which the genus Zeuzera is the type. Some of these moths are of large size. The goat moth is an example.

A carnivorous mammal (Viverra zibetha) closely allied to the civet, from which it differs in having the spots on the body less distinct, the throat whiter, and the black rings on the tail more numerous.
Curd produced from milk by adding acetic acid, after rennet has ceased to cause coagulation.
A mineral wax, vert similar to ozocerite. It is found at Zietrisika, Moldavia, whence its name.
The second month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year, corresponding to our May.
Something that has short turns or angles.
The quality or state of being zigzag
A low, thorny, suffrutescent, crucifeous plant (Zilla myagroides) found in the deserts of Egypt. Its leaves are boiled in water, and eaten, by the Arabs.
A district or local division, as of a province.
A large, venomous, two-winged fly, native of Abyssinia. It is allied to the tsetse fly, and, like the latter, is destructive to cattle.
A kind of water found in copper mines

An abundant element of the magnesium-cadmium group, extracted principally from the minerals zinc blende, smithsonite, calamine, and franklinite, as an easily fusible bluish white metal, which is malleable, especially when heated. It is not easily oxidized in moist air, and hence is used for sheeting, coating galvanized iron, etc. It is used in making brass, britannia, and other alloys, and is also largely consumed in electric batteries. Symbol Zn. Atomic weight 64.9.
Pertaining to, containing, or resembling, zinc
The act or process of applying zinc
To coat or impregnate with zinc.
Pertaining to zinc, or having its appearance.
The positive electrode of an electrolytic cell
The art or process of engraving or etching on zinc, in which the design is left in relief in the style of a wood cut, the rest of the ground being eaten away by acid.
Electrically polarized like the surface of the zinc presented to the acid in a battery, which has zincous affinity.
Of, pertaining to, or containing, zinc
A small, edible, freshwater European perch (Aspro zingel), having a round, elongated body and prominent snout.
Of or pertaining to ginger, or to a tribe (Zingibereae) of endogenous plants of the order Scitamineae.  See Scitamineous.
A steel-gray metallic mineral, a sulphide of antimony and lead.
Any plant of the composite genus Zinnia, Mexican herbs with opposite leaves and large gay-colored blossoms. Zinnia elegans is the commonest species in cultivation.
A kind of mica containing lithium, often associated with tin ore.
A hill in Jerusalem, which, after the capture of that city by the Israelites, became the royal residence of David and his successors.
A combining form (also used adjectively) designating zirconium as an element of certain double compounds
A double fluoride of zirconium and hydrogen, or some other positive element or radical

A mineral occurring in tetragonal crystals, usually of a brown or gray color. It consists of silica and zirconia.  A red variety, used as a gem, is called hyacinth. Colorless, pale-yellow or smoky-brown varieties from Ceylon are called jargon.

The oxide of zirconium, obtained as a white powder, and possessing both acid and basic properties. On account of its infusibility, and brilliant luminosity when incandescent, it is used as an ingredient of sticks for the Drummomd light.
Pertaining to, containing, or resembling, zirconium

A rare element of the carbon-silicon group, intermediate between the metals and nonmetals, obtained from the mineral zircon as a dark sooty powder, or as a gray metallic crystalline substance. Symbol Zr. Atomic weight, 90.4.
A double eight-sided pyramid, a form common with tetragonal crystals

An instrument of music used in Austria and Germany. It has from thirty to forty wires strung across a shallow sounding-board, which lies horizontally on a table before the performer, who uses both hands in playing on it. [Not to be confounded with the old lute-shaped cittern, or cithern.]
A genus of grasses including Indian rice.  See Indian rice, under Rice.
A suborder of Actinaria, including Zoanthus and allied genera, which are permanently attached by their bases.
Of or pertaining to the Zoantharia.
The zooids of a compound anthozoan, collectively.
Of or pertaining to the Zoanthacea.
A kind of monomania in which the patient believes himself transformed into one of the lower animals.

A genus of Actinaria, including numerous species, found mostly in tropical seas. The zooids or polyps resemble small, elongated actinias united together at their bases by fleshy stolons, and thus forming extensive groups. The tentacles are small and bright colored.
